@NODE AEM-1000 "PROGRAM PURPOSE"

                             @{b}What is AEMail?@{ub}

@{b}AEMail@{ub} is a @{i}mail client@{ui} designed to read, process, compose and send e-mail from
an Amiga computer over the Internet.  It provides an easy to use graphical
interface designed specifically for the Amiga.  It connects to an Internet
server through @{" AmiTCP " link AEM-9910} or any TCP/IP stack compatable with @{b}AmiTCP@{ub}. This
includes @{" TermiteTCP " link AEM-9910} and @{" Miami " link AEM-9910}.  It uses the AmigaDOS editor, @{b}ed@{ub}, or any
other editor of the user's choosing for developing email messages.  No other
external programs or modules are required. The @{b}POP3@{ub} and @{b}SMTP@{ub} protocols are
built into the program.

@{b}AEMail@{ub} does use the @{b}ClassAct Boopsi@{ub} classes for building some of it's GUI
(@{i}Graphical User Interface@{ui}).  The @{b}ClassAct@{ub} classes required by @{b}AEMail@{ub} are
included with the @{b}AEMail@{ub} Release.  If you are using the @{b}Amiga OS 3.5@{ub},
@{b}ClassAct@{ub} is built into the OS and will not be installed with this
release.


The current version of @{b}AEMail@{ub} supports attachments following the @{b}MIME@{ub}
(@{i}Multipurpose Internet Mail Extension@{ui}) outlined in @{b}RFC 1341, 1521,
1524@{ub} (@{i}Mailcap files@{ui}), and @{b}1806@{ub} as well as @{b}UUENCODED@{ub} attached files. Not
all of the features of @{b}MIME@{ub} headers are fully supported and exceptions
will be noted in this documentation.

@{b}AEMail@{ub} can also be used as a @{b}mailto:@{ub} agent in web browsers, such as
@{" AWeb " link AEM-9910}, @{" IBrowse " link AEM-9910}, and @{" Voyager " link AEM-9910} which allow the user to specify such
an agent for composing and sending email.

You can also call @{b}AEMail@{ub} from another program to send a message created by
that program.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-2000 "SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS"

                           @{b}System Requirements@{ub}

This program can run on any @{b}Amiga Operating Systen 2.1@{ub} and @{b}above.@{ub}  It uses
the @{b}ClassAct Boopsi Classes@{ub} which are provided with the Installation
script for installations below 3.5.  If you are using @{b}Amiga OS 3.5@{ub},
@{b}ClassAct@{ub} is built into the OS and does not have to be installed.


This program requires a TCP/IP stack compatable with @{" AmiTCP " link AEM-9910}.  It has been
tested with the @{b}4.0 Demo Version@{ub} of @{b}AmiTCP@{ub}, but will possibly run on
earlier versions at level 2.0 or greater.  It also has been tested under
@{" TermiteTCP " link AEM-9910} and @{" Miami " link AEM-9910} which use a TCP/IP stack that is compatable with
@{b}AmiTCP@{ub}.

Other TCP/IP software may or @{i}may not@{ui} be compatable with @{b}AmiTCP@{ub}.  If the
software uses a socket library (@{i}bsdsocket.library@{ui}) with calls that are
compatable with @{b}AmiTCP@{ub}, it possibly will work.

If you wish to display @{b}MIME attachments@{ub} from within @{b}AEMail@{ub}, you will also
need a @{b}Mailcap@{ub} file.  You can define and/or edit entries in the 
@{b}Mailcap@{ub} file through the @{" Viewer Page " link AEM-4600} of the @{" Configuration setup " link AEM-4200}.
The actual specifications for the @{b}mailcap@{ub} file are given under 
@{" AEMAIL FILES:  mailcap " link AEM-9100}.  It is possible to display attachments with 
either AmigaDos 2.x or 3.x.  Depending on the program you select to 
display the attachments, @{i}datatypes may not be @{u}required@{uu} for this display.@{ui}

A @{" sample mailcap " link AEM-9101} file is also provided in the archive.  This @{b}sample
mailcap@{ub} file can be used without modification on any system running under
AmigaDos 3.0 or later since it uses @{b}MultiView@{ub} (@{i}which does use datatypes@{ui})
as the display agent.

If you are using a version of AmigaDos before 3.0, you will have to modify
the @{b}mailcap@{ub} file to specify your own favorite display program for specific 
@{b}Content Type/Subtypes@{ub}.  You can use the @{b}Viewer Page@{ub} of the
@{b}Configuration Setup@{ub} to do this.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-2100 "RESTRICTIONS"

                               @{b}Restrictions@{ub}

Only one version of @{b}AEMail@{ub} can be running at a time.  If you are using
@{b}AEMail@{ub} as a @{" mailto: " link AEM-5300} mail agent in a browser and you set it up to be
called directly (@{i}not through an @{b}ARexx@{ub} script@{ui}), you can not have @{b}AEMail@{ub}
running when you invoke your browser if you expect to send any email from
your browser.  This is because @{b}AEMail@{ub} will be automatically loaded from
the browser when you click on a @{b}mailto:@{ub} link.  This can be avoided if
you call @{b}AEMail@{ub} through an @{b}ARexx@{ub} script which has been provided in the
ARexx directory called @{b}mailto.aem@{ub}.  Consult the @{b}mailto.readme@{ub} file,
also in the @{b}ARexx@{ub} directory, on how to use this script.  Using the @{b}ARexx@{ub}
script allows you to have a running copy of @{b}AEMail@{ub} when your browser is
invoked.

This same restiction applies if you call @{b}AEMail@{ub} from an external program
to @{b}Queue@{ub} or @{b}Send@{ub} a message created by that program.  However, if you use
an ARexx Script (or command) you can interface with a running copy of
@{b}AEMail@{ub}.


                        @{b}@{u}AmigaDOS 2.1 Restrictions@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}ClassAct@{ub} does not correctly handle mouse clicks in button gadgets or
listviews under AmigaDOS 2.1 when these mouse clicks occur within a
"tabbed" page.  The mouse clicks work fine outside the page environment so
that the @{b}[use]@{ub}, @{b}[save]@{ub}, @{b}[save as]@{ub}, and @{b}[cancel]@{ub} gadgets work fine as do
the tabs at the top of the screen.  The problem with mouse clicks does not
effect string gadgets, either.

This means that under AmigaDOS 2.1, the @{" Viewer " link AEM-4600}, @{" ARexx " link AEM-4700}, and @{" Font " link AEM-4800}
pages of the @{" Configuration Setup " link AEM-4200} do not work nor does the @{b}[Printer
Setup]@{ub}, @{b}[Set Screen Mode]@{ub}, @{b}[Set Minimum Headers]@{ub}, or @{b}[Set Menu Flags]@{ub}
buttons on the @{" General " link AEM-4900} page.  The @{b}[CLR]@{ub}, @{b}[DEFAULT]@{ub}, @{b}[Set Password]@{ub} and
@{b}call file requester@{ub} buttons also do not work, but this version has
provided alternate key commands to activate these while editing strings.
(see @{" Editing String Entry Gadgets " link AEM-5400})

The @{b}Drag Select@{ub} option for message list will only work with @{b}AmigaDOS3.0@{ub}
or above.

                       @{b}@{u}Other ClassAct Restrictions@{uu}@{ub}

If you are using a Workbench screen that is restricted to 640 by 200
(@{b}HIRES@{ub}) with versions of the OS @{i}before 3.5@{ui}, you will find that there are
some portions the Configuration Setup Window that appear to be cut off.
All the gadgets on the Configuration Setup Window do work correctly, 
however.  @{b}This problem does not exist with OS 3.5@{ub}.

If you are using a @{b}HIRES@{ub} screen for your Workbench, you can make the
Configuration Setup Window fit correctly by using text overscan to 
increase your visable area.  This is not necessary with @{b}OS 3.5@{ub}.


                        @{b}@{u}System Addon Restrictions@{uu}@{ub}

While AEMail appears to work fine with a standard configured AMIGA, there
are some possible problems with @{b}system addons@{ub} that might not behave
correctly with @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

One such problem had been with hacks or commodities that moved a window to
the front when you clicked into it such as the @{b}Click-To-Front@{ub} commodity.
The folder window disappeared.  @{b}That problem has been corrected.@{ub}  Any
other hack or commodity that automatically brings the current window to
front either when you click on it or when you pass the cursor over it,
@{i}should work now@{ui}.  Please let me know if you are still having problems.

Another commodity that causes problems with @{b}AEMail@{ub} is one that
automatically activates the window under the mouse pointer (@{b}AutoPoint@{ub}).
Since @{b}AEMail@{ub} uses multiple windows, it controls which window is active at
any point in time.  It is not always the window under the mouse pointer
since that might not cause @{b}AEMail@{ub} to react properly.  As a result, if
you activate @{b}AutoPoint@{ub} while @{b}AEMail@{ub} is active, you will experience
flashing windows as @{b}AEMail@{ub} switches control away from the window under the
mouse pointer.

Other system @{i}configurations@{ui} may also cause problems with @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  If you
encounter one of these, please send me e-mail describing the problem and
what @{b}add-on@{ub} you were using.  If it is a public domain program, it would
be helpful if you included the program as an attached archive to your
message. (@{i}see@{ui} @{" composing a message " link AEM-6080}).


                           @{b}@{u}Other Considerations@{uu}@{ub}

When you call an editor that requires a stack size larger than the default
stack size and that program does not create it's own stack, you will have
to create a script for that editor and set the stack size from that
script.  Increasing the stack size of @{b}AEMail@{ub} @{i}will not work@{ui} because @{b}AEMail@{ub}
establishes it's own stack size and called programs do not inherit stack
size from the calling program.

If you are having problems with editors and stack size, you can use the
supplied script for @{b}CED@{ub} (@{b}s:AEMced.scr@{ub}) and modify it to your
specifications.  One warning, however, if you call a word processor you
will need to @{b}ALWAYS@{ub} save the file as ASCII and that program must be able
to accept an already existing ASCII file when it is called.

You can send me e-mail by using the @{" Address Book " link AEM-8500} @{i}Nickname@{ui} @{b}AEMAIL@{ub}.
(@{i}see@{ui} @{" Bug Reports and Suggestions " link AEM-9700})

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-2500 "REGISTRATION"

                           @{b}AEMail Registration@{ub}

@{b}AEMail is shareware.@{ub}  Versions prior to 1.15 were @{i}freeware@{ui}. A shareware 
fee of $30 is requested for @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  The shareware fee (@{b}@{u}US Funds only@{ub}@{uu}) 
should be sent to:

    @{b}John Zacharias
    10004 Vanguard Drive
    Sacramento, CA 95827
    USA@{ub}

You @{i}must@{ui} include your @{b}Real Name@{ub} and @{b}email address@{ub} with your remittance.
A handy form has been provided in the file @{b}registration.form@{ub} which you
can print out and use for this purpose.

The @{b}registration.form@{ub} has an icon which, if you double click on it, will
use the @{b}PrintFiles@{ub} program in your @{b}SYS:Tools@{ub} directory to print out the
registration form.

Your registration will be acknowledged by email that @{i}must be received by
@{b}AEMail@{ub}.@{ui}  @{b}AEMail version 2.30@{ub} does have several features that are not
implemented for un-registered users.

@{b}The features in AEMail 2.30 that are not available to un-registered users
are:@{ub}

    Ability to use multiple signature files.
    Ability to add user defined headers to a message.
    You will not be able to shrink/expand group displays in the Address
        Book displays.  The standard Address Book display will have
        expanded group displays and the Compose window address book
        display will have only the group header displayed.
    Enhanced speed on message display.
    Password protection for separate configurations.
    Filtering messages on "Other Message Hdrs".
    Filtering messages on the content of the message body.
    Certain ARexx commands (see @{" AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE " link AEM-9400} or consult the
        AEMail-ARexx.doc)
    Saving font changes.
    Saving function key and menu assignments for ARexx commands.
    Ability to disable the "Notification" message requester.

@{i}Future versions of AEMail may also have enhancements that will only be
available to registered users.@{ui}

The display speed is now the same for both registered and unregistered
users.  @{i}@{b}You may notice, however, that if you select a proportional font for
your message display, you may have a slower message display, especially if
the message contains lines that are too long to fit in the display window.@{ub}@{ui}

For the un-registered @{i}Freeware@{ui} version, permission is given to test and
evaluate the program in return for feedback on the use of the program and
reporting of any bugs encountered.

I do ask, however, that, in return for the use of this product, you inform me
of any suggestions you have and of any bugs that you encounter.  You can do
that by sending e-mail to me using the @{i}Nickname@{ui} @{b}AEMAIL@{ub} which can be found
in your @{" Address Book " link AEM-8500} when you first load @{b}AEMail@{ub}. (@{i}see also@{ui}
@{" Bug Reports and Suggestions " link AEM-9700})

@{b}AEMail@{ub} no longer automatically sends the special @{b}Notification@{ub} message
when you send your first message.  Instead, when you first load a new
version of @{b}AEMail@{ub}, a @{" special requester " link AEM-2510} will appear asking if you want to
send the notification message for notification of updates and giving you
the ability to select what information you want to send.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-2510 "NOTIFICATION REQUESTER"

                          @{b}Notification Requester@{ub}

When you first load a new version of @{b}AEMail@{ub}, a special requester will 
appear asking if you want to send a notification message for notification 
of updates and giving you the ability to select what information you want 
to send.  You can cancel this message, but if you do, the requester will 
appear each time you load @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  If you are a @{" registered " link AEM-2500} user and 
you cancel, you will be given the opportunity to suppress the message the next 
time you load @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  @{b}For unregistered users the requester will appear 
each time you load AEMail whether or not you send the notification or 
cancel.@{ub}

The requester looks like this:

  @{b}=======================================================================
  [o] Send AEMail Notification Request                                  |
  ====================================================================  |
  |  ---------- ---------                                             | |
  | | Identity | Options |                                            | | 
  | |          |_________|___________________________________________ | |
  ||                                                                 || |
  || Please complete if you want notification of updates sent to you || |
  ||                                                                 || |
  ||  Email Address: [ userid@domain                              ]  || |
  ||                                                                 || |
  ||        Version: [ 2.20         ] Serial Number: [nnnnnnnnn   ]  || |
  ||                                                                 || |
  || ----------------------Optional Information--------------------- || |
  |||                                                               ||| |
  |||    Name: [                                                  ] ||| |
  |||                                                               ||| |
  ||| Address: [                                                  ] ||| |
  |||                                                               ||| |
  |||    City: [             ] State: [         ]   Zip: [        ] ||| |
  |||                                                               ||| |
  ||| Country: [      ] [ ] Do not continue to show this on startup ||| |
  || --------------------------------------------------------------- || |
  | ----------------------------------------------------------------- |_|
  | [       Queue       ] [      Send Now      ] [      Cancel      ] |/|
  ======================================================================|@{ub}


The @{b}Email Address@{ub} will be filled in with information from your
configuration data, @{b}Version@{ub} by the current version number of @{b}AEMail@{ub}, and
@{b}Serial Number@{ub} by information your registration data.  If your version of
@{b}AEMail@{ub} is unregistered, the words @{b}UNREGISTERED@{ub} will appear in the Serial
Number.  The Version number and Serial Number can not be changed, but you
can change the email address.  @{b}All of this is required information.@{ub}

Below this is optional data although your name will be filled in with
either your @{b}real name@{ub} from the configuration data (@{i}if unregistered@{ui}) or the
name from your registration data.  You can clear or change this data if
you wish.  You can also add your address, city, state or province, zip or
postal code, and country.

At the bottom of the screen are three buttons: @{b}[Queue]@{ub}, @{b}[Send Now]@{ub}, and
@{b}[Cancel]@{ub}.  @{b}[Queue]@{ub} will queue the notification message in the @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder,
@{b}[Send Now]@{ub} will send the notification message immediately provided you are
connected to the Internet.  If you are not connected, @{b}[Send Now]@{ub} will
queue the message.  @{b}[Cancel]@{ub} will cancel the notification requester unless
@{b}"Do not continue to show this on startup"@{ub} is checked.  @{i}Unregistered users
will not be able to check this item@{ui} and the notification request will
continue to appear when you startup @{b}AEMail@{ub} regardless of whether you
have previously queued or sent the request.  However you can cancel it at
any time.  The close gadget at the top of the window will act the same as
@{b}[Cancel]@{ub}.

The @{b}Options page@{ub} (indicated by the @{b}Options@{ub} tab) will send optional
information about your configuration if you so desire.  It is primarily to
provide me with information about your setup in the event you have
problems using @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  The @{b}Options page@{ub} looks like this:


  @{b}=======================================================================
  [o] Send AEMail Notification Request                                  |
  ====================================================================  |
  |  ---------- ---------                                             | |
  | | Identity | Options |                                            | |
  | |__________|         |___________________________________________ | |
  ||                                                                 || |
  || [ ] POP Server is: @{ub}@{i}your-POP-Server-name@{ui}@{b}                         || |
  ||                                                                 || |
  || [ ] SMTP Server is: @{ub}@{i}your-SMTP-Server-name@{ui}@{b}                       || |
  ||                                                                 || |
  || [ ] SMTP Domain Name is: @{ub}@{i}your-domain-name@{ui}@{b}                       || |
  ||                                                                 || |
  || [ ] Editor Call is: @{ub}@{i}the-call-line-for-your-editor@{ui}@{b}               || |
  ||                                                                 || |
  || [ ] Exec Version is: @{ub}@{i}exec-version-number@{ui}@{b}                        || |
  ||                                                                 || |
  || [ ] Display ID is: @{ub}@{i}display-ID-for-your-screen-mode@{ui}@{b}              || |
  ||                                                                 || |
  || [ ] Current Config file is: @{ub}@{i}path-and-name-of-your-config-file@{ui}@{b}   || |
  ||                                                                 || |
  || [ ] Mail Directory is: @{ub}@{i}path-to-your-mail-directory@{ui}@{b}              || |
  ||                                                                 || |
  | ----------------------------------------------------------------- |_|
  | [       Queue       ] [      Send Now      ] [      Cancel      ] |/|
  ======================================================================|@{ub}


Checkmark those items you want sent with the notification message.
Perhaps the most inmportant items are your @{b}Editor Call@{ub} (if you are having
problems with your editor), the @{b}Exec Version@{ub}, and the @{b}Display ID@{ub}.
However, you do not have to send any of this information.

When the notification message is received your email address is placed in
a database for informing you of updates.  @{i}If you do not want to be so
informed, cancel and do not send the notification message or send email to
@{b}AEMail@{ub} to that effect and your name will be removed from the database.@{ui}

@{i}Please note@{ui} that the notification message requester will appear when you
upgrade to a new version of @{b}AEMail@{ub} even though you may have previously
sent a notification message for an earlier version.  This lets us know
which version you are using.  Some of the data in future notification
messages may also change to help give feedback on how @{b}AEMail@{ub} is being used 
and what setup you are using.

Also, if you are using multiple @{" configuration files " link AEM-9110}, a separate
notification message will appear the first time you you load any
particular configuration.  If you re-install @{b}AEMail@{ub} for any reason you may
have an additional Notification message request.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-3000 "INSTALLATION"

                          @{b}INSTALLATION OF AEMail@{ub}

The @{b}AEMail Install Script@{ub} uses the @{b}Installer@{ub} program first provided by
Commodore and later revised by @{b}Amiga Technologies@{ub}.  You should use the
Install_AEMail script to install @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  It is @{b}not@{ub} recommended that you
attempt to install AEMail by hand since some actions are necessary through
the install script.  @{i}This is especially true if you are attempting to
install a registered version of @{b}AEMail@{ub}!@{ui}

    @{b}Installer and Installer project icon
    (c) Copyright 1995-96 Escom AG.  All Rights Reserved.
    Reproduced and distributed under license from Escom AG.

    INSTALLER SOFTWARE IS PROVIDED "AS-IS" AND SUBJECT TO CHANGE;
    NO WARRANTIES ARE MADE.  ALL USE IS AT YOUR OWN RISK.  NO LIABILITY
    OR RESPONSIBILITY IS ASSUMED.@{ub}

Starting with Version 2.00 of @{b}AEMail@{ub}, the Installation script was
completely re-written from previous versions.  You can now define multiple
users with the install script and use the install script to add or update
users as well as delete users (Version 2.30 and above).

The script was further modified for Version 2.20 to place additional edits
when naming configuration files and your mail directory.  The script also
installs the @{b}ClassAct@{ub} classes required by @{b}AEMail@{ub} if you are installing with 
an OS prior to 3.5.  If you are installing to @{b}OS 3.5@{ub}, it is not necessary 
to install the @{b}ClassAct@{ub} classes since they are built into the OS.

In OS versions prior to 3.5 you will be asked if you want to install
@{b}ClassAct@{ub}.  It is not necessary to do this if you are already have @{b}ClassAct@{ub}
installed on your system (either by a previous @{b}AEMail@{ub} install or with
another program using @{b}ClassAct@{ub}).

Other changes to the @{b}Version 2.20@{ub} installation script include:

    Changing @{b}RAM:@{ub} to @{b}T:@{ub} for saving temporary files.  On most Amigas, @{b}T:@{ub} is
    in @{b}RAM:@{ub}  However, in some low memory situations, a user may assign @{b}T:@{ub}
    to a hard drive.  By changing @{b}RAM:@{ub} to @{b}T:@{ub}, users with low memory
    conditions can still install @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

    If you have previously installed a version of @{b}AEMail 2.00@{ub} or above, you
    can bypass the @{b}Configuring Users@{ub} portion of the script as long as you
    do not want to add to your users or update a user.

Further changes to the @{b}Version 2.30@{ub} installation script include:

    The ability to @{b}delete@{ub} users.

    The installation script now asks what type of installation you are
    performing: @{b}a demo version, a previously registered version, or a new
    registered version@{ub}.

Please read these instructions before attempting to install @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

If you have the diskette version of @{b}AEMail@{ub}, you will find that it is now a
@{b}two@{ub} disk set.  Place @{b}Disk_1@{ub} in your drive to start the installation.  At
the appropriate time you will be asked to insert @{b}AEMail_V2.30-Disk_2@{ub}.

If you are installing from a version obtained over the Internet or from the
@{b}AEMail@{ub} CD-ROM, you will not get this message.

To install @{b}AEMail@{ub} simply double click on the @{b}Install_AEMail icon@{ub}.  The
install script provides two user levels that the user can choose:

    @{i}Intermediate@{ui}    (control of configuration parameters only)
    @{i}Expert@{ui}          (control of configuration and where files are placed)

See below for actions that are different between the two user levels.

The first thing that the Install script will ask is what type of
installation you are performing:

    @{b}A Demo Version
    A Previously Registered Version
    A New Registered Version@{ub}

If you are installing a @{b}new registered version@{ub} you will need a @{b}key code@{ub}
which was provided when you purchased @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  You will not be able to
continue with the installation if you can not provide the correct key code.
In this event you should re-install using the @{b}Demo Version@{ub} and contact the
author at @{b}jzachar@calweb.com@{ub} for further instructions.

Likewise, if you are installing a @{b}previously registered version@{ub}, the
installion script will attempt to locate your registration information in a
file called @{b}.registration@{ub} in you main @{b}AEMail@{ub} program directory.  If your
previous installed version was @{b}prior to 2.00@{ub}, it will look for the
registration file in @{b}AEMail:.registration@{ub}.  If it can't be found you will
be instructed to install at the @{b}Demo Version@{ub} level and to contact
@{b}jzachar@calweb.com@{ub} for further instructions.  @{i}Before doing that, however,
execute your newly installed @{b}AEMail@{ub} and see if it is a registered version.@{ui}

The Install script then makes an attempt to determine which TCP/IP stack 
that you have installed.  This controls which defaults will be taken.  The 
way the install scripts knows which TCP/IP stacks are present is as follows
(@{i}you must have installed the particular stack before installing @{b}AEMail@{ub}@{uu}):

    @{b}AmiTCP:@{ub}     This is controlled by the presence of the @{b}AmiTCP:@{ub} assign
                statement and the presence of the @{b}AmiTCP:bin@{ub} drawer.  The
                @{b}AmiTCP:@{ub}  assignment and the @{b}AmiTCP:bin@{ub} drawer were
                automatically created when you installed AmiTCP.

    @{b}Miami:@{ub}      This is controlled by the presence of the @{b}Miami:@{ub} assign
                statement.  When you installed Miami you should have let
                the install create the @{b}Miami:@{ub} assign.  This was only
                available under later versions of @{b}Maimi@{ub}.

                While the @{b}Miami:@{ub} assign is not an absolute requirement
                if you are using @{b}Miami@{ub}, it is required if you intend
                to use the supplied @{b}startnet.miami@{ub} script without
                modification.  This script locates @{b}Miami@{ub} with @{b}Miami:Miami@{ub}
                which depends on the @{b}Miami@{ub} assign.  If the @{b}Miami@{ub} assign is
                not present you would have to modify the script to use the
                full path name of where @{b}Miami@{ub} is located.

    @{b}TermiteTCP:@{ub} This is controlled by the presence of the @{b}TermiteTCP.prefs@{ub}
                envronomental variable.  Also, if you want to pick up
                some of the other @{b}TermiteTCP@{ub} variables, such as email
                address, you must have run @{b}TermiteTCP@{ub} prior to installing
                @{b}AEMail@{ub} (@{i}TermiteTCP does not have to be online, however@{ui}).

The install script will ask you to verify which TCP/IP stack you are using.
A fourth alternative @{b}Other@{ub} is provided if you have another TCP/IP stack
or you have not as yet installed your chosen stack software.

If you have multiple stacks installed, the initial stack selection is made
in this priority:

    @{b}Miami
    AmiTCP
    Termite-TCP@{ub}

You can, of course, change this with the requester.

If you select the @{b}Intermediate@{ub} user level, the following actions will be
taken:

    If you have previously installed @{b}AEMail@{ub} with a version 1.10 or greater,
        the install script will determine where @{b}AEMail@{ub} was previously
        installed from the @{b}ENV:AEMail_Dir@{ub} environmental variable.

    If you have @{b}not@{ub} previously installed @{b}AEMail@{ub} or you are updating from
        an @{b}AEMail@{ub} version prior to 1.10, the @{b}AEMail@{ub} executable file will be
        placed in @{b}AmiTCP:bin@{ub} if the @{b}AmiTCP@{ub} stack was selected or, if one of
        the other stacks was selected, on the largest partition on your
        hard drive.

        @{b}Note:@{ub} No special directory will be created if @{b}AmiTCP@{ub} was
        selected, otherwise a directory called @{b}AEMail@{ub} will be created
        for containing the @{b}AEMail@{ub} executable.  When the installation
        script terminates it will tell you where it placed the @{b}AEMail@{ub}
        executable.

        The reason that @{b}AEMail@{ub} is placed in the @{b}AmiTCP:bin@{ub} drawer if the
        @{b}AmiTCP:@{ub} assignment is present and you selected @{b}AmiTCP@{ub} as your
        TCP/IP stack, is that the @{b}startnet@{ub} and @{b}stopnet@{ub} scripts for
        @{b}AmiTCP@{ub} should be in the same directory that contains @{b}AEMail@{ub} if they
        are to work without modification.  The @{b}AmiTCP@{ub} installation places
        these scripts in the @{b}AmiTCP:bin@{ub} drawer.

    For OS Versions prior to 3.5, the @{b}ClassAct@{ub} classes will be normally
        installed to your @{b}SYS:Classes drawer.@{ub}  You will be asked if you
        want the 020 optimized version of the classes.  If you are running
        on an 020 or greater processor, reply @{b}yes@{ub}.  With @{b}OS 3.5@{ub}, the
        @{b}ClassAct@{ub} classes will have been installed when the OS was 
        installed.

    The documentation files that you want copied will be copied to a drawer
        called @{b}documentation@{ub} in the drawer which contains the @{b}AEMail@{ub}
        executable.

    A special @{b}ARexx documentation@{ub} file (which is also part of the
        @{b}AEMail.doc@{ub} and @{b}AEMail.guide@{ub} files), is placed in a drawer called
        @{b}ARexx@{ub} in the drawer which contains the @{b}AEMail@{ub} executable.  @{b}This
        drawer will also contain some sample ARexx scripts.@{ub}

    If you want the @{b}AEMail.readme@{ub} file, it will be copied to the directory
        containing your @{b}AEMail@{ub} executable.

    The @{b}ARexx@{ub} scripts @{b}StartNet.Miami@{ub} and @{b}StopNet.Miami@{ub} will be copied to
        the directory containing your @{b}AEMail@{ub} executable providing they are
        not already there.  This prevents copying over scripts that may
        have been previously modified.

    A handy registration form called @{b}registration.form@{ub} will be available
        in your main @{b}AEMail@{ub} directory.  It has an icon which, if you double
        click on it, will use the @{b}PrintFiles@{ub} program in your @{b}SYS:Tools@{ub}
        directory to print out the registration form.

    You will be asked how many users you want configured.  See the section
        below on @{b}Configuring Users@{ub} to see what happens here.

    If you are updating a user, you can change their mail directory.
        However, if you are creating a new mail directory rather than using
        an existing one,  you will start out with a blank address book and
        empty standard folders.

    If you are running under AmigaDos 3.0 or greater, the supplied
        @{" mailcap " link AEM-9100} file will be copied to the mail directory for each user
        unless a @{b}mailcap@{ub} file already exists in that user's mail directory.
        No @{b}mailcap@{ub} file will be copied if one already exists in the user's
        mail directory or if you are using AmigaDos 2.1.

    An @{b}AEMAIL2:@{ub} assign statement pointing to the drawer containing your
        @{b}AEMail@{ub} executable will automatically be placed in your
        @{b}S:User-Startup@{ub} file.

    An @{b}ASSIGN C: SYS:REXXC ADD@{ub} will also be added to your @{b}s:User-Startup@{ub}
        file to provide a path to your @{b}ARexx@{ub} commands.

The following additional capabilities are provided when you install at the
@{b}Expert@{ub} level:

    You will be able to choose which directory @{b}AEMail@{ub} will be installed in.
        If you are installing @{b}AEMail for first time, this may be desireable
        rather than installing in the largest partition on your hard drive.
        The default directory that is selected will be the one that would
        have been selected under the @{b}Intermediate@{ub} level.

    You will be able to choose which directory you wish to install your
        @{b}Documentation@{ub} files in.  @{b}WARNING:@{ub} for the @{" Help " link AEM-5900} function to properly
        work, the @{b}AEMail.guide@{ub} file must be in the @{b}documentation@{ub} drawer
        within the drawer which contains the @{b}AEMail@{ub} executable.  You can
        change the location of the @{b}.guide@{ub} file by using the @{" HELP= " link AEM-4126} Tool
        Type.  @{b}This must be done manually.@{ub}  The Install script @{b}WILL NOT@{ub} set
        this tool type.

    You will be able to choose which directory you wish to install your
        @{b}ARexx@{ub} files in.  You might want to select the @{b}Rexx:@{ub} directory for
        this so that the supplied @{b}ARexx@{ub} scripts become immediately
        available.

    If you want a @{b}mailcap@{ub} file other than the one provided, you can select
        where you want this file copied from.  If you want to use the
        alternate mailcap provided in the @{b}ARexx@{ub} drawer for displaying @{b}HTML@{ub}
        documents with your browser, you could specify the @{b}AEMail ARexx@{ub}
        drawer for the source of the @{b}mailcap@{ub}.

As noted above, the default drawer in which your documentation is placed is
a drawer called @{b}Documentation@{ub} in the drawer containing your @{b}AEMail@{ub}
executable.  This is different from versions prior to 1.50 where the
documentation files were placed in the same drawer as the @{b}AEMail@{ub}
executable.  Documentation files located in the drawer containing your
@{b}AEMail@{ub} executable @{b}WILL BE@{ub} deleted by the installation script.  If you want
these retained you will have to re-name or save them yourself.

Towards the beginning of the script, after you have identified your TCP/IP
stack, the script will determine if you have already installed the current
version of @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  If you have, you will be asked if you want to do a @{b}Full
Install@{ub} or want to add, delete and/or update users.  If you just want to 
add, delete or update users, you will go immediately to the @{b}Configuring 
Users@{ub} section described below.


                             @{b}Configuring Users@{ub}

You can set up multiple users of @{b}AEMail@{ub} from the Install Script.  Each user
will be provided a @{b}Project Icon@{ub} named as the user wishes.  This project
icon will point to the @{b}AEMail@{ub} executable and will be created with certain
required @{" Tool Types " link AEM-4100} as @{" configuration " link AEM-4000} items.  The Project icons will be
created with the @{b}Install_AEMail@{ub} script.

If you have previously installed a version of @{b}AEMail 2.00@{ub} or above, you
have already established your users.  In this situation all of the users
that have been previously defined will be displayed and you will be asked
if you want to @{b}Add/Delete/Update Users@{ub} or @{b}Accept Current Users@{ub}.  If you
reply with @{b}Accept Current Users@{ub}, the user configuration section will be
bypassed.

If you have not installed @{b}AEMail@{ub} previously or your previously installed
version is prior to 2.00, you will be asked how many users with different
email addresses you wish to configure @{b}AEMail@{ub} for.  You must have at least
one user.  Certain questions will then be asked for each user so that
appropriate @{b}Project@{ub} icons can be created with the appropriate @{b}Tool Types@{ub}.

If you already have established users and replied @{b}Add/Delete/Update Users@{ub}
you will first be asked if you want to delete any users.  If you do, your
existing users will be displayed and you can select the one you want to
delete.

The script will determine the @{b}Configuration@{ub} file used by the user you want
deleted.  It will display a requester asking if you want to delete this
configuration file.  Unless you want to use this configuration file again,
you will want to delete it.

The script will then determine the @{b}Mail directory@{ub} for the user you want
deleted.  Again it will ask if you want this mail directory deleted.  If
the mail directory is being used by another user you should not delete it.

After that user is deleted you will be asked if you want to delete
another user. If you don't, you will then be asked how many users you want
to add or update.  You can reply 0 to this message which will then bypass
establishing or changing any users.

As each user is processed you will get a message asking you to select the
name of the icon you want your user to have.  Since you can both create a
new user or update an existing user, you will be present with a list of
choices that looks like this:

    @{b}Create new icon
    name-of-previously-defined-user-1
    name-of-previously-defined-user-2
    ...........
    name-of-previously-defined-user-n@{ub}

Only the names of previously defined users will appear in this list.  If
you select any of the users or the @{b}Create new icon@{ub} entry you will get a
message that asks you to enter (@{i}or confirm@{ui}) the name of the user (icon
name) that you want the user to have.  When you select @{b}Create new icon@{ub} a
default name will be used that will be one of the following:

    @{b}AEMail_User_1
    AEMail_User_2
    AEMail_User_3
    ...........

    AEMail_User_n@{ub}

You can change the name or use the one provided.  You will then be told if
the icon already exists or not and asked to confirm that this is the
correct name.  If you are editing a previously created icon, that icon, of
course will exist.  You will be given an opportunity to re-enter the name
if you decide it is wrong.

If you are updating from a previous version of @{b}AEMail@{ub} (before @{b}2.00@{ub}), you 
will already have a @{b}Tool Icon@{ub} for @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  If you select @{b}"AEMail"@{ub} as the 
name, the @{b}Tool Icon@{ub} will be turned into a @{b}Project Icon@{ub} for your primary 
user and all existing @{b}Tool Types@{ub} will be obtained as default values.  If 
you choose to change the name of the icon, the @{b}"AEMail" tool icon@{ub} will 
remain.

@{b}@{u}WARNING@{uu}@{ub}:  Do not try to @{b}DELETE@{ub} any icon called @{b}"AEMail"@{ub} (tool or project)
@{b}AFTER@{ub} you have installed @{b}AEMail@{ub} using the workbench @{b}Icons/Delete...@{ub}  menu
item.  This will delete the @{b}AEMail@{ub} executable as well.  If you don't want
the @{b}"AEMail"@{ub} icon it is best to delete it @{b}BEFORE@{ub} installing @{b}AEMail@{ub} or use
the delete function described above to delete the icon.
.

The @{b}@{u}required@{uu} Tool Types@{ub} that will be created for each user's @{b}Project Icon@{ub}
are:

    @{b}CONFIG=
    MAIL_DIR=
    PASSPROTECT=YES@{ub}

The @{b}CONFIG=@{ub} Tool Type points to the configuration file for that user.  This
configuration file must be unique for each user.  Under both install
options (@{b}Intermediate@{ub} and @{b}Expert@{ub}), a file requester will appear for you to
select the configuration file name.  If you are not updating an existing
user, this configuration file will not exist so you can enter whatever you
like (providing a file with the same name is not present).  You can select
any drawer, but either the drawer containing the @{b}AEMail@{ub} executable or the
@{b}s:@{ub} directory are recommended.

If you start @{b}AEMail@{ub} from the shell without any arguments, you will need to
name your primary user's configuration file @{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub}.

If you are doing a full install and you have a @{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub} file, this
file will automatically be selected as your default configuration file for your
first user provided no configuration file was previous specified in the
@{b}AEMail@{ub} Tool Types.  If you install at the @{b}Expert@{ub} level, you will be
able to copy and/or rename this file to another location.

The @{b}MAIL_DIR=@{ub} Tool Type is used to specify where your mail directory is
located.  In versions of @{b}AEMail@{ub} prior to 2.00, the @{b}AEMail:@{ub} assign was used 
to specify the mail directory location and the Tool Type was only used if 
the mail directory differed from that.  This is no longer the case.  With 
version 2.00 and above, the @{b}AEMail: ASSIGN@{ub} statement is no longer used, 
the mail directory will always be specified by the @{b}MAIL_DIR=@{ub} Tool Type. 
After installing a user you can change their mail directory by either 
changing this @{b}Tool Type@{ub} or by running the Installation script again 
to update this user.

If you are updating from a version of @{b}AEMail@{ub} prior to 2.00, however, the
@{b}AEMail ASSIGN@{ub} will be used to specify the default @{b}MAIL_DIR@{ub} unless a
@{b}MAIL_DIR=@{ub} Tool Type was previously specified in an updated icon.

For new users, you will be given an opportunity to accept the default as
the mail directory or specify a new mail directory location for each user.
The @{b}MAIL_DIR=@{ub} does not have to be unique to each user.  Two or more users
can share the same mail directory.  If the mail directory you specify is
not present, it will be created.

The @{b}PASSPROTECT=YES@{ub} Tool Type is used to password protect the mail
directory for a particular user.  You will be told whether the mail file is
currently password protected or not and then be asked if you want to
password protect the mail directory for this particular user.  If the file
was previously password protected, you can turn that feature off by replying
@{b}No@{ub}.  To continue password protection you will have to reply @{b}yes@{ub}.  The
password that is used to password protect the directory is the same one
that is used to access the @{b}POP@{ub} server by that particular user.

Previously an @{b}INTERLACE=YES@{ub} Tool Type was used to specify the screen mode
that @{b}AEMail@{ub} would initially open on.  This Tool Type is now obsolete.
@{b}AEMail@{ub} will now initially open on whatever screen mode is set for your
Workbench screen.  After initially loading @{b}AEMail@{ub}, you can change the
screen mode through the @{" Configuration Edit " link AEM-7101} screen, @{" General " link AEM-4900} page.

You will also be able to provide additional configuration data for each
user that will be stored in the Tool Types parameters of the @{b}AEMail Project@{ub}
icon for that user.  If the user has an existing @{" Configuration " link AEM-9110} file, you
will be asked if you want to re-configure this user's data.  If you do, the
existing configuration file will be renamed with @{b}.old@{ub} appended to it.  If
the user does not have an existing configuration file, you will be asked if
you want to configure now or wait until @{b}AEMail@{ub} is first loaded.

Since you can change the configuration data from @{b}AEMail@{ub}, the @{b}Configuration@{ub}
file always takes precedence over the @{b}Tool Types@{ub}.  The only exceptions to
this are the name of the configuration file (@{b}CONFIG=@{ub}) and the name of the
mail directory (@{b}MAIL_DIR=@{ub}).  That is why any existing configuration file
is renamed to avoid resetting the configuration data when @{b}AEMail@{ub} is first
loaded.

Certain configuration parameters must be provided before @{b}AEMail@{ub} will run.
These configuration parameters are provided either by @{b}Tool Types@{ub} in the
@{b}AEMail@{ub} icon or through a special configuration setup when you first run
@{b}AEMail@{ub} and saved in the user's configuration file.

If these parameters are not provided by Tool Types (through the
installation script) or by an existing configuration file, the
@{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200} will be displayed upon the initial startup of 
@{b}AEMail@{ub}.  You can not proceed beyond this configuration setup until certain 
required configuration parameters are provided.  The absolute minimum 
configuration parameters that must be provided are:

    @{b}POP3 UserID
    Password
    Your email Address
    POP Server Name
    SMTP Server Name
    Domain Name
    Edit Call@{ub}

If you decide to configure using @{b}Tool Types@{ub}, the installation script will
try to automatically configure certain items to default values.  These
include the switch for deleting mail from your POP Server once it has been
transferred to your Amiga and the switch for stripping duplicate messages.
The edit call will default to @{b}c:ed@{ub} and will open the editor on the
Workbench.  Also, if you have your TCP/IP stack @{b}loaded@{ub} (@{i}not necessarily
on-line@{ui}), it will obtain certain default items from environmental variables
stored by the stack software.

The installation script will allow you to provide additional configuration
parameters as Tool Types in your @{b}AEMail@{ub} icon or to change the default ones.

A @{b}POP Server name@{ub} and a @{b}SMTP Server name@{ub} must be provided.  However, if
they are missing AND, @{i}if the Domain Name has been specified@{ui}, default
values will also be assigned to these items.  These default values will
prepend @{b}POP.@{ub} to the domain name for the POP server and @{b}SMTP.@{ub} to the
domain name for the SMTP Server as defaults.  @{b}Please note:@{ub}  these may @{b}@{u}NOT@{uu}@{ub}
be correct for your POP and SMTP servers.  If they are not, you will have
to change these items with the installation script.  Some Internet Service
Providers use @{b}mail.@{ub} prepended to the domain server for both the POP and
SMTP servers.

If you have a problem understanding what should be entered with the
install, use the @{b}HELP@{ub} function of the Install script.  Here is some of the
help information from the script:

  @{b}"The @{i}domain name@{ui} is usually the part of your e-mail address that follows"
  "the '@' sign.  If something else is required by your Internet Provider,"
  "provide it here."

  "As an example, my email address is:"

        "jzachar@calweb.com"

  "The domain name for my Internet provider is therefor 'calweb.com'."@{ub}


  @{b}"@{i}POP Server@{ui}.  POP stands for 'Post Office Protocol' and your "
  "POP Server is the name assigned to the host computer that holds "
  "your Internet mail.  Normally this would be 'pop.' or 'mail.' "
  "prepended to your Domain name."

  "Consult your Internet provider if the POP Server is called "
  "something other than the above."@{ub}


  @{b}"@{i}SMTP Server@{ui}.  SMTP stands for 'Simple Mail Transfer Protocol' and "
  "your SMTP server is the name assigned to the host computer that "
  "sends your Internet mail.  Normally this would be 'smtp.' or 'mail.' "
  "prepended to your Domain name"

  "Consult your Internet provider if the SMTP Server is called "
  "something other than the above."@{ub}


If you have installed and ran your TCP/IP stack before you installing
@{b}AEMail@{ub}, the only configuration parameter you may have to provide is your
password.  If you are using @{b}TermiteTCP@{ub}, the POP3 UserID and the SMTP Domain
Name are extracted from the email address that you gave @{b}TermiteTCP@{ub}.  Other
stacks provide environmental variables to store this information.  If these
are not the correct values you will have to change them in either with the
Installation script or through the @{" Identity " link AEM-4300} page of the @{" Configuration " link AEM-4200}
screen.

One of the things that is needed to run @{b}AEMail@{ub} is an editor.  By default
@{b}AEMail@{ub} will use the AmigaDOS editor, @{b}ed@{ub}, which comes with all Amigas.
However, you can change this through the install to any editor that you
want provided that you have specified that you want to configure @{b}AEMail@{ub}
when you do the install.


                           @{b}Other Considerations@{ub}


If you are using @{b}Miami@{ub} as your TCP/IP software, special @{b}startnet.miami@{ub} and
@{b}stopnet.miami@{ub} scripts have been provided with the install of @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  If
you select Miami as your TCP/IP stack and the Miami assign is present, the
install script assumes the @{b}Miami@{ub} startnet and stopnet scripts should be
used.

If you are using @{b}AmiTCP@{ub}, that software provides its own @{b}StartNet@{ub} and
@{b}StopNet@{ub} scripts.  They are usually in your @{b}AmiTCP:bin@{ub} directory.  It is
recommended that you place @{b}AEMail@{ub} in the same directory that contains these
AmiTCP StartNet and StopNet scripts, although this is not an absolute
requirement.  If @{b}AEMail@{ub} is placed in a different directory, you might have
to modify these scripts to work properly.  If the directory containing your
StartNet or StopNet scripts is @{b}@{u}NOT@{uu}@{ub} the @{b}AmiTCP:bin@{ub} directory or the scripts
have names different from @{b}startnet@{ub} or @{b}stopnet@{ub}, you will have to change
the default values for the @{" STARTNET= " link AEM-4116} and @{" STOPNET= " link AEM-4117} tool types.  You can do
that with the installation script.

If you are using @{b}TermiteTCP@{ub}, there are no @{b}Start Net@{ub} or @{b}Stop Net@{ub} scripts.

@{b}@{u}SPECIAL NOTE FOR MIAMI USERS:@{uu}@{ub}  In the @{b}TCP/IP Settings@{ub} page on @{b}Miami@{ub}, the
@{b}Down when Offline@{ub} item should be checked and the settings @{b}SAVED@{ub}.  If this
item is not checked, it will take AEMail 80 seconds to determine that @{b}Miami@{ub}
is offline if @{b}Miami@{ub} is loaded but not online.

@{b}WARNING:@{ub}  If you are updating and you change the mail directory for a
specific user, you will lose all previous @{b}folder@{ub} configuration data.  You
might also lose your registration information if you are a registered user.
In versions prior to 2.00, the registration information was stored in your
mail directory.  Version 2.00 and later stores it in the @{b}AEMail@{ub} program
directory.  The installation script will attempt to copy this information
from the mail directory to the program directory.  If the installation
script can not find your old mail directory (usually by the @{b}AEMail:@{ub} assign
statement, you will need to copy this data yourself from your old
mail directory to the new mail directory.

The mail directory can start out empty.  The @{b}AEMail@{ub} program will generate
any necessary configuration and support files required.  The mail directory
directory can be anywhere on any one of your hard drive partitions (or on a
floppy or other read/writable media); it does not have to be in any
specific directory; but it must be mounted when you execute @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

As stated above, you will need a @{" mailcap " link AEM-9100} file if you want to display MIME
mail attachments.  A sample @{b}mailcap@{ub} file is provided on the @{b}AEMail@{ub} program
disk which uses @{b}MultiView@{ub} to display audio, images, and video content types
provided that you have the appropriate datatypes loaded into your system.
This, of course, requires AmigaDos 3.0 or higher.  If you are using
AmigaDos 2.1, the mailcap file needs to be modified to reflect the display
programs that you want.  You can do this with the @{" Viewer " link AEM-4600} page of the
@{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

If you are running under AmigaDos 3.0 or higher, the installation script
will automatically move the @{" supplied mailcap " link AEM-9101} file to the mail directory
for each user unless a @{b}mailcap@{ub} file already exists there or unless you
specified a different location for a pre-existing @{b}mailcap@{ub} file (@{b}Expert@{ub}
level only).

A special @{b}mailcap@{ub} file is provided in the @{b}ARexx@{ub} drawer to allow you to
display @{b}HTML@{ub} attachments with your browser.  If you wish to use this
feature you will have to copy the mailcap file in the @{b}ARexx@{ub} drawer to your
mail directory.  This can be done with the installation script at the
@{b}Expert@{ub} level.  Read the @{b}html.readme@{ub} file in the @{b}ARexx@{ub} drawer for details of
this special mailcap file.

The @{b}mailcap@{ub} file can also be created or edited online with @{b}AEMail@{ub} through
the @{b}Viewer@{ub} page of the @{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub}.

@{b}AEMail@{ub} gets the @{i}current time zone@{ui} from either the @{b}locale.prefs@{ub} file that
is part of AmigaDos or the @{b}tz@{ub} @{i}envronmental variable@{ui}.  See
@{" Handling of Time Zones " link AEM-3100} for further information on this.

When the installation script terminates it will store the directory in
which it placed @{b}AEMail@{ub} in the Environmental variable @{b}AEMail_dir@{ub}.  It also
creates an assign statement in your User Startup for the @{b}AEMail @{u}program@{uu}@{ub}
directory called @{b}AEMail2:@{ub}.  Starting with version 2.00 it will also store
the version number of the current @{b}AEMail@{ub} in the environmental variable
@{b}AEMail_Ver@{ub}.  This facilitates updating to future releases of @{b}AEMail@{ub}.
The version 1.30 and later installation scripts, at all installation
levels, will look for the @{b}AEMail_dir@{ub} Environmental variable to try to
determine where to place @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-3100 "TIME ZONES"

                     @{b}Setting the Time Zone for AEMail@{ub}

@{b}AEMail@{ub} will handle time zones in both full hour and half hour increments.
@{b}AEMail@{ub} uses either the @{i}tz@{ui} environmental variable, a special @{i}aem_tz@{ui}
environomental variable, or the @{i}locale.prefs@{ui} file that is part of
@{b}AmigaDos@{ub} to determine your local time zone.  The @{i}locale.prefs@{ui} file will
only allow for full hour time zone offsets.  You can use the @{i}tz@{ui}
environmental variable for half hour time zones, but, if this variable
is used by other programs in your system it is suggested that you use
the @{i}aem_tz@{ui} variable instead.

To set the time zone in the @{i}locale.prefs@{ui} file, execute the @{b}Locale@{ub}
program under your @{b}Prefs@{ub} directory by double clicking on the @{b}Locale@{ub} icon.
At the bottom right of the @{b}Locale Preferences@{ub} window you will see a world
map with a white line through it that indicates the time zone that you are
in.  To change this, click on the country you are in.  The white line will
move to that position and the Time Zone heading at the top of the map will
reflect the time zone offset for your part of the world.  Then click on
the @{b}[Save]@{ub} gadget at the bottom of the window.

Currently @{b}AEMail@{ub} first looks for the environmental variables @{i}aem_tz@{ui} or
@{i}tz@{ui}.  The format for @{i}tz@{ui} is dictated by @{b}SAS_C@{ub} and should be @{i}@{b}aaabbbccc@{ui}@{ub}
where @{i}aaa@{ui} is the abbreviation for local standard time, @{i}bbb@{ui} is the offset
in hours from GMT (-11 to 12) which is SUBTRACTED from GMT to get the
local standard time.  @{i}ccc@{ui} is the abbreviation for local daylight savings
time or @{i}summer time@{ui} (in the United Kingdom or Europe).  If the time zone
has daylight savings time this should be present even if daylight savings
time is not currently in effect (@{i}contrary to the specification for @{b}Tz@{ub}
for the SAS-C compiler@{ui}).  @{b}AEMail@{ub} automatically determines when DST or
@{i}Summer Time@{ui} is in effect.

@{b}AEMail@{ub} also recognizes an alternate form of @{i}tz@{ui} where @{i}aaa@{ui} and @{i}ccc@{ui} can be
abreviations longer than 3 characters.  This is desireable in some
European countries.  AEMail will also recognize time zones in increments
of one half hour.  To specify an half hour time zone, specify it as + or
- @{b}hhmm@{ub}.  As an example:  +230 would specify a time zone in which 2 and a
half hours are SUBTRACTED from GMT.

You can enter the above with the @{i}tz@{ui} environmental variable, but since
this variable might be used with other programs in it's strict sense, an
alternate environmental variable has been provided called @{i}aem_tz@{ui}.

If @{i}aem_tz@{ui} is present it will take precedence over @{i}tz@{ui}.

If the @{i}tz@{ui} or @{i}aem_tz@{ui} environmental variables are not present,
the system then attempts to get the time zone offset from the
@{i}locale.prefs@{ui} file.  Only the time zone offset is present in this
file.  The abbreviations for local standard time and daylight savings
time are obtained from a table that is by no means complete.  Only the
time zone abbreviations for the United States, Canada, and the United
Kingdom are contained in this table, so one of the environmental variables
is preferred.

if neither the @{i}tz@{ui} nor @{i}aem_tz@{ui} environmental variables nor the
@{i}locale.prefs@{ui} file are present, the system defaults to @{b}CST@{ub} with an
offset of @{b}6@{ub}.

@{b}@{u}NOTE:@{uu}@{ub} the standard header in an email message has the time zone offset sign
reversed from that of the @{i}locale.prefs@{ui} and the environmental variables.
@{b}AEMail@{ub} automatically makes this reversal, so the offset should be set to
positive for US time zones and negative for European time zones.  They
will appear as negative (for US) and positive (for Europe) in the Date:
header.

You can set the @{i}tz@{ui} or the @{i}aem_tz@{ui} environmental variables by using
the @{b}SETENV@{ub} AmigaDos Command.  This must be done from the shell.  The
syntax to use is as follows:

    @{b}SETENV tz aaabbbccc                            (@{i}for tz@{ui}) and
    SETENV aem_tz aaaaaaaaabbbbbccccccccc          (@{i}for aem_tz@{ui})@{ub}

@{i}aaa@{ui}, your local time zone abbreviation must always be present.  If you
don't know your abbreviation (or don't want it in the header), use @{b}xxx@{ub}.
If @{b}AEMail@{ub} sees @{b}xxx@{ub} it will assume that no abbreviation is present and
it will be left off the Date: header

@{i}bbb@{ui} is the time offset in hours from GMT.  @{b}Plus@{ub} indicates that you are @{i}west@{ui}
of GMT and @{b}minus@{ub} indicates that you are @{i}east@{ui} of GMT.  Acceptable values are
-12 to 24.  If you want to specify a half our time zone it can be entered
as @{b}hhmm@{ub}.  If @{b}AEMail@{ub} sees a value of 30 or above it assumes that a half hour
increment is being used.  In this case -1200 to 2400 are acceptable.

If your time zone observes daylight savings time, @{i}ccc@{ui} is the abbreviation to
use for daylight savings time.  If @{i}ccc@{ui} is not present, no adjustment will be
made during the times of the year that daylight savings time is observed.

The result of the @{b}SETENV@{ub} command is only in effect while your computer is on.
If you want to make the @{i}tz@{ui} or @{i}aem_tz@{ui} environmental variables always
present enter the one of the following AmigaDOS command after the @{b}SETENV@{ub}
command:

    @{b}COPY ENV:tz ENVARC:tz                          (@{i}or@{ui})
    COPY ENV:aem_tz ENVARC:aem_tz@{ub}

Using the @{i}tz@{ui} or @{i}aem_tz@{ui} environmental variables gives you more control
over which abbreviations will be used for your time zone.  However, the
@{i}locale.prefs@{ui} file may be more useful for those that prefer the "point and
click" method of doing things.  To set the correct time zone for
@{i}locale.prefs@{ui}, enter the @{b}Locale editor@{ub} in your @{b}Prefs@{ub} drawer.  You will
see a time zone map with which you can move the white strip indicating
the time zone on the map.  Click either to the left or right of the strip
to move the strip.  The correct time zone offset for standard time will be
shown at the top of the map.

Since the @{i}locale.prefs@{ui} does not have any abbreviations, @{b}AEMail@{ub} makes certain
assumptions as to what the abbreviation should be.  These assumptions are as
follows:

@{b}Time Zone Name           Standard    DST  -----------Time Zone-----------
                         Time             (in "locale")  (in email Date:)@{ub}

Greenwich Mean Time      GMT@{b}*@{ub}        BST       0              +0000

Atlantic Time            AST         ADT       4              -0400
Eastern Time (US)        EST         EDT       5              -0500
Central Time (US)        CST         CDT       6              -0600
Mountain Time (US)       MST         MDT       7              -0700
Pacific Time (US)        PST         PDT       8              -0800
Yukon Time               YST         YDT       9              -0900
Hawaiian Time            HST         ---      10              -1000

International Date Line  IDL         ---      12              -1200

--- indicates this time zone does not observe DST

@{b}*Note:@{ub}  @{b}GMT@{ub} (@{i}Greenwich Mean Time@{ui}) is also known as @{b}UTC@{ub} or @{i}Universal
Time Coordinated@{ui}.

If you want to use a different abbreviation or control whether DST is used
or not, you should use the @{i}tz@{ui} or @{i}aem_tz@{ui} environmental variable.

@{i}DST in the United States and Canada begins on the first Sunday in
April.

"Summer Time" in the United Kingdom and Europe begins on the last
Sunday in March.

Both DST and "Summer Time" end on the last Sunday in October.@{ui}


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4000 "CONFIGURATION"

                            @{b}Configuring AEMail@{ub}

The configuration of @{b}AEMail@{ub} is provided by parameters presented as
@{" Tool Types " link AEM-4100} in the @{b}AEMail icon@{ub} or by a @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200} 
that can be called up from within @{b}AEMail@{ub} using the 
@{" Project/Configuratio/Edit.. " link AEM-7101} menu item.  All configuration items provided 
by @{b}Tool Types@{ub} can also be provided by the @{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub} with 
the exception of the @{" MAIL_DIR= " link AEM-4102}, the @{" CONFIG= " link AEM-4119}, and the @{" PASSPROTECT= " link AEM-4123} 
Tool Types.  These three Tool Types have special uses, as explained below, 
that can not be duplicated by the @{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub}; but they are 
set during the installation of @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

You will also find that if you want to change your @{b}ARexx port name@{ub}, that
can only be done with the @{" AREXXPORT= " link AEM-4125} Tool Type.  Adding this Tool Type must
be done manually, since it is not possible to do it with the Installation
script.

Certain configuration parameters can ONLY be provided by the @{b}Configuration
Setup Window@{ub}.

Currently, setting the time zone that you are in is done outside the
@{b}AEMail@{ub} environment.  To set the time zone for @{b}AEMail@{ub} see
@{" SETTING THE TIME ZONE " link AEM-3100}.

If you are running @{b}AEMail@{ub} from the shell or as a @{" mailto: " link AEM-5300} agent, it must
be either pre-configured with the @{" S:aemail.cnfg file " link AEM-9110} or you will
have to specify the @{" config= " link AEM-5200} parameter on the @{b}AEMail@{ub} call line.  You can
specify an alternate configuration file (other than @{b}S:aemail.cnfg@{ub}) by
using the @{b}config=@{ub} parameter on the @{b}AEMail@{ub} call line.  Also, the
configuration file you use must be present or @{b}AEMail@{ub} will be unable to
find the mail directory.  Tool types used in a program's icon are not
available from the shell; however, a @{b}mail_dir=@{ub} parameter is provided on
the @{" shell call line " link AEM-5200} to allow the mail directory to be specified.

The first thing @{b}AEMail@{ub} does when it is activated is check to see that
certain configuration information has been provided either through @{b}Tool
Types@{ub} or as contained in the @{b}AEMail configuration@{ub} file.  The necessary
items are:


        @{" POP3 UserID " link AEM-4104}
        @{" Password " link AEM-4107}
        @{" From Addr" link AEM-4120} @{i}(your email address)@{ui}
        @{" POP Server " link AEM-4108}
        @{" SMTP Server " link AEM-4109}
        @{" Domain Name " link AEM-4105}
        @{" Edit Call " link AEM-4110}


If any of these items are missing, the following requester will be
displayed:


        @{b}The following Configuration items are empty

        @{i}list of empty items@{ui}

        They are required items!@{ub}


The @{b}Edit Call@{ub} item, if it is missing, will default to:

        @{b}C:ed %s@{ub}

with the @{i}editor opening on the Workbench@{ui}.  The only way the Edit Call can
appear in the list is if the @{" General Parameters " link AEM-4900} page of the
@{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200} had been entered and the @{b}EditCall@{ub} field cleared.


If this requester is displayed, you will be given the following choices:


           @{b}[Configure AEMAIL now]               [Cancel AEMAIL]@{ub}


If you were to click on @{b}[Cancel AEMAIL]@{ub}, @{b}AEMail@{ub} will terminate.  You can
not proceed any further until you have entered these items with the
@{b}Configure Setup Window@{ub} or by providing them as @{b}Tool Types@{ub}.

Clicking on the @{b}[Configure AEMAIL now]@{ub} will bring up the
@{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

Also, if @{b}Mail Directory@{ub} appears in the list of empty items, it means
that the the @{" MAIL_DIR " link AEM-4102} Tool Type has not been given.  Even though the mail
directory will be displayed on the Configuration Setup Window, there is no 
way you can provide this information through the Configuration Setup 
Window.  You will have to add the @{b}MAIL_DIR@{ub} Tool Type.  If you use the 
standard install script, this should never be necessary.

The three Tool Types, @{b}MAIL_DIR=@{ub}, @{b}CONFIG=@{ub}, and @{b}PASSPROTECT=YES@{ub} have special
uses.  @{b}CONFIG=@{ub} is used to specify the configuration file that @{ub}AEMail@{ub} is to 
open with.  If @{b}AEMail@{ub} is called from the @{" shell " link AEM-5200}, @{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub} will be used 
as the configuration file for the shell invocation of @{b}AEMail@{ub} unless the 
@{b}config= parameter@{ub} is used in the shell call.  You must have executed 
@{b}AEMail@{ub} at least once from the workbench with the @{b}CONFIG=@{ub} tool type 
pointing to @{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub} for this file to be created.

@{b}MAIL_DIR=@{ub} is used to specify the mail directory that this user will use.
When the configuration file is first created, this directory will be
stored in that file and if @{b}AEMail@{ub} is called from the shell without a
@{b}mail_dir=@{ub} parameter in the call line the configuration file defaults to
the mail directory stored in @{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub}.

@{b}PASSPROTECT=YES@{ub} is used to password protect @{b}AEMail@{ub} when you click on it's
icon.  Using this Tool Type will call up a requester as soon as you load
@{b}AEMail@{ub} which will force you to enter the password that was configured for
that instance of the configuration file.  The @{b}PASSPROTECT=YES@{ub} condition is
not stored in the configuration file but is only obtained from the Tool
Type and therefor is not effective when @{b}AEMail@{ub} is called from the shell.

The @{" Installation  " link AEM-3000} script will take care of providing all of the Tool Types
necessary so it will not be necessary to add them manually.

If you have two or more users of @{b}AEMail@{ub} on the same system and you want
each user to have different locations for their mail files, you can
establish an alternate location for their mail directories.  To do this, you 
will have to have two different @{b}AEMail@{ub} Project icons with different names
if they are in the same directory.  You can still have only one @{b}AEMail@{ub}
executable, however.

With @{b}AEMail 2.xx@{ub}, all of the icons will have to be @{b}Project@{ub} icons and
they will be automatically created by the @{b}Installation script@{ub}.  It is
recommended that you use the @{b}Installation script@{ub} to establish, update, or
add users.  Once you have installed the @{b}AEMail@{ub} executables, the @{b}Install
script@{ub} will give you the option of only configuring your users.

If you are updating from a previous version of @{b}AEMail@{ub}, you will already
have a @{b}Tool@{ub} icon called @{b}"AEMail"@{ub}.  If you choose to, you can create an
icon with a different name for your primary user or leave the primary
user's icon as @{b}"AEMail"@{ub}.  If you choose to keep @{b}"AEMail"@{ub} as your primary
user's icon, this icon will be changed to a @{b}Project@{ub} icon.

If you want password protection (only available to registered @{b}AEMail@{ub}
users) you should also add the Tool Type @{b}PASSPROTECT=YES@{ub} through the
@{b}Installation@{ub} script.  Do this for each user that you want to password
protect.  @{i}Password protection is not available if you call @{b}AEMail@{ub} from the
shell.@{ui}

Please Note:  The @{b}Project@{ub} icon will also inherit the @{b}Tool Types@{ub} from any
icon named "AEMail" even if it is only a Project icon; however, if there
is an identical Tool Type, the current @{b}Project@{ub} icon's Tool Type will take
precedence.

@{u}@{b}WARNING:@{ub}@{uu} If you are updating and you decide to use a different name for
the primary user's icon, the @{b}AEMail@{ub} old Tool icon will remain.  @{b}Do not
delete this icon from the workbench after you have installed AEMail or you
will delete the AEMail executable along with it.@{ub}  This is true even if the
icon has been changed to a @{b}Project@{ub} icon.  If you are going to use a
different name, delete the @{b}AEMail@{ub} icon @{u}BEFORE@{uu} installing @{b}AEMail 2.xx@{ub}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4100 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types"

                    @{b}Configuring AEMail with Tool Types@{ub}

@{b}Tool Types@{ub} have been provided to initially provide certain Configuration
information when @{b}AEMail@{ub} is first activated without the need to build the
Configuration information through the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

To modify or delete any specific @{b}Tool Type@{ub}, select the @{b}AEMail@{ub} icon and
then select the @{b}Information@{ub} item from the Workbench menu.  You will have
to select the appropiate @{b}Tool Type@{ub} and modify it when it appears in the
string gadget below the @{b}Tool Type@{ub} list.

The @{" Installation " link AEM-3000} script will handle @{b}Tool Type@{ub} creation and updating
automatically with the exception of the @{b}AREXXPORT=@{ub} and @{b}HELP= Tool Types@{ub}.
If you need to add these @{b}Tool Types@{ub}, it must be done manually.  There are
default actions that are automatically performed by @{b}AEMail@{ub} if these Tool
Types are missing (see the desciption of each of these @{b}Tool Types@{ub} to see
what the default action is).  Also, the @{b}FLDRFONT=@{ub} and @{b}FLDRFONSZ= Tool
Types@{ub} are not handled by the Installation script since the action of these
@{b}Tool Types@{ub}, unlike @{b}AREXXPORT=@{ub} and @{b}HELP=@{ub}, can be performed by the 
@{" Fonts Page " link AEM-4800} of the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

The @{" Installation " link AEM-3000} script will handle @{b}Tool Type@{ub} creation and updating
automatically.

The current @{b}Tool Types@{ub} utilized by the program are:

    @{" INTERLACE=YES " link AEM-4101}
    @{" MAIL_DIR= " link AEM-4102}
    @{" CONFIG= " link AEM-4119}
    @{" MAILCAP_DIR= " link AEM-4103}
    @{" USERID= " link AEM-4104}
    @{" PASSWRD= " link AEM-4107}
    @{" PASSPROTECT=YES " link AEM-4123}
    @{" DOMAIN= " link AEM-4105}
    @{" FROM= " link AEM-4120}
    @{" REALNAME= " link AEM-4106}
    @{" REPLYTO= " link AEM-4121}
    @{" ORGANIZATION= " link AEM-4122}
    @{" POP_SERVER= " link AEM-4108}
    @{" SMTP_SERVER= " link AEM-4109}
    @{" EDITOR= " link AEM-4110}
    @{" TCPLOG= " link AEM-4111}
    @{" DELETEMAIL=YES " link AEM-4112}
    @{" FULLHEADER=YES " link AEM-4113}
    @{" STRIPDUPS=YES " link AEM-4114}
    @{" HDRINREPLY=YES " link AEM-4115}
    @{" STARTNET= " link AEM-4116}
    @{" STOPNET= " link AEM-4117}
    @{" AUTOCONNECT=YES " link AEM-4118}
    @{" FLDRFONT= " link AEM-4124}
    @{" FLDRFONTSZ= " link AEM-4124}
    @{" AREXXPORT= " link AEM-4125}
    @{" HELP= " link AEM-4126}


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4101 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/INTERLACE="

@{b}INTERLACE=YES@{ub}

@{b}This Tool Type is now obsolete@{ub}, and, if used, will have @{b}no effect@{ub}.  It was
used to open the AEMail Public Screen (@{b}AEMAIL-1@{ub}) in hires, interlace mode.  
AEMail has been changed so that initially it will open in the same screen
mode as the Workbench screen.

You can actually have more control over the @{b}Screen Mode@{ub} you
desire by selecting the @{b}[Set Screen Mode]@{ub} button in the
AEMAIL @{" Configuration: General Parameters " link AEM-4900} configuration display.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4102 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/MAIL_DIR="

@{b}MAIL_DIR=@{i}directory-path@{ui}@{ub}

This @{b}Tool Type@{ub} is required to assign your mail directory.  This is a
@{b}@{u}required@{uu} Tool Type@{ub} and @{u}CAN NOT@{uu} be provided with the @{b}Configuration 
Setup Window@{ub}.

The @{" Installation " link AEM-3000} script automatically handles providing this @{b}Tool Type@{ub}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4119 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/CONFIG="


@{b}CONFIG=@{i}configuration-file@{ui}@{ub}

If you do not care to use the standard @{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub} file for your
configuration data, but want a file named something else or in a
different location, you can use this tool type.  When AEMail opens
it will look here for the configuration file.  YOU MUST PRECEDE THE
FILE NAME WITH THE FULL PATH NAME.  This parameter CAN NOT be provided
with the @{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub}, although the initial file can be 
created, saved, and edited from the @{" Project/Configuration " link AEM-7101} menu.  
(DEFAULTS TO @{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub})

This @{b}Tool Type@{ub} is automatically created by the @{" Installation " link AEM-3000} script.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4103 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/MAILCAP_DIR"

@{b}MAILCAP_DIR=@{i}directory-path@{ui}@{ub}


@{b}This Tool Type is now obsolete.@{ub}  The @{b}mailcap@{ub} file will always reside in
the mail directory for any particular user.

The @{b}mailcap file@{b} must be called "@{b}mailcap@{ub}".  Since the @{"mailcap file" link AEM-9100}
follows a standard format dictated by the internet (@{b}RFC 1524@{ub}), you can use
the same @{b}mailcap file@{ub} used by another process.  The @{" Installation " link AEM-3000} script will
handle copying this @{b}mailcap@{ub} to your mail directory @{i}if you install at the
@{b}expert@{ub} level@{ui}.

You can change the contents of the @{b}mailcap@{ub} file with the @{" Viewer Page " link AEM-4600} of
the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4104 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/USERID"

@{b}USERID=@{i}UserId@{ui}@{ub}

Enter your @{b}POP3 UserId@{ub} for signing onto your POP Server on your
Internet provider (ISP).  This may be the same as the one initially
used to sign into your ISP.  It is also very possibly (but not
always) the part of your email address that precedes the @ sign.
@{i}Check with your ISP for what should be used@{ui}.

@{i}Example:@{ui} my @{b}POP3 UserId@{ub} is "@{i}jzachar@{ui}" so I would enter

    @{b}USERID=jzachar@{ub}

for this @{b}Tool Type.  THIS IS A REQUIRED PARAMETER@{ub}, but it can be provided
with the @{" Identity " link AEM-4300} page of the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4107 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/PASSWRD="

@{b}PASSWRD=@{i}your_password@{ui}@{ub}

Enter the password required for signing onto your POP3 server.  This
may or not be the same as that used to sign onto your Internet provider.
@{b}THIS IS A REQUIRED PARAMETER@{ub}, but it can be provided with the
@{" Identity " link AEM-4300} page of the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

@{b}SPECIAL NOTE:@{ub} if the @{b}password@{ub} is provided by a @{b}Tool Type@{ub} it can be read by
anyone that performs an @{b}Information@{ub} on the @{b}AEMail@{ub} icon.  If you provide the
@{b}password@{ub} through the @{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub}, it can not be seen.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4123 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/PASSPROTECT="

@{b}PASSPROTECT=YES@{ub} (@{i}registered users only@{ui})

Use this Tool Type if you want to password protect your copy of @{b}AEMail@{ub}.
This will call up a special password window when you first load @{b}AEMail@{ub}
which will require you to enter your password before you procede.  You
will be given three chances to enter the correct password.  If the
password fails validation after the third try, @{b}AEMail@{ub} will terminate.
@{b}This Tool Type is ignored for unregistered users.@{ub}

The Password that is used is the one required for signing onto your POP3
server (see @{" PASSWRD= " link AEM-4107}).

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4105 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/DOMAIN="

@{b}DOMAIN=@{i}Domain_Name@{ui}@{ub}


Enter the @{b}Domain@{ub} name used by your Internet provider's @{b}SMTP server@{ub}.
@{i}It very possibly is the same as the @{b}Domain@{ub} part of your email address
(the part following the @ sign)@{ui}

@{i}Example: @{ui}my Internet provider's @{b}domain name@{ub} is "@{i}calweb.com@{ui}" so I would
enter:

    @{b}DOMAIN=calweb.com@{ub}

for this @{b}Tool Type.  THIS IS A REQUIRED PARAMETER,@{ub} but it can be provided
with the @{" Identity " link AEM-4300} page of the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4120 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/FROM="

@{b}FROM=@{i}your_email_address@{ui}@{ub}

Enter your @{u}FULL@{uu} email address (i.e. @{b}user@domain@{ub}).  This is email address
that you are known by on the Internet.

Example: my email address is "jzachar@calweb.com" so I would enter

    @{b}FROM=jzachar@calweb.com@{ub}

for this @{b}Tool Type.  THIS IS A REQUIRED PARAMETER,@{ub} but it can be provided
with the @{" Identity " link AEM-4300} page of the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.  If it is 
missing it defaults to @{b}UserID@Domain@{ub}.  @{i}This default action may @{u}NOT@{uu} be 
correct for your situation, so be sure to change it if required to.@{ui}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4106 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/REALNAME="

@{b}REALNAME=@{i}your_real_name@{ui}@{ub}

Enter your @{b}full name@{ub}.  @{i}Example:@{ui}

    @{b}REALNAME=John Zacharias@{ub}

This is an @{b}OPTIONAL@{ub} parameter, but if it is omitted your full name will NOT
be provided in the @{b}FROM:@{ub} address of any messages you send unless you add it
yourself when you @{" compose a message " link AEM-6080}.  This parameter can also be provided
with the @{" Identity " link AEM-4300} page of the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4121 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/REPLYTO="

@{b}REPLYTO=@{i}reply-email-address@{ui}@{ub}

This is the @{b}email address@{ub} that you want all @{i}replies@{ui} directed to.  This
may be the same as your @{b}From:@{ub} email address or it can be a different
address if you want replies sent somewhere else.  This is an @{b}OPTIONAL@{ub}
parameter and can also be provided with the @{" Identity " link AEM-4300} page of the
@{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

The standard @{b}Reply-To@{ub} address provided here can also be modified each
time you @{" compose a message " link AEM-8700} to send.

@ENDNODE
@NODE AEM-4122 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/ORGANIZATION="

@{b}ORGANIZATION=@{i}organization-name@{ui}@{ub}

This parameter is @{b}OPTIONAL@{ub} and, if present, will provide an @{b}Organization:@{ub}
header for any message that you compose and send.  This parameter can
also be provided with the @{" Identity " link AEM-4300} page of the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE AEM-4108 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/POP_SERVER="

@{b}POP_SERVER=@{i}your_POP_host@{ui}@{ub}

Enter the name of your @{b}POP host@{ub}.  This sometimes is @{b}pop.@{ub} or @{b}mail.@{ub}
prepended to your @{b}Domain name@{ub}.  @{i}As an example@{ui}, mine is "@{i}pop.calweb.com@{ui}"
so I would enter:

    @{b}POP_SERVER=pop.calweb.com@{ub}

If this parameter is omitted, @{b}pop.@{i}domain-name@{ui}@{ub} will be generated as
your @{b}POP_SERVER@{ub} name provided a @{b}domain name@{ub} has been specified.  If your's 
uses a different name you should use this @{b}Tool Type@{ub} or change it with the
@{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub}.

This parameter can also be provided by the @{" Identity " link AEM-4300} page of the
@{" Configuration Setup Window. " link AEM-4200}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4109 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/SMTP_SERVER="

@{b}SMTP_SERVER=@{i}your_SMTP_host@{ui}@{ub}

Enter the name of your @{b}SMTP host@{ub}.  This sometimes is @{b}smtp.@{ub} or @{b}mail.@{ub}
prepended to your @{b}Domain name@{ub}.  @{i}As an example@{ui}, mine is
"@{i}smtp.calweb.com@{ui}" so I would enter

    @{b}SMTP_SERVER=smtp.calweb.com@{ub}

If this parameter is omitted, @{b}smtp.@{i}domain-name@{ui}@{ub} will be generated as
your @{b}SMTP_SERVER@{ub} name provided a @{b}domain name@{ub} has been specified.  If
your's uses a differnt name you should use this @{b}Tool Type@{ub} or change it
with the @{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub}.

This parameter can also be provided by the @{" Identity " link AEM-4300} page of the
@{" Configuration Setup Window. " link AEM-4200}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4110 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/EDITOR="

@{b}EDITOR=@{i}call_line_for_your_editor@{ui}@{ub}

Enter the full call parameter required to activate your editor from the
shell.  Use @{i}%s@{ui} where you would place the file name.

You are no longer restricted to an editor call that does not remain in
control when you call it as you were with previous versions of @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  In
other words, a direct call to @{b}CygnusEd (CED)@{ub} is acceptable.

If you editor opens on the Workbench screen rather than a screen of its
own, you should prepend @{b}WB;@{ub} in front of you editor call.  As an
example, the standard @{b}AmigaDos ED@{ub} program always opens on the Workbench 
screen.  An example edit call for the @{b}Amiga ED@{ub} would be as follows:

    @{b}EDITOR=WB;c:ed %s WINDOW raw:0/0/640/400/AEMailCompose@{ub}

The window statement in the above call is used to create a full screen
window with an interlaced display.

If you are not using an interlaced display you can remove the WINDOW
parameter or change it to @{i}raw:0/0/640/200/AEMailCompose@{ui}. You can, of
course, make other changes to the window parameters if you desire.

If you are using Amiga ED you should probably also remove or rename
the @{b}ED-Startup@{ub} file in the @{b}S:@{ub} directory so that you will have a full set
of ED menus.

If this Tool Type is missing, the following call is the default editor
call:

    @{b}EDITOR=WB;c:ed %s@{ub}

This defaults to using the Amiga Ed program for your editor.

The specification for your editor call can also be provided by the
@{" General Parameters " link AEM-4900} page of the  @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.  A
convenient check mark item is provided in the @{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub} to open
the editor on the Workbench screen.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4111 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/TCPLOG="

@{b}TCPLOG=@{i}name_of_log_file@{ui}@{ub}

Enter the full path, including file name, of your @{" TCP logging file " link AEM-9180}.
If this parameter is omitted, it defaults to @{b}tcplog@{ub} in the directory
@{b}AEMail@{ub} is loaded from.

This parameter does @{i}not@{ui} start @{b}TCP logging@{ub}, it only establishes the name of
the TCPLOG file.  Logging can be started or stopped at any time by the menu
item @{" TCP/IP/TCP Logging File/Active " link AEM-7503}.  The Logging file can be set
active when @{b}AEMail@{ub} is started through a parameter in the @{" Paths " link AEM-4500} page
of the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

When TCP logging is active, all sends and receives over the TCP/IP
connection are recorded to this file.  Each time an @{b}AEMail@{ub} session is
started and logging is active, data is appended to this file.  As a result
this file can become quite large.  @{i}IT IS THE USER'S RESPONSIBILITY TO
PERIODICALLY PURGE (@{u}DELETE@{uu}) THIS FILE@{ui}.  A menu item is provided to perform
this @{" purge " link AEM-7503} and another item to @{" display " link AEM-7503} the log file with your editor from
within @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub}  When there is a need to report a problem, especially with your
TCP/IP connection, the TCP Logging file should be set active and a copy of
the resultant file provided with any feedback on the program activity (see
@{" Bug Reports & Suggestions " link AEM-9700}).  The file can be sent as an attachment
to any message that you send to @{b}AEMAIL@{ub}.  You probably should compress the
file with @{b}LHA@{ub} before attaching it as an @{b}Applicatio/Octet Stream@{ub}
Content Type/Subtype with @{b}encoded binary@{ub} encoding.

I have discovered that this file comes in handy when analysing problems
with your Internet provider since it time stamps all entries to the
nearest second.

This parameter can also be provided by the @{" Default Path Parameters " link AEM-4500}
page of the @{" Configuration Setup Window. " link AEM-4200}


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4112 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/DELETEMAIL="

@{b}DELETEMAIL=YES@{ub}

This @{b}Tool Type@{ub} sets the initial value of the @{" Delete Host Mail " link AEM-7402}  menu item
under the @{" RETRIEVE MESSAGES menu " link AEM-7400}.  If this @{b}Tool Type@{ub} is entered, the
@{b}Delete Host Mail@{ub} menu item will be initially checked.

This parameter can also be set by the @{" General Parameters " link AEM-4900} page of the
@{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200} or the @{b}DELETEMAIL@{ub} flag can be set with the 
@{b}Delete Host Mail@{ub} menu item and its state can be saved in the 
@{" configuration file " link AEM-9110} by selecting the @{" PROJECT/CONFIGURATION/SAVE " link AEM-7101} menu 
item.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4113 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/FULLHEADER"

@{b}FULLHEADER=YES@{ub}

This @{b}Tool Type@{ub} sets the initial value of the @{" Display Full Header " link AEM-7307}  menu
item under the @{" MESSAGES menu " link AEM-7300}.  If this @{b}Tool Type@{ub} is entered, the
@{b}Display Full Header@{ub} menu item will be initially checked.

This parameter can also be set by the @{" General Parameters " link AEM-4900} page of the
@{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200} or the @{b}FULLHEADER@{ub} flag can be set with the 
@{b}Display Full Header@{ub} menu item and its state can be saved in the 
@{" configuration file " link AEM-9110} by selecting the @{" PROJECT/CONFIGURATION/SAVE " link AEM-7101} 
menu item.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4114 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/STRIPDUPS"

@{b}STRIPDUPS=YES@{ub}

This @{b}Tool Type@{ub} sets the initial value of the @{" Exclude Duplicate Messages " link AEM-7402}
menu item under the @{" RETRIEVE MESSAGES menu " link AEM-7400}.  If this @{b}Tool Type@{ub} is entered,
the @{b}Exclude Duplicate Messages@{ub} menu item will be initially checked.

This parameter can also be set by the @{" General Parameters " link AEM-4900} page of the
@{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200} or the @{b}STRIPDUPS@{ub} flag can be set with the 
@{b}Exclude Duplicate Messages@{ub} menu item and its state can be saved in the 
@{" configuration file " link AEM-9110} by selecting the @{" PROJECT/CONFIGURATION/SAVE " link AEM-7101} menu
item.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4115 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/HDRINREPLY"

@{b}HDRINREPLY=YES@{ub}

This @{b}Tool Type@{ub} sets the initial value of the @{" Include Header in Response " link AEM-7308}
menu item under the @{" MESSAGES menu " link AEM-7300}.  If this @{b}Tool Type@{ub} is entered, the
@{b}Include Header in Response@{ub} menu item will be initially checked.

This parameter can also be set by the @{" General Parameters " link AEM-4900} page of the
@{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200} or the @{b}HDRINREPLY@{ub} flag can be set with the 
@{b}Include Header in Response@{ub} menu item and its state can be saved in the 
@{" configuration file " link AEM-9110} by selecting the @{" PROJECT/CONFIGURATION/SAVE " link AEM-7101} menu
item.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4116 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/STARTNET"

@{b}STARTNET=@{i}call_line_for_your_startnet_script@{ui}@{ub}

This @{b}Tool Type@{ub} is used to specify the call line for your script that
starts up your TCP/IP stack.  If you are using @{" AmiTCP " link AEM-9910}, this is normally
the file @{b}startnet@{ub} in the @{b}AMITCP:bin@{ub} directory.  If you are using @{" Miami " link AEM-9910},
an AREXX script has been provided with the @{b}AEMail@{ub} archive called
@{b}startnet.miami@{ub} and it is located in the @{b}AEMail@{ub} program directory.

A full path name to that script must be entered.  If the script is an
@{b}AREXX@{ub} script it should be preceded with @{b}"rx "@{ub} (a space is between the @{b}rx@{ub}
and the script name).  The standard @{b}AmiTCP startnet@{ub} script is @{b}NOT@{ub} an @{b}AREXX@{ub}
script even though it uses @{b}AREXX@{ub} commands.  It is an AmigaDOS script.  The 
@{b}Miami@{ub} script, on the other hand, is an @{b}AREXX@{ub} script.

If you do not use the @{b}STARTNET@{ub} Tool Type, @{b}AEMail@{ub} assumes that you do not
have a script.  If you activate the @{" Start Net " link AEM-7501} item in the @{" TCP/IP " link AEM-7500} menu
and you don't have a @{b}startnet@{ub} script, @{b}AEMail's@{ub} action is to @{" iconify " link AEM-7103} and
allow you to manually start your TCP/IP stack.  Connect using the method
prescribed by your TCP/IP stack.  When you @{b}un-iconify AEMail@{ub}, @{b}AEMail@{ub} will
immediately check to see if any mail is present on your POP server.

If you are using a TCP/IP stack that can't use a script (such as
@{" TermiteTCP " link AEM-9910}) or you have no script to make connection to your Internet
provider, then this Tool Type should not be used.  Then if you select the
@{b}Start Net@{ub} menu item, the system will automatically iconify @{b}AEMail@{ub} and
present the Workbench screen.

Since @{b}AmiTCP Demo Version 4.0@{ub} puts up a requester on the workbench screen
that must be responded to, @{b}AEMail@{ub} will automatically switch to the
Workbench screen before calling this script.  Although the @{b}Miami@{ub} script
does not require manual intervention, the default action is to also switch
to the Workbench screen since this allows you to see the action of the
dialer.  When the connection has been made using @{b}Miami@{ub}, the screen will
automatically switch back to the @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen.

The @{b}Start Net@{ub} script can also be set by the @{" TCP/IP " link AEM-4400} page of the
@{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.  The @{b}Configuration Seyup Window@{ub} will also 
allow you to set whether or not the system switches to the Workbench 
screen when the @{b}Start Net@{ub} script is executed.

@{b}Note:@{ub} Check your @{i}startnet@{ui} script to be sure that full path names are
specified.  If you are using the standard @{b}AmiTCP@{ub} startnet script, that
script will not be executed from the @{b}Amitcp:bin@{ub} directory if @{b}AEMail@{ub} is in
another directory.  Therefor, you should verify that @{b}Amitcp:bin/@{ub} is
prepended to all calls to functions within the @{b}AmiTCP/bin@{ub} directory within
the script.  Pay particular attention to the @{b}online@{ub} call - it should be
@{b}AmiTCP:bin/online@{ub}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4117 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/STOPNET"

@{b}STOPNET=@{i}call_line_for_your_stopnet_script@{ui}@{ub}

This @{b}Tool Type@{ub} is used to specify the call line for your script that
terminates your TCP/IP connection.  If you are using @{" AmiTCP " link AEM-9910}, this is
normally the file @{b}stopnet@{ub} in the @{b}AMITCP:bin@{ub} directory.  If you are using
@{" Miami " link AEM-9910}, an AREXX script has been provided with the @{b}AEMail@{ub} archive
called @{b}stopnet.miami@{ub} and it is located in the @{b}AEMail@{ub} program
directory.

A full path name to that script must be entered.  If the script is an
@{b}AREXX@{ub} script it should be preceded with @{b}"rx "@{ub} (a space is between the
@{b}rx@{ub} and the script name).  The standard @{b}AmiTCP stopnet@{ub} script is @{b}NOT@{ub} an
@{b}AREXX@{ub} script even though it uses @{b}AREXX@{ub} commands.  It is an AmigaDOS
script.  The @{b}Miami@{ub} script, on the other hand, is an @{b}AREXX@{ub} script.

If you do not use the @{b}STOPNET@{ub} Tool Type, @{b}AEMail@{ub} assumes that you do not
have a script.  If you activate the @{" Stop Net " link AEM-7502} item in the @{" TCP/IP " link AEM-7500} menu
and you don't have a @{b}stopnet@{ub} script, @{b}AEMail's@{ub} action is to @{" iconify " link AEM-7103} and
allow you to manually stop your TCP/IP stack.  You can then disconnect
using the method prescribed by your TCP/IP stack.  When you @{b}un-iconify@{ub}
@{b}AEMail@{ub}, @{b}AEMail@{ub} will test to see if you are, in fact, disconnected.

If you are using a TCP/IP stack that can't use a script (such as
@{" TermiteTCP " link AEM-9910}) or you have no script to terminate your connection to
your Internet provider, then this Tool Type should not be used.  Then if
you select the @{b}Stop Net@{ub} menu item, the system will automatically
iconify @{b}AEMail@{ub} and present the Workbench screen.

The @{b}Stop Net@{ub} script can also be set by the @{" TCP/IP " link AEM-4400} page of the
@{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.  The @{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub} will also 
allow you to set whether or not the system switches to the Workbench 
screen when the @{b}Stop Net@{ub} script is executed.  Since terminating your 
connection with a script usually does not require any visual interaction, 
the default action is to @{b}NOT@{ub} switch to the Workbench screen.

@{b}Note:@{ub} Check your @{i}stopnet@{ui} script to be sure that full path names are
specified.  If you are using the standard @{b}AmiTCP@{ub} stopnet script, that
script will not be executed from the @{b}Amitcp:bin@{ub} directory if @{b}AEMail@{ub} is in
another directory.  Therefor, you should verify that @{b}Amitcp:bin/@{ub} is
prepended to all calls to functions within the @{b}AmiTCP/bin@{ub} directory within
the script.  Pay particular attention to the @{b}offline@{ub} call - it should be
@{b}AmiTCP:bin/offline@{ub}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4118 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/AUTOCONNECT"

@{b}AUTOCONNECT=YES@{ub}

When @{b}AEMail@{ub} is first activated it attempts to determine if you are connected
to your Internet provider.  If you are not and this @{b}Tool Type@{ub} is present,
@{b}AEMail@{ub} will automatically run your @{" StartNet " link AEM-4116} script.  (see
@{" Starting AEMAIL " link AEM-5000}.)

Before activating this @{b}Tool Type@{ub}, you should check to see if @{b}AEMail@{ub} can
activate your TCP/IP stack properly using the @{" Start Net " link AEM-7501} menu item in the
@{" TCP/IP menu " link AEM-7500}.  If there are any problems with your @{b}Start Net@{ub} activation
they will show up at this time rather than constantly every time you try to
activate @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

@{u}@{b}WARNING:@{ub}@{uu} You should not use this Tool Type if a @{b}StartNet@{ub} script is not
present for your TCP/IP stack.  You should activate your TCP/IP stack
manually before you start @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

You can also set the @{b}AUTOCONNECT@{ub} flag with the @{" TCP/IP Parameters " link AEM-4400} page
of the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4124 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/FLDRFONT & FLDRFONTSZ"

@{b}FLDRFONT=@{i}fontname@{ui}@{ub}

This allows the user to specify their own font for the folder strip.
Since the size of the folders in the folder strip is constrained by
the size of the font that you use, you can specify a different font
and font size (see @{b}FLDRFONTSZ=@{ub} below) to reduce the size of the folder
strip.  If not specified the folder font will default to the standard
@{b}Topaz 8@{ub} font.  When you enter the font name it is entered @{b}@{u}WITHOUT@{uu}@{ui} the
@{b}.font@{ub} suffix and it must be found in your @{b}FONTS:@{ub}  directory.

If you use @{b}FLDRFONT=@{ub} without @{b}FLDRFONTSZ=@{ub}, the resulting font will be
the one you specify at the @{b}8@{ub} size.  If no such size exists in your
@{b}FONTS:@{ub}  directory, it will be computed.  This can sometimes be
unsatisfactory.

This parameter can also be set with the @{" Fonts Page " link AEM-4800} of the 
@{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.


@{b}FLDRFONTSZ=@{i}fontsize@{ui}@{ub}

This @{b}Tool Type@{ub} is used in conjuction with the @{b}FLDRFONT= Tool Type@{ub}
described above.  These two @{b}Tool Types@{ub} allow the user to specify their
own @{b}font@{ub} and @{b}font size@{ub} for the folder strip.  Since the size of the
folders in the folder strip is constrained by the size of the font
that you use, you can specify a different font and font size to reduce
the size of the folder strip.  If not specified the folder font will
default to the standard @{b}Topaz 8@{ub} font.

If you use @{b}FLDRFONTSZ=@{ub} without @{b}FLDRFONT=@{ub}, the resulting font will be
Topaz with a computed font size corresponding to this parameter

This parameter can also be set with the @{" Fonts Page " link AEM-4800} of the 
@{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4125 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/AREXXPORT"

@{b}AREXXPORT=@{i}portname@{ui}@{ub}

This Tool Type will allow you to change the default ARexx Port Name.  By
default the ARexx Port Name is @{b}AEMAIL1@{ub}.  A @{b}1@{ub} will be appended to
whatever port name you specify unless that port is already active in your
system.  In this event a number next in sequence will be appended to the
port name.

The ARexx Port Name will be shown in the About message obtained with the
@{" About " link AEM-7104} item under the @{" Project Menu " link AEM-7100}.

@{b}This parameter can only be provided with a Tool Type@{ub}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4126 "CONFIGURATION: Tool Types/HELP"

@{b}HELP=@{i}full-path-name-to-"AEMail.guide"-file@{ui}@{ub}

This Tool Type will allow you to change the default @{b}AEMail.guide@{ub} path
name.  You should include the file name of the guide file.  By default the
@{b}AEMail.guide@{ub} path name is @{b}AEMail2:documentation/AEMail.guide@{ub}.  If you
are using the default path name you do not have to use this tool type.

If @{b}AEMail@{ub} can not find the help file, it will display a requester like
this when you first load @{b}AEMail@{ub}:

                     @{b}Error: (AG) Can't Open database!

                                [Continue]@{ub}

You can continue without the guide file, but the @{b}[Help]@{ub} key will be
deactivated.

@{b}This parameter can only be provided with a Tool Type@{ub}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4200 "CONFIGURATION: Configuration Setup Window"

                           @{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub}


The @{b}Configuration setup window@{ub} is displayed in the center of the @{b}AEMail@{ub}
screen whenever you click on either the @{b}[Configure AEMAIL now]@{ub} button or
when you select the @{" Project/Configuration/Edit " link AEM-7101} menu item.  The
@{b}Configuration Setup@{ub} is divided into seven pages with the page name shown
with a tab at the top of the page area.  When you click on any one tab,
that tab will stand out and become bold and the appropriate page will be
displayed.

The seven pages are:

    @{" Identity " link AEM-4300}
    @{" TCP/IP " link AEM-4400}
    @{" Paths " link AEM-4500}
    @{" Viewer " link AEM-4600}
    @{" ARexx " link AEM-4700}
    @{" Fonts " link AEM-4800}
    @{" General " link AEM-4900}

When the @{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub} first opens, the @{b}Identity page@{ub} will be
displayed and the first string gadget (@{" POP3 User ID) " link AEM-4300} will be activated.
However, when you bring up another page by clicking into the tab for that
page (or using the tab hot key), the first string gadget on that page will
not be activated.  You will have to click into one of the string gadgets
to activate it.  From then on the tab and shift tab keys will work
correctly for going between string gadgets.

You will also have to re-activate the string gadgets after pressing the
@{b}[Help]@{ub} key.

You will notice that several of the gadgets have underlined characters.
These are hot keys that you can use to activate the gadget rather than
clicking on the gadget.  If a string gadget is currently activated, the
hot keys will not work since it will be interpreted as a key being entered
into the string.  You can always hit return when you have finished
entering something in the string gadget and the hot keys will now be
available.

You can also use the tab key to go the next string gadget while a string
gadget is active (indicated by the cursor in the gadget).  Shift tab will
go to the previous string gadget.  Besides the normal editing keys used
for strings, each string can also copy to the clipboard (@{i}RIGHT AMIGA 'c'@{ui}),
copy from the keyboard (@{i}RIGHT AMIGA 'v'@{ui}), and change clipboard units
(@{i}RIGHT AMIGA 'u' and 'U'@{ui}) (see also @{" Editing String Entry Gadgets " link AEM-5400})

Additional editing keys have also been provided just for the Configuration
Setup Window string gadgets.  This are:  @{b}RIGHT AMIGA 'd'@{ub} which will bring 
the default entry into the string; @{b}RIGHT AMIGA 'f'@{ub} which will bring up the
file requester for those strings that have a file requester associated
with them; and @{b}RIGHT AMIGA 'p'@{ub} for the @{b}POP3 UserId@{ub} string gadget on the
@{" Identity " link AEM-4300} page to bring up the @{b}Set Password@{ub} requester.

At the bottom of the @{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub} is a row of buttons as 
follows:


@{b}[      Use      ] [      Save      ] [    Save As    ] [     Cancel     ]@{ub}


Clicking on any one of these buttons (or using the appropriate hot key)
will perform the requested action, regardless of which page you are on,
and return you to the current @{b}AEMail@{ub} window.

If you want the configuration information to apply only to the current 
@{b}AEMail@{ub} session select @{b}[USE]@{ub}.  If you want to make the configuration 
permanent, select @{b}[SAVE]@{ub}.  This will cause a new @{" configuration file " link AEM-9110} to be 
written over the current @{i}active@{ui} @{b}configuration file@{ub}.

The @{b}configuration file@{ub} is the file specified in the  @{" CONFIG= " link AEM-4119} tool type for
the Project icon you selected to load @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  However, if you opened
another @{b}configuration file@{ub} with the @{" Project/Configuration/Open... " link AEM-7101} menu
item, that configuration file will be the @{i}current active one@{ui}.

The @{b}[SAVE AS]@{ub} button does the same as @{b}[SAVE]@{ub} except that a file requester
will be displayed that will allow you to rename and place the @{b}configuration
file@{ub} anywhere you wish.  @{b}WARNING:@{ub} when you use the @{b}[SAVE AS]@{ub} button,
@{b}AEMail@{ub} assumes that that file is now your @{i}active@{ui} @{b}configuration file@{ub} and
any saves occuring after that will be to that file.

To return to the @{i}base@{ui} configuration (the @{b}CONFIG=@{ub} file), use the
@{" Project/Configuration/Restore Default " link AEM-7101} menu item.

@{b}@{u}WARNING:@{uu}@{ub}  Any @{b}Open@{ub} or @{b}Save As@{ub} operations are made to what is termed
@{i}"shared"@{ui} configurations.  These are configurations that generally DO NOT
HAVE a project icon and share the same mail directory (each use the same
folder setup).  @{i}You should not open a configuration that has a different
mail directory.@{ui}

When @{b}AEMail@{ub} opens it will always use the base configuration file specified
in the @{b}CONFIG=@{ub} Tool Type.  To change this specification, you will have to
do this manually or use the @{" Installation " link AEM-3000} script which handles setting the
@{b}CONFIG=@{ub} Tool Type automatically.

@{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} will abort the operation without making any changes to the
configuration information.

The @{b}[USE], [SAVE], [SAVE AS]@{ub} or @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} buttons are active no matter
which configuration page is currently active.  When the @{b}Configuration
Setup Window@{ub} is first activated, the @{b}Identity@{ub} page will be active.

Before exiting from the Configuration Setup Window with @{b}[USE], [SAVE]@{ub} or 
@{b}[SAVE AS]@{ub} the required configuration parameters must be present. If not, 
the following requester will be displayed:


        @{b}The following Configuration items are empty

        @{i}list of empty items@{ui}

        They are required items!@{ub}


This is the same requester that is displayed when @{b}AEMail@{ub} is started without
these parameters being provided.  Your choices with this requester are:


    @{b}[Reenter Configuration Data]   [Cancel Configuration Request]@{ub}


Clicking on the @{b}[Cancel Configuraion Request]@{ub} will act the same as if you
clicked on @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} in the main Configuration Setup Window.  In this event 
your "old" configuration data will still be active and if you did not have 
the required parameters in the first place, you will not be able to do
anything but enter the data or exit from @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

The one exception to the "old" configuration remaining the same is with the
@{" .headers " link AEM-9120} file.  This is always updated no matter which button is pressed.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4300 "CONFIGURATION: Configuration Setup Window/Identity Page"

                              @{b}Identity Page@{ub}

The @{b}Identity page@{ub} appears as follows:

    @{b}=========================================================================
    [o] AEMAIL Configuration Setup
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------
      ----------
     | Identity |___________________________________________________________
    |                                                                       |
    |         POP3 UserID: [                  ][CLR][DEFAULT] [Set Password]|
    |                                                                       |
    |From (email) Address: [                                 ][CLR][DEFAULT]|
    |                                                                       |
    |    Reply To Address: [                                 ][CLR]{DEFAULT]|
    |                                                                       |
    |           Real Name: [                                 ][CLR][DEFAULT]|
    |                                                                       |
    |        Organization: [                                 ][CLR][DEFAULT]|
    |                                                                       |
    |          POP Server: [                                 ][CLR][DEFAULT]|
    |                                                                       |
    |         SMTP Server: [                                 ][CLR][DEFAULT]|
    |                                                                       |
    |         Domain Name: [                                 ][CLR][DEFAULT]|
    |_______________________________________________________________________|

    [      Use      ] [      Save      ] [    Save As    ] [     Cancel     ]

    =========================================================================@{ub}

When this page is first called up, values from the @{" Tool Types " link AEM-4100} or the @{i}current@{ui}
@{" configuration file " link AEM-9110} (which ever takes precedence) will be displayed in each
of the string gadgets.

Appropriate information can be entered into each of the string gadgets. @{i}Up
to 99 characters can be entered in each of the string gadgets.@{ui}


The buttons to the side of each string gadget perform the following actions:

    @{b}[CLR]@{ub} will cause the string gadget to be cleared.
          (@{u}string edit key:@{uu} @{b}RIGHT AMIGA 'x'@{ub})

    @{b}[DEFAULT]@{ub} (@{u}string edit key:@{uu} @{b}RIGHT AMIGA 'd'@{ub})will cause default 
        information to be loaded into the string gadgets as follows:

            @{b}POP3 UserID:@{ub} information from the @{" USERID= " link AEM-4104} Tool Type  if
                present; otherwise it will use information from the
                @{b}USER@{ub} environmental variable or by parsing the
                @{b}ttcp-email-address@{ub} environmental variable created
                by Termite-TCP.

            @{b}Domain Name:@{ub} Information from the @{" DOMAIN= " link AEM-4105} Tool Type if
                present; otherwise it will use information from either
                the @{b}DOMAIN@{ub} or @{b}DOMAINNAME@{ub} environmental variable or
                by parsing the @{b}ttcp-email-address@{ub} environmental
                variable created by Termite-TCP.

            @{b}From Address:@{ub} information from the @{" FROM= " link AEM-4120} Tool Type  if
                present; otherwise, if a @{b}Domain Name@{ub} is present, it
                will be the combination @{b}UserID@DomainName@{ub}.

            @{b}Reply To Address:@{ub} information from the @{" REPLYTO= " link AEM-4121} Tool Type or,
                 if missing, the @{b}From Address@{ub}.

            @{b}Real Name:@{ub} information from the @{" REALNAME= " link AEM-4106} Tool Type if
                present; otherwise from the @{b}NAME@{ub} environmental 
                variable.

            @{b}Organization:@{ub} information from the @{" ORGANIZATION= " link AEM-4122} Tool Type.

            @{b}POP Server:@{ub} information from the @{" POP_SERVER= " link AEM-4108} Tool Type if
                present; otherwise , if a @{b}Domain Name@{ub} is present,
                this will be the domain name with @{b}pop.@{ub} prepended
                to it.

            @{b}SMTP Server:@{ub}  Information from the @{" SMTP_SERVER= " link AEM-4109} Tool
                Type if present; otherwise, if a @{b}Domain Name@{ub} is
                present, this will be the domain name with @{b}smtp.@{ub}
                prepended to it.

        The environmental variables indicated above are only available
        if your TCP/IP software has been loaded before calling @{b}AEMail@{ub}.
        The TCP/IP stack doesn't have to be running (i.e., on line),
        but it must be loaded.  If the default is missing, nothing
        is loaded into the corresponding string gadget.


The @{b}[SET PASSWORD]@{ub} button gadget will bring up the @{" Set Password Window " link AEM-4310}
which will allow you to add or change your password.  When you are
entering your @{b}POP3 UserID@{ub} you can also use @{b}RIGHT AMIGA 'p'@{ub} to call up this
window.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4310 "CONFIGURATION: Identity Page Set Password Window"

                           @{b}Set Password Window@{ub}

The @{b}[SET PASSWORD]@{ub} window looks like the following:

                  @{b}|========================================|
                  |0|Enter Password                        |
                  |----------------------------------------|
                  |                                        |
                  |     Enter your new password below      |
                  |                                        |
                  |  [                                  ]  |
                  |                                        |
                  |                                        |
                  |                                        |
                  |  [START OVER]            [  CANCEL  ]  |
                  |________________________________________|@{ub}


The string gadget will be automatically activated when the window is
displayed.  You can type in your new password, but for each character you
type an * will appear.  You must hit return when you finish
entering your password.  After hitting return, the heading:

                        @{b}Enter your password below@{ub}

will be replaced by the following heading:

                 @{b}For verification, re-enter your password@{ub}

You must re-enter your password and, when you hit return, if the
re-entered password matches the first password, the password window will
close.  The new password will not take effect until you hit the @{b}[USE]@{ub},
@{b}[SAVE]@{ub} or @{b}[SAVE TO]@{ub} buttons at the bottom of the Configuration Setup
Window.  If you hit the @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} button at the bottom of the Setup Window
even though the new password has been accepted, the new password will not
be used.

If the re-entered password does not match, the following will appear below the
password entry string gadget:

                       @{b}Password failed Validation!@{ub}

and the @{b}Enter your password below@{ub} heading will re-appear.

If at any time you want to start over with entering the new password, you can
click on the @{b}[START OVER]@{ub} gadget.  If you want to cancel the password entry
process you can either click on the close gadget at the top left of the window
or on the @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} gadget in the window.

@{i}Only 30 characters can be entered into the password string gadget.@{ui}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4400 "CONFIGURATION: Configuration Setup Window/TCP/IP Page"

                               @{b}TCP/IP Page@{ub}

The @{b}TCP/IP page@{ub} appears as follows:

    @{b}=========================================================================
    [o] AEMail Configuration Setup
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------
                 --------
     ___________| TCP/IP |__________________________________________________
    |                                                                       |
    |Start Net Call: [                                  ][|=|][CLR][DEFAULT]|
    |                                                                       |
    |                [ ] Start Net Opens on the Workbench [ ] ARexx Command |
    |                                                                       |
    |                                                                       |
    | Stop Net Call: [                                  ][|=|][CLR][DEFAULT]|
    |                                                                       |
    |                [ ] Stop Net Opens on the Workbench  [ ] ARexx Command |
    |                                                                       |
    | [ ] Automatic connection to Internet on AEMail Start Up               |
    | [ ] Display disconnect check on AEMail exit                           |
    |                                                                       |
    |Disable Queued Mail Check [] on Internet connection   [] at AEMail exit|
    |   Disable New Mail Check [] on Internet connection   [] at AEMail exit|
    |                                                                       |
    |Check for new mail every [  ]/| minutes                                |
    |_______________________________________________________________________|

    [      Use      ] [      Save      ] [    Save As    ] [     Cancel     ]

    =========================================================================@{ub}


The @{b}Start Net Call@{ub} and @{b}Stop Net Call@{ub} are required if you are going to
start up or stop your TCP/IP connection from within @{b}AEMail@{ub} with a script.
If you are using @{" AmiTCP " link AEM-9910}, this is normally either the file @{b}startnet@{ub} or
@{b}stopnet@{ub} in the @{b}AMITCP:bin@{ub} directory.  If you are using @{" Miami " link AEM-9910}, two @{b}AREXX@{ub}
scripts, called @{b}startnet.miami@{ub} and @{b}stopnet.miami@{ub} have been provided
with the @{b}AEMail@{ub} archive located in the @{b}AEMail@{ub} program directory.

When first presented, these two string gadgets will contain the values given
in your @{" STARTNET " link AEM-4116} and @{" STOPNET " link AEM-4117} @{b}Tool Types@{ub} or what was last stored in your
@{" configuration file " link AEM-9110}.  If these two @{b}Tool Types@{ub} are not present, these two
string gadgets will be blank unless a previous configuration file is present
and has these calls.

If you do not want what is presented as the default in these two string
gadgets, you can enter the correct path and script name in the string
gadgets.  A full path name to that script must be entered.  If the script
is an @{b}ARexx@{ub} script you should check @{b}ARexx command@{ub}.  @{b}Do not precede the
script name with "rx ".@{ub}  The standard @{b}AmiTCP startnet@{ub} script is @{b}NOT@{ub} an
@{b}ARexx@{ub} script even though it uses @{b}ARexx@{ub} commands.  It is an AmigaDOS
script.  The Miami script which comes with @{b}AEMail@{ub}, on the other hand, is
an @{b}ARexx@{ub} script.

The @{b}[|=|]@{ub} button (@{i}a file folder glyph@{ui}) brings up a file requester to allow
you to find the script you want.  When the string gadget is active you can
also use @{b}Right Amiga f@{ub} to bring up the file requester.

@{b}[CLR]@{ub} will clear the string gadget.  When the string gadget is active you 
can also use @{b}Right Amiga x@{ub} to clear the string gadget.

@{b}[DEFAULT]@{ub} will place the script path and name from your @{b}Tool Types@{ub} in the
appropriate string gadget.  When you are in the string gadget you can use
the string editing key, @{b}Left Amiga d@{ub}, to also bring the default into the
string gadget.

If you need the @{b}Start Net@{ub} script or the @{b}Stop Net@{ub} script to open on the
workbench screen, click on the approriate check mark gadget for the
particular script.  When the TCP/IP Configuration page first opens the
@{b}Start Net Opens on the Workbench@{ub} item will be checkmarked.


                  @{b}@{u}SPECIAL NOTE FOR USERS OF TERMITE TCP@{uu}@{ub}

If you are using a TCP/IP stack that does not have a @{b}Start Net@{ub} or @{b}Stop Net@{ub}
script (such as @{" TermiteTCP " link AEM-9910}), you should use the @{b}[CLR]@{ub} button to clear these
two string gadgets.  Starting and stopping your Internet connection is then
done manually.  Then, when you use the @{" Start Net " link AEM-7501} or @{" Stop Net " link AEM-7502} menu item, 
the action that is performed is to @{" iconify " link AEM-7103} @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  You can then perform 
the network connection in what ever manner was provided by your TCP/IP stack
software.  Once the connection is made, un-iconify @{b}AEMail@{ub} and @{b}AEMail@{ub} will
then check your POP Server for any available messages if that option
was selected (@{i}see below@{ui}).

The @{b}Automatic connection to Internet Provider on AEMAIL Start Up@{ub} check box
provides the same capability as the @{" AUTOCONNECT=YES " link AEM-4118} @{b}Tool Type@{ub}.  When
@{b}AEMail@{ub} is first activated it attempts to determine if if you are connected
to your Internet provider.  If you are not and this item is checked, @{b}AEMail@{ub}
will automatically run your @{b}Start Net@{ub} script.  @{i}However, the @{b}AUTOCONNECT@{ub}
function will be disabled if you do not have a @{b}Start Net@{ub} script.@{ui}

Except when you are using @{b}AEMail@{ub} as a @{" mailto: " link AEM-5300}  agent or when you use the
@{b}ARexx@{ub} command @{" QUIT " link AEM-9531}, when @{b}AEMail@{ub} terminates and you are still connected
to your Internet provider, the following requester will be displayed:


            @{b}Do you wish to terminate your Host connection now?@{ub}


You will given the opportunity to reply with either a @{b}[YES]@{ub} or @{b}[NO]@{ub}. If you
never want you Internet connection to be terminated when you exit from @{b}AEMail@{ub},
you can prevent the above requester from being displayed by @{u}NOT@{uu} checking the
@{b}Display disconnect check on AEMAIL exit@{ub} box.  By default, this box @{u}WILL BE
CHECKED@{uu}, so, to disable the function, you would have to click in this box.
@{i}However, this function will automatically be disabled if you do not have a
@{b}Stop Net@{ub} script.@{ui}

@{i}Please Note:@{ui}  The way @{b}AEMail@{ub} determines if you are still connected is to check
if the @{b}bdsocket.library@{ub} is present.  This library may become present when you
load your TCP/IP stack software.  @{i}Even though you may not be connected, the
@{b}bdsocket.library@{ub} will then be present@{ui}, so you will get the above notification
even though you are not actually connected.  In this event replying with
either @{b}[YES]@{ub} or @{b}[NO]@{ub} to the requester will have no effect.

Whenever @{b}AEMail@{ub} is first loaded and is connected to Internet Provider or
if you select @{" Start Net " link AEM-7501} from the @{" TCP/IP " link AEM-7500} menu, a check will be made for
any mail on your @{b}POP server@{ub} or any mail that must be sent from your @{b}QUEUED@{ub}
folder.  Except when you are using @{b}AEMail@{ub} as a @{b}mailto:@{ub} agent, this same
check is also performed when you quit @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  You can disable any of
these checks by checking the appropriate box in the following lines:


@{b}Disable Queued Mail Check [] on Internet connection [] at AEMAIL exit@{ub}
   @{b}Disable New Mail Check [] on Internet connection [] at AEMAIL exit@{ub}


@{b}AEMail@{ub} also has the capability for checking for mail periodically on your
@{b}POP Server@{ub}.  This function is performed in the background so you can be
doing other activities while this check is going on.  When mail is found,
the following requester will pop up on your screen:


                             @{b}YOU HAVE MAIL!!

                  @{i}n@{ui} Messages available on the POP Server

                Do you wish to receive these messages now?@{ub}


Replying @{b}[YES]@{ub} to the above requester will start the retrieval of the
messages. If you are in iconify mode when this occurs, the retrieval will
occur in the background without bringing up the @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen.

You can set the time interval for this check by entering the appropriate
number of minutes in the following numeric gadget:

                  @{b}Check for new mail every [  ] minutes@{ub}

The default time interval is @{i}2 minutes@{ui}.  If you enter a zero in this
numeric gadget, no check will be made.  This gadget has an up/down arrow
for incrementing or decrementing the value.  You can not decrement it
below zero.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4500 "CONFIGURATION: Configuration Setup Window/Path Page"

                            @{b}Default Path Page@{ub}

The @{b}Default Path page@{ub} appears as follows:

    @{b}=========================================================================
    [o] AEMail Configuration Setup
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          -------
     ____________________| Paths |__________________________________________
    |                                                                       |
    |            Mail Directory: [                                         ]|
    |                                                                       |
    |          TCP Logging File: [                      ][|=|][CLR][DEFAULT]|
    |                                                                       |
    |                            [ ] TCP Logging Active on AEMail startup   |
    |                                                                       |
    |   Retrieve Mail Directory: [                      ][|=|][CLR][DEFAULT]|
    |                                                                       |
    |       Save Mail Directory: [                      ][|=|][CLR][DEFAULT]|
    |                                                                       |   
    | Add Attachments Directory: [                      ][|=|][CLR][DEFAULT]|
    |                                                                       |
    |Save Attachments Directory: [                      ][|=|][CLR][DEFAULT]|
    |_______________________________________________________________________|

    [      Use      ] [      Save      ] [    Save As    ] [     Cancel     ]

    ==========================================================================@{ub}


String gadgets are provided for giving the full path for each of the
default directories and or file.  The directory paths that can be
specified are:

    @{b}Mail Directory:@{ub} This is the directory that contains your
        mail files.  This string gadget is read only and cannot be
        modified.  It is for informational purposes only.  @{i}To change
        mail directory you will have to change it with the @{" Installation " link AEM-3000}
        script with an update for this user.@{ui}

    @{b}TCP Logging File:@{ub}  This allows you to enter a file name as well
        as a path.  The default path and file name is @{b}tcplog@{ub} in
        the @{b}AEMail@{ub} @{i}program directory@{ui}.  If this field is cleared, no
        TCP logging can take place.  When the @{b}[SAVE], [SAVE AS]@{ub} or
        @{b}[USE]@{ub} gadgets are selected, if @{b}TCP Logging@{ub} was @{" Active " link AEM-7503} and
        the @{" TCP logging File " link AEM-9180} name that was entered is different
        from the @{i}current@{ui} @{b}log file@{ub}, the current log file will be
        @{i}closed@{ui} and a new file @{i}opened@{ui}.  If you @{i}clear@{ui} this field
        TCP logging will stop since there is no file to log to.

        Whether logging takes place or not will depend on the
        @{" TCP/IP/TCP Logging File/Active " link AEM-7503} menu item (checkmarked
        flag).

        You can cause @{b}TCP logging@{ub} to be @{i}active@{ui} when @{b}AEMail@{ub} @{i}starts up@{ui} by
        checking the @{b}TCP Logging Active on AEMAIL startup@{ub} check mark
        gadget below the @{b}TCP Logging File@{ub} string gadget. If this item
        is checked, the logging will become @{b}Active@{ub} when you exit from
        @{b}Configuration Setup@{ub}.  You will have to turn off the @{b}Active@{ub}
        flag in the @{b}TCP/IP/TCP Logging File@{ub} menu item to stop logging.

        Note: none of the actions mentioned above will take place 
        until you select @{b}[USE], [SAVE]@{ub} or @{b}[SAVE TO]@{ub} at the bottom 
        of the Configuration Setup Window.  If you select @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} no 
        change will be made in your TCP logging activity.


    @{b}Retrive Mail Directory:@{ub}  This is the initial path that will appear
        in the file requester when you @{" Retrieve mail from a file  " link AEM-6111} rather
        than your @{b}POP Server@{ub}.  The default directory for these files is 
        @{b}PROGDIR:@{ub} which is your current @{b}AEMail@{ub} program directory.  If you 
        regularly are trying to bring in mail that was previously transferred 
        using another mail user agent such as @{i}AmiPOP@{ui}, @{i}AirMail@{ui}, or @{i}Voodoo@{ui},
        you should use the directory that was used for these agents for 
        storing mail.  You can specify any directory of your choosing as 
        the default path for the @{b}Retrieve Mail file requester@{ub}.  You enter
        that default in this string gadget.

    @{b}Save Mail Directory:@{ub}  This is the initial path that will appear
        in the file requester when you select the @{" Save Message to File " link AEM-6050}
        icon in the @{" command icon strip " link AEM-6000}.  The default directory for this
        path is @{b}PROGDIR:@{ub}, which is your current program directory.
        However, you can specify any other path of your choosing as
        the default path for the @{b}Save Mail file requester@{ub}.  You enter
        that default in this string gadget.

    @{b}Add Attachments from Directory:@{ub}  This is the initial path that will
        appear in the file requester when you select the @{b}[REQ]@{ub} button
        in the @{" Add Attachment requester " link AEM-8710}.  The default directory for this
        path is @{b}PROGDIR:@{ub}. However, you can specify any other path of your
        choosing as the default path for the @{b}Add Attachment requester@{ub}.
        You enter that default in this string gadget.

    @{b}Save Attachments Directory:@{ub}  This is the initial path that will
        appear in the file requester when you select the @{b}[Save]@{ub} or
        @{b}[View & Save]@{ub} buttons in the @{" Attachment requester " link AEM-8610}.  The default
        directory for this path is @{b}RAM:@{ub}.  However, you can specify any
        other path of your choosing as the default path for the
        @{b}Attachment file requester@{ub}.  You enter that default in this
        string gadget.

When this page is first activated, the values that were last saved in the
@{i}current@{ui} @{" configuration file " link AEM-9110} will be displayed.

The buttons to the side of each string gadget perform the following
actions:

    @{b}[|=|]@{ub} (@{i}a file folder glyph@{ui}) causes a file requester to appear for
        selecting the appropriate directory and file name (@{b}TCP Logging
        File@{ub} only) to be loaded into the appropriate string gadget.
        The file requester will start out with the last path that was
        used for that particular string gadget.  If no path was last
        used, a dummy name of @{b}VOLUMES@{ub} will be used, the requester
        will flash, and the volumes and assigns will be displayed.

        When the string gadget is active you can also use @{b}Right Amiga f@{ub}
        to bring up the file requester.

    @{b}[CLR]@{ub} will cause the string gadget to be cleared.  When the string
        gadget is active you can also use @{b}Right Amiga x@{ub} to clear the
        string gadget.


    @{b}[DEFAULT]@{ub} will cause default information, as described above, to be
        loaded into the appropriate string gadget except that the @{b}PROGDIR:@{ub}
        designation will be expanded to the full path name of the program
        directory.  When the string gadget is active, you can also use
        @{b}Right Amiga d@{ub} to bring the default information into the string
        gadget.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4600 "CONFIGURATION: Configuration Setup Window/Viewer Page"

                               @{b}Viewer Page@{ub}

The @{b}Viewer page@{ub} appears as follows:

    @{b}=========================================================================
    [o] AEMail Configuration Setup
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------
                                  --------
     ____________________________| Viewer |_________________________________
    |  __________________________________________________________________   |
    | | Mime Type/Subtype | Viewer Program                               |  |
    | |---------------------------------------------------------------------|
    | | text/*            | sys:Utilities/multiview %s                   | ||
    | | message/*         | sys:Utilities/multiview %s                   | ||
    | | image/*           | sys:Utilities/multiview %s screen            | ||
    | | audio/*           | sys:Utilities/multiview %s screen            | ||
    | | video/*           | sys:Utilities/multiview %s screen            | ||
    | |                   |                                              | ||
    | |                   |                                              |^||
    | |___________________|______________________________________________|V||
    |                                                              ________ |
    | Mime Type: [ text              |<] / [                 ][*] |        ||
    |                                                             |[ New  ]||
    |            [] Opens on Workbench [] Called with Run [] ARexx|        ||
    |                                                             |[Delete]||
    |    Viewer: [                                        ] [|=|] |        ||
    |                                                             |[  OK  ]||
    | Arguments: [                                        ] [%s ] |________||
    |_______________________________________________________________________|

    [      Use      ] [      Save      ] [    Save As    ] [     Cancel     ]

    =========================================================================@{ub}

The @{b}Viewer page@{ub} is used to create and or modify your @{" mailcap file " link AEM-9100}.  When
the page is activated the currrent mailcap file will be displayed in the
listview list.  The items at the bottom of the page will be disabled with
the exception of the @{b}[ New ]@{ub} button.

To create a new entry in the @{b}mailcap@{ub}, click on @{b}[ New ]@{ub}.  At this point all
of the items at the bottom of the page, with the exception of the @{b}[Delete]@{ub}
button will become enabled.  You can now enter the information for the
mailcap entry in the gadgets below the listview.

@{b}Mime Type:@{ub} is a chooser box.  If you click into the body of the gadget, a
list of mime types will appear as follows:

    @{b}text
    message
    image
    audio
    video@{ub}

You can choose the @{b}Mime Type@{ub} that you want and it will be transferred to
the @{b}Mime Type@{ub} box.  The button to the right of the box (@{b}[<]@{ub}) acts like a
cycle gadget, cycling through the varies @{b}Mime Types@{ub}.

The large box to the right of the @{b}/@{ub} is for the mime subtype.  It is a
string gadget in which you can enter the subtype you want.  The gadget @{b}[*]@{ub}
to the right of this brings up a list of possible mime subtypes.  You can
select from this list, or, if the one you want is not in the list, enter it
into the string gadget.  If you select from the list, it will be
transferred to the string gadget.

The boxes below the @{b}Mime Type/Subtype@{ub} row are for entering information
about your viewer.  The check boxes, @{b}Opens On Workbench@{ub}, @{b}Called with
Run@{ub} and @{b}ARexx@{ub}, indicate how your viewer program will be executed.  If
@{b}Opens On Workbench@{ub} is checked, your viewer program will open on the
Workbench.  If the viewer program must be called with @{b}run >NIL:@{ub}, check
the @{b}Called with Run@{ub} box, and if it is an @{b}ARexx@{ub} command, check the
@{b}ARexx@{ub} box.

The string gadget, @{b}Viewer:@{ub}, contains the full path name of your viewer
program.  The [@{b}|=|@{ub}] (@{i}folder glyph@{ui}) calls up a file requester so you can
select the Viewer program from the file list.

Enter any arguments the Viewer program needs into the @{b}Arguments:@{ub} string
gadget.  You must always have a @{b}%s@{ub} in the argument to specify the file
that will be displayed with the viewer.  If you click on the @{b}[%s]@{ub} gadget,
a @{b}%s@{ub} will be placed at the end of what has so far been typed into the
argument.

Also, the normal clipboard commands (@{b}Right Amiga c@{ub}, @{b}Right Amiga v@{ub},
etc) work in any of the string gadgets.

When everything is entered correctly, click on @{b}[ OK ]@{ub}.  Your @{b}Mime
Type/Subtype@{ub} and @{b}Viewer Program@{ub} will be trasferred to the listview.
Placement of the line in the listview will be according to the Mime Type
positioning (i.e., text before message before image, etc.).

As an example of how the Viewer program entry gadgets work let's assume
you have entered or checked:

    @{b}"Called with Run"
    "ARexx"
    Viewer: @{ub}REXX:html.aem
    @{b}Arguments: @{ub}%s

The following will be shown under the Viewer Program:

    @{b}run >NIL: rx REXX:html.aem %s@{ub}

If you had added @{b}"Opens On Workbench"@{ub}, the following would be shown:

    @{b}wb;run >NIL: rx REXX:html.aem %s@{ub}

If you want to modify or delete an entry in your @{b}mailcap file@{ub}, simply
click on the entry in the listview.  Information from the listview line
you clicked on will be transferred to the gadgets below the listview.  The
@{b}Mime Type/Subtype@{ub} row will be disabled allowing you to only modify the
@{b}Viewer@{ub} program.

If you click on @{b}[Delete]@{ub}, the entry in the listwiew will be deleted.  If
you click on @{b}[ OK ]@{ub} after making any changes in your Viewer program, the
line for that @{b}Mime Type/Subtype@{ub} in the listview will be replaced with the
information you just modified.

If you wish to recover an entry you have just deleted, information about
that entry will remain in the gadgets even though the gadgets are
disabled.  Clicking on @{b}[ New ]@{ub} and then @{b}[ OK ]@{ub} will restore the entry.

You are not allowed to create a new @{b}Mime Type/Subtype@{ub} that is the same as
an existing @{b}Mime Type/Subtype@{ub}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4700 "CONFIGURATION: Configuration Setup Window/ARexx Page"

                                @{b}ARexx Page@{ub}


The @{b}ARexx page@{ub} appears as follows:

    @{b}=========================================================================
    [o] AEMail Configuration Setup
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------
                                           -------
     _____________________________________| ARexx |_________________________
    |                                                                       |
    | ___________________________________________________________________   |
    || Event/Key|Title   |Type |FLG|Command                              |  |
    ||----------------------------------------------------------------------|
    || Web Addr |        |AREXX|   |AEMail2:ARexx/html.aem               | ||
    ||Email Add |        |AREXX|   |AEMail2:ARexx/sendmsg.aem            | ||
    ||          |        |     |   |                                     | ||
    ||       F1 |Get WWW |AREXX|   |REXX: html.aem                       | ||
    ||       F2 |IBROWSE |DOS  | A |IBrowse:IBrowse                      | ||
    ||       F3 |Place In|AREXX|   |AEMail2:ARexx/placeaddr.aem          | ||
    ||       F4 |Place Ad|AREXX|   |AEMail2:ARexx/placefrp.aem           | ||
    ||       F5 |Delete A|AREXX|   |AEMail2:ARexx/deladrgrp.aem          | ||
    ||       F6 |        |     |   |                                     |^||
    ||       F7 |        |     |   |                                     |V||
    |-----------------------------------------------------------------------|
    | ------------Select Event/Function Key from the above list------------ |
    ||                                                                     ||
    || [AREXX |<] [                                          ] [|=|] [CLR] ||
    ||                                                                     ||
    || Menu Title: [                    ]                            [CLR] ||
    ||                                                                     ||
    || [ ] Opens on Workbench        [ ] Executes Asychronously       [OK] ||
    ||_____________________________________________________________________||
    |_______________________________________________________________________|

    [      Use      ] [      Save      ] [    Save As    ] [     Cancel     ]

    ==========================================================================@{ub}

The @{b}ARexx Page@{ub} will allow you to assign @{b}ARexx@{ub} or @{b}DOS@{ub} commands to function
keys and to certain events that occur within @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  It will also allow
you to assign a menu title for the @{b}ARexx@{ub} or @{b}DOS@{ub} command that will be
placed in the @{" ARexx/DOS menu " link AEM-7600}.

At the present time there are only two events that can be defined:  when
you double click on a @{b}web address@{ub} in a message or when you double click on
an @{b}email address@{ub} in a message.

At the top of the page is a scrolling listview that displays all of the 
events and function keys on the left hand side.  Not only are function 
keys included in the list, but also the shift key plus the function keys 
@{b}(SHFT F@{i}n@{ui})@{ub}, the control key plus the function keys @{b}(CTRL F@{i}n@{ui})@{ub}, and the Alt 
key plus the function keys @{b}(ALT F@{i}n@{ui})@{ub}.  This gives the possibility of 40 
commands being associated with function keys; although, some key 
combinations may not be effective if they are used by other programs or 
commodities.

The column entitled @{b}Title@{ub} gives the @{b}Menu Title@{ub} that will be used in the
@{" ARexx/DOS menu " link AEM-7600}.  If an entry in the column is blank, no menu entry will be 
made for this command.

The column entitled @{b}Type@{ub} indicates the type of command: @{b}AREXX@{ub} or @{b}DOS@{ub}.
The @{b}FLG@{ub} column indicates @{b}W@{ub} if the command opens on the Workbench and
@{b}A@{ub} if the command executes asychronously (with @{b}RUN >NIL:@{ub}).  These two 
flags only apply to @{b}DOS@{ub} commands.

The @{b}Command@{ub} column indicates the @{b}ARexx@{ub} or @{b}DOS@{ub} command script or program
that will be executed when the function key is pressed.  This should be
the full path name for the script or program.

In the example above, the two events have been defined to call @{b}html.aem@{ub},
which calls your selected browser if a web address is double clicked, and
@{b}sendmsg.aem@{ub} to send an email message to the selected address if a email
address is double clicked.

Since other action may be desireable when an email address is selected,
you will notice that the @{b}F3, F4,@{ub} and @{b}F5@{ub} function keys have been defined to
call @{b}placeaddr.aem@{ub} (to place address in address book), @{b}placegrp.aem@{ub} (to
place address in a group), and @{b}deladrgrp.aem@{ub} (to delete address from a
group) respectively.  They have also been defined with menu items ("Place
Individual Address", "Place Address in Group", and "Delete Address from
Group".

To ensure that the @{b}sendmsg.aem@{ub} script is not automatically called when you
double click on the email address, you will have to hold down the @{b}CTRL@{ub} key
when you double click.  This will bring up the Clipboard requester (see
@{" Using the Clipboard with AEMail " link AEM-5500}) and you can either press the appropriate
function key or select the appropriate menu item to execute the @{b}ARexx@{ub}
script.

Below the listview is a boxed area which initially has the heading @{b}Select
Event/Function Key from the above list@{ub}.  Initially all of the gadgets in 
this boxed area are disabled.

When you click on one of the events or function keys in the listview, the 
heading of the boxed area changes to @{b}Command for F@{i}n@{ui}@{ub}, where @{b}F@{i}n@{ui}@{ub} is the 
function key you clicked on (or "Command for @{i}event@{ui}"), and the boxed area 
becomes enabled.  If there was a command already defined for that function 
key or event, the information will be transferred to the appropriate 
gadgets within the boxed area.

The cycle gadget (@{i}indicated by @{ui}@{b}|<]@{ub}) has two states: @{b}AREXX@{ub} and @{b}DOS@{ub}.  If you
select @{b}AREXX@{ub} the checkmarked gadgets @{b}Opens on Workbench@{ub} and @{b}Executes
Asychronously@{ub} are disabled; they only are used with @{b}DOS@{ub} commands.

The string gadget following the cycle gadget is for entering the full path
name of your @{b}ARexx@{ub} or @{b}DOS@{ub} script or @{b}DOS@{ub} program.  The @{b}[|=|]@{ub} (@{i}file folder
glyph@{ui}) is used to bring up a file requester to find the script or program
that you want.  If you have activated the string gadget, you can also use
@{b}Right Amiga f@{ub} to call up the file requester.

The @{b}[CLR]@{ub} next to the file folder glyph will clear the string gadget; 
although @{b}Right Amiga x@{ub} will also do this if the string gadget is 
enabled.  The string gadget also supports clipboard actions.

The @{b}Menu Title@{ub} string gadget is used to assign a menu name to the
@{" ARexx/DOS menu " link AEM-7600} that will call this command.  A maximum of 21 characters 
can be used for a @{b}Menu Title@{ub}.  If this string gadget is left blank, no 
menu name will be assigned and you can only use the appropriate function 
key to call the command.  The @{b}[CLR]@{ub} to the far right on this row clears 
the @{b}Menu Title@{ub}.  When you are in the string gadget, @{b}Right Amiga x@{ub} will
also clear the string.  This string gadget also supports clipboard
actions.

The two checkmark gadgets on the second row are used for @{b}DOS@{ub} commands
only.  They will be disabled for @{b}ARexx@{ub} commands.

If @{b}Opens on Workbench@{ub} is checked, a switch will be made to the Workbench
screen when the command is executed.  This is not necessary for @{b}ARexx@{ub}
command since there is an @{b}AEMail ARexx@{ub} command that will do this.

The @{b}Execute Asynchronously@{ub} checkmark gadget is used to execute the @{b}DOS@{ub}
command in the background.  This will allow @{b}AEMail@{ub} to function when the
program that is called is being executed.  This item is, by default,
checkmarked.  If for some reason you want @{b}AEMail@{ub} to freeze while the
command (program) is being executed, you can un-checkmark this item.
Since all @{b}ARexx@{ub} commands automatically execute in the background, this item
is uneccessary for @{b}ARexx@{ub} command scripts.

When you have completed entering the data, click on @{b}[OK]@{ub}.  The information
will be transferred to the appropriate entry in the listview.  If you 
cleared the string gadget, any command information, including @{b}Type@{ub} and 
@{b}FLGS@{ub} as well, will be cleared for this event or function key in the 
listview.

@{b}Please Note:  If you are an Un-Registered user of AEMail, @{i}you can not save
the ARexx/DOS command list@{ui}.  This means that whenever you quit AEMail the
list of commands will not be remembered.  You will need to re-enter them
the next time you load AEMail.@{ub}


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4800 "CONFIGURATION: Configuration Setup Window/Fonts Page"

                                @{b}Fonts Page@{ub}


The @{b}Fonts page@{ub} appears as follows:

    @{b}=========================================================================
    [o] AEMail Configuration Setup
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------
                                                   -------
     _____________________________________________| Fonts |_________________
    |                                                                       |
    | -Configuration Page Font------------------------ ____________________ |
    |                                                 |                    ||
    | Font: [topaz.font  ] Size: [  8] [Ff] [DEFAULT] |AaBbCcDcEeFfGg..1234||
    |                                                 |____________________||
    | -AEMail Screen Font----------------------------- ____________________ |
    |                                                 |                    ||
    | Font: [topaz.font  ] Size: [  8] [Ff] [DEFAULT] |AaBbCcDcEeFfGg..1234||
    |                                                 |____________________||
    | -AEMail General Font---------------------------- ____________________ |
    |                                                 |                    ||
    | Font: [topaz.font  ] Size: [  8] [Ff] [DEFAULT] |AaBbCcDcEeFfGg..1234||
    |                                                 |____________________||
    | -Folder Font------------------------------------ ____________________ |
    |                                                 |                    ||
    | Font: [topaz.font  ] Size: [  8] [Ff] [DEFAULT] |AaBbCcDcEeFfGg..1234||
    |                                                 |____________________||
    | -Message Font----------------------------------- ____________________ |
    |                                                 |                    ||
    | Font: [topaz.font  ] Size: [  8] [Ff] [DEFAULT] |AaBbCcDcEeFfGg..1234||
    |                                                 |____________________||
    |_______________________________________________________________________|

    [      Use      ] [      Save      ] [    Save As    ] [     Cancel     ]

    =========================================================================@{ub}


The @{b}Fonts Page@{ub} will allow you to change the fonts for certain AEMail
displays.  The areas that you can change fonts for are:

    @{b}Configuration Page Font
    AEMail Screen Font
    AEMail General Font
    Folder Font
    Message Font@{ub}

The @{b}Configuration Page Font@{ub} will change the font for the @{b}Configuration
screen@{ub} and each of the pages on it.  If you are running on a
non-interlaced Workbench screen with a width of no more than 640
characters, you might find that you will have to change this font to allow
everything to fit on the screen.  You can use any font or font size
including proportional or fixed fonts.

The @{b}Configuration Page Font@{ub} will not take effect until you exit from the
@{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub} and then recall the @{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub}.

The @{b}AEMail Screen Font@{ub} will change the font for the main @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen and
window titles, the font used by system requesters, and the font used for
menus.  Any font or font size can be used, fixed or proportional.  @{i}This
will not effect the screen font used by the configuration Setup Window, 
however.@{ui}  You will have to do that with the @{b}Workbench Fonts Preferences.@{ub}

The @{b}Folder Font@{ub} will only change the font in the folder strip.  It has the
same effect as the @{" FLDRFONT= " link AEM-4124} and @{" FLDRFONTSZ= " link AEM-4124} Tool Types.  Any font or
font size can be used, fixed or proportional.

The @{b}Message Font@{ub} will change the font used for displaying messages.  While
any font or font size, fixed or proportional, can be used, watch out for
proportional fonts.  @{i}If the message has long lines, it may take
significantly longer to display the message than with a fixed font.@{ui}

Finally, the @{b}AEMail General Font@{ub} effects the body fonts used in all other
windows in @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  This font has certain restrictions.  @{b}It must be size 8
and must be a fixed font.@{ub}

The only gadgets that are active for each font are the @{b}[Ff]@{ub} and @{b}[DEFAULT]@{ub}
gadgets.  @{b}[Ff]@{ub} will bring up a font requester so that you can select the
font you want and @{b}[DEFAULT]@{ub} will change the font to @{b}topaz.font@{ub} size @{b}8@{ub}.
The @{b}Font:@{ub} and @{b}Size:@{ub} gadgets are @{i}read only@{ui} to show you what font is
currently being used and the boxed area to the right which shows a sample
of the font.  If you want to change a font use the font requester.

Take care when you change fonts.  If you do not choose your fonts
carefully, you could end up with windows that are too big to fit on the
ecreen or requesters that are chopped off at the bottom.  A proportional
font used as the @{b}Screen font@{ub} could cause certain requesters to appear
mis-proportioned.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4900 "CONFIGURATION: Configuration Setup Window/General Parameters Page"

                         @{b}General Parameters Page@{ub}

The @{b}General Parameters page@{ub} appears as follows:

    @{b}=========================================================================
    [o] AEMail Configuration Setup
    -------------------------------------------------------------------------
                                                           ---------
     _____________________________________________________| General |_______
    |                                                                       |
    | Printer Device: [PRT:        ][|=|][CLR][DEFAULT]   Top Margin:[ 4]/| |
    |                                                                       |
    | [ ] Include Attachment List in Print Out              [Printer Setup] |
    |                                                                       |
    |           Editor: [                              ][|=|][CLR][DEFAULT] |
    |                                                                       |
    | Editor Arguments: [               ] [ ] Editor Opens on the Workbench |
    |                                                                       |
    | ------------------Default Reply to Message Parameters---------------- |
    ||                                                                     ||
    || [ ] Quote Original Message Text          Quote Prefix: [>         ] ||
    ||                                                                     ||
    || Quote Header: [                                                   ] ||
    | --------------------------------------------------------------------- |
    |                                                                       |
    | [ ] Clone Workbench Screen Mode                     [Set Screen Mode] |
    |                                                                       |
    | [Set Minimum Headers]                                [Set Menu Flags] |
    |_______________________________________________________________________|

    [      Use      ] [      Save      ] [    Save As    ] [     Cancel     ]

    =========================================================================@{ub}


The @{b}General Parameters@{ub} page allows you to set up certain general type
parameters such as specifications for your @{b}printer device@{ub}, the @{b}screen
mode@{ub} that you want your @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen to open on, the @{b}list of minimum
headers@{ub} you want displayed in a message, certain @{b}default menu checkmarked@{ub}
items, the specification for your @{b}editor@{ub}, and the specifications for the
@{b}default message reply headers@{ub}.

For the @{b}Printer Device@{ub} you can specify the device that you want to do your
printing on.  By default this is @{b}PRT:@{ub}, but you can specify a file if you
care to.  If you specify a file, your printer output will be sent as
standard @{b}ASCII@{ub} text with form feeds and margin spacing included in the
output.  The @{b}[|=|]@{ub} (@{i}file folder glyph@{ui}) button will call up a file 
requester through which you can enter the path and file name of this 
printer file.  @{b}[CLR]@{ub} will clear the string gadget and @{b}[DEFAULT]@{ub} will enter 
@{b}PRT:@{ub} into the gadget.  When this screen is first displayed, the @{b}PRT:@{ub} 
default name will be in the gadget.

If the @{b}Printer Device@{ub} string gadget is activated you can also use @{b}Right
Amiga f@{ub} to call up the file requester, @{b}Right Amiga x@{ub} to clear the
string, and @{b}Right Amiga d@{ub} to bring @{b}PRT:@{ub} into the gadget.

You can also specify the @{b}Top Margin@{ub} of the printout with the numeric
string gadget to the right of the @{b}Printer Device@{ub}.  The default top margin
is @{i}4@{ui}.

If you do want the list of attachments to appear on the last page of your
printout, you can check the @{b}Include Attachment List in Print Out@{ub} box.
By default, this box is checked when you first call up the @{b}General
Parameters@{ub} page.

If you want to modify your printer setup parameters that are normally set
with your @{b}PRINTER PREFERENCES@{ub}, you can click on the @{b}[Printer Setup]@{ub}
button.  This will call up the standard @{b}Printer Preferences@{ub} program so
that you can change your printer setup.  @{i}Please @{ub}Note@{ub}@{ui} that, if you change
the printer preferences, the new preferences will remain in effect when
you quit @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

For the @{b}Editor@{ub} string gadget you must use the full path name of the
editor of your choice.  The @{b}Editor Arguments:@{ub} string gadget is used to
enter any parameters you want to use when you call your editor.  To
specify where the file name you are editing goes use @{b}%s@{ub}.  An example
would be:

    @{b}Editor:@{ub} c:ed
    @{b}Editor Arguments:@{ub} %s

Next to the @{b}Editor Arguments:@{ub} string gadget is a checkmark gadget which
is used to tell @{b}AEMail@{ub} that your editor will open on the Workbench screen.
If your editor of choice does not open on it's own screen, you must check
this item.  The @{b}AmigaDos editor, ed@{ub}, does @{u}NOT@{uu} open on it's own screen;
therefor @{i}you must check this item if you are using @{b}ed@{ub}@{ui}.

The @{b}[DEFAULT]@{ub} for the @{b}Editor@{ub} is the information from the @{b}EDITOR= Tool Type@{ub}.
If the key word @{b}WB;@{ub} precedes the editor call information in the tool
type, the @{b}Editor Opens on Workbench@{ub} item will be checkmarked.  @{b}WB;@{ub}
will @{u}NOT@{uu} appear in the @{b}Editor@{ub} string gadget.

If the @{b}EDITOR= Tool Type@{ub} was not provided, the following will be the
default edit call:

    @{b}Editor:@{ub} c:ed
    @{b}Editor Arguments:@{ub} %s

and the @{b}Editor Opens on Workbench@{ub} item @{i}will be@{ui} checkmarked.  This
uses the default AmigaDos editor, @{b}ed@{ub}.

If you need to find where your editor is located, @{b}[|=|]@{ub} (@{i}file folder
glyph@{ui}) causes a file requester to appear for selecting the appropriate 
program file to be loaded into the @{b}Editor@{ub} string gadget.

If the @{b}Editor:@{ub} string gadget is activated you can use @{b}Right Amiga f@{ub} to 
call up the file requester, @{b}Right Amiga d@{ub} to call up the default, and
@{b}Right Amiga x@{ub} to clear the @{b}Editor:@{ub} string gadget.

The section below the heading @{b}Default Reply to Message Parameters@{ub} is
used to set up the default actions when you are replying to a message.
The @{b}Quote Original Message Text@{ub} box sets up the default action for
quoting the original text in a message.  Even though you take the default
of not quoting text, you will given an opportunity to change you mind
about this when you compose the message.

The @{b}Quote Prefix:@{ub} string gadget indicates what is to be placed in front 
of each quoted line if an original message is quoted.  This, by default,
is @{b}>@{ub}; however, you can use any other prefix as the default that you
like.

A @{b}Quote header:@{ub} will be placed on the line in front of the quoted
material. You can choose what you would like as the default heading and
enter it in this string gadget.  By default, the header which will
initially appear in the @{b}Quote Header:@{ub} string gadget is:

    @{b}On &(week), &(date2), at &(time), &(name) wrote:@{ub}

The @{b}&@{ub} followed by a field name in parenthesis indicates substitution of
data from the original message's headers.  The values that can be
substituted are:

    @{b}&(name)@{ub}     The @{b}Real Name@{ub} of the sender of the original
                message.  If the @{b}Real Name@{ub} is not available,
                the sender's @{b}UserID@{ub} will be used instead

    @{b}&(subject)@{ub}  The subject from the original message.  Any @{b}RE:@{ub}
                or @{b}(fwd)@{ub} will be stripped.

    @{b}&(week)@{ub}     The day of the week that the original message
                was sent.

    @{b}&(date)@{ub}     The date the original message was sent in the form
                @{i}dd mmm yyyy@{ui}, where @{i}dd@{ui} is the day of the month,
                @{i}mmm@{ui} is month in the form @{b}Jan, Feb, Mar,@{ub} etc, and
                @{i}yyyy@{ui} is the full 4 digit year.

    @{b}&(date1)@{ub}    Same as @{b}&(date)@{ub}.

    @{b}&(date2)@{ub}    The date in the form @{i}mmm dd, yyyy@{ui}.

    @{b}&(time)@{ub}     The time the original message was sent in the
                form @{i}hh:mm x@{ui}@{b}M@{ub} where @{i}hh@{ui} is the hour on a @{u}12 hour@{uu}
                clock, @{b}mm@{ub} is the minute, and @{i}x@{ui}@{b}M@{ub} is @{b}AM@{ub} or @{b}PM@{ub}.

    @{b}&(to)@{ub}       The email address the message was sent to.  For
                mailing lists this could be the name of the mailing
                list if that is what appeared in the @{b}To:@{ub} header.

The @{b}Quote Header@{ub} is designed to be modified by the user and can be
changed with this string gadget.  This is a permanent change if you select
@{b}[SAVE]@{ub} to save the Configuration data, or it can be in effect as the
default for only this running of @{b}AEMail@{ub} if you select @{b}[USE]@{ub}.  You can
always change this default, however, when you @{" compose " link AEM-8700} a message.

If you want to set your screen mode for @{b}AEMail@{ub}, you can click on the
@{b}[Set Screen Mode]@{ub} button.  This will call up a standard @{b}Screen Mode Requester@{ub}
which will allow you to set whatever screen mode you wish.  Your overscan mode
can also be set.  This defaults to @{b}OVERSCAN-TEXT@{ub}.

To the left of the @{b}[Set Screen Mode]@{ub} button is a checkmark gadget labeled
@{b}Clone Workbench Screen Mode@{ub}.  If you select this gadget @{b}AEMail@{ub} will use
whatever screen mode is currently set for your Workbench through the @{b}Set
Screen Mode Preferences@{ub} program.  If the @{b}Workbench Screen Mode@{ub} is changed,
@{b}AEMail@{ub} will open with that screen mode the next time it is loaded.

If the @{b}Clone Workbench Screen Mode@{ub} is checkmarked, the @{b}[Set Screen Mode]@{ub}
button will be disabled.

When you save your configuration settings, the screen mode you selected 
and the overscan setting are saved in the @{b}AEMail@{ub} @{" configuration file " link AEM-9110} and 
will be used the next time you load @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  They will also be in effect 
when you return from the @{b}Edit Configuration@{ub} Setup Window.

The minimum header set that you want displayed in your message can be set
by clicking on the @{b}[Set Minimum Headers]@{ub} button.  This will bring up the
@{" Set Minimum Headers " link AEM-4910} requester.

The @{b}[Set Menu Flags]@{ub} gadget brings up the @{" Set Menu Flags " link AEM-4920} window that has
five check boxes in it which correspond to the flags under the @{" Messages " link AEM-7300}
and @{" Retrieve Msgs " link AEM-7400} menus.

@{b}Please Note:@{ub} Because of a problem with @{b}ClassAct@{ub}, the @{b}[Printer Setup]@{ub}, @{b}[Set 
Screen Mode]@{ub}, @{b}[Set Minimum Headers]@{ub} and @{b}[Set Menu Flags]@{ub} gadgets will not
work under @{b}AmigaDOS 2.x@{ub}.  There is no problem with these gadgets under
@{b}AmigaDOS 3.x@{ub}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4910 "CONFIGURATION: Set Minimum Headers requester"

                           @{b}Set Minimum Headers@{ub}

The @{b}Set Minimum Headers@{ub} requester looks like this:

                   @{b}|==================================|
                   |[o]  Set Minimum Headers          |
                   |==================================|
                   |      Select/Deselect Headers     |
                   |          to be displayed         |
                   |==================================|
                   || *bcc:                        | ||
                   || *cc:                         | ||
                   ||  Content-Transfer-Encoding:  | ||
                   ||  Content-Type:               | ||
                   || *Date:                       | ||
                   || *From:                       | ||
                   |==================================|
                   |         Enter New Header         |
                   |[                                ]|
                   |                                  |
                   |              [OK]                |
                   |==================================|@{ub}


A list of possible message headers is displayed in the scrollable list.
An asterick (@{b}*@{ub}) in front of a header indicates that it has been selected
for inclusion in the minimum header list.  Clicking on an item in the list
will select it with an (@{b}*@{ub}).  If it is already selected, it will be
deselected (@{i}the asterick will change to a blank@{ui}).

The string gadget at the bottom of the requester is used to enter a header
that is not in the list.  Be sure to end the header with a colon (@{b}:@{ub}).
After entering the header, press return and the header will be placed
properly in the scollable list.  It will be deselected when it is first
entered in the list.  You will have to click on it to select it.

When you are through entering items in the list, click on @{b}[OK]@{ub} and you will
be returned to the @{b}General Parameters@{ub} page.  Clicking on the @{b}close@{ub}
gadget at the top of the requester has the same effect as clicking on @{b}[OK]@{ub}.

@{b}@{i}Please@{ui} NOTE:@{ub} anything you enter in the list or select/deselect will
remain in the list in that state during the current run of @{b}AEMail@{ub} even if
you click on @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} in the main @{b}Configuration window@{ub}.  In other words,
@{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} for the minimum header list has the same effect as @{b}[USE]@{ub}.
Clicking on @{b}[SAVE]@{ub} or @{b}[SAVE AS]@{ub} at the bottom of the window will
permanently save the headers you have selected.

There is no way to delete a header once it has been entered in the list
and saved except by deleting the @{" .headers " link AEM-9120} file in the @{b}AEMAIL:@{ub} directory.
This is really not a problem, however, since, if you entered an incorrect
header and haven't selected it, it will have no effect on the program.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-4920 "CONFIGURATION: Set Menu Flags window"

                              @{b}Set Menu Flags@{ub}

The @{b}[Set Menu Flags]@{ub} gadget brings up a window that has five check boxes
in it.  These five check boxes are:

    @{b}[ ] Display Full Header
    [ ] Forward Body text Only
    [ ] Include Header in Reply
    [ ] Exclude Duplicate Messages
    [ ] Delete Host Mail@{ub}

These check boxes correspond to the flags under the @{" Messages " link AEM-7300} and
@{" Retrieve Msgs " link AEM-7400} menus.  If you @{b}[SAVE]@{ub} or @{b}[SAVE AS]@{ub} when you exit from the
@{b}Configuration Setup@{ub}, they will set the initial values of these menu items
when you load @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  When you exit from the @{b}Configuration Setup@{ub} with
either @{b}[USE]@{ub}, @{b}[SAVE]@{ub} or @{b}[SAVE AS]@{ub}, the corresponding menu items will be
checked or unchecked depending on the state of these check boxes.

Clicking on the close gadget of the @{b}AEMail Set Menu Flags@{ub} window or
clicking on @{b}[OK]@{ub} will close this window.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-5000 "STARTING AEMAIL"

                             @{b}Starting AEMail@{ub}

@{b}AEMail@{ub} can be started either from the @{b}Workbench@{ub} by double clicking on it's
icon or from the @{b}shell@{ub}.  It is recommended that AEMail be normally run
from the Workbench.  The shell invocation is primarily designed for
@{" mailto: " link AEM-5300} agents in web browsers or to call @{b}AEMail@{ub} from another program
that passes a message to it.

To see how @{b}AEMail@{ub} is invoked from the shell, click @{" here " link AEM-5200}.

@{b}AEMail@{ub} can be run either in an @{b}@{i}offline@{ui}@{ub} or @{b}@{i}online@{ui}@{ub} mode.  This means that
you do not have to be connected to your Internet provider when @{b}AEMail@{ub} is
activated.  However, to actually receive or send mail via your Internet
provider, you must have your TCP/IP stack (@{b}AmiTCP, TermiteTCP, Miami@{ub}, etc)
running and connected to your provider.  You can activate @{b}AEMail@{ub} before
connecting to your provider or after; it makes no difference.

Both a convenient menu item and a command icon have been provided in
@{b}AEMail@{ub} to start your TCP/IP stack (@{" TCP/IP/Start Net " link AEM-7501}) after @{b}AEMail@{ub} is up
and running provided a script can be used to make this connection.  If
a script is not provided for this purpose, @{b}AEMail@{ub} will iconify to allow
you to start your TCP/IP stack manually.  A menu item (@{" TCP/IP/Stop Net " link AEM-7502})
and command icon have also been provided to disconnect your network
connection.

To cause your TCP/IP stack to be executed manually, clear the script names
in the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}, @{" TCP/IP page " link AEM-4400}.

Two command icons have been provided in the Command Icon tool bar to also 
perform @{" Starting and Terminating " link AEM-6130} your TCP/IP Network Connection.

You can also automatically activate your Internet connection at program
startup by providing the @{" AUTOCONNECT=YES " link AEM-4118} @{b}Tool Type@{ub} or by 
checkmarking the @{b}Automatic connection to Internet Provider on AEMAIL Start Up@{b}
in the @{" TCP/IP Page " link AEM-4400} of the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.  

@{b}WARNING:@{ub} for this to work, you will need to be able to activate your 
TCP/IP stack @{i}automatically by a @{b}script@{ub}@{ui}.


                   @{i}Activating AEMail from the Workbench@{ui}


To activate @{b}AEMail@{ub} from the Workbench simply double click on the @{b}AEMail@{ub}
Project icon.  You can also activate @{b}AEMail@{ub} from the shell, but, if 
activated in this manner, it will not have access to the configuration 
information provided by the @{" Tool Types " link AEM-4100}.  It does, however, have access to 
the configuration information in the specified AEMail configuration file
(either @{" s:aemail.cnfg " link AEM-9110} or the file specified with @{" config= " link AEM-5200} in the 
shell calling argument).

@{b}AEMail@{ub} opens on it's own 16 color Public Screen.  The Public Screen name
is @{b}AEMAIL-1@{ub}.  4 of the colors are defined by the first four colors of
the Workbench screen.  The following 8 colors are pre-defined with the
following colors: @{b}Red@{ub} (13R, 0B, 0G), @{b}Green@{ub} (0R, 15G, 0B), @{b}Blue@{ub} (0R, 0G,
15B), @{b}Magenta@{ub} (15R, 0G, 15B), @{b}Yellow@{ub} (15R, 15G, 0B), @{b}Orange@{ub} (15R, 10G,
0B), @{b}Brown@{ub} (10R, 5G, 0B), and @{b}Purple@{ub} (9R, 3G, 9B).  These colors have been
preset to provide a consistant color scheme for displaying icons and
folder tab colors.  Under consideration is the possibility of allowing
these colors to be user settable in the future.

Click @{" here " link AEM-5100} for a description of the main @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen.

Since multiple windows are opened by @{b}AEMail@{ub}, the program opens on it's own
screen to allow uniformity in being able to push the screen to the back
(with all of it's member windows) and back again to the front.  The
@{b}LEFT-AMIGA-M@{ub} key can be used for this purpose.

You can also iconify @{b}AEMail@{ub} with an iconify bar on the Workbench screen. A menu
item in the @{" Project menu " link AEM-7100} has been provided to perform the @{" iconify " link AEM-7103} action.
When this menu item is selected, the @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen will disappear and a @{b}button
bar@{ub} will appear on the Workbench screen with

    @{b}AEMAIL (Click on Close or with RMB to restore)@{ub}

in the title.  When the iconified bar is selected, clicking either on the
@{b}close@{ub} gadget or with the @{b}Right Mouse Button@{ub} (@{i}RMB@{ui}) will restore the @{b}AEMail@{ub}
screen.

There is also a hotkey provided for iconifying @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  This is
@{b}RIGHT-AMIGA-I@{ub}.  This same hot key will also take @{b}AEMail@{ub} out of iconify
mode.  The @{b}LEFT-AMIGA-I@{ub} key will also accomplish this.

Periodically during the running of @{b}AEMail@{ub}, the program will automatically
switch to the Workbench screen for executing certain functions and then
switch back when the function is complete.

The first thing @{b}AEMail@{ub} does when it is activated is check to see that
certain configuration information has been provided.  The necessary items
are:


    @{b}POP3 UserID
    Password
    From Addr (your email address)
    POP Server
    SMTP Server
    Domain Name
    Edit Call@{ub}


If any of these items have not been provided, the following requester will be
displayed:


    @{b}The following Configuration items are empty

    @{i}list of empty items@{ui}

    They are required items!@{ub}


If this requester is displayed, you will be given the following choices:


       @{b}[Configure AEMAIL now]               [Cancel AEMAIL]@{ub}


If you were to click on @{b}[Cancel AEMAIL]@{ub}, @{b}AEMail@{ub} will terminate.  You can
not proceed any further until you have entered these items with the
@{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub} or by providing them as @{" Tool Types " link AEM-4100}.

Clicking on the @{b}[Configure AEMAIL now]@{ub} will bring up the
@{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

If the @{" PASSPROTECT=YES " link AEM-4123} Tool Type was provided (@{b}registered users only@{ub}) the
following window will be displayed:

                @{b}|========================================|
                |0|Enter Password                        |
                |----------------------------------------|
                |                                        |
                |     Enter your new password below      |
                |                                        |
                |  [                                  ]  |
                |                                        |
                |                                        |
                |                                        |
                |  [START OVER]            [  CANCEL  ]  |
                |________________________________________|@{ub}


You must enter your password before you can procede.  You will be allowed
@{i}three@{ui} attempts to enter a correct password.  If the correct password has
not been entered after three attempts, @{b}AEMail@{ub} @{i}will terminate@{ui}.  If the
password is correct, @{b}AEMail@{ub} will continue.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} @{i}since activating the password protection is done by a Tool Type,
password protection is not available when you activate @{b}AEMail@{ub} from the
shell.@{ui}

If this is the first time AEMail has been executed after a new version has
been installed, the @{b}Send AEMail Notification Request@{ub} will appear.  See
@{" REGISTRATION " link AEM-2500} for a description of the Notification Request.

After verifying that required configuration information has been provided
and that correct password has been entered (if required), @{b}AEMail@{ub} will
check to see if you are connected to your Internet provider.  If you are,
connection will be made to your @{b}POP server@{ub} to see if there are any
messages available on the server in your mail box.  If there are, the
following requester will appear:


                  @{b}@{i}n@{ui} Messages Available on the POP Server

                Do you wish to receive these messages now?@{ub}


If you click on the @{b}[YES]@{ub} button, those message will be retrieved at this
point.  See the @{" RETRIEVE MESSAGES " link AEM-6110} command for details on this process.

If you click on @{b}[NO]@{ub}, no message retrieval will take place at this time.
You will need to retrieve these messages later using the @{b}RETRIEVE MESSAGES@{ub}
command icon.

After @{b}AEMail@{ub} checks to see if any messages are available on the @{b}POP
Server@{ub}, it also checks to see if any messages are in the @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder
(messages queued to be sent).  If there are, the following requester will
appear:


                  @{b}You have n messages queued to be sent

                 Do you wish to send these messages now?@{ub}


If you click on the @{b}[YES]@{ub} button, all of the messages in the @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder will
be sent immediately.  This is the same as selecting the @{" Send Queued Mail " link AEM-7102}
item under the @{" Project " link AEM-7100} menu or selecting the @{b}QUEUED FOLDER@{ub} and clicking
on the @{" Send Message Immediately " link AEM-6090} command icon.

If you click on @{b}[NO]@{ub}, the queued messages will not be sent at this time.
You will need to send these messages later using either the @{b}Send Queued
Mail@{ub} item under the @{b}Project menu@{ub} or selecting the @{b}QUEUED FOLDER@{ub} and
clicking on the @{b}Send Message Immediately@{ub} command icon.

If you successfully connected at program startup the following message
will appear in the Title bar of the @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen:


    @{b}TCP/IP session started with @{i}Your-POP-Server-Name@{ui}@{ub}


If you were not connected the following message will appear in the Title
bar:


    @{b}Not Connected to @{i}Your-POP-Server-Name@{ui} Host@{ub}


You can disable either or both the POP mail check or the queued mail check at
startup by checkmarking the appropriate items in the @{" TCP/IP " link AEM-4400} page of the 
@{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

When @{b}AEMail@{ub} is first activated and you are @{b}online@{ub} and have mail and accept it's
transfer, the @{" message list " link AEM-8200} for the @{b}INBOX@{ub} folder will be displayed.  As each
mail message is received you will see it added to the message list of the
@{b}INBOX@{ub}.

If you are @{b}offline@{ub} @{i}or@{ui} there is no mail or mail is not being checked,
the @{" folder list " link AEM-8100} will be displayed.  Double clicking on either the name of a
folder in the list or one of the folder icons will cause the @{b}message list@{ub}
for that folder to be displayed.

Double clicking on a message in the @{b}message list@{ub} will cause that
particular @{" message " link AEM-8600} to be displayed.

If you have selected a time increment in the @{b}TCP/IP@{ub} page of the
@{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub} (@{i}the default is 2 minutes@{ui}), a background 
process will be started which checks your @{b}POP server@{ub} every few minutes (@{i}as 
specified by the interval@{ui}) for messages.  If there are any messages, the 
following requester will pop up:


                             @{b}YOU HAVE MAIL!!

                  @{i}n@{ui} Messages available on the POP Server

                Do you wish to receive these messages now?@{ub}


Replying @{b}[YES]@{ub} to the above requester will start the retrieval of the
messages.  This requester will only pop up when you are not in the middle
of some function such as composing a message, transferring or saving a
message, printing a message, or performing configuration changes.  It will
pop up on the @{b}Workbench screen@{ub} if you have @{b}AEMail@{ub} @{" iconified " link AEM-7103}.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} @{i}if you did not specify that you wanted messages deleted from your
@{b}POP server@{ub} as you transferred them to your Amiga, the @{b}YOU HAVE MAIL!!@{ub}
requester will pop up each time the system checks for mail.@{ui}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-5100 "MAIN AEMAIL SCREEN"

                          @{b}The Main AEMAIL Screen@{ub}

When @{b}AEMail@{ub} first starts, three windows are opened in horizontal bands on
the AEMail screen.  A window is displayed just below the screen
menu/title bar and provides a contextual help title bar and a @{" Command Icon " link AEM-6000}
Tool Bar.  This Tool Bar provides icons for accessing the major functions
of @{b}AEMail@{ub} and consists (from left to right) of the following icons:

    @{" Display Folder List " link AEM-6010}
    @{" Display Address Book " link AEM-6020}
    @{" Retrieve Messages " link AEM-6110}
    @{" Display Previous Message " link AEM-6030}
    @{" Display Previous Folder's Message List " link AEM-6120}
    @{" Display Current Folder's Message List " link AEM-6120}
    @{" Display Next Folder's Message List " link AEM-6120}
    @{" Display Next Message " link AEM-6040}
    @{" Compose a Message " link AEM-6080}
    @{" Queue Message for Later Delivery " link AEM-6100}
    @{" Send Message Immediately " link AEM-6090}
    @{" Save Message To File " link AEM-6050}
    @{" Print " link AEM-6060}
    @{" Delete/Undelete Message " link AEM-6070}
    @{" Copy Messages " link AEM-6140}
    @{" Transfer Messages " link AEM-6150}
    @{" Start TCP/IP Network Connection " link AEM-6130}
    @{" Terminate TCP/IP Network Connection " link AEM-6130}

The window below the command icon tool bar contains a @{b}folder strip@{ub}
set of @{b}icons@{ub}.  An @{b}icon@{ub} is provided for each folder with a colored @{b}tab@{ub} to
indicate the type of folder (of the user's own choosing - see
@{" Folder Configuration Window " link AEM-8300}).

Within each folder icon is a short name (not exceeding 9 characters) for
that folder.  Below this is the total number of messages @{i}minus any deleted
messages@{ui}.  It may be followed by the number of un-read messages in
parenthesis.  If there are unread messages, both numbers will be displayed
in @{b}red@{ub}.  These messages counts will be updated as messages are added or
deleted from the folders.

The height of the folder strip is defined by the @{b}font size@{ub} that is used
for the @{b}folder name@{ub} and the @{b}folder contents@{ub}.  The font and font size that
is used can be selected by the user with either the @{" FLDRFONT= " link AEM-4124} or
@{" FLDRFONTSZ= " link AEM-4124} Tool Types or the @{" Fonts Page " link AEM-4800} on the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.
The folder icons will adjust accordingly.

Four pre-defined folders are provided: @{b}INBOX@{ub} for holding retrieved
messages, @{b}PENDING@{ub} which holds messages that the user is currently
composing and has not decided to send as yet, @{b}QUEUED@{ub} which holds
completed messages for later transmission, and @{b}SENT@{ub} which holds messages
that have been sent and accepted by the @{b}SMTP Server@{ub}.  Since these folders
must always be present, @{i}you can not delete or change the name of these
folders@{ui}.

A facility has been provided to allow the user to add as many additional
folders of his own choosing that he wants to the list of folders (@{i}see@{ui}
@{" Folder menu  " link AEM-7200}).

As each new folder is created, an @{b}icon@{ub} will be created and placed next to 
the last folder icon.  Any number of folders can be created and the 
@{b}folder strip@{ub} has the ability to scroll horizontally so that all of the 
@{b}folder icons@{ub} can be viewed and accessed.

The displayed folder list (activated by using the @{" Display Folder List " link AEM-6010} icon
in the Command Icon Tool Bar) will be in the same order as the folder
icons in the folder strip.  You can change the order of both the folder
icons and the list of folders by using the @{" Move... " link AEM-7201} menu item under the
@{" Folders " link AEM-7200} menu.

You can use the menu items @{" Transfer... " link AEM-7304} and @{" Copy... " link AEM-7304} under the
@{" MESSAGE menu " link AEM-7300} to transfer or copy messages between folders.

The last window is placed below the @{b}folder strip@{ub} and is used to display
either @{" folder lists " link AEM-8100}, @{" address books " link AEM-8500}, @{" message lists " link AEM-8200}, or @{" messages " link AEM-8600} themselves.
If a @{b}non-interlaced@{ub} screen is provided, the @{b}message@{ub} and @{b}address book@{ub}
displays will start below the @{b}Command Icon Tool Bar@{ub} (overlaying the @{b}folder
strip@{ub}) rather than below the @{b}folder strip@{ub}.  This is done to provide more
room for the @{b}message@{ub} or @{b}address book@{ub} display since the number of
displayable lines is limited.

Other @{" windows " link AEM-8000} are also provided which cover the entire screen below the
title bar for the purpose of providing configuration information and for
composing messages.

While the @{b}Command Icon Tool Bar@{ub} and the @{b}folder strip@{ub} are being displayed,
a contextual help line is provided in the @{b}Command Icon Tool Bar@{ub} window
title bar below the screen's title bar.  As you pass the mouse cursor over
any command or folder icon, a description of that command or folder will
be displayed in the window title bar.  The main window menu bar should
also be active whenever the mouse pointer moves to the @{b}folder strip@{ub} or
above.

All command and folder icons are surrounded by a @{b}raised box@{ub}.  Whenever a
command or folder is @{b}selected@{ub}, the box will become @{b}depressed@{ub}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-5200 "INVOKING AEMAIL FROM THE SHELL"

                      @{b}Invoking AEMail from the Shell@{ub}

The shell invocation is primarily designed for @{" MailTo: " link AEM-5300} agents in web
browsers or to call @{b}AEMail@{ub} from another program that passes a message to
it.  When @{b}AEMail@{ub} is invoked from the shell, there are @{i}six@{ui} optional
arguments that can be used as follows:

 @{b}AEMail [@{i}email-addr-of-recipient-of-email@{ui}] [@{b}config=@{ub}@{i}configuration_file@{ui}]
   [@{b}pubscr=@{ub}@{i}browser-screen-name@{ui}] [@{b}mail_dir=@{ub}@{i}full-path-to-mail-directory@{ui}]
   [@{b}message=@{ub}@{i}full-path-name-of-message-to-send@{ui}] [@{b}CONT@{ub}]

If either the recipient's @{b}email address@{ub} is present or the @{b}message=@{ub}
argument is present, @{b}AEMail@{ub} assumes that we are using @{b}AEMail@{ub} as a @{b}MailTo@{ub}
agent or you are trying to queue or send a message composed outside of
@{b}AEMail@{ub}.  AEMail will load and immediately display the @{" Compose message " link AEM-8700}
window.

If the @{b}message=@{ub} argument was used, you will be in the @{i}edit@{ui} mode of the
compose screen.  You can either edit the supplied message or immediately
@{b}[Save in Pending]@{ub}, @{b}[Queue Message]@{ub}, @{b}[Send Message Now]@{ub}, or @{b}[Cancel
Message]@{ub}.  You can also perform any other action on the message including
@{i}adding headers@{ui}, @{i}adding attachments@{ui}, or @{i}adding your signature block@{ui} (@{i}see
Compose Message Window@{ui}).

The message that the @{b}message=@{ub} argument points to must be a complete
message with at least one header.  It is suggested that you include at
least a @{b}To:@{ub} and @{b}Subject:@{ub} header.  @{i}These should be followed with at
least one blank line before the body of the message@{ui}.

If both the @{b}mail address of the recipient@{ub} argument and the @{b}message=@{ub}
argument are used, the @{b}mail address@{ub} will take precedence over the @{b}To:@{ub}
header in the message.

The recipient's name in either the mailto argument or the @{b}To:@{ub} header in the
message referenced by the @{b}Message=@{ub} argument, can be a @{b}nickname@{ub} present
in your @{" Address Book " link AEM-8500}.  This is a convenient way to send messages to groups
where you are periodically adding or deleting members from the group.
Just use the @{b}group nickname@{ub} in the @{b}To: @{ub} address to send the message to
the entire group.

If the @{b}message=@{ub} argument is not present but a recipient's @{b}email address@{ub}
is present, you will enter the @{b}compose window@{ub} in a @{b}new@{ub} message mode.
You must compose a message or Cancel the operation in order to procede.

When you exit from the @{b}Compose window@{ub} by clicking on one of the action
requesters at the bottom of the window, @{b}AEMail@{ub} will terminate
automatically unless the @{b}CONT@{ub} keyword was present in the argument
stream.  If @{b}CONT@{ub} is used, @{b}AEMail@{ub} will continue so that you can perform
other AEMail functions.  You will then have to quit using the @{" Quit... " link AEM-7105}
menu item in the @{" Project Menu " link AEM-7100}.

The @{b}config=@{ub} keyword parameter is used to specify a @{" configuration file " link AEM-9110}
other that the default @{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub} file.  All pertanent data on the
@{b}AEMail@{ub} configuration to be used will be in this file.  If you wish to
invoke @{b}AEMail@{ub} from the shell have it run with a different
configuration file, you can use the @{b}config=@{ub} parameter to direct @{b}AEMail@{ub}
to use this @{i}different@{ui} @{b}configuration file@{ub} on startup.  To use @{b}AEMail@{ub} in
this manner, you could simply type:


    @{b}AEMAIL config=@{i}name_of_configuration_file@{ui}


If the @{b}config=@{ub} keyword parameter or the @{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub} file are both not
present a default @{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub} file will be created.  Of course, if this
happens, your normal configuration data @{i}will not be present@{ub} (such as your
@{b}POP3 UserID@{ub}, @{b}Password@{ub}, @{b}POP Server name@{ub}, or @{b}SMTP Server name@{ub}) and your
normal mail directory will not be found unless the @{b}mail_dir=@{ub} keyword
parameter described below is present.

If your normal configuration file is not @{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub} and you wish to
execute AEMail from the shell (or as a @{b}MailTo@{ub} agent), you should load
@{b}AEMail@{ub} from the workbench using the icon specifying the configuration file
you want to use and then do a @{" Save As... " link AEM-7101} from the @{b}Configuration@{ub} menu
item of the @{" Project " link AEM-7100} menu.  Specify @{b}"s:aemail.cnfg"@{ub} in the Save As file
requester.  This will create a vaild @{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub} file.

The @{b}mail_dir=@{ub} is used to specify the mail directory for the user
specified in the @{b}config=@{ub} parameter.  It corresponds to the @{" MAIL_DIR= " link AEM-4102} Tool
Type.  Normally, this is unnecessary (@{i}in fact, discouraged@{ui}) if the
@{b}configuration file@{ub} is present since the mail directory will be stored in
the @{b}configuration file@{ub}.  You must specify a full path name if the
@{b}mail_dir@{ub} parameter is used.  @{i}Be very careful in using this parameter
since it could change the mail directory specified in your configuration
file with undesireable results.@{ui}

If @{b}AEMail@{ub} is used as a @{b}mailto:@{ub} agent for your browser and that browser
passes it's public screen name along with the userid, you can use the
keyword argument @{b}pubscn=@{ub} to specify that public screen.  @{b}AEMail@{ub} will
then bring the browser's screen to the front when @{b}AEMail@{ub} terminates.  If
this argument is missing and the browser opens on it's own screen but does
not, itself, bring the screen to the front when it returns from the
@{b}mailto:@{ub} command, you might have to manually bring the browser's screen to
the front with the @{b}LEFT-AMIGA M@{ub} key.

When you invoke @{b}AEMail@{ub} from the shell with an @{b}email address@{ub} parameter or a
@{b}message=@{ub} argument, you normally will not be able to use any of the
@{b}AEMail@{ub} menus or commands unless the @{b}CONT@{ub} key word was used.  However,
@{b}AEMail@{ub} will always check for Mail on your POP Server and for Queued
messages to send before displaying the Compose message screen (see
@{" initial AEMail action " link AEM-5000}) and ask for configuration data if required
parameters are not present in the @{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub} file or the @{b}config=@{ub}
configuration file.

If you invoke @{b}AEMail@{ub} from the shell without any parameters, @{b}AEMail@{ub} will 
behave the same as if it was invoked from the Workbench by clicking on 
it's icon except that @{b}tool types@{ub} will not be utilized and the 
@{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub} file will be used by default.  If you are a new user of
@{b}AEMail@{ub} and do not have an @{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub} file (you assigned a different
name and place for the configuration file), you can create one easily.
Bring up the primary user of @{b}AEMail@{ub} from the Workbench (the user you want
to activate from the shell) and perform a @{" Configuratio/Save As " link AEM-7101} from the
@{" Project " link AEM-7100} menu.  When the file requester comes up, specify the "S:"
directory and "aemail.cnfg" as the file name.  Invoking from the Workbench
is described in @{" Starting AEMail " link AEM-5000}).

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-5300 "USING AEMAIL AS MAILTO AGENT"

                     @{b}USING AEMail AS A "MailTo" AGENT@{ub}

A number of @{b}Amiga web Browsers@{ub} allow you to select an @{b}external@{ub} Mail agent
to be used for sending email when a @{b}mailto:@{ub} HTML link is specified.
@{b}AEMail@{ub} can be used as such an external mail agent.

There are two methods in which @{b}AEMail@{ub} can be used as an external Mail
agent for sending @{b}mailto:@{ub} email messages.  The first method is to call
@{" AEMail directly " link AEM-5310}.  This method has the restriction that @{b}AEMail@{ub} must NOT be
running when you start up your browser.  When you click on the @{b}mailto:@{ub}
link, @{b}AEMail@{ub} will be loaded, the Compose message window will be displayed,
you will then be able to compose and send the message, and @{b}AEMail@{ub} will
terminate.

The second method is to use an @{" ARexx script " link AEM-5320} to call @{b}AEMail@{ub} for composing
and sending your email.  With this method @{b}AEMail@{ub} can be running in the
background and is entered each time you want to compose and send a
message.  When the @{b}ARexx@{ub} script is used, you can also receive email while
your browser is running.  A generic @{b}ARexx@{ub} script is descibed below, but a
more sophisticated one called @{b}mailto.aem@{ub} is provided in the @{b}AEMail ARexx@{ub}
directory.  If you use this script you should move it to the @{b}REXX:@{ub}
directory.

To use either method, set the @{b}mailto@{ub} function to call an external
program.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-5310 "USING AEMAIL AS MAILTO AGENT/Direct Call"

                    @{b}Mailto by Calling AEMail Directly@{ub}

On the configuration setup for your browser specify @{b}AEMail@{ub} as your
@{b}mailto:@{ub} agent by using the full path name of @{b}AEMail@{ub} and the token for
specifying the @{b}mailto:@{ub} email address.

As an example, for @{" AWeb-II " link AEM-9910} you can specify the following:

    @{b}AEMail2:AEMail %e@{ub}

You do this by bringing up the @{b}Network Settings@{ub} menu item under @{b}Settings@{ub}.
On the display click on the @{b}Mail/News@{ub} tab and then the @{b}Mail@{ub} tab.

In the display, checkmark @{b}Use external mailer@{ub} and the @{b}Command@{ub} and
@{b}Argument@{ub} string gadgets will become unghosted.  Enter

    @{b}AEMail2:AEMail@{ub}

on the @{b}Command@{ub} line, and

    @{b}%e@{ub}

on the @{b}Argument@{ub} line

Be sure and save your @{b}AWeb-II@{ub} settings once you make the change.

Other browsers, if they use this capability, may have a different way to
specify the @{b}mailto@{ub} user agent and the token for specifying where to
place the email address.  The token may change from version to version of
your browser.  Consult your browser documentation for how to do this.

The documentation for @{" IBrowse " link AEM-9910}, unfortunately, does not provide any
information on how to set up an external @{b}mailto:@{ub} agent.  However it can
be done.  Follow these steps for @{b}IBrowse@{ub} versions @{u}before@{uu} @{b}2.x@{ub}:

    @{b}Select the Preferences menu in IBrowse
    Select Network
    Select "Email & Telnet" tab
    Under "Mailto:" Set the External mode
    For the command give the full path name of the AEMail program and
        follow it with %h

    example:  AEMail2:AEMail %h

    Select O.K.

    Be sure to "Save Settings" under the Preferences menu@{ub}

The display used in @{b}IBrowse version 2.1@{ub} and above is slightly different.
The menu item that you use is @{b}Preferences/Settings@{ub}.  Instead of tabs it
has a list of items on the left of the @{b}Preferences/Settings@{ub} display.
Under @{b}Network@{ub} you need to expand the list by clicking on the @{b}[+]@{ub}.  You
will now see the @{b}Email & Telnet@{ub} on the list and the @{b}[+]@{ub} will become @{b}[-].@{ub}

Click on @{b}Email & Telnet@{ub} and you will see a similar display to that used
in @{b}1.x@{ub} shown on the right.  Continue as you would with earlier versions of
@{b}IBrowse@{ub}.  

@{b}SPECIAL NOTE:@{ub}  @{i}In @{b}IBrowse 2.1@{ub} the @{b}Command@{ub} string gadget remains ghosted
which means that with 2.1 you @{u}CAN NOT@{uu} specify an external @{b}mailto:@{ub} agent.
Hopefully this will be corrected in later versions of @{b}IBrowse@{ub}.@{ui}

In order for the @{b}mailto:@{ub} agent to work properly, @{b}AEMail@{ub} must @{u}@{b}NOT@{ub}@{uu} be
running when you start up your browser.  When you click on the @{b}mailto:@{ub}
link, @{b}AEMail@{ub} will be loaded, the @{" Compose message window " link AEM-8700} will be displayed,
you will then be able to compose and send the message, and @{b}AEMail@{ub} will
terminate.

If you have a @{i}custom@{ui} @{b}configuration file@{ub} (@{i}other than@{ui} @{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub}), you
should also add the argument @{b}config=name-of-config-file@{ub} to the @{b}mailto@{ub}
calling argument.  As an example, using @{b}IBrowse@{ub}:

    @{b}AEMail2:AEMail %h config=@{i}name-of-file@{ui}@{ub}

@{i}See @{" Invoking AEMail from the Shell " link AEM-5200}.@{ui}


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-5320 "USING AEMAIL AS MAILTO AGENT/ARexx Call"

                            @{b}MailTo Using ARexx@{ub}


Rather than use the @{b}mailto:@{ub} capability described above, you can also
call an @{" ARexx " link AEM-9400} script which calls the @{" Compose " link AEM-8700} function of @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  Such a
script for any browser would be as follows:

    @{b}/* Arexx AEMail Mailto Compose */
    OPTIONS RESULTS
    parse arg userid screen a

    ADDRESS AEMAIL1
    SCREENTOFRONT AEMAIL
    COMPOSE MAILTO userid
    SCREENTOFRONT screen
    if (result = 0) then okay1 "Bad Public Screen"
    exit@{ub}

This script requires @{b}AEMail@{ub} to be running when the script is called.  A
more sophisticated script @{i}which is contained in the@{uu} @{b}AEMail ARexx@{ub} @{i}directory@{ui}
called @{b}mailto.aem@{ub} automatically loads @{b}AEMail@{ub} if it was not already
loaded.

The above script is saved in the @{b}REXX:@{ub}  directory as @{b}mailto.aem@{ub}.

The call that is placed on the @{b}command@{ub} line in the @{b}Mailto:@{ub} in @{b}IBROWSE@{ub}
would be:

    @{b}rx mailto.aem %h %p@{ub}

If you have not moved or saved the @{b}mailto.aem@{ub} script in the @{b}REXX:@{ub}
directory you can call it from the @{b}AEMail ARexx@{ub} directory by specifying:

    @{b}rx AEMail2:ARexx/mailto.aem %h %p@{ub}

Note the use of the full path name for calling the @{b}mailto.aem@{ub} script.

The advantage of using @{b}ARexx@{ub} is that @{b}AEMail@{ub} can be running while you are
doing your web browsing.  If you happen to receive email during this time,
a requester will then pop up saying that you have mail and asking if you
want to read it.

In the @{b}IBrowse ARexx@{ub} call above notice the argument @{b}%p@{ub}.  This is the token
that passes the @{b}IBrowse@{ub} screen name to @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  This allows @{b}AEMail@{ub} to
bring the @{b}IBrowse@{ub} screen to the front after the message is sent (or
queued).

@{b}PLEASE NOTE:@{ub}  @{i}There is a problem with @{b}IBrowse 2.1@{ub} in that you can not
enter an external mailer.@{ui}

With @{b}AWeb-II@{ub} you would enter @{b}rx@{ub} on the @{b}command@{ub} line and

    @{b}mailto.aem %e %n@{ub}

if @{b}mailto.aem@{ub} is in the @{b}REXX:@{ub} directory @{i}or@{ui}, if calling from the @{b}AEMail
ARexx@{ub} directory:

    @{b}AEMAIL2:ARexx/mailto.aem %e %n@{ub}

on the @{b}argument@{ub} line.

Notice the difference between the tokens in @{b}IBrowse@{ub} and @{b}AWeb-II@{ub}.  @{b}%h@{ub} and
@{b}%p@{ub} are used for the email and screen tokens in @{b}IBrowse@{ub}; @{b}%e@{ub} and @{b}%n@{ub} are used
for these tokens in @{b}AWeb-II@{ub}.

@{i}See @{" Mailto by Calling AEMail Directly " link AEM-5310} to see how to set up the command and
argument lines for the various browsers.@{ui}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-5700 "USING KEYBOARD HOT KEYS"

                         @{b}Using Keyboard Hot Keys@{ub}

While @{b}AEMail@{ub} was designed to utilize the mouse for activating commands,
there are a number of keyboard hot keys that can be used to activate
commands on the @{" command strip " link AEM-6000} without using the mouse.  There are also
keyboard actions for moving the various listviews up and down.  Also, most
of the menu items can use a keyboard hot keys for activating them.

A key command has been assigned to each of the @{b}command strip@{ub} icons.  When
a menu item duplicates the action of a command on the @{b}command strip@{ub}, the
menu keyboard hot key is used.  A summary of the keyboard action that can
be taken for each of the commands on the @{b}command icon strip@{ub} is given
below:

    @{b}@{u}Command Strip Icon@{uu}@{ub}                             @{b}@{u}Key Code@{uu}@{ub}

    @{" Display Folder List " link AEM-6010}                         @{b}f@{ub}
    @{" Display Address Book " link AEM-6020}                        @{b}a@{ub}
    @{" Retrieve Messages " link AEM-6110}                           @{b}Right Amiga m@{ub}
    @{" Display Previous Message " link AEM-6030}                    @{b}Cursor Left@{ub}
    @{" Display Previous Folder's Message List " link AEM-6120}      @{b}Shift Cursor Left@{ub}
    @{" Display Current Folder's Message List " link AEM-6120}       @{b}=@{ub}
    @{" Display Next Folder's Message List " link AEM-6120}          @{b}Shift Cursor Right@{ub}
    @{" Display Next Message " link AEM-6040}                        @{b}Cursor Right@{ub}
    @{" Compose A Message " link AEM-6080}
        Compose a new message                      @{b}Right Amiga n@{ub}
        Reply to current message                   @{b}Right Amiga r@{ub}
        Forward current message                    @{b}Right Amiga >@{ub}
        Edit current message                       @{b}Right Amiga e@{ub}
    @{" Queue Message For Later Delivery " link AEM-6100}            @{b}q@{ub}
    @{" Send Message Immediately " link AEM-6090}                    @{b}s@{ub}
    @{" Export (Save) Message To File " link AEM-6050}               @{b}Right Amiga v@{ub}
    @{" Print " link AEM-6060}                                       @{b}Right Amiga p@{ub}
    @{" Delete/Undelete Message " link AEM-6070}                     @{b}x@{ub}, @{b}Right Amiga x@{ub}
    @{" Copy Messages to a New Folder " link AEM-6140}               @{b}Right Amiga =@{ub}
    @{" Transfer Messages to a New Folder " link AEM-6150}           @{b}Right Amiga -@{ub}
    @{" Start TCP/IP Network Connection " link AEM-6130}             @{b}Right Amiga t@{ub}
    @{" Terminate TCP/IP Network Connection " link AEM-6130}         @{b}Right Amiga h@{ub}

These key codes are also shown on the icon information line that appears
when you pass the mouse over the command icons.

The @{b}=@{ub} key also toggles the message selection indicator (*)

When you are displaying a list, the following keys move the listview:

    @{b}Cursor Down@{ub} moves the listview one row down.
    @{b}Cursor Up@{ub} moves the listview one row up.
    @{b}Home@{ub} or @{b}ALT Cursor Up@{ub} moves the listview to the top.
    @{b}End@{ub} or @{b}ALT Cursor Down@{ub} moves the listview to the botton.
    @{b}PgUp@{ub} or @{b}Shift Cursor Up@{ub} pages the listview one "page" up.  The
        top line of the previous page will be displayed as the bottom
        line of the new page.
    @{b}PgDn@{ub} or @{b}Shift Cursor Down@{ub} pages the list view one "page" down.
        The bottom line of the previous page will be displayed as the
        top line of the new page.
    The cursor up/down keys on the keypad will have the same action as
        the normal cursor keys with the exception of the shift and ALT
        feature.

Since the cursor keys are used to move the listview up or down, the space
bar is used to manipulate the selected row on the listview.  The action of
the the space bar in conjuction with control keys is as follows:

    @{b}Space Bar@{ub}               Selects the next item in the list
    @{b}Shift Space Bar@{ub}         Selects the previous item in the list
    @{b}Left Amiga Space Bar@{ub}    Selects the first item in the list
    @{b}Right Amiga Space Bar@{ub}   Selects the last item in the list

The item selected will be highlighted.  If it was previously selected with
the @{b}*@{ub} indicator, it will be de-selected (@{b}*@{ub} removed); otherwise it will
be selected with an @{b}*@{ub}.

When one of the above sets of keys are pressed, the current item is
unselected (@{b}*@{ub} is toggled).  To keep the current item selected, press the
@{b}Ctrl@{ub} key at the same time as you press the appropriate key combination.
Always remember to press the control keys (@{b}shift@{ub}, @{b}left Amiga@{ub}, @{b}right Amiga@{ub},
or @{b}Ctrl@{ub}) before you press the space bar.

Pressing the @{b}RETURN@{ub} key when a row is highlighted is the same as double
clicking on that item.  In other words, if you are displaying the folder
list and you hit the @{b}RETURN@{ub} key, the message list for the highlighted
folder will be displayed.

Unfortunately, gadgets in subsiderary windows @{i}do not@{ui} have key codes
assigned to them at this time.  You can activate requester gadgets however
by pressing @{b}Left Amiga v@{ub} for the left most gadget and @{b}Left Amiga b@{ub} for
the right most gadget.  Center gadgets, if present, do not have an assigned
key code.  Requesters with this action are @{i}only@{ui} those that appear at the
@{b}left most top@{ub} corner of the screen.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-5400 "EDITING STRING ENTRY GADGETS"

                       @{b}Editing String Entry Gadgets@{ub}

A number of windows in @{b}AEMail@{ub} use string entry gadgets for entering data.
These gadgets look like long rectangles with a cursor which allows you to
type in the data you want.  There are a number of special key combinations
that can aid you in the entry process.  These are:

    @{b}Cursor Left@{ub}         Move cursor to previous character
    @{b}Shift Cursor Left@{ub}   Move cursor to the beginning of the string
    @{b}Cursor Right@{ub}        Move cursor to next character
    @{b}Shift Cursor Right@{ub}  Move cursor to the end of the string
    @{b}Del@{ub}                 Delete the character under the cursor
    @{b}Shift Del@{ub}           Delete from the character under the cursor to the
                        end of the line
    @{b}Backspace@{ub}           Delete the character to the left of the cursor
    @{b}Shift Backspace@{ub}     Delete from the character to the left of the cursor
                        to the start of the line
    @{b}RETURN @{i}or@{ui} Enter@{ub}     Terminate input and deactivate the gadget
    @{b}Tab@{ub}                 Terminate input and activate the next string gadget
    @{b}Shift Tab@{ub}           Terminate input and activate the previous string
                        gadget
    @{b}Right Amiga c@{ub}       Copy the string to the current clipboard unit
                        (@{i}either @{ui}@{b}c@{ub}@{i} or @{ui}@{b}C@{ub}@{ui} will work@{ui})
    @{b}Right Amiga d@{ub}       Copy default value to the string.  Only works on
                        the @{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub} (@{i}Note: either @{ui}@{b}d@{ub}@{i} or 
                        @{ui}@{b}D@{ub} @{i}will work@{ui})
    @{b}Right Amiga f@{ub}       Calls the file requester in strings that use file
                        requesters.  Only works on the @{b}Configuration
                        Setup Window@{ub} (@{i}Note: either @{ui}@{b}f@{ub}@{i} or @{ui}@{b}F@{ub}@{i} will work@{ui}).
    @{b}Right Amiga p@{ub}       Used only in the @{b}Identity Page@{ub} of the
                        @{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub} with the @{b}POP3 UserID:@{ub} 
                        string to call @{b}Set Password@{ub} (@{i}Note: either @{ui}@{b}p@{ub}@{i} or @{ui}@{b}P@{ub}@{i} 
                        will work@{ui}).
    @{b}Right Amiga q@{ub}       Undo (cancel) the last editing change to the string
                        (@{i}Note: either @{ui}@{b}q@{ub}@{i} or @{ui}@{b}Q@{ub}@{i} will work@{ui})
    @{b}Right Amiga u@{ub}       Change the current clipboard unit
    @{b}Right Amiga U@{ub}       Display a list of the current active clipboard
                        units and their contents
    @{b}Right Amiga v@{ub}       Paste the contents of the current clipboard unit
                        to the string (@{i}either @{ui}@{b}v@{ub}@{i} or @{ui}@{b}V@{ub}@{ui} will work@{ui})
    @{b}Right Amiga x@{ub}       Clears the string (@{i}either @{ui}@{b}x@{ub}@{i} or @{ui}@{b}X@{ub}@{i} will work@{ui})

In addition, the following editing functions are available if the @{b}IControl@{ub}
preferences editor has "@{b}Text Gadget Filter@{ub}" selected.
@{i}@{b}Note:@{ub} either the upper or lower case alphabetic character will work@{ui}.

    @{b}Ctrl A@{ub}              Jump cursor to the start of the string
    @{b}Ctrl H@{ub}              Delete the character to the left of the cursor
    @{b}Ctrl K@{ub}              Delete from the character under the cursor to the
                        end of the line
    @{b}Ctrl M@{ub}              Same as Return or Enter
    @{b}Ctrl W@{ub}              Delete the previous word
    @{b}Ctrl U@{ub}              Delete from the character to the left of the cursor
                        to the start of the line
    @{b}Ctrl X@{ub}              Clears the string
    @{b}Ctrl Z@{ub}              Jump cursor to end of the string.

All of the above characteristics of string editing are standard with the
Amiga with the exception of those keystrokes that involve the clipboard
file requesters, and default values.

The clipboard functions are specific to @{b}AEMail@{ub}, although other programs
may have similar functions using the same key combinations built into
them.  For more information on using the clipboard see
@{" Using the Clipboard with AEMail " link AEM-5500}.

The @{b}default@{ub}, @{b}file requester@{ub}, and @{b}Set Password@{ub} functions are also
specific to @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-5500 "USING THE CLIPBOARD WITH AEMAIL"

                      @{b}Using the Clipboard with AEMail@{ub}

On the Amiga, the clipboard provides a facility for passing information
from one program to another, or for saving information for re-use in the
same program.  @{b}AEMail@{ub} utilizes the clipboard in several ways:

Each @{" string entry gadget " link AEM-5400} has the ability of copying the current contents
of the string to the clipboard or of pasting the contents of the clipboard
to the string gadget.  In that manner information can be saved and re-used
at a later time.

You can also obtain a line from a message, edit it, and save that to the
clipboard; or you can save the entire contents of the message body to the
clipboard.  If you are using an editor that also supports the clipboard,
you can retrieve information that you previously copied to the clipboard
and insert it into a message you are composing.

If your browser supports the clipboard, you can use the above method to
capture a URL that is embedded in a message and then paste it into the
browser's URL string.  There is also a facility to directly transfer an
email or web (URL) address to a browser or within AEMail by the use of a
function key and an ARexx script.

AEMail supports the use of multiple clipboards (up to 256 separate
clipboard units), so different information can be copied to separate
clipboard units and retrieved later.  If other external programs also
support multiple clipboard units you can pass separate pieces of
information to those programs.

With each @{b}string entry gadget@{ub} in @{b}AEMail@{ub} you can use @{b}Right Amiga C@{ub} or @{b}Right
Amiga c@{ub} (@{i}either upper or lower case @{b}c@{ub}@{ui}) to copy the information from a
string to a clipboard unit.  Likewise, you can use @{b}Right Amiga V@{ub} or @{b}Right
Amiga v@{ub} (@{i}upper or lower case @{b}v@{ub}@{ui}) to paste the information into the string
gadget.  This works with all string gadgets except the @{" Enter Password " link AEM-5000} or
"@{b}Set Password@{ub}" (in the @{" Identity Page " link AEM-4300} of the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200})
string gadgets.

Generally speaking when you use the paste operation in a string gadget, it
will replace the contents of the string gadget with the contents of the
clipboard.  The exception to this is with the @{b}To:, cc:@{ub}, and @{b}bcc:@{ub} string
gadgets on the @{" Compose Message Window " link AEM-8700} and when editing a string that is
captured from a message (see below).

For the @{b}To:, cc:@{ub}, and @{b}bcc:@{ub}  string gadgets, the clipboard data will be
@{b}ADDED@{ub} to what was previously in the string gadget.  Any added email
addresses added with the paste operation will be separated from the
previous addresses with a comma.

If you double click on a line in a message that is being displayed, a
special window will open at the top of the screen which looks like this:


@{b}|=========================================================================|
|o| Edit and save message line to clipboard                               |
|-------------------------------------------------------------------------|
|                                                                         |
| [Message line appears here                                            ] |
|                                                                         |
| [ SAVE CLIP ]              [CHANGE CLIP UNIT]              [  CANCEL  ] |
|_________________________________________________________________________|@{ub}


You can use the copy and paste to and from the clipboard unit while you
are editing within the string entry gadget above.  However, if you paste
to the string, the data in the clipboard will be @{i}inserted@{ui} at your cursor
position.  This is different from all other string entry gadgets where the
pasted data @{i}replaces@{ui} whatever was in the string gadget before.  This
feature for the editing and saving of a line from a message can facilitate
building a clipboard line from different lines in the message.  To do
this, edit the first line so that just the portion that you want added or
inserted to a second line remains in the string.  Copy this to a clipboard
unit (@{b}[SAVE CLIP]@{ub}).  Then double click on a second line.  Position the
cursor where you want the first clipboard data to appear and perform the
paste operation.  The previously copied data will be inserted at that
point.

When you click on either the @{b}[SAVE CLIP]@{ub}, @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub}, or the close gadget at
the top of the window, the edit window will disappear.  Clicking on the
@{b}[SAVE CLIP]@{ub} will save the edited string to the current clipboard unit and
clicking on the @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} or close gadget will exit without saving.

@{b}Warning:@{ub}  using the copy function from within the string gadget with
@{b}Right Amiga c@{ub} will always copy the current contents of the string to the
clipboard whether or not you later click on the @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} or the close
gadget.  @{i}There is no way to undo this operation.@{ui}  However, using the copy
function from within the string gadget will not close the edit window.

Clicking on the @{b}[CHANGE CLIP UNIT]@{ub} in the edit window or typing @{b}Right Amiga
u@{ub} (@{i}lower case u only@{ui}) from any string gadget will bring up a special
window that will allow you to change the current clipboard unit.  This
window looks like this:


                         @{b}|=======================|
                         |o|Enter Clipboard Unit |
                         |-----------------------|
                         |                       |
                         | [         ] (0 - 255) |
                         |                       |
                         | [  OK  ]     [CANCEL] |
                         |_______________________|@{ub}


You can enter any clipboard unit between 0 or 255 in the numeric gadget.
If you type @{b}RETURN@{ub} after entering the number or click on @{b}[OK]@{ub}, the
clipboard unit you entered will become the new clipboard unit and the
window will close.  Clicking on the @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} gadget or the close gadget
will close the window without changing the current clipboard unit.

Since you may have data stored in multiple clipboard units and may forget
which clipboard unit has what data, another feature has been provided.  If
you type @{b}Right Amiga U@{ub} (@{i}upper case U - shift and u@{ui}) while you are editing
a string, the Clipboard Display window will be shown which looks like this:


               @{b}|===========================================|
               |o| Contents of Clip List                   |
               |-------------------------------------------|
               | Clip Contents                             |
               | ========================================= |
               | |  0 Contents of clip 0               | | |
               | |  2 Contents of clip 2               | | |
               | |                                     | | |
               | |                                     | | |
               | |                                     | | |
               | ========================================= |
               |                                           |
               | [  OK  ]     [NEW CLIP UNIT]     [CANCEL] |
               |___________________________________________|@{ub}


This shows all of the clipboard units that have data stored in them and
the contents of each clipboard unit in a listview.  Clipboard units may be
skipped as shown in the illustration above.  Since the contents of a
clipboard can be a complete file, @{i}the first non-blank line will be
displayed and leading spaces will be stripped@{ui}.  @{b}Only text clips will be
displayed@{ub}.  Only 40 characters can be displayed.  If the line is longer
than 40 characters, the first 30 characters will be shown followed by
three periods and the last 7 characters.

Only clips with data will be shown.  The current clipboard unit will be
highlighted if it contains data.  Since it is possible to have a clipboard
unit assigned @{b}WITHOUT@{ub} any data, you may see none of the units highlighted.
You can change to one of the clipboard units shown by clicking on it (it
will become highlighted) and then clicking on @{b}[OK]@{ub}.  You can also change to
a clipboard unit not shown by clicking on @{b}[NEW CLIP UNIT]@{ub}.  @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} and
the close gadget will close the window without any changes taking place.

A further feature of this window is to provide an automatic paste
capability by double clicking on one of the units being displayed.  That
will automatically paste the contents of the selected unit to the string.
If the selected clip is a file, only the first non-blank line will be
pasted and leading spaces will be stripped.  The @{ub}Right Amiga V@{ub} method of
pasting from within a string gadget also has this feature for multiple
line files.

Another clipboard feature of @{b}AEMail@{ub} is the ability to save the body of
messages and text attachments to the clipboard.  When you click on the
@{" [SAVE TEXT] " link AEM-8620} or @{" [ATTACHMENT] " link AEM-8610} button when you are displaying a message you
will be given the chance to save the text as a CLIP and also to change the
clipboard unit.  See also the @{" Message Display Window " link AEM-8600}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-5510 "USING THE CLIPBOARD WITH AEMAIL/Entering Clipboard Unit"

                       @{b}Entering the Clipboard Unit@{ub}

The @{b}Enter Clipboard Unit@{ub} window allows you to change the current clipboard
unit.  This window looks like this:


                         @{b}|=======================|
                         |o|Enter Clipboard Unit |
                         |-----------------------|
                         |                       |
                         | [         ] (0 - 255) |
                         |                       |
                         | [  OK  ]     [CANCEL] |
                         |_______________________|@{ub}


You can enter any clipboard unit between 0 or 255 in the numeric gadget.
If you type @{b}RETURN@{ub} after entering the number or click on @{b}[OK]@{ub}, the
clipboard unit you entered will become the new clipboard unit and the
window will close.  Clicking on the @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} gadget or the close gadget
will close the window without changing the current clipboard unit.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-5520 "USING THE CLIPBOARD WITH AEMAIL/Display Clip List Contents"

                    @{b}Display Contents of the Clip List@{ub}

Since you may have data stored in multiple clipboard units and may forget
which clipboard unit has what data, another feature has been provided.  If
you type @{b}Right Amiga U@{ub} (@{i}upper case U - shift and u@{ui}) while you are editing
a string, the Clipboard Display window will be shown which looks like this:


               @{b}|===========================================|
               |o| Contents of Clip List                   |
               |-------------------------------------------|
               | Clip Contents                             |
               | ========================================= |
               | |  0 Contents of clip 0               | | |
               | |  2 Contents of clip 2               | | |
               | |                                     | | |
               | |                                     | | |
               | |                                     | | |
               | ========================================= |
               |                                           |
               | [  OK  ]     [NEW CLIP UNIT]     [CANCEL] |
               |___________________________________________|@{ub}


This shows all of the clipboard units that have data stored in them and
the contents of each clipboard unit in a listview.  Clipboard units may be
skipped as shown in the illustration above.  Since the contents of a
clipboard can be a complete file, @{i}the first non-blank line will be
displayed and leading spaces will be stripped@{ui}.  @{b}Only text clips will be
displayed@{ub}.  Only 40 characters can be displayed.  If the line is longer
than 40 characters, the first 30 characters will be shown followed by
three periods and the last 7 characters.

Only clips with data will be shown.  The current clipboard unit will be
highlighted if it contains data.  Since it is possible to have a clipboard
unit assigned @{b}WITHOUT@{ub} any data, you may see none of the units highlighted.
You can change to one of the clipboard units shown by clicking on it (it
will become highlighted) and then clicking on @{b}[OK]@{ub}.  You can also change to
a clipboard unit not shown by clicking on @{b}[NEW CLIP UNIT]@{ub}.  @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} and
the close gadget will close the window without any changes taking place.

A further feature of this window is to provide an automatic paste
capability by double clicking on one of the units being displayed.  That
will automatically paste the contents of the selected unit to the string.
If the selected clip is a file, only the first non-blank line will be
pasted and leading spaces will be stripped.  The @{ub}Right Amiga V@{ub} method of
pasting from within a string gadget also has this feature for multiple
line files.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-5600 "FILTERING MESSAGES WITH AEMAIL"

                      @{b}Filtering Messages with AEMail@{ub}

@{b}@{i}What is message filtering?@{ui}@{ub}  Message filtering is the ability to direct
incoming messages to specific folders or to automatically exclude certain
messages from being stored in the system.

@{b}AEMail@{ub} has a very powerful message filtering system.  It can direct (or
exclude) messages based upon information in the @{b}To:@{ub}, @{b}From:@{ub}, @{b}Reply-To:@{ub},
@{b}Subject:@{ub}, @{b}cc:@{ub}, @{b}bcc:@{ub}, or @{b}Date:@{ub} headers and (@{i}for registered users only@{ui}) any
other header or text in the body of the message.  It can also use the fact
that a message is a reply, has attachments, or is forwarded as filtering
criteria.  Information in the header or body text that is checked can be a
word or phrase and wild cards can be used.  Information can also be case
sensitive or insensitive as the user desires.

AND and OR relationships can also be made with information coming from
different headers.

Filtering criteria is defined in the folder description which can be be
modified or created by using either the @{" Edit " link AEM-7201} or @{" New " link AEM-7201} sub-topic under
the @{" Folders menu " link AEM-7200}.  The description under the @{" Filter Selection Window " link AEM-8330}
gives a complete description on how to set up the filtering criteria.

Setting up the appropriate filtering criteria for any folder designed to
receive incoming messages with cause incoming messages (either from your
POP server or from files) to be stored in that folder rather than the
@{b}INBOX@{ub}.

Setting up filtering criteria for the @{b}INBOX@{ub} will automatically exclude any
message meeting that criteria from being stored in the @{b}INBOX@{ub}.  In other
words, filtering criteria in the @{b}INBOX@{ub} is used to prevent certain messages
from being stored on your system.

Filtering criteria can not be set up for folders designed for messages
sent out of your system.  Only messages as they are being received are
checked.  Filtering is done "on the fly" as a message enters the system.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-5800 "USING WEB AND EMAIL ADDRESSES EMBEDDED IN MESSAGES"

            @{b}Using Web and Email addresses embedded in messages@{ub}

If a message you have received contains a web address you can capture that
address, copy it to the clipboard, or actually call your web browser to
display the web page directly.

You can also capture email addresses embedded in a message, compose a
message to be directed to that address, or add that address to your
address book.

The method used to do this in @{b}AEMail@{ub} is similar to that used in the
section which described the use of the @{" clipboard " link AEM-5500}.  We combine that with
the help of some pre-defined ARexx scripts.

Two event exits have also been provided to directly call @{b}ARexx@{ub} scripts
when you double click on either the web or email address (@{i}see below@{ui}).

If a message contains an email address (@{i}determined by the @{b}@@{ub} between
adjoining strings@{ui}) or a web address (@{i}determined by @{b}www.@{ub} or @{b}http:@{ub} within
the string@{ui}) you can double click on that line.  Depending on how you set
up your @{b}ARexx@{ub} commands you will either directly execute an appropriate
@{b}ARexx@{ub} script or the @{b}Edit and save message line to clipboard; set ARexx 
variable@{ub} window as shown below:


@{b}|=========================================================================|
|o| Edit and save message line to clipboard; set ARexx variable           |
|-------------------------------------------------------------------------|
|                                                                         |
| [http://www,calwe.com/~jzachar/                                       ] |
|                                                                         |
| [ SAVE CLIP ]              [CHANGE CLIP UNIT]              [  CANCEL  ] |
|_________________________________________________________________________|@{ub}


will appear at the top of the screen.  Rather than the entire line, just
the email address or the web address will be transferred to the string.
If the web address does not have @{b}http://@{ub} at the beginning of the string,
that will be added.  The example above shows the @{b}AEMail@{ub} web address which
is included as part of the signature block of messages I send.

If you hold down the shift key when you double click on such an address,
the entire line will be transferred (@{i}just as is normally done with other
message lines@{ui}) and not just the email or web address.

The @{b}Edit and save message line to clipboard; set ARexx variable@{ub} window
has one menu associated with it: the @{" ARexx/DOS menu " link AEM-7600} that is the same as
that used in the @{" main menu strip " link AEM-7000}.  Holding down the right mouse button
when this window is activated will bring up that menu.

If you have transferred an email or web address you can hit a @{" function key " link AEM-4700} 
or use the right (Menu) mouse button to call the AREXX/DOS command to
to execute an @{b}ARexx@{ub} script.  The email address or web address
will be transferred to a special variable and the script will be executed.
If the script contains the @{b}ARexx@{ub} command @{" GETVAR " link AEM-9530} it will receive the
variable string in the @{b}RESULT@{ub} variable and can act on it.

Two event exits have also been provided which avoid bringing up the
clipboard window.  If these exits are activated, the @{b}ARexx@{ub} script assigned
to the exit will be immediately executed when you double click on the web
address or the email address.  Assigning the @{b}ARexx@{ub} scripts to the event
exits is done in the same manner as assigning @{b}ARexx@{ub} scripts to function
keys and to menu items (see the @{" ARexx Page " link AEM-4700} of the @{b}Configuration Setup
Window@{ub}.)

You can force the clipboard window to appear by pressing the @{b}CTRL@{ub} key when
you double click on the web or email address.  This is desireable if you
want alternative actions to take place when double clicking on an address.
You can then select the appropriate action with the function key or the
@{b}ARexx/DOS@{ub} menu.

Several sample @{b}ARexx@{ub} scripts have been placed in your @{b}ARexx@{ub} directory 
which can extract the address from the special variable and call your web 
browser to go to that web page (@{b}html.aem@{ub}), send a message to the email 
address (@{b}sendmsg.aem@{ub}) or place the email address in the address book 
either as an individual address (@{b}placeaddr.aem@{ub}) or as a group address 
(@{b}placegrp.aem@{ub}), and to delete an address from a group (@{b}deladrgrp.aem@{ub}).

Before using this feature, you will have to assign the scripts to a
function key (your choice) or an event exit using the @{" ARexx Page " link AEM-4700} of the 
@{b}Configuration Setup Window.@{ub}  You should also give each of the scripts a 
@{b}Menu Title@{ub} so that it will show up in your @{" ARexx/DOS " link AEM-7600} menu.  If you did 
not assign an event exit, function key or @{b}Menu Title@{ub}, you can always find 
the script using the @{" Send ARexx/DOS Command... " link AEM-7106} menu item in the 
@{b}ARexx/DOS@{ub} menu.

@{i}Keep in mind, however, if you are an @{b}un-registered user@{ub}, the function key
and menu information will not be saved between calls to @{b}AEMail@{ub}.@{ui}  If you
quit @{b}AEMail@{ub}, this information (function key or menu) will not be available
when you next load @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

When the function key is activated or a menu item selected, the clip
window will disappear whether or not a script is attached to that function
key.

If you have transferred a line to the clip window that is not a email or
web address or have edited the clip line, the function key will not work
unless you press return first.  That is because the string gadget is
activated in those situations.  With the email or web address the string
gadget is not activated.  You can tell if the string gadget is activated
or not by the presence of a cursor in the string.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-5900 "GETTING HELP WITH AEMAIL"

                         @{b}Getting HELP with AEMail@{ub}

@{b}AEMail@{ub} has a very extensive context sensitive help system.  Some help is
provided automatically.  As you pass the cursor over the @{" Command Icon Tool " link AEM-6000}
bar, the description of the icons appear in the window title bar above the
icons.  Likewise, as you pass the cursor over the folder icons, the folder
description also appears in the window title bar.

In addition, pressing the @{b}[Help]@{ub} key will bring up a description of what
you are currently seeing or trying to do.  This help is taken from the
@{b}AEMail.guide@{ub} file which normally is located in the @{b}AEMail2:documentation@{ub}
directory.  If you located the guide file somewhere else you will have to
use the Tool Type @{" HELP= " link AEM-4126} to identify the location of the guide file.
This must be done manually in each of your @{b}AEMail@{ub} project icons.

If you did not choose to install the current @{b}AEMail.guide@{ub} file, you will
not be able to use the @{b}[Help]@{ub} key.  In fact you will receive a requester
that looks like this when you first load @{b}AEMail@{ub}:

                     @{b}Error: (AG) Can't Open database!

                                [Continue]@{ub}

Clicking on @{b}[Continue]@{ub} will allow you to continue running @{b}AEMail@{ub} but the
@{b}[Help]@{ub} key will be effectively disabled.  If you are using an old
@{b}AEMail.guide@{ub} file you may get a requester saying that a particular help
page could not be found.  Also, the information on the page being
displayed may not be up to date.

You can receive help with any of the menus as well as with any of the
windows that are being displayed.  To receive help with a menu or menu
item, press the @{b}[Help]@{ub} key when you hold down the Right Mouse button.
Help will be displayed for the menu or menu item that is currently
highlighted.

Also, certain key combinations will display different @{b}AEMail.guide@{ub}
pages.  If you press either Shift keys when you press @{b}[Help]@{ub}, the main
guide table of contents will be displayed.

If you are in a string entry gadget, pressing either @{b}[Alt]@{ub} keys with the
@{b}[Help]@{ub} key will display the page describing 
@{" Editing String Entry Gadgets " link AEM-5400}.

@{b}WARNING:@{ub}  Because of a bug in @{b}ClassAct@{ub}, some string gadgets will not be
reactivated after the help page is displayed.  You will have to click into
the gadget to reactivate it.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-6000 "COMMAND ICON TOOL BAR"

                          @{b}COMMAND ICON TOOL BAR@{ub}

This @{b}Command Icon Tool Bar@{ub} provides icons for accessing the major
functions of @{b}AEMail@{ub} and consists (from left to right) of the following
icons:

    @{" Display Folder List " link AEM-6010}
        @{i}This icon looks like a file cabinet.@{ui}
    @{" Display Address Book " link AEM-6020}
        @{i}This icon looks like a closed book with the letter A on its cover.@{ui}
    @{" Retrieve Messages " link AEM-6110}
        @{i}This icon looks like an envelope with an arrow coming in.@{ui}
    @{" Display Previous Message " link AEM-6030}
        @{i}This icon is a long yellow backward arrow.@{ui}
    @{" Display Previous Folder's Message List " link AEM-6120}
        @{i}This icon is a short backward arrow.@{ui}
    @{" Display Current Folder's Message List " link AEM-6120}
        @{i}This icon looks like a folder.@{ui}
    @{" Display Next Folder's Message List " link AEM-6120}
        @{i}This icon is a short forward arrow.@{ui}
    @{" Display Next Message " link AEM-6040}
        @{i}This icon is a long yellow forward arrow.@{ui}
    @{" Compose a Message " link AEM-6080}
        @{i}This icon looks like a sheet of paper with a pen on it.@{ui}
    @{" Queue Messages for Later Delivery " link AEM-6100}
        @{i}This icon looks like a mailbox.@{ui}
    @{" Send Messages Immediately " link AEM-6090}
        @{i}This icon looks like an envelope with an arrow going out.@{ui}
    @{" Export (Save) Message To File " link AEM-6050}
        @{i}This icon looks like a diskette.@{ui}
    @{" Print " link AEM-6060}
        @{i}This icon looks like a printer.@{ui}
    @{" Delete/Undelete Messages " link AEM-6070}
        @{i}This icon looks like a garbage can.@{ui}
    @{" Copy Messages " link AEM-6140}
        @{i}This icon looks like two sheets of paper, one laying over the
        other.@{ui}
    @{" Transfer Messages " link AEM-6150}
        @{i}This icon looks like a sheet of paper with arrows pointing to the
        right.@{ui}
    @{" Start TCP/IP Network Connection " link AEM-6130}
        @{i}This icon is a horizontal jagged line@{ui}
    @{" Terminate TCP/IP Network Connection " link AEM-6130}
        @{i}This icon is a horizontal jagged line with a red slash through it.@{ui}


Click on the links above for a description of each of the @{b}Command Icons@{ub} and
the functions that it performs.  Clicking on the @{b}Command Icon@{ub} while in
@{b}AEMail@{ub} will activate the function described.

Besides clicking on an icon to activate that function, you can also use
certain @{b}hot keys@{ub} to perform that function.  These are described with
each icon description.

Many of the functions activated by the icon tool bar can also be activated
by @{" menu " link AEM-7000} items.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-6010 "COMMAND ICON TOOL BAR/Display Folder List"

                           @{b}DISPLAY FOLDER LIST@{ub}

@{i}Activation key code:@{ui} @{b}f@{ub}

Clicking on the @{b}Display Folder List@{ub} icon will cause the @{" folder list " link AEM-8100} to be
displayed in the lower window.  This list shows each folder with its short
name (@{b}INBOX@{ub}, @{b}PENDING@{ub}, etc), a description of the folder, the number of
unread mesages in the folder, and the total number of messages in the folder.

Unlike the count displayed in the folder icon, the total number of
messages includes any messages marked for deletion.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-6020 "COMMAND ICON TOOL BAR/Display Address Book"

                           @{b}DISPLAY ADDRESS BOOK@{ub}

@{i}Activation key code:@{ui} @{b}a@{ub}

Clicking on the @{b}Display Address Book@{ub} icon will display the
@{" Address Book window " link AEM-8500}.

Each address book entry contains three fields:  @{i}Nickname, Real Name,@{ui} and
@{i}UserID (Address)@{ui}.  In addition, entries can be provided for groups with a
distribution list.  The group is identified with the heading @{b}DISTRIBUTION
LIST@{ub} along with the number of items in the list in the top most @{i}UserID@{ui}
field.  The @{i}UserID's@{ui} for the members of that list are shown below that
heading.

For items in the distribution list, real @{i}UserID's@{ui} or @{i}Nicknames@{ui} can be
used.  An item in the distribution list can also be another distribution
list (@{i}In this case, only a @{u}Nickname@{uu} can be used@{ui}).  All nicknames are
expanded to @{i}Real Name@{ui} and @{i}UserID@{ui} when mail is sent.

A checkbox item, called @{b}Expand@{ub} to the right of the Address Book headings
allows the user to either @{i}expand@{ui} and show all members of the group or
@{i}shrink@{ui} the address book so that only the group header is displayed.  This
item is normally checked indicating the groups are in expanded mode.  If
the check mark is removed, the group entries will shrink showing only the
group headings.  @{b}This feature is only available to registered users@{ub}.

Currently, @{b}Address Book@{ub} entries are sorted by @{i}Nickname@{ui} and group entries
are interspersed with single entries.  Also @{i}Real Names@{ui} are presented as
first name followed by last name rather than last name, first name.

If you are displaying a message, or have a message selected, when you
click on the @{b}Address Book@{ub} icon, the @{b}Reply-To:@{ub} address, if present, will
be transferred to the @{b}UserID@{ub} address in the @{b}Address Book@{ub}.  If the
@{b}Reply-To:@{ub} address is not present, the @{b}From:@{ub} address will be used.  If a
Real Name is present in the address it also will be transferred.  You can
force the @{b}From:@{ub} address to be transferred by holding down the @{i}shift@{ui} key
when you click on the @{b}Address Book@{ub} icon.  This process facilitates
transferring names and UserIDs to the @{b}Address Book@{ub}.  @{i}Please keep in mind
that @{b}Reply-To:@{ub} addresses normally do not have real names associated with
them, but @{b}From:@{ub} addresses many times do.@{ui}  If you want the real name you
may have to hold down the shift key when you click on the @{b}Address Book@{ub}
icon.

The first time @{b}AEMail@{ub} is loaded, a special @{b}Address Book@{ub} entry with a
@{i}Nickname@{ui} of @{b}AEMAIL@{ub} is created.  This entry can be used to send bug
reports and messages about @{b}AEMail@{ub} to my email address.

@{b}Address Book@{ub} data is stored in a file in your AEMAIL: directory called
@{" .addrbook " link AEM-9150}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-6030 "COMMAND ICON TOOL BAR/Display Previous Message"

                         @{b}DISPLAY PREVIOUS MESSAGE@{ub}

@{i}Activation key code:@{ui} @{b}Cursor Left@{ub}

When you are @{" displaying a message " link AEM-8600}, clicking on this icon will display the
previous message in the @{" message list " link AEM-8200}.  If you are at the first message in the
list, a requester will be displayed informing you of this.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-6120 "COMMAND ICON TOOL BAR/Display Folder's Message List"

                  @{b}DISPLAY PREVIOUS FOLDER'S MESSAGE LIST@{ub}

@{i}Activation key code:@{ui} @{b}Shift Cursor Left@{ub}

Clicking on this icon will display the previous folder's @{" message list " link AEM-8200}.



                  @{b}DISPLAY CURRENT FOLDER'S MESSAGE LIST@{ub}

@{i}Activation key code:@{ui} @{b}=@{ub}

Clicking on this icon will display the current folder's @{b}message list@{ub}.
This is one way to get back to the current message list when you are
displaying a message and the folder list is obstructed.



                    @{b}DISPLAY NEXT FOLDER'S MESSAGE LIST@{ub}

@{i}Activation key code:@{ui} @{b}Shift Cursor Right@{ub}

Clicking on this icon will display the next folder's @{b}message list@{ub}.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-6040 "COMMAND ICON TOOL BAR/Display Next Message"

                           @{b}DISPLAY NEXT MESSAGE@{ub}

@{i}Activation key code:@{ui} @{b}Cursor Right@{ub}

When you are @{" displaying a message " link AEM-8600}, clicking on this icon will display the
next message in the @{" message list " link AEM-8200}.  If you are at the last message in the
list, a requester will be displayed informing you of this.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-6050 "COMMAND ICON TOOL BAR/Export (Save) Message to File"

                     @{b}EXPORT (SAVE) MESSAGE TO A FILE@{ub}

@{i}Activation key code:@{ui} @{b}Right Amiga v@{ub}

This function can be activated from either the icon strip or the @{b}Export...@{ub}
sub-item in the @{" Messages menu " link AEM-7300}.  A message must be selected before activating
this function and @{" multiple messages can be selected " link AEM-8600}.  A message that is
currently being displayed is considered a selected message.

You can save multiple messages as a @{b}block of messages@{ub} or as @{b}individual
messages@{ub}.  If you have selected multiple messages a requester will be
displayed as follows:

                   @{b}More than one message marked to save

                   Do you want to save them as a group
                             or Individually

                        If you select Individually
                       a File Requester will appear
                             for each message

                [Save as Group]        [Save Individually]@{ub}


Unless you are saving the messages as a group, a requester will also be
displayed for each message which will describe the message as to @{b}Date,
From, To,@{ub} and @{b}Subject@{ub} and ask you if you want to perform the requested
action.  Selecting @{b}[SAVE]@{ub} will display a file requester in which you will
be asked to enter the file name you want the message saved as, and
selecting @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} will not save the current message.

If you are saving the message as a group, only the file requester will
appear.

The complete message, including all attachments, is saved in the format
in which the message was received from the @{b}POP server@{ub} except that
@{b}CARRAGE-RETURN/LINEFEED@{ub} sequences are stored as @{b}LINEFEED@{ub}s alone.  Also,
the message ending sequence (@{b}.<CR><LF>@{ub}) is eliminated and any embedded
@{b}..<CR><LF>@{ub} are changed to @{b}.<LF>@{ub} as they would normally appear in a
message.

If the messages are saved as a group, each message will have a special
header separating it from the following message.  This header consists of
a line feed followed by:

    @{b}From [your UserID]@[Your POP Server name] [date]@{ub}

Only the special header (not the line feed) will appear for the first
message.

This facilitates importing a group of messages back into @{b}AEMail@{ub}. (@{i}See@{ui}
the @{" Retrieve Messages " link AEM-6111} command and the menu item @{" From Local File... " link AEM-7401} under
the @{" Retrieve Msgs " link AEM-7400} menu.)

If you want to save the body of the message or an attachment in its
converted format, you can do that with either the @{b}[SAVE TEXT]@{ub} gadget in
the @{" message display window " link AEM-8600} or with the @{" Attachment Requester " link AEM-8610} that can be
brought up when you display a message with attachments.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-6060 "COMMAND ICON TOOL BAR/Print"

                                  @{b}PRINT@{ub}

@{i}Activation key code:@{ui} @{b}Right Amiga p@{ub}

This function can be activated from either the icon strip or the @{b}Print@{ub} sub-item
in the @{" Messages menu " link AEM-7300}.  You must select the messages you want printed
prior to selecting this function.  @{" Multiple message selection " link AEM-8210} works with
this function.  @{b}If you don't select any messages you will print a list of the
this command.  If no messages have been selected, you will be asked if you
want to print a list of the messages in that folder.  Also, if this icon
is selected while you are in the @{b}Address Book@{ub}, the address book contents
will be printed.

When first activated, the print function will bring up a requester asking
how many copies you wish to print.  It will be preset to 1.  You can
change this number to the number of copies you wish to print.  The @{b}[+]@{ub} and
@{b}[-]@{ub} gadgets to the right of the numeric entry gadget allow you to
increment or decrement the number.  Pressing @{b}RETURN@{ub} or selecting the @{b}[OK]@{ub}
gadget will then start the printing process.

When first activated, the print function will bring up a requester asking
how many copies you wish to print.  It will be preset to 1.  You can
change this number to the number of copies you wish to print.  Pressing
@{b}RETURN@{ub} or selecting the @{b}OK@{ub} gadget will then start the printing process.

Each of the messages will be printed in the order that they appear in your
@{" message list " link AEM-8200}.  All selected messages will be printed whether they are
marked for deletion or not.

A progress indicator will appear as each message is being sent to your
printer which shows the percent being printed and the total bytes being
printed.  This progress indicator has an @{b}[ABORT]@{ub} button which allows you
to terminate the printing.  However, beware, most printers have a
substantial buffer which will probably receive all of your messages quite
quickly.  Once the messages are in the printer's buffer, the printing can
not be cancelled without turning your printer off.

A heading line will be printed on each page of the listing which contains the
following information:

@{b}Message Sent on @{i}mm/dd/yy@{ui} (@{i}dow@{ui}) at @{i}hh:mm@{ui} [AM/PM], [from/to] [name]  Page @{i}n@{ui}@{ub}

@{i}where@{ui}
    @{b}mm/dd/yy@{ub} is the date the message was sent (received) or composed,

    @{b}dow@{ub} is the day of the week the message was sent (received) or
        composed,

    @{b}hh:mm@{ub} is the hour and minute the message was sent (received) or
        composed using a 12 hour clock,

    @{b}[AM/PM]@{ub} is either @{b}AM@{ub} or @{b}PM@{ub}.

    [@{b}from/to@{ub}] if the message was received you will see "@{b}from@{ub}", and if you
        composed or sent the message you will see "@{b}to@{ub}",

    [@{b}name@{ub}] is the full name of the sender or nickname of recipient,

    @{b}n@{ub} is the page number.


On the first page only, if there are attachments, the following line will
appear below the heading line:

    @{b}This message has attachments (See last page for list).@{ub}

On a separate page, after the message, the attachment list will appear,
providing the @{b}"Include Attachment List in Print Out"@{ub} item is checkmarked
in the @{" General Parameters " link AEM-4900} portion of the @{" Configuration Setup Window" link AEM-4200}.  
Printing the attachment list is the default action.

If attachments are a @{b}Text@{ub} or @{b}Message@{ub} type and are either @{b}7-bit, 8-bit,@{ub} or
@{b}quoted-printable@{ub} encoding format they will be printed following the body
of the message.  Other types of attachments you will have to save to a
file and print the file with an appropriate printing program.

@{b}Note:@{ub} no check is made whether a selected message is deleted or not.  If
a deleted message is selected it will be printed anyway (this is probably
desireable in certain circumstances).  If you don't want to print it,
de-select it!

This function can also print a list of all messages in a folder.  To do
this, @{b}DO NOT@{ub} select any messages in the folder.  A requester will appear
when you select either the @{i}printer command icon@{ui} or the @{i}Print menu@{ui} item
which says:



                      @{b}No messages selected to print!

                       Do you want to print a list
                        of all the messages in the
                         [@{i}name of folder@{ui}] folder?

                      [YES]                     [NO]@{b}


By selecting @{b}[YES]@{ub} you will print a list of the messages.  Messages will
be printed in the order that they appear in the message list.

Selecting @{b}[NO]@{ub} will terminate the printing function.

Printing uses your Preferences Printer.  You should set it up properly
before executing @{b}AEMail@{ub}, or you can set it up while in @{b}AEMail@{ub} by using
the @{" General Parameters " link AEM-4900} page on the @{" Configuration Setup Window" link AEM-4200}.  You can 
also specify a print file that the output will be directed to.

As a default @{b}AEMail@{ub} will space 4 lines down before starting to print.
This @{i}Top Margin@{ui}, however, can be changed in the @{b}General Parameters@{ub} section
of the @{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-6070 "COMMAND ICON TOOL BAR/Delete/Undelete Messages"

                        @{b}DELETE/UNDELETE MESSAGES@{ub}

@{i}Activation key code:@{ui} @{b}x@{ub}
                     @{b}Right Amiga x@{ub}

This function can be activated from either the icon strip or the @{b}Delete/Undelete@{ub}
sub-item in the @{" Messages menu " link AEM-7300}.  It will delete OR undelete all messages that
have been selected in a @{" message list " link AEM-8200}.

Whether deleting or undeleting takes place depends on the current status
of the message.  If it is currently marked for deletion, it will be
undeleted.

This function only @{i}marks@{ui} (or @{i}unmarks@{ui}) messages for @{b}deletion@{ub}.  The messages
will actually be deleted only when @{b}AEMail@{ub} exits.  The message counts in
the folder icons, however, will @{i}only@{ui} represent @{b}undeleted@{ub} messages.  You
can also suppress the display of deleted messages in the message list by
unchecking the @{" Show/Deleted Messages " link AEM-7309} item under the @{" Messages " link AEM-7300} menu.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-6080 "COMMAND ICON STRIP/Compose a Message"

                            @{b}COMPOSE A MESSAGE@{ub}

@{i}Activation key codes:@{ui} @{b}Right Amiga n@{ub} (Compose a new message)
                      @{b}Right Amiga r@{ub} (Reply to current message)
                      @{b}Right Amiga >@{ub} (Forward current message)
                      @{b}Right Amiga e@{ub} (Edit Current Message)

The @{b}Compose a Message@{ub} function brings up the @{" Compose Message window " link AEM-8700} so that
you can enter information about the message you are about to compose.  The
information you enter includes the @{b}Nickname@{ub} or @{b}UserID@{ub} of the receipient of the
message, the @{b}subject@{ub} and whether or not you want to send @{b}cc@{ub}'s to anyone.

A special @{b}[Call Address Book]@{ub} button is provided that allows you to call
up an abreviated version of the @{" Address Book " link AEM-8500}.  By clicking on an address
book name you can transfer the nickname for that address to any of the
@{b}To:, cc:,@{ub} or @{b}bcc:@{ub}  fields.  You select the field you want to transfer the
nickname to by a special cycle gadget in the address book display.

When the @{b}Address Book@{ub} is displayed from the @{b}Compose@{ub} window, all groups
will show as the group header and number of entries in that group.  For
@{b}AEMail registered users@{ub}, an @{b}[Expand]@{ub} checkmarked gadget will allow you to
expand the groups so you can see all of the entries.  Exiting from the
@{b}Address Book@{ub} display is accomplished by double clicking on an address (it
will be transferred to the appropriate field and then the @{b}Address Book@{ub}
will be closed) or by clicking on the Close gadget in the window border or
at the bottom of the window.

To compose the message text you would click on the @{b}[Compose/Edit Message]@{ub}
which will call up your editor.  When you save and exit from the editor,
you will be brought back to the @{b}Compose Message@{ub} window.

You can specify the format that you want you text to be sent as.  You can
select between @{b}8-bit, 7-bit, quoted-printable,@{ub} or @{b}encoded binary (BASE64)@{ub}.
This facilitates sending messages with foriegn character sets through
gateways that only handle 7 bit data.  @{b}The default is 8 bit@{ub}.  Both
@{b}quoted-printable@{ub} and @{b}encoded binary@{ub} are 7 bit schemes for representing
8 bit data.  When you display a message which is in either
@{b}quoted-printable@{ub} or @{b}encoded binary@{ub}, it will be displayed correctly.

You can also specify any attachments you want to send with the message
through the @{" Add Attachment Requester " link AEM-8710} or you can specify a signature file
or additional headers.

After supplying the required information, you can then save your message
into either the @{b}PENDING@{ub} or @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder or send it directly.  If you
select @{b}[Send Message Now]@{ub} you @{u}MUST@{uu} be connected to your Internet provider.

If a message has been selected in any folder, @{i}except the @{b}PENDING, QUEUED,@{ub}
or @{b}SENT@{ub} folders, before clicking on the @{b}COMPOSE MESSAGE@{ub} icon, the compose
will be treated as a reply to the selected message.  The original @{b}Reply-To@{ub}
address for the message you are replying to will appear in the @{b}To:@{ub}  field
on the Compose window.  If the @{b}Reply-To:@{ub} address is not present the @{b}From:@{ub}
field will be used as recipient of the reply.  You can force the @{b}From:@{ub}
field to be used by holding down the @{i}shift@{ui} key when you click on the
@{b}Compose@{ub} icon.

If you are not interested in creating a reply, you can change to creating
a new message to be sent to the same (or different) recipient, or you can
forward the message to a different recipient.

If the message selected was in the @{b}PENDING@{ub} or @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder, you will be
allowed to either edit the selected message or create a new message.  If
you edit the message it will be stored back into the the folder you
selected or will be sent (if you click on @{b}[Send Message Now]@{ub}.  The old
message will be automatically removed from the system.

If the message selected was in the @{b}SENT@{ub} folder you will only be able to
create a new message.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-6090 "COMMAND ICON TOOL BAR/Send Message Immediately"

                         @{b}SEND MESSAGE IMMEDIATELY@{ub}

@{i}Activation key code:@{ui} @{b}s@{ub}

With the @{b}Send Message Immediately@{ub} function an attempt will be made to send
the Selected Message(s) to their recipients.  The messages to be sent must be
in either the @{b}PENDING@{ub} or @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder. The messages will be sent from the
@{b}PENDING@{ub} folder only if the @{b}PENDING@{ub} folder is selected; otherwise they will
be sent from the @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder.

If messages are selected (see @{" Multiple Selection " link AEM-8210}), a requester will appear
that asks:

    @{b}Do you wish to send the entire [@{u}pending/queued@{uu}] folder
    or just selected messages?@{ub}

The choices available are:

        @{b}[ENTIRE FOLDER]     [SELECTED MESSAGES]     [CANCEL SEND]@{ub}


If no messages have been selected or all of the messages in the folder are
selected, the entire selected folder will be sent without a requester
appearing.  @{i}Deleted messages are never sent.@{ui}

If there are no undeleted messages in the selected folder a notification
requester will appear that indicates that "@{b}No messages available to send@{ub}".

A check will then be made to see if you have an active connection to your
Internet provider.  If you do not, a requester will be displayed which
informs the user that we are in offline mode and that the messages can not
be sent.

If you are connected to your Internet provider, a message will appear in
the top title bar that says "@{b}Connecting to SMTP Host to send mail@{ub}".  Once
the connection is made. @{b}AEMail@{ub} will display "@{b}Starting to send @{i}n@{ui}
messages@{ub}" where @{i}n@{ui} is the number of messages selected to send.  If we are
unable to connect or an error is reported back from your Internet
provider, a message will appear in the title bar showing the nature of the
error and the messages will not be sent.

Sometimes, if the error message is from your Internet Provider, you will
not be able to see all of it.  If your @{" TCPLOG " link AEM-9180} is active, you will be able
to see it on the Log File, however.

A progress window will also be displayed which will show the current
number of the message being sent, the total number of messages being sent,
the percentage of the current message already sent and the total bytes in
the current message being sent.  The percentage will be shown as both a
number and on a graphic slider.

If there is more than one recipient for the message, the progress
indicator will also show @{b}Sending to @{i}n@{ui} of @{i}n@{ui} recipients of message@{ub} as each
recipient of the message is contacted.  This way you will see the progress
of contacting recipients for large groups of recipients.

This progress window also has an @{b}[ABORT]@{ub} button which allows you to
terminate the sending of the current and all remaining messages to your
@{b}SMTP Server@{ub}.

All nicknames used in @{b}To:, cc:,@{ub} and @{b}bcc:@{ub} header fields will be expanded
to the form:  @{b}@{i}Real Name<userid>@{ui}@{ub}.  Group nicknames will be expanded to the
@{b}Real Names@{ub} and @{b}userids@{ub} of all members of the group, or, if @{b}Send Header
Only@{ub} is set for that group, @{i}only@{ui} the group header will be displayed in
the @{b}To:@{ub} field.

When each message is successfully sent, the following message will be
displayed in the upper title bar:

    @{b}Mail @{i}n@{ui} of @{i}n@{ui} successfully sent to [@{u}@{i}To: addressee@{ui}@{uu}]@{ub}

The @{i}n@{ui} in the above message indicates the message number and the total messages
to be sent.  The [@{u}@{i}To: addressee@{ui}@{uu}] indicates who the message was addressed to.
If it was addressed to multiple addressees, the first addressee will appear
followed by @{b}, et al...@{ub}.

The message will also be placed in the @{b}SENT@{ub} folder and marked as deleted
in the @{b}PENDING@{ub} or @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder.

In the current version of @{b}AEMail@{ub}, the send process operates in the same
execution mode as @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  This means that you can not perform any other
@{b}AEMail@{ub} operation until the message is either rejected by your Internet
provider or successfully received by your provider (unless you abort the
process).  In a future version, this process will be moved to a background
process so that you can perform work in @{b}AEMail@{ub} while the sending of the
message proceeds.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-6100 "COMMAND ICON TOOL BAR/Queue Message for Later Deliverly"

                     @{b}QUEUE MESSAGE FOR LATER DELIVERY@{ub}

@{i}Activation key code:@{ui} @{b}q@{ub}

This function is provided to allow the user to mark messages that you want
sent later.  Normally, @{i}NO MORE EDITING OF THESE MESSAGES should occur once
they are moved to the @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder@{ui}.  However, @{b}AEMail@{ub} does allow this to
occur.  Messages can be moved back to the @{b}PENDING@{ub} folder with the
@{" Transfer... " link AEM-7305} item in the @{" Messages  " link AEM-7300} menu.  Messages for queuing must come
from the @{b}PENDING@{ub} folder.  The messages can also be placed in either the
@{b}PENDING@{ub} or @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folders (or sent) by the @{" Compose Message " link AEM-8700} window.

You can send these messages manually from the @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder any time you
want by either sending the entire folder or individual messages in the
folder.  This is done by selecting the @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder and clicking on the
@{" SEND IMMEDIATE " link AEM-6090} icon or by selecting the @{" Send Queued Mail " link AEM-7102}
item under the @{" Project " link AEM-7100} menu.  Alternately you can press the @{b}q@{ub} key.

@{b}AEMail@{ub} also allows the user the option of sending queued messages
automatically when @{b}AEMail@{ub} is first activated, or when the program
terminates provided you are connected to your Internet provider (see
@{" STARTING AEMAIL " link AEM-5000}).  @{b}AEMail@{ub} will also perform this check when you make
connection to your Internet provider through the @{b}StartNet@{ub} script unless
you have disabled this feature with the @{" TCP/IP Parameters " link AEM-4400} page of your
@{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

With this option you can compose messages when you are in an off-line
mode, save them in @{b}PENDING@{ub} while you are working on them, and then @{b}QUEUE@{ub}
them when you are satisfied with the message you want to send.  The Queued
messages are then automatically sent when you log onto your Internet
Provider by the @{b}StartNet@{ub} command.

If no messages have been selected (or if all of the messages have been
selected),  the entire @{b}PENDING@{ub} folder will be queued.  Deleted messages in
the @{b}PENDING@{ub} folder are never queued.

If there are no undeleted messages in the @{b}PENDING@{ub} folder a notification
requester will appear that indicates that "@{b}No messages available to
queue@{ub}".

The messages that are selected will be placed in the @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder and
removed from the @{b}PENDING@{ub} folder.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-6110 "COMMAND ICON TOOL BAR/Retrieve Messages"

                            @{b}RETRIEVE MESSAGES@{ub}

@{i}Activation key code:@{ui} @{b}Right Amiga m@{ub}

When the @{b}Retrieve Messages@{ub} function is selected, @{b}AEMail@{ub} will attempt to
connect to the @{b}POP host server@{ub} and transfer any mail at the server to
your AMIGA.

If you are in @{b}offline mode@{ub} (you are not connected to your Internet Service
Provider or @{b}AEMail@{ub} can not connect, for some reason, to your POP server),
see @{" Retrieving Messages from Files " link AEM-6111}.

If you are online with your Internet provider and connection can be made
to your @{b}POP mail server@{ub}, all messages stored on the server will be
transferred to the AMIGA.  They will be stored as individual messages in
the @{b}AEMAIL:@{ub}  directory with cryptic file names (see @{" messages " link AEM-9170} file).

A progress window will also be displayed which will show the number of the
current message being received, the total number of messages being
received, the percentage of the current message already received and the
total bytes in the message being received.  The percentage will be shown
as both a number and a graphic slider.

This progress window also has an @{b}[ABORT]@{ub} button which allows you to
terminate the receipt of the current and all remaining messages from your
@{b}POP Server@{ub}.

@{b}PLEASE NOTE:@{ub} The abort process only aborts the receipt of messages into
the AMIGA, It does NOT abort the transfer of data from the @{b}POP Server@{ub}.
While @{b}AEMail@{ub} disconnects from the server, the server may be unaware of
this and continue to send the remainder of the message.  If @{b}AEMail@{ub}
attempts to re-establish contact with the Server while it is still sending
the message @{b}AEMail@{ub} may start to receive the middle of the previously
requested message. @{b}AEMail@{ub} has been programmed to recognize this and will
temporarily report that the POP connection could not be established.  Once
the @{b}POP Server@{ub} finishes transferring the message, it should become
available for another connection.

The progress window will be shown both when retrieving messages from your
@{b}POP server@{ub} and from files, however, if you are retrieving a message
stream, @{b}AEMail@{ub} will not be able to correctly determine the number of
messages being retrieved.  Therefor the "@{i}n@{ui} of @{i}n@{ui}" indicator will be
incorrect.

If mail on the server is to be deleted, the @{" Delete Host Mail " link AEM-7402} item in the
@{" Retrieve Messages " link AEM-7400} menu must be checked.  If this menu item is not checked,
mail will NOT be deleted on your @{b}POP server@{ub}.  This has no effect when you
are retrieving messages from a file.  @{b}NOTE:@{ub} the AEMAIL @{" Installation " link AEM-3000}
script automatically defaults to deleting host mail.  You will have to
un-check this item if you want to keep mail on your @{b}POP Server@{ub}.

Since old mail may not be deleted on your server, a menu item has been
provided under the @{" Retrieve Messages " link AEM-7400} menu called @{" Excl Dup Msgs " link AEM-7402}. When
this item is checked duplicate messages from the mail server which are
currently stored in any incoming folder will not be stored again.  The
only folders not checked for duplicate messages are the @{b}PENDING, QUEUED@{ub}
and any folder designed to hold @{b}SENT@{ub} messages.  Again, the default action
with the installation script is to delete duplicate messages.

Currently, like sending messages to your Internet provider, the retrieval
process is run in the same execution mode as @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  This means that all
of the messages must be received from the @{b}POP Server@{ub} before any other @{b}AEMail@{ub}
process can take place.  Again, a future version will move the retrieval
process to a background process so you can proceed with other @{b}AEMail@{ub}
functions while retrieval takes place.

You can be running another program on your Amiga, however when the message
retrieval takes place.  If you are in iconify mode when retrieval takes
place it will be done totally in the background although you will see the
@{b}You have mail@{ub} requester (@{i}see below@{ui}).

Every time a new message is retrieved AND stored, the total and new
message counts in the folder list AND the folder icon strip will be
updated.  Also the top title bar will display the following message:

 @{b}Message @{i}n@{ui} of @{i}n@{ui} retrieved[@{u}/deleted@{uu}] from [@{u}POP server/file@{uu}], [@{u}not@{uu}] saved@{ub}

The first @{i}n@{ui} indicates the current message number and the second @{i}n@{ui}
indicates the total number of messages being retrieved. (@{b}NOTE:@{ub} This
message will also appear when local mail files are being transferred, but
the counts may not be accurate if you are retrieving from a message
stream.  Also, the retrieval process from local files is so fast, you may
only see the message for the last retrieval.)

The @{b}@{i}/deleted@{ui}@{ub} will appear if the message has been deleted on the @{b}POP
server@{ub} and @{b}@{i}not@{ui}@{ub} will appear if the message was a duplicate and was not
saved.

You can check for messages on your @{b}POP server@{ub} and retrieve these messages
manually any time you wish by clicking on the @{b}RETRIEVE MESSAGES@{ub} icon.
Also, the user has the option of retrieving messages automatically when
@{b}AEMail@{ub} is first activated (provided you are connected to your Internet
provider), each time you execute your @{" StartNet " link AEM-7501} script from within
@{b}AEMail@{ub} (see the @{" TCP/IP menu " link AEM-7500}), and when you quit @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

You can also set a time interval in minutes in which @{b}AEMail@{ub} will
periodically check for new mail (see @{" TCP/IP " link AEM-4400} parameters page on the
@{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}). This function is done in the background and 
if one or more messages are on your @{b}POP server@{ub}, the following requester 
will pop up:


                             @{b}YOU HAVE MAIL!!

                  @{i}n@{ui} Messages available on the POP Server

                Do you wish to receive these messages now?@{ub}


Replying @{b}[YES]@{ub} to the above requester will start the retrieval of the
messages.  This requester will only pop up when you are in the main @{b}AEMail@{ub}
screen and are not in the middle of some function such as composing a
message, transferring or saving a message, printing a message, or
performing configuration changes.

@{i}@{b}NOTE:@{ub} if you did not specify that you wanted messages deleted from your
@{b}POP Server@{ub} as you transferred them to your AMIGA, the @{b}YOU HAVE MAIL@{ub}
requester will pop up each time the system checks for mail.@{ui}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-6111 "COMMAND ICON TOOL BAR/Retrieve Messages (From Files)"

                      @{b}Retrieving Messages from Files@{ub}

If you are in offline mode (you are not connected to your Internet Service
Provider or @{b}AEMail@{ub} can not connect, for some reason, to your @{b}POP server@{ub}),
you will see a requester that asks:


                   @{b}!! We are running in Offline mode !!

               Do you wish to receive messages from files?@{ub}


Clicking on @{b}[NO]@{ub} will terminate the retrieval process.

Clicking on @{b}[YES]@{ub} will bring up a file requester which will allow you to
select one or more files.  The directory for these files is setup as the
@{b}Retrieve Mail Directory@{ub} in the @{" Paths Page " link AEM-4500} of the @{" Configuration Setup " link AEM-4200}.
Window.  The default @{b}Retrieve Mail Directory@{ub} is your program directory.

@{b}AEMail@{ub} automatically recognizes mail stored as individual messages or as
message streams (such as stored by @{i}AmiPOP@{ui}).  The only requirement is that
the message stream must separate messages with data beginning:

    @{b}...<LF><LF>From @{i}UserID@{ui}@{ub}

The first message in the stream must begin with the separator without the
leading @{b}<LF>@{ub}.  This is saved and checked against each line in the mail
stream (with leading @{b}<LF>@{ub}) to determine where the message boundary
occurs.  This allows @{b}UserID@{ub}s other that the user's @{b}UserID@{ub} in separators.

This also works with message streams saved by the @{" Save Message to File " link AEM-6050}
or the @{b}Export..@{ub} item in the @{" messages menu " link AEM-7300}.

It is also assumed that lines have been stored in the file ending in @{b}<LF>@{ub} and
not @{b}<CR><LF>@{ub} (@{b}<CR>@{ub} is $0D and @{b}<LF>@{ub} is $0A).

If you encounter a message stream that does not use the above to separate
messages, please report what was used and what product was used to create
the message stream.  A copy of the message stream on floppy or sent to me
as an email attachment would be very handy. (@{i}see@{ui}
@{" Bug Reports and Suggestions " link AEM-9700})

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-6130 "COMMAND ICON TOOL BAR/Start/Terminate Network Connection"

                     @{b}Start TCP/IP Network Connection@{ub}

@{i}Activation key code:@{ui} @{b}Right Amiga t@{ub}

This will start your network connection to your Internet Provider using
your @{b}StartNet@{ub} script.  It performs the same function as the @{" Start Net " link AEM-7501}
item under the @{" TCP/IP " link AEM-7500} menu.


                   @{b}Terminate TCP/IP Network Connection@{ub}

@{i}Activation key code:@{ui} @{b}Right Amiga h@{ub}

This will terminate your network connection to your Internet Provider
using your @{b}StopNet@{ub} script.  It performs the same function as the
@{" Stop Net " link AEM-7502} item under the @{" TCP/IP " link AEM-7500} menu.
@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-6140 "COMMAND ICON TOOL BAR/Copy Messages"

                      @{b}Copy Messages to a New Folder@{ub}

@{i}Activation key code:@{ui} @{b}Right Amiga =@{ub}

Clicking on this icon copies all @{" selected messages " link AEM-8200} from the
@{" selected folder " link AEM-8100} to a new folder.  When you select this icon, a
@{b}Notification window@{ub} appears which says:


                    @{b}Select Folder to Copy Messages To!

                                 [CANCEL]@{ub}


When the window appears, click on the folder icon that represents the
folder you want the messages copied to.  The window will automatically
disappear at that time.

The selected messages will be copied to that folder.  Messages will remain
in both folders.

Clicking on @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} before clicking on a folder will cancel the
operation.

As the messages are being copied, the folder message list that the the
messages are copied to will be displayed.  Once the copy is complete, the
folder message list from which the messages are copied will be displayed.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-6150 "COMMAND ICON TOOL BAR/Transfer Messages"

                    @{b}Transfer Messages to a New Folder@{ub}

@{i}Activation key code:@{ui} @{b}Right Amiga -@{ub}

Clicking on this icon moves all @{" selected messages " link AEM-8200} from the
@{" selected folder " link AEM-8100} to a new folder.  When you select icon, a @{b}Notification
window@{ub} appears which says:


                  @{b}Select Folder to Transfer Messages To!

                                 [CANCEL]@{ub}


When the window appears, click on the folder icon that represents the
folder you want the messages transferred to.  The window will
automatically disappear at that time.

The selected messages will be copied to that folder, and the messages in
the folder from which the messages are copied will be marked as
@{" deleted " link AEM-6070}.

Clicking on @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} before clicking on a folder will cancel the
operation.

As the messages are being transferred, the folder message list that the
the messages are transferred to will be displayed.  Once the transfer is
complete, the folder message list from which the messages are copied and
deleted will be displayed.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7000 "AEMAIL MENUS"

                              @{b}AEMAIL Menus@{ub}

Whenever you are displaying folder lists, message lists, or messages
themselves a menu strip is active and will be displayed when you press the
right mouse button.

Below is a list of all the current menus in the @{b}AEMail@{ub} menu strip.
Clicking on a menu item in this list will bring up a list of the menu
sub-items and clicking on a sub-item will bring up a description of the
sub-item's functions:

    @{" Project menu " link AEM-7100}
    @{" Folders menu " link AEM-7200}
    @{" Messages menu " link AEM-7300}
    @{" Retrieve Messages menu " link AEM-7400}
    @{" TCP/IP menu " link AEM-7500}
    @{" ARexx/DOS menu " link AEM-7600}

The @{b}ARexx/DOS@{ub} menu is also available when the @{b}"Edit and save message line
to @{" clipboard " link AEM-5500}; set @{" ARexx variable " link AEM-5800}"@{ub} window is active.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7100 "AEMAIL MENUS/Project menu"

                            @{b}Project menu@{b}

The Project menu consists of the following items:

    @{" Configuration... " link AEM-7101}
    @{" Send Queued Mail " link AEM-7102}
    @{" Iconify AEMAIL " link AEM-7103}
    @{" Send Notification... " link AEM-7108}
    @{" Getting Help " link AEM-7104}
    @{" About... " link AEM-7104}
    @{" Quit... " link AEM-7105}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7101 "AEMAIL MENUS/Project menu/CONFIGURATION..."

                              @{b}Configuration...@{ub}

This has five submenu items for controlling your configuration.  These
sub-menu items are:

@{b}Open...@{ub}

    This brings up a file requester which allows you to specify
    a configuration file other than the @{" configuration file " link AEM-9110} assigned to 
    the current user.  This configuration file @{i}must@{ui} have the same mail
    directory as your current configuration.  Once you have opened
    this configuration file it becomes your @{i}current active
    configuration@{ui}.

    Although you can specify an alternate configuration file with this
    menu sub-item, your original configuration file will be used if
    you quit @{b}AEMail@{ub} and reload it.  To permanently change the
    configuration file name and or location you will have to re-perform
    the @{" Installation " link AEM-3000} process.

    The use of this menu sub-item and the @{b}SAVE AS@{ub} sub-item allows
    you to specify alternate locations for your mail @{" Identity " link AEM-4300} items
    (i.e., @{b}POP3 Userid, Password, Pop Server, SMTP Server,@{ub} etc.).


@{b}Edit...@{ub}

    The @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200} will be activated allowing complete
    configuration data to be entered for the @{i}current active
    configuration@{ui} file.

@{b}Save@{ub}

    This will save the current configuration settings in the @{i}currently
    active configuration@{ui} file.  It serves the same purpose as the
    previously @{b}Save Settings@{ub} menu item (@{i}versions prior to 1.13@{ui}) in which
    all of the current settings including the current state of the
    @{" Display Full Header " link AEM-7307}, @{" Foward Body Text Only " link AEM-7306},
    @{" Include Header in Response " link AEM-7308}, @{" Exclude Duplicate Messages " link AEM-7402},
    and @{" Delete Host Mail " link AEM-7402} menu items.

@{b}Save As...@{ub}

    This is the same as @{b}Save@{ub} except that a file requester will be
    brought up which allow you to rename the @{i}current active
    configuration@{ui} file.  This new configuration file will have the same
    mail directory as the current configuration file.  The new name
    becomes the @{b}new@{ub} @{i}current active configuration@{ui} file;  however, 
    if you quit @{b}AEMail@{ub} and reload, the original configuration file
    specified in the @{" CONFIG= " link AEM-4119} Tool Type will again be the active
    configuration file.

    To permanently change the configuration file name and or location
    you will have to re-perform the @{" Installation " link AEM-3000} process.


@{b}Restore Default@{ub}

    This reads in the file specified in the @{" CONFIG= " link AEM-4119} Tool Type OR the
    @{" config= " link AEM-5200} parameter on the Shell call to @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  The particular file
    that is used is referred to as your @{ub}base configuration@{ub}.  The @{ub}base
    configuration@{ub} now becomes your @{i}currently active configuration@{ui} file.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7102 "AEMAIL MENUS/Project menu/SEND QUEUED MAIL"

                            @{b}Send Queued Mail@{ub}

This will send all messages in the @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder.  (See the
@{" SEND MESSAGE IMMEDIATELY " link AEM-6090} command in the @{" COMMAND ICON STRIP " link AEM-6000}.

This action will also occur automatically when you first load @{b}AEMail@{ub} and
when you exit @{b}AEMail@{ub} provided you are connected to your Internet provider.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7103 "AEMAIL MENUS/Project menu/ICONIFY AEMAIL"

                              @{b}Iconify AEMail@{ub}

You can iconify @{b}AEMail@{ub} with an iconify bar on the Workbench screen
with this menu item.  When this menu item is selected, the @{b}AEMail@{ub}
screen will be closed and a button bar will appear on the Workbench
screen with

              @{b}AEMAIL (Click on Close or with RMB to restore)@{ub}

in the title.  When the iconified bar is in selected mode, clicking
either on the close gadget or with the right mouse button will restore
the @{" AEMail screen " link AEM-5100}.

Initially the iconify bar will open at the top center of the
Workbench screen, but it can be dragged anywhere on the screen.
@{b}AEMail@{ub} remembers where you dragged the bar so the next time
you iconify, the bar will be at that new position.

There is also a hotkey provided for iconifying @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  This is
@{b}RIGHT-AMIGA-I@{ub}.  This hot key, and also @{b}LEFT-AMIGA-I@{ub},  will also
restore the @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen when in the iconify mode.

When in iconify mode, periodic checking of mail on your POP server
is still done.  If mail is found, the @{b}YOU HAVE MAIL@{ub} requester
will pop up on the Workbench screen.  You can retrieve the mail
immediately by clicking on the @{b}[YES]@{ub} gadget.  The requester will
disappear and retrieval of messages will occur in the background
and no progress indicator will appear.  When you return to the
@{b}AEMail@{ub} screen, the new messages will be in your @{b}INBOX@{ub} folder.

You can also push the @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen to the back exposing the
screen immediately behind the @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen or the WorkBench
screen by hitting @{b}LEFT-AMIGA-M@{ub} when the @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen is being
displayed.  This is standard Amiga action.

If the @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen has been pushed to the back, hitting
@{b}LEFT-AMIGA-M@{ub} will bring the screen forward.  Note: if other
screens, besides the Workbench screen, are also present, they
may be moved to the front first so that you may have to hit
@{b}LEFT-AMIGA-M@{ub} several times before the @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen appears.

Since there is no screen to bring forward, this will not work
if the iconify action has been taken.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7104 "AEMAIL MENUS/Project menu/HELP & ABOUT"

                               @{b}Getting Help@{ub}

This will bring up the AEMail.guide page that describes how to get help
with AEMail using the [HELP] key.  There are also special help command
that can be obtained by using qualifier keys (SHIFT, ALT) with the [Help]
key.


                               @{b}About...@{ub}


This will display the @{b}name, version,@{ub} and @{b}date@{ub} of the program followed by
the @{b}ARexx Port Name@{ub} and information as to whether or not the shareware
registration message has been received and who the version is registered
to (with serial number).

Below that is information on how to contact the author of the program.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7105 "AEMAIL MENUS/Project menu/QUIT"

                                @{b}Quit...@{ub}

Exits @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

When this menu item is selected, @{b}AEMail@{ub} first checks to see if you are
connected to your Internet provider.  If you are, a connection will be
made to your @{b}POP Server@{ub} to see if there are any messages available on the
server.  If there are, the following requester will appear:


                   @{b}@{i}n@{ui} Messages Available on the POP Server

                 Do you wish to receive these messages now?@{ub}


If you click on the @{b}[YES]@{ub} button, those message will be retrieved at this
point. If you click on @{b}[NO]@{ub}, no message retrieval will take place.

After @{b}AEMail@{ub} checks to see if any messages are available on the @{b}POP
Server@{ub}, it also checks to see if any messages are in the @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder
(messages queued to be sent).  If there are, the following requester will
appear:


                     @{b}You have @{i}n@{ui} messages queued to be sent

                    Do you wish to send these messages now?@{ub}


If you click on the @{b}[YES]@{ub} button, all of the messages in the @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder
will be sent immediately. If you click on @{b}[NO]@{ub}, the queued messages will
not be sent.

After checking for POP messages and QUEUED messages, the following requester
will appear:


                 @{b}Do you wish to terminate your Host connection now?@{ub}


Selecting the @{b}[YES]@{ub} button will cause the @{i}stopnet@{ui} script to be executed
terminating your TCP/IP connection to your Internet provider.

@{i}You can disable all of these requesters with a checkmarked item in the
@{" TCP/IP " link AEM-4400} display on the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.  If they are disabled,
the @{b}[NO]@{ub} action will be assumed which each of the requesters.@{ui}

Finally, a requester will be displayed that asks:


                         @{b}Do You Really Want to Quit?@{ub}


Clicking on @{b}[YES]@{ub} will terminate the program and @{b}[NO]@{ub} will return to the
program.

When @{b}AEMail@{ub} exits, all messages marked for deletion will be deleted and
any configuration files in which data has been updated will be re-written.
You will probably see a great deal of disk activity at this time.  While
this disk activity is going on, a window will be displayed on the
Workbench screen saying:


                   @{b}Updating all AEMail Configuration Files!@{ub}


When updating is complete, this window will disappear.  @{u}@{b}WARNING:@{uu} DO NOT@{ub} turn
your computer off while this window is being displayed.  @{b}If you do your disk
will be corrupted!@{ub}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7106 "AEMAIL MENUS/Arexx/DOS menu/SEND AREXX/DOS COMMAND..."

                        @{b}Send AREXX/DOS Command...@{ub}

This will bring up a requester that looks like this:

         @{b}|=====================================================|
         |o| Send AREXX/DOS Command                            |
         |=====================================================|
         |                                                     |
         | |@| AREXX |[                         ][V][CLR][REQ] |
         |                                                     |
         | [ ] Opens On Workbench   [X] Execute Asynchronously |
         |                                                     |
         | [  OK  ]                                 [ CANCEL ] |
         |=====================================================|@{ub}

The cycle gadget has two states: @{b}AREXX@{ub} and @{b}DOS@{ub}.  Select the kind of
command (execute script or program) you want to start.  The string gadget
to the right of the cycle gadget is for entering the command.  Unless the
command (program or script) is in the same directory as the @{b}AEMail@{ub} program
or @{b}REXX:@{ub} (if it is an @{b}ARexx@{ub} command script), you must include the full
path name.  The last command you executed will always appear in this
string gadget when you first call up the requester.

The @{b}[V]@{ub} gadget is used to call up a listview of the past commands you have
executed.  You can click on one of these if you want to use a previous
command.  The last command you executed will always appear at the top of
the list.  The list of commands (up to the last 10) will be maintained
even after you quit @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  This list will close when you click on any
item in the list or, if you don't want any of the items, when you click
into any of the other gadgets in the requester.

Yhe @{b}[CLR]@{ub} gadget will clear the string gadget and the @{b}[REQ]@{ub} will call up a
file requester with which you can select the program or script you want to
execute.  The initial directory that is used in the requester is the
@{b}PROGDIR:@{ub} if it is a @{b}DOS@{ub} command or @{b}REXX:@{ub} if it is an @{b}ARexx@{ub} command.

The two checkmark gadgets on the second row are used for DOS commands
only.  They will be disabled for @{b}ARexx@{ub} commands.

If @{b}Opens on Workbench@{ub} is checked, a switch will be made to the Workbench
screen when the command is executed.  This is not necessary for @{b}ARexx@{ub}
command since there is an @{b}AEMail ARexx@{ub} command that will do this.

The @{b}Execute Asynchronously@{ub} checkmark gadget is used to execute the DOS
command in the background.  This will allow @{b}AEMail@{ub} to function when the
program that is called is being executed.  This item is, by default,
checkmarked.  If for some reason you want @{b}AEMail@{ub} to freeze while the
command (program) is being executed, you can un-checkmark this item.
Since all @{b}ARexx@{ub} command automatically execute in the background, this item
is uneccessary for @{b}ARexx@{ub} command scripts.

When you are ready to execute the command, click on @{b}[OK]@{ub}.  If you want to
cancel the operation, click on @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub}.

You can also bind @{b}ARexx@{ub} or @{b}DOS@{ub} commands to a function key.  You can have
up to 40 selections since the @{b}Shift, CTRL@{ub}, and @{b}ALT@{ub} keys can be used in
conjunction with the function keys.  This is done with the @{" ARexx Page " link AEM-4700} of
the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.  When you press the appropriate function 
key the @{b}ARexx@{ub} or @{b}DOS@{ub} command bonded to it will be executed.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7107 "AEMAIL MENUS/ARexx/DOS menu/SEND LAST COMMAND"

                            @{b}Send Last Command@{ub}


This menu item will send the last ARexx or DOS command sent by @{b}Send
AREXX/DOS command@{ub} without bringing up the @{" Send AREXX/DOS command " link AEM-7106}
requester.  It will @{u}not@{uu} send the last command activated by a function key.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7108 "AEMAIL MENUS/Project menu/SEND NOTIFICATION"

                           @{b}Send Notification...@{ub}

This menu item will bring up the @{" Send AEMail Notification Request " link AEM-2500}
window.  The purpose of this menu item is to allow users to send an @{b}AEMail
notification message@{ub} after they have initially loaded the current version
of @{b}AEMail@{ub} to inform the author of any changes in your information such as
a change of email address or any change in the optional information.  If
you had not previously sent some of the optional information under the
@{b}Options@{ub} tab and care to do so now, you can use this menu item to so
inform the author.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7200 "AEMAIL MENUS/Folders menu"

                            @{b}Folders menu@{ub}

The Folders menu consists of the following items:

    @{" New... " link AEM-7201}
    @{" Edit... " link AEM-7201}
    @{" Delete " link AEM-7201}
    @{" Move... " link AEM-7201}
    @{" Set Sort Key... " link AEM-7202}
    @{" Folder List " link AEM-7204}
    @{" Remove DELETED msgs " link AEM-7203}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7201 "AEMAIL MENUS/Folders menu/FOLDER MAINTENANCE"

                                  @{b}New...@{ub}

The @{" Configure Folder window " link AEM-8300} will be activated indicating that a new folder
should be created.  The  @{b}Configure Folder window@{ub} description details
how to create a new folder.



                                 @{b}Edit...@{ub}

The @{b}Configure Folder window@{ub} will be activated indicating that the current
selected folder description should be edited.  The current selected folder is
the folder that has a depressed frame.  You can change the selected folder
by single clicking on the appropriate folder icon or selecting a folder from
the @{" folder list " link AEM-8100}.  See the description of the @{" Configure Folder window " link AEM-8300}
for details on how to change the folder description.



                                  @{b}Delete@{ub}

This will delete the folder that has been selected.  You will not be able to
delete a folder that has active messages in it.  If there are deleted messages
in the folder, the messages will be immediately deleted along with the folder.
@{i}There is no way you can get these deleted messages back.@{ui}


                                 @{b}Move...@{ub}

This menu item allows you to re-arrange the folder list.  Select the
folder you want to move either from the folder list or the folder icon.
When you select this menu item, a Notification window appears which says:

             @{b}Select folder to place @{i}folder-name@{ui} folder after@{ub}

                                 @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub}

When the window appears, click on the folder icon (or the line in the
folder list) that represents the folder you want to move the selected
folder after.  The window will automatically disappear at that time and
the folder list and icons will be re-arranged.

Clicking on @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} before clicking on a folder will cancel the
operation.

You can not re-arrange the position of the @{b}INBOX@{ub}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7202 "AEMAIL MENUS/Folders menu/SET SORT KEY"

                              @{b}Set Sort Key...@{ub}

Activates the @{b}Set Sort Key window@{ub} for the current selected folder.  See the
description of the @{" Set Sort Key window " link AEM-8400} for details on how to set the folder
sort keys.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7204 "AEMAIL MENUS/Folders menu/FOLDER List"

                               @{b}Folder List@{ub}

This has three submenu items as follows:

@{b}Display@{ub}

    This will display the folder list in the lower window.  This is the
    same as clicking on the @{b}Display Folder List@{ub} icon.  This list shows
    each folder with its short name (@{b}INBOX@{ub}, @{b}PENDING@{ub}, etc), a description
    of the folder, the number of unread mesages in the folder, and the
    total number of messages in the folder.

@{b}Backup...@{ub}

    This will backup your current @{b}folder.config@{ub} file.  A file requester
    will be presented asking for the name of your backup file.  The
    default name will be @{b}folder.config.bak@{ub}, but you can name it anything
    but @{b}folder.config@{ub}.  This facility has been provided to create a
    backup of the folder.config file in the event it becomes corrupted.

    @{b}WARNING:@{ub} The format of the backup @{b}folder.config@{ub} file is @{i}not the same@{ui}
    as that of the @{b}folder.config@{ub} file.  You @{i}cannot@{ui} copy the backup file
    over the @{b}folder.config@{ub} file and have a valid @{b}folder.config@{ub} file.  You
    must use the @{b}Restore@{ub} menu item listed below to properly restore the
    backup file.

    If you mistakenly copy the backup file over the @{b}folder.config@{ub} file you
    can restore a valid folder.config file by first deleting the bad
    @{b}folder.config@{ub} file and then using the @{b}Restore@{ub} command below.

@{b}Restore...@{ub}

    This will restore your current @{b}folder.config@{ub} file from a previously
    saved @{b}folder.config@{ub} backup file.  A file requester will be presented
    asking for the name of the backup file.  The default name will be
    @{b}folder.config.bak@{ub}.

    @{b}YOU MUST USE THIS COMMAND TO PROPERLY RESTORE THE BACKUP FILE.@{ub}

    @{b}WARNING:@{ub}  If you restore a backup file that has a different list of
    folders (or a different order of files), the new folder list will not
    take effect until you quit and then reload @{b}AEMail@{ub}.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7203 "AEMAIL MENUS/Folders menu/Remove DELETED msgs"

                            @{b}Remove DELETED Msgs@{ub}

This will @{b}IMMEDIATELY@{ub} delete @{b}ALL@{ub} messages marked for deletion in the
current active folder.  This means that they will no longer appear in
the message list for that folder and they will be physically deleted
from your mail directory.

Before actually removing the messages the following requester will appear:


                @{b}This will remove all deleted messages in the
                          [@{i}folder_name@{ui}] folder
                 If you continue you can not retrieve them!@{ub}


You will given the option to either @{b}[CONTINUE]@{ub} or @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub}.  If you select
@{b}[CONTINUE]@{ub} all the messages marked for deletion in the folder will be
removed.  @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} will abort the operation.

A busy pointer will be displayed while the messages are being removed.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7300 "AEMAIL MENUS/Messages menu"

                             @{b}Messages menu@{ub}

The Messages menu consists of the following items:

    @{" Show " link AEM-7309}
    @{" Compose... " link AEM-7301}
    @{" Reply " link AEM-7301}
    @{" Forward... " link AEM-7301}
    @{" Edit... " link AEM-7301}
    @{" Select    None " link AEM-7302}
    @{" Select All " link AEM-7302}
    @{" Last Selected " link AEM-7302}
    @{" Export... " link AEM-6050}
    @{" Copy... " link AEM-7304}
    @{" Transfer... " link AEM-7305}
    @{" Print " link AEM-6060}
    @{" Delete/Undelete... " link AEM-6070}
    @{" Lock/Unlock " link AEM-7310}
    @{" Display Full Header " link AEM-7307}
    @{" Forward Body Text Only " link AEM-7306}
    @{" Include Header in Response " link AEM-7308}


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7309 "AEMAIL MENUS/Messages menu/SHOW"

                                   @{b}Show@{ub}

This has @{i}two@{ui} checkmarked submenu items for controlling your @{" message list " link AEM-8200}
display.  These sub-menu items are:

@{b}Deleted Messages@{ub}

    If this sub-item is checked, @{b}deleted messages@{ub} will be shown in the
    message list.  If it is unchecked, @{b}deleted messages@{ub} @{i}will @{u}not@{uu}@{ui} be
    shown.  This sub-item is checked when @{b}AEMail@{ub} first comes up.

@{b}UnRead Msgs Only@{ub}

    If this sub-item is checked, @{i}only@{ui} @{b}unread messages@{ub} will be
    displayed in the message list.  If it is unchecked all messages
    will be displayed.  This sub-item is unchecked when @{b}AEMail@{ub} first
    comes up.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7301 "AEMAIL MENUS/Messages menu/COMPOSE..."

                               @{b}Compose...@{ub}

Activates the @{" Compose Message window " link AEM-8700} to create a @{b}NEW@{ub} message to be sent
whether or not a message is currently selected.

(@{i}see also the @{" Compose a Message " link AEM-6080} function@{ui})




                                  @{b}Reply@{ub}


Activates the @{" Compose Message window " link AEM-8700} to reply to the current selected
message.

There are @{i}two@{ui} sub-menus which are:

@{b}Use Reply-To...@{ub}

    The @{b}Reply-To:@{ub} address of the selected message will be used as the
    recipient of the reply.  If the @{b}Reply-To:@{ub} address is not present,
    the @{b}From:@{ub} address will be used.

@{b}Use From...@{ub}

    This forces the @{b}From:@{ub} address to be used as the recipient of the
    reply.

If a message is not selected when one of the sub-menu items is activated
an error requester will appear.

(@{i}see also the @{" Compose a Message " link AEM-6080} function@{ui})




                                @{b}Forward...@{ub}

Activates the @{" Compose Message window " link AEM-8700} to @{b}forward@{ub} the current selected message.

If a message is not selected when this menu item is activated an error
requester will appear.

(@{i}see also the @{" Compose a Message " link AEM-6080} function@{ui})


                                 @{b}Edit...@{ub}

Using this menu item will allow you to edit a message selected in either the
@{b}PENDING@{ub} or @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folders.  It has the same effect as clicking on the
Compose icon when you have selected a message in either the @{b}PENDING@{ub} or
@{b}QUEUED@{ub} folders.

If you have not selected a message in either the PENDING or QUEUED folder
when this menu item is activated an error requester will appear.

(@{i}see also the @{" Compose a Message " link AEM-6080} function@{ui})



@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7302 "AEMAIL MENUS/Messages menu/SELECT..."

                               @{b}Select None@{ub}

This menu item will de-select all messages in the selected folder.

(@{i}See also @{" Message Selection " link AEM-8210}@{ui})




                               @{b}Select All@{ub}

This menu item will select all messages in the selected folder. Selected
messages will be marked with an asterick (*) in the first position of the
message in the @{" message list " link AEM-8200} display.

(@{i}See also @{" Message Selection " link AEM-8210}@{ui})


                              @{b}Last Selected@{ub}

This menu item will re-select those messages that were last selected.  If
you did a multiple selection on a group of messages and then performed an
operation on the group of messages (such as deleting, copying, saving the
group to a file, etc.), the messages will be de-selected as the operation
is performed on each message.  The @{b}Last Selected@{ub} menu item will allow
you to re-select the same previously selected messages so that you can
perform another operation on the same group of messages.

(@{i}See also @{" Message Selection " link AEM-8210}@{ui})

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7304 "AEMAIL MENUS/Messages menu/COPY"

                                  @{b}Copy...@{ub}

This menu copies all @{" selected messages " link AEM-8200} from the @{" selected folder " link AEM-8100} to a new
folder.  When you select this menu, a @{b}Notification window@{ub} appears which says:


                        @{b}Select Folder to Copy Messages To!

                                    [CANCEL]@{ub}


When the window appears, click on the folder icon that represents the folder
you want the messages copied to.  The window will automatically disappear at
that time.

The selected messages will be copied to that folder.  Messages will remain
in both folders.

Clicking on @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} before clicking on a folder will cancel the operation.

As the messages are being copied, the folder message list that the the messages
are @{i}copied to@{ui} will be displayed.  Once the copy is complete, the folder message
list @{i}from which@{ui} the messages are copied will be displayed.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7305 "AEMAIL MENUS/Messages menu/TRANSFER"

                                @{b}Transfer...@{ub}

This menu moves all @{" selected messages " link AEM-8200} from the @{" selected folder " link AEM-8100} to a new
folder.  When you select this menu, a @{b}Notification window@{ub} appears which says:


                     @{b}Select Folder to Transfer Messages To!

                                    [CANCEL]@{ub}


When the window appears, click on the folder icon that represents the folder
you want the messages transferred to.  The window will automatically disappear
at that time.

The selected messages will be copied to that folder, and the messages in
the folder from which the messages are copied will be marked as @{" deleted " link AEM-6070}.

Clicking on @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} before clicking on a folder will cancel the operation.

As the messages are being transferred, the folder message list that the the
messages are @{i}transferred to@{ui} will be displayed.  Once the transfer is complete,
the folder message list @{i}from which@{ui} the messages are copied and deleted will
be displayed.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7310 "AEMAIL MENUS/Messages menu/LOCK/UNLOCK"

                               @{b}Lock/Unlock@{ub}

This menu item will prevent messages from being sent from either the 
@{b}PENDING@{ub} or @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folders.  A locked message is indicated by an "@{b}L@{ub}" in 
the message list.  A deleted message can not be locked (although it 
also can not be sent).

This command works as a toggle.  When this menu item is selected, all
messages marked as selected (@{b}*@{ub}) but not marked as @{b}DELETED@{ub} or @{b}LOCKED@{ub} will
be @{b}LOCKED@{ub}.  All selected messages marked as @{b}LOCKED@{ub} will be @{b}UNLOCKED@{ub}.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7307 "AEMAIL MENUS/Messages menu/DISPLAY FULL HEADER"

                           @{b}Display Full Header@{ub}

This is a checkmarked menu sub-item.  When checked, all message headers will
be displayed in the message.  Since many of these headers are somewhat cryptic
and could be confusing and not always understood by the user, the normal
action is display only certain header lines.  The default action is to
display the following headers: @{b}From:, To:, Date:, Subject:, cc:@{ub} and @{b}bcc:@{ub}, but
you can control this default minimum header list with the @{" General Parameters " link AEM-4900}
display of the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

This menu sub-item is very useful for debugging purpose to see all of the
headers what any particular message carries.

The current state of this checkmarked item is saved in the @{" configuration " link AEM-9110}
file whenever the @{" Configuration/Save " link AEM-7101} menu item is selected.  It can also
be set or reset by the @{" General Parameters " link AEM-4900} page on the @{" Configuration " link AEM-4200}
Setup Window.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7306 "AEMAIL MENUS/Messages menu/FORWARD BODY TEXT ONLY"

                          @{b}Forward Body Text Only@{ub}

This is a checkmarked menu sub-item.

When you forward a message, the normal action is to include the header
lines in the forwarded message.  The number of header lines is controlled
by the @{" Display Full Hdr " link AEM-7307} checkedmark menu item.  Minimum headers will be
included if that item is not checked.  If the message to be forwarded
contains attachments, full headers will always be sent regardless of the
state of the @{b}Display Full Hdr@{ub} item.

You can suppress all headers and forward only the body text by checking
this checkmarked menu sub-item.  This will also forward only the body text
for messages with attachments.  In other words, the attachments will not
be included with the forwarded message.

The current state of this checkmarked item is saved in the @{" configuration " link AEM-9110}
file whenever the @{" Configuration/Save " link AEM-7101} menu item is selected.  It can also
be set or reset by the @{" General Parameters " link AEM-4900} page on the @{" Configuration " link AEM-4200}
Setup Window.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7308 "AEMAIL MENUS/Messages menu/INCLUDE HEADER IN RESPONSE"

                        @{b}Include Header in Response@{ub}

This is a checkmarked menu sub-item.  When checked the minimum header lines
(@{b}To:, From:, Date:, Subject, cc:@{ub} and @{b}bcc:@{ub}) will be included for the quoted
message when composing a response.  If it is not checked, no header
information will appear.

The current state of this checkmarked item is saved in the @{" configuration " link AEM-9110}
file whenever the @{" Configuration/Save " link AEM-7101} menu item is selected.  It can also
be set or reset by the @{" General Parameters " link AEM-4900} page on the @{" Configuration " link AEM-4200}
Setup Window.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7400 "AEMAIL MENUS/Retrieve Messages menu"

                          @{b}Retrieve Messages menu@{ub}

The Retrieve Messages menu consists of the following items:

    @{" From POP Host " link AEM-7401}
    @{" From Local File... " link AEM-7401}
    @{" Exclude Duplicate Messages " link AEM-7402}
    @{" Delete Host Mail " link AEM-7402}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7401 "AEMAIL MENUS/Retrieve Msgs menu/FROM ..."

                             @{b}Retrieve Messages@{ub}

@{i}From POP Host@{ui}

    This will only retrieve messages from the @{b}POP Server@{ub}.  See the
    @{" RETRIEVE MESSAGES " link AEM-6110} command a full explanation of the retrieval process.

    If @{b}AmiTCP@{ub} is not active or connection to the @{b}POP Server@{ub} can not be
    made, the @{b}RETRIEVE MESSAGES@{ub} command will return silently with the
    information that connection to the @{b}POP Server@{ub} could not be made in
    the title bar.


@{i}From Local File...@{ui}

    This will only retrieve messages from a local file.  No attempt will be made
    to connect to the @{b}POP Server@{ub}.  See the @{" Retrieve Messages from Files " link AEM-6111}
    command for a full explanation of the retrieval process.

    This menu sub-item allows you to retrieve messages from files even when
    online (connected to a host through @{b}AmiTCP@{ub}).

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7402 "AEMAIL MENUS/Retrieve Messages menu/CHECKMARKED ITEMS"

                        @{b}Exclude Duplicate Messages@{ub}

This is a checkmarked menu sub-item.  When checked, duplicate messages (ones
that were previously retrieved and stored in one of @{b}AEMail@{ub}'s folders), will
not be stored.  See the description under the @{" RETRIEVE MESSAGES " link AEM-6110} command for
the use and full explanation of the function of this item.

The current state of this checkmarked item is saved in the @{" configuration " link AEM-9110}
file whenever the @{" Configuration/Save " link AEM-7101} menu item is selected.  It can also
be set or reset by the @{" General Parameters " link AEM-4900} page on the @{" Configuration " link AEM-4200}
Setup Window.


                           @{b}Delete Host Mail@{ub}

This is a checkmarked menu sub-item.  When checked mail retrieved from your
@{b}POP server@{ub} will be deleted after it is retrieved.  If it is not checked, mail
will not be deleted and you will have to use the @{b}Excl Dup Msgs@{ub} checkmark
item discussed above to insure that a duplicate message are not saved the next
time you retrieve messages.

The current state of this checkmarked item is saved in the @{" configuration " link AEM-9110}
file whenever the @{" Configuration/Save " link AEM-7101} menu item is selected.  It can also
be set or reset by the @{" General Parameters " link AEM-4900} page on the @{" Configuration " link AEM-4200}
Setup Window.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7500 "AEMAIL MENUS/TCP/IP menu"

                          @{b}TCP/IP menu@{ub}

The TCP/IP menu consists of the following items:

    @{" Start Net " link AEM-7501}
    @{" Stop Net " link AEM-7502}
    @{" TCP Logging File " link AEM-7503}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7501 "AEMAIL MENUS/TCP/IP menu/START NET"

                                 @{b}Start Net@{ub}

This menu item makes connection to your Internet Provider.  It executes
the script that has been assigned by the @{" Start Net " link AEM-4116} Tool Type or the
@{" TCP/IP " link AEM-4400} page of @{" Configuration Setup " link AEM-4200}.  If no @{b}Start Net@{ub} script
has been assigned, the action that is performed is to @{" iconify " link AEM-7103} @{b}AEMail@{ub}.
You can then perform the network connection in whatever manner was provided
by your TCP/IP stack software.  Once the connection is made, un-iconify 
@{b}AEMail@{ub}.

When this menu item is selected and a @{b}Start Net@{ub} script has been assigned,
the system will, by default, switch to the workbench screen and execute
the @{b}Start Net@{ub} script.  This allows the initial dialing window to display.
Once your Internet connection has been made the system will switch back to
the @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen.

You can control the switching to the workbench screen by a checkmarked item
in the @{b}TCP/IP Parameters@{ub} page on the @{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub}.

If you are using @{" AmiTCP " link AEM-9910}, the script that should be run is 
@{b}AmiTCP:bin/startnet@{ub}; although the user may specify a different script
and path with the @{b}STARTNET Tool Type@{ub} or in the @{b}TCP/IP Parameters@{ub} page
on the @{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub}.

If you are using @{" Miami " link AEM-9910}, a @{b}"startnet.miami"@{ub} script has been provided for
connecting with your Internet provider.  This is usually run from the @{b}AEMail@{ub}
program directory.  This is an AREXX script so you will have to precede the
script name with @{b}"rx "@{ub} (refer to the CONFIGURATION links above for setting
up your @{b}Start Net@{ub} script).  This is set up automatically with the @{b}AEMail@{ub}
@{" install " link AEM-3000} provided a @{b}Miami:@{ub} assignment is present in the system.

If you are using a TCP/IP stack that does not have a @{b}Start Net@{ub} script (such
as @{" TermiteTCP " link AEM-9910}), you should be sure that the @{b}Start Net@{ub} call gadget in the
@{b}TCP/IP parameters@{ub} page of the @{b}Configuration Setup@{ub} has been cleared.  Your
Internet connection is then done manually as explained above.

Once a connection is made to your Internet provider and you have returned
to the @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen, a connection will be made to your POP server to see
if there are any messages available on the server.  If there are, the
following requester will appear:

Once a connection is made to your Internet provider and you have returned
to the @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen, a connection will be made to your @{b}POP server@{ub} to see
if there are any messages available on the server.  If there are, the 
following requester will appear:


              @{b}@{i}n@{ui} Messages Available on the POP Server

            Do you wish to receive these messages now?@{ub}


If you click on the @{b}[YES]@{ub} button, those message will be retrieved at this
point.  See the @{" RETRIEVE MESSAGES " link AEM-6110} command in the @{" COMMAND ICON STRIP " link AEM-6000} for
details on this process.

If you click on @{b}[NO]@{ub}, no message retrieval will take place at this time.
You will need to retrieve these messages later using the @{b}RETRIEVE MESSAGES@{ub}
command icon.

After @{b}AEMail@{ub} checks to see if any messages are available on the @{b}POP Server@{ub},
it also checks to see if any messages are in the @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder (messages
queued to be sent).  If there are, the following requester will appear:


             @{b}You have n messages queued to be sent

            Do you wish to send these messages now?@{ub}


If you click on the @{b}[YES]@{ub} button, all of the messages in the @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder
will be sent immediately. If you click on @{b}[NO]@{ub}, the queued messages will
not be sent.

After the connection is made, the following message will be displayed in
the screen's title bar:

    @{b}TCP/IP Session started with @{i}your-domain-name@{ui}.@{ub}

If for any reason the connection can not be made, the following message
will be displayed in the screen's title bar:

    @{b}TCP/IP connection to @{i}your-domain-name@{ui} failed@{ub}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7502 "AEMAIL MENUS/TCP/IP menu/STOP NET"

                                 @{b}Stop Net@{ub}

This menu item terminates the connection to your Internet Provider.  It
executes the script that has been assigned by the @{" Stop Net " link AEM-4117} Tool Type or
the @{" TCP/IP " link AEM-4400} page of the @{" Configuration Setup " link AEM-4200}.  If no Stop Net script has
been assigned, the action that is performed is to @{" iconify " link AEM-7103} @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  You
can then terminate the network connection in what ever manner was provided
by your TCP/IP stack software.  Once the connection is terminated,
un-iconify @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

When this menu item is selected and a @{b}Stop Net@{ub} script has been assigned,
the system will terminate the connection silently in the background.  Since
no action is required by the user (unlike @{" Start Net " link AEM-7501}), the screen display
will remain on the @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen.

If you want to switch to the Workbench screen while the connection is being
terminated, you can do this through a checkmarked item in the @{b}TCP/IP
Parameters@{ub} page on the @{b}Configuration Setup@{ub}.

If you are using @{" AmiTCP " link AEM-9910}, the script that should be run is
@{b}AmiTCP:bin/stopnet@{ub}; although the user may specify a different script and 
path with the @{b}STOPNET Tool Type@{ub} or in the TCP/IP Parameters page on the 
Configuration Setup.

If you are using @{" Miami " link AEM-9910}, a @{b}"stopnet.miami"@{ub} script has been provided for
terminating the connection with your Internet provider.  This script is
usually run from the @{b}AEMail@{ub} program directory.  This is an AREXX script
so you will have to precede the script name with @{b}"rx "@{ub} (refer to the
CONFIGURATION links above for setting up your @{b}Stop Net@{ub} script).  This
is set up automatically with the @{b}AEMail@{ub} @{" install " link AEM-3000} provided a @{b}Miami:@{ub}
assignment is present in the system.

If you are using a TCP/IP stack that does not have a @{b}Stop Net@{ub} script (such
as @{" TermiteTCP " link AEM-9910}), you should be sure that the @{b}Stop Net@{ub} call gadget in the 
@{b}TCP/IP parameters@{ub} page of the @{b}Configuration Setup@{ub} has been cleared.  Your
Internet connection is then terminated manually as explained above.

The following messages will be displayed in the screen's title bar when the
connection is terminated:


    @{b}TCP/IP session with @{i}your-domain-name@{ui} terminated.@{ub}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7503 "AEMAIL MENUS/TCP/IP menu/TCP Logging File"

                              @{b}TCP Logging File@{ub}

This has @{i}three@{ui} submenu items for controlling your @{b}TCP Logging file@{ub}.  See
@{" TCP Trace Log File " link AEM-9180} for how to read the entries in this file.

The sub-menu items are:

@{b}Active@{ub}

    This is a checkmarked menu sub-item which indicates whether the @{b}TCP
    Logging@{ub} is active or not.  If a TCP Logging File has @{i}not@{ui} been defined
    with the @{" Paths " link AEM-4500} page of the @{" Configuration Setup " link AEM-4200}, this sub-item is
    ghosted.

    Clicking on this item when it is not checkmarked will @{b}activate TCP
    Logging@{ub}.  Clicking on it when it is checkmarked will @{b}deactivate
    logging@{ub}.


@{b}Purge@{ub}

    This is a handy way to delete all previous @{b}TCP Logging@{ub} entries.
    @{b}Purge@{ub} will delete the current logging file and open another file
    with the same name if logging is @{b}active@{ub}.

    If logging is @{i}not@{ui} active, the current logging file will be deleted,
    but a new file will not be opened until the @{b}Active@{ub} sub-item is
    checkmarked.

    @{i}This menu item can be used whether the logging file is currently
    active or not@{ui}.


@{b}Display/Edit...@{ub}

    @{b}Display/Edit...@{ub} will call your editor to display the @{i}current@{ui} @{b}TCP 
    logging@{ub} file.  The logging file @{i}MUST NOT@{ui} be @{b}Active@{ub} in order to
    display or edit it.  If it is active you will get a requester that
    informs you that you can't display the file beause it is active.
    If this happens, de-activate logging by turning off the @{b}Active@{ub}
    checkmark and then try the @{b}Display/Edit...@{ub} again.

    If a @{b}TCP Logging@{ub} file has not been defined in the @{" Paths " link AEM-4500} page of
    the @{" Configuration Setup " link AEM-4200}, you will receive a requester saying
    that it is not present.

    @{b}NOTE:@{ub}  The @{b}TCP logging@{ub} file can become quite large and it may take
    some time for your editor to bring in the file. Some editors are
    slower than others in this regard.  If you are using the AmigaDos
    editor (Ed), you will see a series of astericks (@) moving across
    the screen as the file is being read in.  You might want to
    periodically purge the file (if it is always active), to prevent
    a very large @{b}TCP Log@{ub} file from being created.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7600 "AEMAIL MENUS/ARexx/DOS menu"

                           @{b}ARexx/DOS menu@{b}

The ARexx/DOS menu consists of the following items:

    @{" Send AREXX/DOS Command... " link AEM-7106}
    @{" Send Last Command... " link AEM-7107}

    @{" Commands Specified by ARexx Configuration Page " link AEM-7601}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-7601 "AEMAIL MENUS/ARexx/DOS menu/ARexx Commands"

              @{b}@{i}Commands Specified by ARexx Configuration Page@{ui}@{ub}

This portion of the @{b}ARexx/DOS@{ub} menu consists of those items specified by
the @{" ARexx Page " link AEM-4700} of the @{" Configuration Setup " link AEM-4200}.  A menu item will be created
for each @{b}ARexx/DOS@{ub} command for which a @{b}Menu Title@{ub} is specified.  If no
@{b}Menu Title@{ub} is specified, no menu item will be created.

Each of these menu items have the same effect as if the corresponding
function key is pressed.

Depending on the number of commands that are defined, you might @{i}not@{ui} want
to give all of them a @{b}Menu Title@{ub} to avoid having too many menu items
specified.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-8000 "AEMAIL WINDOWS"

                              @{b}AEMAIL Windows@{ub}

@{b}AEMail@{ub} has the following window displays:

    @{" Folder List Window " link AEM-8100}
    @{" Message List Window " link AEM-8200}
    @{" Folder Configuration Window " link AEM-8300}
    @{" Filter Selection Window " link AEM-8330}
    @{" Set Sort Keys Window " link AEM-8400}
    @{" Address Book Window " link AEM-8500}
    @{" Message Display Window " link AEM-8600}
    @{" Compose Message Window " link AEM-8700}
    @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-8100 "AEMAIL WINDOWS/Folder List Window"

                            @{b}Folder List Window@{ub}

The @{b}Folder List@{ub} window will be displayed in the lower portion of the
screen when @{b}AEMail@{ub} is first loaded and whenever you click on the
@{" DISPLAY FOLDER LIST " link AEM-6010} icon in the @{" Command Icon Strip " link AEM-6000}.

The @{b}Folder List@{ub} window looks like the following:

  @{b}========================================================================

                              Folder List

  Name      Description of Folder                        Not Read Total
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------
  INBOX     Messages Received                               nnnnn nnnnn| |
  PENDING   Messages composed and pending for action              nnnnn| |
  QUEUED    Messages Queued to be sent                            nnnnn| |
  SENT      Messages that have been sent                          nnnnn| |
  xxxxxxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx nnnnn nnnnn| |
  xxxxxxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx nnnnn nnnnn| |
                                                                       | |
  ========================================================================@{ub}

The @{b}folder list@{ub} is a scrolling list.  Double clicking on any of the
folders in the list will bring up the @{" Message List " link AEM-8200} window for that folder.
If the @{" Folder Icon strip " link AEM-5100} is also being displayed, double clicking on any
particular @{b}folder icon@{ub} will also bring up the @{b}message list@{ub} for that
folder.

If there are too many folders to fit in the window, you can scroll the
list by using the @{b}scroll bar@{ub}, clicking on the @{b}up or down arrows@{ub} below the
scroll bar, or by using the @{b}up or down cursor keys@{ub}.

Additionally the following keys can be used to move the list as follows:

    @{b}Home@{ub} or @{b}ALT Cursor Up@{ub} moves the listview to the top.
    @{b}End@{ub} or @{b}ALT Cursor Down@{ub} moves the listview to the botton.
    @{b}PgUp@{ub} or @{b}Shift Cursor Up@{ub} pages the listview one @{i}page@{ui} up.  The
        top line of the previous page will be displayed as the bottom
        line of the new page.
    @{b}PgDn@{ub} or @{b}Shift Cursor Down@{ub} pages the list view one @{i}page@{ui} down.
        The bottom line of the previous page will be displayed as the
        top line of the new page.
    The cursor up/down keys on the keypad will have the same action as
        the normal cursor keys with the exception of the shift
        feature.

Single clicking on a item in the list or on a @{b}folder icon@{ub} merely selects
that folder.  The selected folder is then the folder referenced by the
@{" Folders Menu " link AEM-7200} group items (@{" Edit.. " link AEM-7201}, @{" Delete... " link AEM-7201}, @{" Set Sort Key ... " link AEM-7202})
and by such commands as @{" Message Delete/Undelete " link AEM-6070}, @{" Message Copy " link AEM-7304},
@{" Message Transfer " link AEM-7304}, or @{" Message Select ALL/NONE " link AEM-7302}.

One of the folders is always active (selected).  On program startup, the
active folder will be @{b}INBOX@{ub}.  You can always tell the current active
folder by the depressed frame around the folder icon.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-8200 "AEMAIL WINDOWS/Message List Window"

                           @{b}Message List Window@{ub}

The @{b}Message List@{ub} window will be displayed in the lower portion of the
screen whenever you double click on either an item in the @{" folder list " link AEM-8100} or
one of the @{" folder icons " link AEM-5100}.

You can also bring up the current folder list by clicking on the
@{" Display Current Folder's Message List " link AEM-6120} command icon in the @{b}command icon
tool bar@{ub}.  The @{b}previous@{ub} and @{b}next@{ub} folder's message list can also be
displayed from the @{b}command icon tool bar@{ub}.

The @{b}Message List@{ub} looks like the following:

  @{b}==========================================================================

      Message List for @{i}folder-name@{ui} Folder (@{i}folder Description...@{i})

   FLGS Date       Time  From           Size Subject        (@{i}nnn@{ui} messages)
  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
   NARF MM/DD/YYYY HH:MM xxxxxxxxxxxxx xxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx| |
  *NARF MM/DD/YYYY HH:MM xxxxxxxxxxxxx xxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx| |
   . . . . .                                                              | |
   NARF MM/DD/YYYY HH:MM xxxxxxxxxxxxx xxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx| |
                                                                          | |
  ===========================================================================@{ub}

The column header line displays the number of messages in the folder as
@{b}@{i}nnn@{ui} messages@{ub}.  This is the total number of messages @{i}including@{ui} those
marked for deletion.

The message descriptions are presented in a scrollable list.   You can
scroll the list by using the @{b}scroll bar@{ub}, clicking on the @{b}up or down arrows@{ub}
below the scroll bar, or by using the @{b}up or down cursor keys@{ub}.

Additionally the following keys can be used to move the list as follows:

    @{b}Home@{ub} or @{b}ALT Cursor Up@{ub} moves the listview to the top.
    @{b}End@{ub} or @{b}ALT Cursor Down@{ub} moves the listview to the botton.
    @{b}PgUp@{ub} or @{b}Shift Cursor Up@{ub} pages the listview one @{i}page@{ui} up.  The
        top line of the previous page will be displayed as the bottom
        line of the new page.
    @{b}PgDn@{ub} or @{b}Shift Cursor Down@{ub} pages the list view one @{i}page@{ui} down.
        The bottom line of the previous page will be displayed as the
        top line of the new page.
    The cursor up/down keys on the keypad will have the same action as
        the normal cursor keys with the exception of the shift
        feature.

The meaning of the various fields of each message description are as
follows:

    @{b}FLGS:@{ub}   (@{i}starts in the 2nd column@{ui})
            @{b}N@{ub} indicates an unread message
            @{b}A@{ub} indicates a message has attachments (either @{b}MIME@{ub} or @{b}UUENCODED@{ub})
            @{b}R@{ub} indicates the message is a reply
            @{b}F@{ub} indicates the message is a forwarded message.
            @{b}D@{ub} (@{i}in the same position as @{ui}@{b}N@{ub}) indicates the message is
              a deleted message.
            @{b}L@{ub} (@{i}in the same position as @{ui}@{b}N@{ub}) indicates that a message in
              either the @{b}PENDING@{ub} or @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder is @{" locked " link AEM-7310} so it will not
              be sent until the lock is removed (@{i}it is unlocked@{ui}).

    @{b}Date:@{ub}   This is the message date from the @{b}DATE:@{ub}  header in the form of
            @{i}MM/DD/YYYY@{ui} (2 digit month, 2 digit day, and the 4 digit year).

    @{b}Time:@{ub}   This is the time the message was received in the form
            of @{i}HH:MM@{ui} (2 digit hour, 2 digit minute).  Time uses a
            @{u}24 hour@{uu} clock.

    @{b}From:@{ub}   Is the @{i}Real Name@{ui} (if present) from either the @{b}From:@{ub} or
            @{b}To:@{ub} header.  If the folder represents messages being
            sent from @{b}AEMail@{ub} (@{b}PENDING, QUEUED, SENT@{ub}) then this
            field will be headed @{b}To@{ub} and the @{b}To:@{ub} header will be used.
            If the @{i}Real Name@{ui} is not present in the header, then the
            @{i}UserID@{ui} will be used instead.  If a @{i}Nickname@{ui} is being
            used for a message being sent, then the @{i}Nickname@{ui} will
            appear.

    @{b}Size:@{ub}   This is the size, in bytes, of the message in the
            form @{i}nnn,nnn@{ui}.  If the size exceeds @{b}999,999 bytes@{ub} then
            @{b}***,***@{ub} will appear.  The size includes the size of
            the message with all its attachments.

    @{b}Subject:@{ub} Up to 50 characters from the @{b}Subject:@{ub} header after
            @{b}RE:@{ub} and @{b}(fwd)@{ub} are stripped.  You can tell if the
            message is forwarded or is a reply by examining the
            @{b}FLGS@{ub} field.  @{b}RE:@{ub} and @{b}(fwd)@{ub} are stripped from the
            @{b}Subject:@{ub} header to allow sorting to place all
            messages with the same subject (whether original,
            replied, or forwarded) together.  You can also control
            where 'replied' and 'forwarded' messages go in
            the list since these use separate sorting criteria.  The
            number of characters fitting in the subject field depends
            on the display mode you are using.


An asterick (*) in the first position indicates that the message is
selected.  This position will be blank if the message is not selected.
@{i}See@{ui} @{" Message selection " link AEM-8210} for how to do multiple selection of
messages.

The Message list can be sorted under a number of different categories (see
@{" Set Sort Keys " link AEM-8400} window).

Double clicking on any message in the @{b}Message List@{ub} will bring up the
@{" Message Display " link AEM-8600} window for that message.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-8210 "AEMAIL WINDOWS/Message Selection"

                            @{b}Message Selection@{ub}

A single click will highlight and select the message.  An asterick will
appear in the first column of the line indicating the message is selected.
You can click on another message to highlight and select that message.
Clicking on a message that is already selected will deselect the message.

If you are running under AmigaDOS 3.0 or higher, you can also select (or
deselect) a group of messages by @{b}drag selecting@{ub}.  Place the cursor over
the message you first want to select or deselect and then, holding down
the left mouse button, drag either up or down.  @{i}Whether selecting or
deselecting occurs depends on the state of the first message you select.@{ui}

Only one message is highlighted.  If that message is selected it will be
considered the current message to @{b}reply to@{ub}, @{b}forward@{ub}, or @{b}edit@{ub} when
composing messages.

Other operations such as DELETE/UNDELETE MESSAGE, SAVE/EXPORT MESSAGES,
COPY MESSAGE, TRANSFER MESSAGE, PRINT SELECTED MESSAGES, SEND MESSAGE
IMMEDIATELY, and QUEUE MESSAGE FOR LATER DELIVERY will use the entire
selected list of messages.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-8300 "AEMAIL WINDOWS/Folder Configuration Window"

                       @{b}Folder Configuration Window@{ub}

The @{b}Folder Configuration window@{ub} will be displayed over the entire screen
below the top title line when either the @{" New... " link AEM-7201} or @{" Edit... " link AEM-7201} menu items
are selected from the @{" Folders menu " link AEM-7200}.

The @{b}Folder Configuration window@{ub} looks like the following:

  @{b}=====================================================================

         Folder Name: [         ]   (1 - 9 Characters only) [SORT KEYS]

  Folder Description: [            __                                 ]
                                  |  |___
           Tab Color: [@|  Red  | |______| [ ] Folder for Sent Messages

    =================================================================
    |Filter Parameters for Selecting Messages                       |
    =================================================================
    |                                                               |
    | [ ] Not [ ] Start Group                       [ ] Ignore Case |
    |                                                               |
    | For [@|    To:     ]               [@|   Contains    ] [] END |
    |                                                               |
    | Search [                                             ] [] AND |
    |                                                               |
    | [ ] End Group                                          [] OR  |
    |  ___________________________________________________________  |
    | |                                                         | | |
    | |                                                         | | |
    | |                                                         | | |
    | |                                                         | | |
    | |                                                         | | |
    | |                                                         | | |
    | |                                                         | | |
    | |                                                         |^| |
    | |_________________________________________________________|V| |
    |                                                               |
    |                            [ Add ] [Insert] [Modify] [Delete] |
    |                                                               |
    =================================================================

                    [ SAVE ]                  [CANCEL]

  ===================================================================@{ub}

If you are editing an existing folder, the @{i}Folder Name@{ui} will be filled in,
but the string gadget will be disabled.  You will not be able to modify
it.

If you are creating a new folder you must name it with a 1 to 9 character
@{i}folder name@{ui}.  This will appear below the @{b}folder icon@{ub} in the @{" Folder Strip " link AEM-5100}
and in the @{" Folder List " link AEM-8100}.  There are certain characters that are illegal
when creating folder names.  Because a special configuration file is
created for each folder called @{b}@{i}folder-name@{ui}.cnfg@{ub}, any character that
would be illegal as part of a file name is illegal in creating a file
name.  These include @{b}:@{ub}, @{b}/@{ub} and @{b}\@{ub}.  Also the name @{b}folder@{ub} (@{i}case
insensitive@{ui}) is illegal since @{b}folder.cnfg@{ub} is the master list of folders.

If you are creating a new folder you must name it with a 1 to 9 character
@{i}folder name@{ui}.  This will appear below the @{b}folder icon@{ub} in the @{" Folder Strip " link AEM-5100}
and in the @{" Folder List " link AEM-8100}.

The @{b}[SORT KEYS]@{ub} button is used to call the @{" Set Sort Keys " link AEM-8400} window to set
the sort keys for the folder.

The @{i}folder description@{ui} can be up to 99 characters, but of course that many
characters will never appear anywhere.  Up to 52 characters will appear in
the @{b}Folder List@{ub} display under @{i}Description of Folder@{ui}.  This will also
appear in the contextual help line in the window bar preceded by "@{b}Folder
for@{ub}".

The @{b}Tab Color@{ub} is a cycle gadget with the following possible values:
@{i}Red, Green, Blue, Yellow, Orange, Magenta, Brown,@{ui} or @{i}Purple@{ui}.  This provides
a color on the folder tab to help classify the folders according to the
user's preferences.  The actual tab color will be displayed to the right
of this cycle gadget.

The checkbox gadget marked @{b}Folder for Sent Messages@{ub} is used to indicate
when a folder is for messages that have been sent or ready to be sent
rather than in-coming folders.  The @{b}PENDING, QUEUED,@{ub} and @{b}SENT@{ub} folders
all have this box checked.

The special window in the center of the @{b}Folder Configuration window@{ub} is
used to set filter parameters for this folder.  A full description of how
this works is given under @{" Filter Selection Window " link AEM-8330}.  The filtering
parameters are used to distribute in-coming messages to various folders.
For the @{b}INBOX@{ub}, these filters have a special meaning which will reject any
message meeting the filtering criteria.  The heading for the filtering
criteria for the @{b}INBOX@{ub} will read @{i}"Filtering Parameters for Rejecting
Messages"@{ui} instead of @{i}"Filtering Parameters for Selecting Messages"@{ui}.

Since filtering can only occur with in-bound messages, @{i}folders for sent
messages can not have filtering parameters associated with them@{ui}.  For all
folders for @{b}sent@{ub} messages, all of the gadgets in the filtering window
will be disabled preventing the entry of any filtering information.  This
is true of the @{b}PENDING, QUEUED, and SENT@{ub} folders as well as any folders that
have been added with the @{b}Folder for Sent Messages@{ub} box checked.

Finally, you are given the choice of canceling the operation or saving the
folder data in the @{" folder.config " link AEM-9130} file with the @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} and @{b}[SAVE]@{ub}
buttons.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-8330 "AEMAIL WINDOWS/Filter Selection Window"

                         @{b}Filter Selection Window@{ub}

The @{b}Filter Selection Window@{ub}, which is part of the @{" Folder Configuration " link AEM-8300}
@{b}Window@{ub}, is used to set filter parameters,  This window looks like this:

    @{b}=================================================================
    |Filter Parameters for Selecting Messages                       |
    =================================================================
    |                                                               |
    | [ ] Not [ ] Start Group                       [ ] Ignore Case |
    |                                                               |
    | For [@|    To:     ]               [@|   Contains    ] [] END |
    |                                                               |
    | Search [                                             ] [] AND |
    |                                                               |
    | [ ] End Group                                          [] OR  |
    |  ___________________________________________________________  |
    | |                                                         | | |
    | |                                                         | | |
    | |                                                         | | |
    | |                                                         | | |
    | |                                                         | | |
    | |                                                         | | |
    | |                                                         | | |
    | |                                                         |^| |
    | |_________________________________________________________|V| |
    |                                                               |
    |                            [ Add ] [Insert] [Modify] [Delete] |
    |                                                               |
    =================================================================@{ub}

The gadgets in the top half of the window are used to enter filtering
parameters.  The first two checkmark gadgets (@{b}[ ] Not, [ ] Start Group@{ub})
and the @{b}[ ] End Group@{ub} checkmark gadget at the bottom of the group are
currently disabled.  They are designed to be used for advanced selection
criteria that will be added to a future version of @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

The cycle gadget which is prefaced with @{b}For@{ub} is used to select the header
that you want to check.  This gadget has the following states:

    @{b}To:
    From:
    Reply-To:
    Subject:
    cc:
    bcc:
    Date:
    Msg is Reply
    Msg w/Attachments
    Msg is Forwarded
    Other Message Hdrs      (@{i}Registered Users only@{ui})
    Message Body            (@{i}Registered Users only@{ui})@{ub}

@{b}Note:@{ub} it is unlikely that you would see the @{b}bcc:@{ub} header in an incoming
message even though it is contained in the header list.

To the right of this is a cycle gadget which specifies the condition this
header will be checked for.  For the @{b}To:, From:, Reply-To: Subject:, cc:,@{ub}
and @{b}bcc:@{ub} headers, @{b}Other Message Hdrs@{ub}, and @{b}Message Body@{ub} the condition can
be either:

    @{b}Contains@{ub}, or
    @{b}Does Not Contain@{ub}

For the @{b}Date:@{ub} header it can be one of the following conditions:

    @{b}Equal
    Not Equal
    Greater Than
    Greater Than / Equal
    Less Than
    Less Than / Equal@{ub}

and for @{b}Msg is Reply, Msg w/Attachments, Msg is Forwarded@{ub} it can be:

    @{b}Is Present
    Is Not Present@{ub}

The argument to be searched against is entered into the string gadget that
is titled @{b}Search@{ub}.  For the @{b}To:, From:, Reply-To:, Subject:, cc:,@{ub} and
@{b}Bcc:@{ub} headers and the @{b}Other Message Hdrs@{ub} and @{b}Message Body@{ub} you can
enter an argument that has @{b}wild cards@{ub}.  The wild cards that are used are
as follows:

    ?   matches any single character.
    c*  matches zero or more occurances of character c.  If an unknown
        character is to be matched you can use ?*.
    c+  matches one or more occurances of character c (at least one
        occurance of c must be present).
    \?  matches the character ?.
    \*  matches the character *.
    \+  matches the character +.

Any other characters must match @{i}exactly@{ui} (@{i}except that case can be ignored -
see below@{ui}).  The match can occur @{i}anywhere@{ui} in the header.  The following
are some examples of how the match occurs:

    abc     matches "abc", "abcdef", or "xxabc"
    ab*c    matches "ac", "abc", "abbc", or "abbbc", etc.  Characters may
            be present either before or after the match.
    ab+c    matches "abc", "abbc", or "abbbc", etc.  Characters may be
            present either before or after the match.  This @{i}will not@{ui} match
            "ab+c".  You would have to use "ab\+c" for this to occur.
    ab?*    matches a substring starting with "ab" and ending with "c".
            Characters may be present either before or after the match.
    ab\*c   matches "ab*c" only.  However charcters may be either before
            or after the match.

@{u}@{b}WARNING:@{ub}@{uu}  Please pay particular attention to the characters @{b}+@{ub}, @{b}?@{ub}, and @{b}*@{ub}.
If any of these characters appear in the information to be matched, you
must use @{b}\+@{ub}, @{b}\?@{ub}, or @{b}\*@{ub} in the argument if you want an exact match to
occur.

If @{b}Other Message Hdrs@{ub} is used, you probably would want to use the Header
designation as part of the search argument.

Searching on header data will search the entire string of characters
contained within that header even though that header may span multiple
lines.  This means that if an address you want to locate is contained in
the @{i}n@{ui}th line of the @{b}To:@{ub} header, it will be found.

When searching data in the message body, the entire argument must be found
in a @{i}single line@{ui} of the body.  If you are searching for a multiple word
phrase which may be broken up onto more than one line, you should specify
multiple arguments with AND separating the arguments.

If you want to ignore the case of the header or message body data when the
comparison is made check the @{b}Ignore Case@{ub} item.  The @{b}Ignore Case@{ub} item
will only ignore the case of the 26 alphabetic characters of the
American/English alphabet.  It will not ignore the case of special
characters used in forign alphabets although these special characters @{b}can@{ub}
be used in the @{b}Search@{ub} criteria.

The @{b}Search@{ub} argument for the @{b}Date:@{ub} header can be of one or two formats.
The first format is either:

    @{b}dd mmm yyyy@{ub} or
    @{b}mmm dd yyyy@{ub}

@{i}mmm@{ui} is the three character month abbreviation:  @{b}jan, feb, mar, apr, may,
jun, jul, aug, sep, oct, nov,@{ub} or @{b}dec@{ub}.  You can enter either upper case,
lower case, or mixed case month abbreviations (i.e., @{b}jan, JAN@{ub}, or @{b}Jan@{ub} are
all o.k.).

@{i}dd@{ui} is the numeric digits for the day of the month and @{i}yyyy@{ui} must be the
full 4 digit year.  If you want any day of a particular month to be used,
leave off the @{i}dd@{ui} parameter.  Likewise, using just the 4 digit @{i}yyyy@{ui} will
accept any month and day for that year.

The absence of any of the elements of the date (@{i}mmm, dd,@{ui} or @{i}yyyy@{ui}) will
indicate that that particular element should not be checked.  As an
example:  if you want only messages for the month of September to be
placed in a particular folder you would enter:

    @{b}sep@{ub}

by itself and the condition would be entered as @{b}equal to@{ub}.  This would
capture messages with a @{b}Date:@{ub} header of September of any year (Sep 1997,
Sep 1998, etc.).  If you were interested in messages with a @{b}Date:@{ub} header
of September of 1997 you would enter:

    @{b}sep 1997@{ub}

An alternate method of entering the date would be:

    @{b}mm/dd/yy@{ub}    or
    @{b}mm/dd/yyyy@{ub}  or
    @{b}mm-dd-yy@{ub}    or
    @{b}mm-dd-yyyy@{ub}

@{i}mm@{ui} is a one or 2 digit month (1 or 01 to 12), @{i}dd@{ui} is a one or 2 digit day
(1 or 01 to 31) and @{i}yy@{ui} is either a 2 digit or 4 digit year. 0 is invalid
for any of the @{i}mm, dd,@{ui} or @{i}yy@{ui}.  If you want to indicate the absence of any
of the elements use @{b}xx@{ub} or @{b}XX@{ub}.  As an example, to capture messages with a
@{b}Date:@{ub} header equal to any day within September 1997 you could enter:

    @{b}09/xx/97@{ub}

Before the search for a @{b}Date:@{ub} header is made, the date in the @{b}Date:@{ub} header
is converted to an internal format.  The search argument is also converted
to this same internal format so that the match can be performed correctly.

The @{b}Search@{ub} argument for @{b}Msg is Reply, Msg w/Attachments@{ub}, and @{b}Msg is Forwarded@{ub}
is ignored.

The @{b}END@{ub}, @{b}AND@{ub}, and @{b}OR@{ub} gadgets are used to indicate that this is the
last comparison argument (@{b}END@{ub}), or that there is another comparison
argument following this with either an @{b}AND@{ub} or @{b}OR@{ub} relationship.

Some examples of specific types of filtering parameters are given under
@{" Examples of using Message Filtering " link AEM-8340}.

The list view in the lower half of the window lists the comparison arguments.
Each comparison arguement is listed on two lines.  The first line shows
the header to be checked and the comparison criteria in the following
format:

@{b}FOR header-name comparison-criteria (ignoring case)@{ub}

@{b}(ignoring case)@{ub} will not be present if @{b}Ignore Case@{ub} is not checked.

The second line will show the search argument surrounded by quote (@{b}"@{ub})
marks.  It will be followed by @{b}AND@{ub} or @{b}OR@{ub} if either of these were
specified.  If @{b}Ignore Case@{ub} was checked, the @{b}Search@{ub} argument will be in
all lower case characters no matter how it was entered in the @{b}Search:@{ub}
string gadget.

To add a selection criteria to the list, enter the appropriate items in
the gadgets at the top of the window and click on the @{b}[ Add ]@{ub} gadget at
the bottom of the window.  That item will be transfered to the listview at
the end of the current list of items.

To modify or delete an item, click on the item in the listview.  Clicking
on either the first or second line of any item in the list is acceptable.
The information from the listview will be transferred to the gadgets at
the top of the window.  Then make the modifications you want (for modify)
and click on either the @{b}[Modify]@{ub} or @{b}[Delete]@{ub} gadgets at the bottom of the
window.

To insert an item into the list, enter the data in the gadgets at the top
of the window as you did to add an item.  This time click on the @{b}[Insert]@{ub}
gadget.  The words @{b}Click on item you want to insert IN FRONT OF!@{ub} will
appear in yellow at the top of the listview.  Now, as instructed, click on
the item you want the selection criteria to be inserted @{i}in front of@{ui}.  This
allows you to insert at the head of the list by clicking on the first item
in the list.  Clicking on either the first or second line of any item in
the list is acceptable.

All of the selection criteria except for the last item must have an AND or
OR relationship to the criteria following.  You can have relationships as
follows:

    @{b}a OR b OR c@{ub}

indicating that if any of the conditions (@{b}a, b@{ub}, or @{b}c@{ub}) are met that message
@{b}will be@{ub} selected for that particular folder, or

    @{b}a AND b AND c@{ub}

indicating that all of the conditions @{b}must@{ub} be met for that message to be
selected.

Be careful of mixing AND and OR conditions.

    @{b}a OR b AND c@{ub}

will work but

    @{b}b AND c OR a@{ub}

will @{i}not@{ui} work correctly.

Conditions are checked serially.

In the first example above, if condition @{b}a@{ub} is not met, then @{b}b@{ub} will be
checked.  If @{b}b@{ub} is not met no selection is made; however, if condition @{b}c@{ub} is
also met, the message will be selected.  If condition a is met the
message will be selected and the @{b}b or c@{ub} conditions are not checked.

In the second example, if condition @{b}b@{ub} is not met, no further check will be
made so that even if @{b}a@{ub} is met, the message will not be selected.  In this
example condition @{b}a@{ub} will never be checked.

@{b}Advanced selection@{ub} is designed to get around this problem.  @{b}HOWEVER, THIS
ADVANCED SELECTION HAS NOT BEEN IMPLIMENTED AS YET!  AND WHEN IT IS
IMPLIMENTED, IT WILL ONLY BE AVAILABLE TO REGISTERED USERS.@{ub}

With advanced selection you will be able to group items in this manner:

    @{b}(a AND b) OR (c AND d)@{ub}

conditions @{b}a@{ub} and @{b}b@{ub} are a group and conditions @{b}c@{ub} and @{b}d@{ub} are a group.  The
checkmarked items @{b}Start Group@{ub} and @{b}End Group@{ub} are used to specify the
first item in a group and the last item in a group.  You will also be able
to embed groups within groups such as

    @{b}(a AND b AND (c OR d))@{ub}

and use a @{b}not@{ub} condition for a group such as

    @{b}(a AND b AND NOT (c OR d))@{ub}

or simply

    @{b}NOT (a OR b)@{ub}

@{b}Filtering Restrictions@{ub}.  Currently the following restriction is placed on
filtering.  @{i}This restriction will be lifted in a later release of @{b}AEMail@{ub}.@{ui}

Advanced selection (grouping selection criteria as described above), can
not be done.

Other selection criteria (such as size of message) may be added later.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-8340 "AEMAIL WINDOWS/Examples of using Message Filtering"

                   @{b}Examples of using Message Filtering@{ub}

How would you use message filtering?  Here is a practical example of how I
use it.  As you all know, when you implement a new version of @{b}AEMail@{ub} and
send your first message a special @{b}notification@{ub} message is sent to me
indicating the version you are using.  This notification message is stored
in a special folder for notification messages that I have received.  All
of the notification messages indicate what they are in the @{b}Subject:@{ub}
header.  However, over the development of @{b}AEMail@{ub}, the format of this
subject header has changed.  Before version 1.10 the Subject header looked
like this:

    @{b}Subject: Registration of AEMAIL (Amiga EMAIL), Version x.xx@{ub}

From version 1.10 through version 1.15, the Subject header looked like
this:

    @{b}Subject: AEMAIL Version x.xx Registration@{ub}

After version 1.15 the Subject header looked like this:

    @{b}Subject: AEMAIL Version x.xx Notification@{ub}

Since I am still receiving notification messages back to version 1.03, I
wanted all such notification messages to go into the same folder.  The
selection criteria for this folder was set to the following:

    @{b}For Subject: Contains (ignoring case)
    "aemail version ???? registration" OR

    For Subject: Contains (ignoring case)
    "aemail version ?* notification" OR

    For Subject: Contains (ignoring case)
    "registration of aemail (amiga email), version"@{ub}

Notice how I handled the variable of the version number in each case.  In
the first criteria I used a fixed replacement wild card (@{b}????@{ub}) to specify
the version number.  In the second criteria I used a variable replacement
wild card (@{b}?*@{ub}) and in the third criteria I did not use any wild card for
the version number replacement.  That is because the version number occurs
at the end of the line.

Another use of filtering can be used if you are subscribed to a listserve.
The example I will show you is for the @{b}Miami@{ub} list serve.  Miami actually
has two listserves: @{b}miami-talk-ml@nordicglobal.com@{ub} and
@{b}miami-announce-ml@nordicglobal.com@{ub}.  The @{b}To:@{ub} address usually reflects
which listserve the message is coming from but the @{b}Reply-To:@{ub} address
always reflects @{b}miami-talk-ml@nordicglobal.com@{ub}.

If you want the folder to include all messages from both listserves you
can set the following criteria for the that folder:

    @{b}For Reply-To: Contains (ignoring case)
    "miami-talk-ml@nordicglobal.com"@{ub}

If you set up two folders, one for the @{b}"talk"@{ub} message list and the other
for the @{b}"announcement"@{ub} message list you could set the @{b}"talk"@{ub} folder to
reflect the following criteria:

    @{b}For To: Contains (ignoring case)
    "miami-talk-ml@nordicglobal.com"@{ub}

and the @{b}"announcement"@{ub} folder as follows:

    @{b}For To: Contains (ignoring case)
    "miami-announce-ml@nordicglobal.com"@{ub}

If messages meet the selection criteria for two different folders, the
@{i}first@{ui} folder in the folder list which meets the criteria will be selected.
So, if you were to have two folders set up as described above (one for
@{b}"talk"@{ub} messages and one for @{b}"announcement"@{ub} messages) and you used the
@{b}Reply-To:@{ub} address instead of the @{b}To:@{ub} address as the selection criteria for
the @{b}"talk"@{ub} folder and if the @{b}"talk"@{ub} folder was first, all of the
@{b}"announcement"@{ub} messages would go in the @{b}"talk"@{ub} folder.  However, if the
@{b}"announcement"@{ub} folder was first, then the messages would be distributed to
the correct folders.  By using the To: header field, however, you would
always insure that they go to the right folders.

You will find that the clipboard capability is very helpful in setting up
your filtering conditions.  If there is a particular header that you want
selected, display the message that has that header, and then double click
on the header in the message.  Edit out the header designator (To:, From:,
Subject:, etc) and save it to the clipboard.  You can save various items
changing the clipboard unit for each item.  Then when you are in the
Folder Configuration window, select the Search string gadget and use Right
Amiga U to call up the clipboard list.  Then double click on the item you
want to select on.  It will then be automatically pasted into the Search
string gadget.

As was stated in the earlier description of the Filter Selection Window,
the window for the INBOX is used to EXCLUDE messages meeting the INBOX
criteria from entering your system.  Use this with CARE!  If you exclude a
message and you are deleting messages from you POP server, YOU WILL NEVER
SEE THAT MESSAGE!

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-8400 "AEMAIL WINDOWS/Set Sort Keys Window"

                           @{b}Set Sort Keys Window@{ub}

The @{b}Set Sort Keys@{ub} window will be displayed over the entire screen below
the top title line when either the @{" Set Sort Key... " link AEM-7202} menu item from the
@{" Folders menu " link AEM-7200} is selected or the @{b}[Sort Keys]@{ub} button is clicked in the
@{" Folder Configuration Window " link AEM-8300}.

The @{b}Set Sort Keys@{ub} window looks like the following:

   @{b}=====================================================================

                  1       2       3       4       5       6       7
   Priorities: ------- ------- ------- ------- ------- ------- -------

   Un-Read Messages: FIRST [ ]      Messages with Attachments: FIRST [ ]
   Priority [@|0|     LAST [ ]      Priority [@|0|              LAST [ ]

   Replied Messages: FIRST [ ]      Forwarded Messages: FIRST [ ]
   Priority [@|0|     LAST [ ]      Priority [@|0|       LAST [ ]

   Latest Date:      FIRST [ ]      Largest Messages: FIRST [ ]
   Priority [@|0|     LAST [ ]      Priority [@|0|     LAST [ ]

   Group by FROM at Priority [@|0|    Group by Subject at Priority [@|0|

   [ ] Order Received
                      --> at Priority [@|0|     [ ] Apply to all Folders
   [ ] Latest Received

   [LAST SAVED]    [LAST USED]    [   USE   ]    [  SAVE  ]   [ CANCEL ]

   =====================================================================@{ub}

Messages in each of the folders can be displayed in various sort orders
and each folder can have a different sort order.  Up to seven levels of
@{i}sort priority@{ui} can be given.  The various sorting criteria are shown on
this window and a particular @{i}sort order@{ui} can be given for any @{i}sort
priority@{ui}.  The sorting criteria for any particular priority is selected by
the @{b}priority cycle gadget@{ub} under or opposite each criteria.  A priority of
0 is used to indicate that this criteria is not used in the sort.

To help visualize which criteria applies to which priority a list at the
top of the window shows the current position of any particular sort
criteria in the priority list. With the exception of priority 0 (@{i}no
priority@{ui}), no two criteria can have the same priority.  If this happens,
@{b}**DUP**@{ub} will appear for that priority in the priority list.

If you want the sorting criteria to be used for all folders check the
@{b}Apply to all Folders@{ub} box.

At the bottom of the window is the @{b}[LAST SAVED]@{ub}, @{b}[LAST USED]@{ub}, @{b}[USE]@{ub},
@{b}[SAVE]@{ub}, and @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} buttons.  If you want the sorting to apply only to
this @{b}AEMail@{ub} session only select @{b}[USE]@{ub}.  If you want to make the sorting
permanent, select @{b}[SAVE]@{ub}.  @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub}, of course, will abort the operation
without setting any sort keys.  The @{b}[LAST SAVED]@{ub} button is used to restore
the sort keys to those last saved and the @{b}[LAST USED]@{ub} is used to restore
the last used sort keys.

If this window was called from the @{" Folder Configuration Window " link AEM-8300},
selecting @{b}[USE], [SAVE],@{ub} or @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} will return you to the @{b}Folder
Configuration Window.@{ub}

The @{b}[LAST SAVED]@{ub} and @{b}[LAST USED]@{ub} buttons will simply restore the
appropriate sorting order and will not terminate the @{b}Folder Configuration
Window@{ub}.  You will have to use the @{b}[USE]@{ub}, @{b}[SAVE]@{ub}, or @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} buttons to do
that.

For examples of setting sort keys see @{" Examples of Setting Sort Keys " link AEM-8410}


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-8410 "AEMAIL WINDOWS/Sort Key Examples"

                      @{b}Examples of Setting Sort Keys@{ub}

You may want your list of messages displayed in different orders in the
@{" Message List Window " link AEM-8200}.  This is the purpose of the @{" Set Sort Keys Window " link AEM-8400}.

Let's assume that you want your messages displayed with @{i}unread messages
first@{ui}.  Within both the unread and previously read sections you want the
messages sorted by the @{i}latest date first@{ui}.  To do this click on the @{b}Un-Read
Messages: FIRST@{ub} box and set the @{b}Priority@{ub} underneath @{b}Un-Read Messages@{ub} to
@{b}1@{ub}.  Then click on the @{b}Latest Date: FIRST@{ub} box and set it's @{b}Priority@{ub} to @{b}2@{ub}.  Notice that as you change
the @{b}Priority@{ub} cycle gadget for @{b}Latest Date@{ub} from @{b}0@{ub} to @{b}1@{ub} to @{b}2@{ub},
you will see @{b}*DUP*@{ub} appear in @{i}priority 1@{ui} as the @{b}Date@{ub} moves
through the @{i}priority 1@{ui} position.

The final sort window for the above sorting priority will look like this:

   =====================================================================

                  1       2       3       4       5       6       7
   Priorities:  @{b}UNREAD@{ub}   @{b}DATE@{ub}  ------- ------- ------- ------- -------

   Un-Read Messages: FIRST [@{b}X@{ub}]      Messages with Attachments: FIRST [ ]
   Priority [@|@{b}1@{ub}|     LAST [ ]      Priority [@|0|              LAST [ ]

   Replied Messages: FIRST [ ]      Forwarded Messages: FIRST [ ]
   Priority [@|0|     LAST [ ]      Priority [@|0|       LAST [ ]

   Latest Date:      FIRST [@{b}X@{ub}]      Largest Messages: FIRST [ ]
   Priority [@|@{b}2@{ub}|     LAST [ ]      Priority [@|0|     LAST [ ]

   Group by FROM at Priority [@|0|    Group by Subject at Priority [@|0|

   [ ] Order Received
                      --> at Priority [@|0|     [ ] Apply to all Folders
   [ ] Latest Received

   [LAST SAVED]    [LAST USED]    [   USE   ]    [  SAVE  ]   [ CANCEL ]

   =====================================================================

When you are satisfied with the order click on @{b}[SAVE]@{ub} to save this order for
@{i}this folder only@{ui}.  If you want to use this order for @{i}all@{ui} your folders
click on @{b}Apply to all Folders@{ub} before clicking on @{b}[SAVE]@{ub}.


Another example might have the messages displayed with @{i}unread messages
first@{ui}, followed by messages @{i}grouped by SUBJECT@{ui}, and within the SUBJECT
grouping, by the @{i}latest date received@{ui}.  This, in effect, creates a message
threading condition with like subjects grouped together.

To create this sort condition, click on the @{b}Un-Read Messages: FIRST@{ub} box
and set it's @{b}Priority@{ub} to @{b}1@{ub}.  Then set the @{b}Group by Subject at Priority@{ub}
cycle gadget to @{b}2@{ub}.  Finally click on the @{b}Latest Date: FIRST@{ub} box and set
it's @{b}Priority@{ub} to @{b}3@{ub}.  The final sort window for this grouping would be:

   =====================================================================

                  1       2       3       4       5       6       7
   Priorities:  @{b}UNREAD SUBJECT   DATE@{ub}  ------- ------- ------- -------

   Un-Read Messages: FIRST [@{b}X@{ub}]      Messages with Attachments: FIRST [ ]
   Priority [@|@{b}1@{ub}|     LAST [ ]      Priority [@|0|              LAST [ ]

   Replied Messages: FIRST [ ]      Forwarded Messages: FIRST [ ]
   Priority [@|0|     LAST [ ]      Priority [@|0|       LAST [ ]

   Latest Date:      FIRST [@{b}X@{ub}]      Largest Messages: FIRST [ ]
   Priority [@|@{b}3@{ub}|     LAST [ ]      Priority [@|0|     LAST [ ]

   Group by FROM at Priority [@|0|    Group by Subject at Priority [@|@{b}2@{ub}|

   [ ] Order Received
                      --> at Priority [@|0|     [ ] Apply to all Folders
   [ ] Latest Received

   [LAST SAVED]    [LAST USED]    [   USE   ]    [  SAVE  ]   [ CANCEL ]

   =====================================================================

If you want the messages sorted with the @{i}earlier messages first@{ui} within the
subject grouping, you would click on @{b}Latest Date: LAST@{ub} rather than @{b}Latest
Date: FIRST@{ub}.

Since the date sort is controlled by the @{i}local date and time@{ui} that the
message was @{b}SENT@{ub}, you might want to use the @{b}Order Received@{ub} or @{b}Latest
Received@{ub} instead of @{b}Latest Date@{ub}.  @{b}Order Received@{ub} will list the messages
with the oldest received first, while @{b}Latest Received@{ub} will list the
messages with the newest received first.

You, of course, can set different sort orders for different folders.  In
this case select the folder you want to change the sort order for and @{b}DON'T@{ub}
click on the @{b}Apply to all Folders@{ub} @{i}checkmark@{ui} gadget.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-8500 "AEMAIL WINDOWS/Address Book Window"

                           @{b}Address Book Window@{ub}

The @{b}Address Book@{ub} window will be displayed in the lower portion of the
screen whenever you double click on the @{" ADDRESS BOOK " link AEM-6020} command icon or on
the @{b}[Call Address Book]@{ub} button in the @{" COMPOSE MESSAGE window" link AEM-8700}.

If you have a non-interlaced screen (640 x 200), the display will cover
the folder strip to allow more room for the @{b}Address Book@{ub} display.  With an
interlaced screen (640 x 400) you will be able to see the @{" folder strip " link AEM-5100}.

The @{b}Address Book@{ub} window looks like the following:

  @{b}========================================================================
  Address Book
  ========================================================================

  Nick Name: [        ] Address: [                      ] Select [@| To: |

  Real Name: [                           ] Group [ ]  Send Header Only [ ]

  Nickname Real Name                 UserID (Address)           [x] Expand
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------
  xxxxxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx| |
  xxxxxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx DISTRIBUTION LIST WITH n ENTRIES  | |
                                     xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx| |
                                     xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx| |
  ------------------------------------------------------------------------

     [ ADD ]     [MODIFY]      [DELETE]      [SELECT]      [ EDIT ]

  ========================================================================@{ub}

This window can be used to @{i}create, modify,@{ui} or @{i}delete@{ui} @{b}Address Book@{ub} entries.
It can also be used to select a @{b}Nickname@{ub} to be used as a recipient of a
message when composing messages.

Several of the @{" Command icons " link AEM-6000} remain active when you are displaying the
@{b}Address Book@{ub} window, although there meaning maybe slightly changed.  These
are the @{b}DISPLAY NEXT MESSAGE@{ub} icon, the @{b}DISPLAY PREVIOUS MESSAGE@{ub} icon, the
@{b}DISPLAY NEXT FOLDER@{ub} icon, the @{b}DISPLAY PREVIOUS FOLDER@{ub} icon, the @{b}DISPLAY
CURRENT FOLDER@{ub} icon, the @{b}PRINT@{ub} icon, the @{b}DELETE@{ub} icon, and the @{b}COMPOSE
MESSAGE@{ub} icon.

The three fields of an address book entry are:  a one to eight character
@{b}Nickname@{ub}, an individual's @{b}Real Name@{ub} (up to 99 characters), and the address
of the individual (@{b}UserId@{ub} and @{b}Domain@{ub} in the form @{b}userid@domain@{ub}) which is
limited to 70 characters.

@{i}Group lists@{ui} can also be created which distribute a message to a number of
different individuals.  The group is identified with the heading
@{b}DISTRIBUTION LIST WITH @{i}nnn@{ui} ENTRIES@{ub} in the top most UserID field.  The
@{i}nnn@{ui} indicates the number of entries in the group.  The @{b}UserID's@{ub} for the
members of that list are shown in alphabetic order below that heading.  For
items in the distribution list, real @{b}UserIDs@{ub} or @{b}Nicknames@{ub} can be used.  An
item in the distribution list can even be another distribution list
identified by the @{b}Nickname@{ub} for that group. By clicking on the Checkmarked
item @{b}Group@{ub}, you can identify the entry as a group item.

The checkmarked item identified as @{b}Send Header Only@{ub} is only active when
@{b}Group@{ub} is checked.  If a checkmark is in the @{b}Send Header Only@{ub} box, only
the group name will be sent in the @{b}To:@{ub} field when a message is sent to
the group; otherwise, every @{b}UserId@{ub} in the group will be listed in the @{b}To:@{ub}
header. It is a good idea to check this item if you have large groups or
if you don't want the other members of the group to know all the members
of the group.

If a @{b}Nickname@{ub} rather than a @{b}UserID@{ub} is used in the group list @{b}Address@{ub}
field, then, if a modification is made to the @{b}UserID@{ub} of the @{b}Nickname@{ub}, you
do not have to change the item in the Group list.  The modification will
be automatic when the group rather than the individual is selected.

When composing a message, a @{b}Nickname@{ub} can be used to identify the recipient
of a message.  All @{b}Nicknames@{ub} are expanded to @{b}Real Name@{ub} and @{b}UserID@{ub} when
mail is sent.

For @{b}registered users of AEMail@{ub}, the checkmarked box to the far right of
the list heading labeled @{b}Expand@{ub} is used to shrink or expand the group
entries in the list.  When this box is not checked, only the group heading
is displayed without the entries in the group showing.  When it is
checked, the groups are expanded to show all the members of the group.
When first displayed, this item will be checked.  However, the system
remembers the state of this checkmark so if you should shrink the groups,
the next time you select the @{b}Address Book@{ub} only the group headings will be
displayed.

For @{b}un-registered users@{ub}, this item will be checked and ghosted.  @{i}You will
not be able to shrink the groups@{ui}.

@{b}Address Book@{ub} entries are sorted by @{b}Nickname@{ub} and group entries are
interspersed with single entries.  Also @{b}Real Names@{ub} are presented as first
name followed by last name rather than last name, first name.

This is a scrolling list.  If there are too many entries to fit in the
window, you can scroll the list by using the @{b}scroll bar@{ub}, clicking on the
@{b}up or down arrows@{ub} below the scroll bar, or by using the @{b}up or down cursor
keys@{ub}.

Additionally the following keys can be used to move the list as follows:

    @{b}Home@{ub} or @{b}ALT Cursor Up@{ub} moves the listview to the top.
    @{b}End@{ub} or @{b}ALT Cursor Down@{ub} moves the listview to the botton.
    @{b}PgUp@{ub} or @{b}Shift Cursor Up@{ub} pages the listview one @{i}page@{ui} up.  The
        top line of the previous page will be displayed as the bottom
        line of the new page.
    @{b}PgDn@{ub} or @{b}Shift Cursor Down@{ub} pages the list view one @{i}page@{ui} down.
        The bottom line of the previous page will be displayed as the
        top line of the new page.
    The cursor up/down keys on the keypad will have the same action as
        the normal cursor keys with the exception of the shift
        feature.

@{b}WARNING:@{ub}  @{i}if you have selected one of the string gadgets for entering
data, the cursor keys will not work for scrolling the list.@{ui}  You
will have to click outside of the string gadget to re-activate scrolling
with the cursor keys.

For adding entries to the @{b}Address Book@{ub}, the entries at the top of the
window are used to place data in the various fields of the @{b}Address Book@{ub}
entry.  If a message was selected when the address book was called, the
@{b}Real Name:@{ub}, if present,  and @{b}Address:@{ub} fields are filled in with
information from the @{b}Reply-To:@{ub} header of the message.  If the @{b}Reply-To:@{ub}
header is not present, the @{b}From:@{ub} header will be used.  You can @{i}force@{ui} the
@{b}From:@{ub} header to be used by holding down the @{i}shift@{ui} key when you click on
the @{b}Address Book@{ub} icon.

Please keep in mind that @{b}Reply-To:@{ub} addresses normally do not have real
names associated with them, but @{b}From:@{ub} addresses many times do.  If you
want the real name you may have to hold down the shift key when you click
on the @{b}Address Book@{ub} icon.

If you access the @{b}Address Book@{ub} from the @{" Compose message window " link AEM-8700} during a
@{" mailto: " link AEM-5300} call to @{b}AEMail@{ub}, the @{b}userid@{ub} from the @{b}mailto:@{ub} will be placed in
the address field.  This allows you to assign a @{b}Nickname@{ub} and @{b}Real Name@{ub} to
this address and save it in your @{b}Address Book@{ub}.

If you click on one of the entries in the list view, that entry will be
transferred to the @{b}Nickname:@{ub}, @{b}Real Name:@{ub}, and @{b}Address:@{ub} fields at the top
of the window.  If you click on a group entry line which has the @{b}Group
Nickname@{ub} and @{b}DISTRIBUTION LIST@{ub} in the address portion, only the
@{b}Nickname:@{ub} and the Group name (in the @{b}Real Name:@{ub} field) will be transferred
leaving any previous address in the @{b}Address:@{ub} field.  The @{b}Group@{ub} box will
also be checked.  This facilitates adding items to a Group list.

When adding an entry to the address book, you must always enter a @{b}Nickname@{ub}
and @{b}Address@{ub}.  @{b}Real Name@{ub} is optional, but recommended.

To add a group entry, the @{b}Group@{ub} box must be checked.  Groups need a
@{b}Nickname@{ub} that is unique (@{i}not the same as that used for an individual@{ui}) and
should have a group description entered in the @{b}Real Name:@{ub}  string gadget.
Group entries are entered one at a time.  The maximum number of entries
that can be added to a group is @{b}3000@{ub}.  When a message is sent to a group,
the message will be sent to a @{i}maximum@{ui} of @{b}50@{ub} recipients at a time.  This
takes care of problems when there is a limit on the number of recipient
addresses that a SMTP server can handle at a time.

After correctly filling in the top portion of the window, click on the
@{b}[ADD]@{ub} button to add the item to the list.  Except for group @{b}Nicknames@{ub},
there can't be a duplicate @{b}Nickname@{ub} when @{i}adding@{ui} to the list.  An already
existing group @{b}Nickname@{ub} will cause the entry to be added to that groups
distribution list.

To modify an entry, the @{b}Nickname@{ub} for the entry must already exist in the
list.  You can @{i}not@{ui} modify @{b}Nicknames@{ub}.  If you need to do this, delete the
old entry and add a new one.  For individual entries, you can modify
either the @{b}Real Name:@{ub} or @{b}Address:@{ub} fields.  For group entries you can
only modify the @{b}Real Name:@{ub} field.  If you need to modify an address in
the distribution list, delete the old one and add a new one.

One of the reasons that @{b}Nicknames@{ub} are preferred in distribution lists is
that, if you need to modify a user's address,  you can do so by simply
modifying the individual's entry.  The address in the group is then
automatically updated by reference.

Selecting one of the entries in the address list will move the data from
that entry to the fields at the top of the window.  Make the modifications
you want then click on the @{b}[MODIFY]@{ub} button to make the modifications.

To delete an entry, select it in the list and then click on the @{b}[DELETE]@{ub}
button.  You can also use the @{" DELETE icon " link AEM-6000} to do this.

The @{b}[SELECT]@{ub} button is used only for one special purpose.  If the full
Address Book was called from a @{b}mailto:@{ub} call to @{b}AEMail@{ub}, this button is
used to select an address from the @{b}Address Book@{ub} and place it in the
appropriate recipients address line while composing the message.  The
@{b}Address Book@{ub} display is slightly different if it was not a @{b}mailto:@{ub} call
(@{i}see below@{ui}).

When you click on the @{b}[SELECT]@{ub} button, the @{b}Address Book@{ub} display is closed
and the @{b}COMPOSE MESSAGE@{ub} window is re-activated.  To determine which header
field is to receive the address, the @{b}Select@{ub} cycle gadget at the top of
the window is used.  There are three items for this gadget:  @{b}To:, cc:,@{ub} and
@{b}bcc:@{ub}.  Determine which field should receive the address and then click on
the @{b}[SELECT]@{ub} button.  The @{b}Nickname@{ub} for the selected item is transferred to
the appropriate field in the compose window.

If the @{b}Address Book@{ub} was not called from the Compose window, the @{b}Select@{ub}
cycle gadget will be ghosted and can not be used.  If the @{b}Address Book@{ub} was
called from the @{" COMPOSE MESSAGE window " link AEM-8700}, clicking on one of the address
fields before calling the @{b}Address Book@{ub} will automatically select the
appropriate field in the @{b}Select@{ub} cycle gadget.

You can avoid using the @{b}[SELECT]@{ub} button for returning to the @{b}COMPOSE
MESSAGE@{ub} Window by double clicking on an item in the @{b}Address Book@{ub} list
view.

If the Address Book was not called from the @{b}COMPOSE MESSAGE window@{ub},
instead of double clicking, the @{" COMPOSE MESSAGE " link AEM-6080} command icon can be
selected when in the @{b}Address Book@{ub} window.  When this is done, the @{b}COMPOSE
MESSAGE window@{ub} is activated for composing a new message with the selected
address field always being the @{b}To:@{ub} field.  The selected address in the
Address Book will be moved to the @{b}To:@{ub} field.

The @{b}[EXIT]@{ub} button is used to exit from the @{b}Address Book window@{ub} without
performing an address selection for a composed message.  You will need to
@{b}[EXIT]@{ub} from the Address Book if you want to quit @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

If the @{b}Address Book@{ub} was called while displaying a message, clicking on the
@{" DISPLAY NEXT MESSAGE " link AEM-6040} or the @{" DISPLAY PREVIOUS MESSAGE " link AEM-6030} icons will
automatically exit from the @{b}Address Book@{ub} and display either the next or
previous message in the currently displayed message list.

If you click on the @{" DISPLAY NEXT FOLDER " link AEM-6120}, the @{" DISPLAY PREVIOUS FOLDER " link AEM-6120}, or
@{" DISPLAY CURRENT FOLDER " link AEM-6120} icons, the @{b}Address Book@{ub} will be closed and the
appropriate message list for the selected folder will be displayed.

If the @{b}PRINT@{ub} icon is selected while you are displaying the @{b}Address Book@{ub},
you will get a printout of your @{i}complete@{ui} Address Book.  All individual
entries will be displayed first followed by group entries.  Unless a group
is too large to fit on one page, an attempt will be made to ensure that a
group will be printed in it's entirety on a page.

When the @{b}Address Book@{ub} is be called from the @{b}COMPOSE MESSAGE window@{ub} and the
COMPOSE MESSAGE window was not activated during a @{b}mailto:@{ub} call to
@{b}AEMail@{ub}, the @{b}Address Book@{ub} display will be slightly different.  It will look
like this:

  @{b}=====================================================================
  |+| Address Book For Compose
  =====================================================================

  Nickname Real Name               UserID (Address)          [ ] Expand
  ---------------------------------------------------------------------
  xxxxxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx| |
  xxxxxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx DISTRIBUTION LIST WITH n ENTRIES | |
  xxxxxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx DISTRIBUTION LIST WITH n ENTRIES | |
  xxxxxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx| |
  ---------------------------------------------------------------------

  Click on Address Book entry to transfer to [@| To: | field  [ CLOSE ]

  =====================================================================@{ub}

This is an abreviated window which does not have the string gadgets for
creating or deleting @{b}Address Book@{ub} entries.  It is designed for selecting
addresses to transfer to the @{b}COMPOSE MESSAGE window@{ub} only.  When you click
on an address in the window it will be transferred to the appropriate
field in the @{b}COMPOSE MESSAGE window@{ub} as determined by the cycle gadget at
the bottom of the window.  There are three items for this gadget:  @{b}To:,
cc:@{ub}, and @{b}bcc@{ub}:  (the same as the @{b}Select@{ub} cycle gadget in the @{i}full@{ui} @{b}Address
Book@{ub} window.  Select which field should receive the address and click on
the address in the @{b}Address Book@{ub}.  You can select multiple addresses; the
window will not close until you click on either the Close gadget at the
top of the @{b}Address Book@{ub} window or the @{b}[CLOSE]@{ub} button at the bottom of the
window.  The @{b}Address Book@{ub} window will also close if you @{i}double click@{ui} on a
name (It will be transferred and then the window will close).

You can also select which field you want to receive the address by
clicking into the appropriate field in the @{" COMPOSE MESSAGE window " link AEM-8700}.  You
will see the cycle gadget switch to that field and the cursor will
disappear from the field since the @{b}Address Book@{ub} window will again become
activated.

When the Address Book is called from the @{b}COMPOSE MESSAGE window@{ub} it will be
in the @{i}un-expanded@{ui} state.  @{b}If you are a registered user@{ub}, you can expand
the group names by clicking on the @{b}Expand@{ub} checkmark gadget to the right
of the listview headings.

You can also have the full @{b}Address Book@{ub} display called from the @{b}COMPOSE
MESSAGE window@{ub} by holding down the @{i}shift key@{ui} when you click on the @{b}[Call
Address Book]@{ub} gadget.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} When @{b}AEMail@{ub} is loaded it will automatically create an address book
entry for the @{i}Nickname@{ui} @{b}AEMAIL@{ub} with a @{i}UserID@{ui} for my email address:
@{b}jzachar@calweb.com@{ub}.  You can use this entry whenever you wish to
@{" report a bug " link AEM-9700} or send a message concerning @{b}AEMail@{ub} to me.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-8510 "AEMAIL WINDOWS/Address Book for Compose"

                         @{b}Address Book for Compose@{ub}

When the @{b}Address Book@{ub} is be called from the @{b}COMPOSE MESSAGE window@{ub} and the
COMPOSE MESSAGE window was not activated during a @{b}mailto:@{ub} call to
@{b}AEMail@{ub}, the @{b}Address Book@{ub} display will be slightly different.  It will look
like this:

  @{b}=====================================================================
  |+| Address Book For Compose
  =====================================================================

  Nickname Real Name               UserID (Address)          [ ] Expand
  ---------------------------------------------------------------------
  xxxxxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx| |
  xxxxxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx DISTRIBUTION LIST WITH n ENTRIES | |
  xxxxxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx DISTRIBUTION LIST WITH n ENTRIES | |
  xxxxxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx| |
  ---------------------------------------------------------------------

  Click on Address Book entry to transfer to [@| To: | field  [ CLOSE ]

  =====================================================================@{ub}

This is an abreviated window which does not have the string gadgets for
creating or deleting @{b}Address Book@{ub} entries.  It is designed for selecting
addresses to transfer to the @{b}COMPOSE MESSAGE window@{ub} only.  When you click
on an address in the window it will be transferred to the appropriate
field in the @{b}COMPOSE MESSAGE window@{ub} as determined by the cycle gadget at
the bottom of the window.  There are three items for this gadget:  @{b}To:,
cc:@{ub}, and @{b}bcc@{ub}:  (the same as the @{b}Select@{ub} cycle gadget in the @{i}full@{ui} @{b}Address
Book@{ub} window.  Select which field should receive the address and click on
the address in the @{b}Address Book@{ub}.  You can select multiple addresses; the
window will not close until you click on either the Close gadget at the
top of the @{b}Address Book@{ub} window or the @{b}[CLOSE]@{ub} button at the bottom of the
window.  The @{b}Address Book@{ub} window will also close if you @{i}double click@{ui} on a
name (It will be transferred and then the window will close).

You can also select which field you want to receive the address by
clicking into the appropriate field in the @{" COMPOSE MESSAGE window " link AEM-8700}.  You
will see the cycle gadget switch to that field and the cursor will
disappear from the field since the @{b}Address Book@{ub} window will again become
activated.

When the Address Book is called from the @{b}COMPOSE MESSAGE window@{ub} it will be
in the @{i}un-expanded@{ui} state.  @{b}If you are a registered user@{ub}, you can expand
the group names by clicking on the @{b}Expand@{ub} checkmark gadget to the right
of the listview headings.

You can also have the full @{b}Address Book@{ub} display called from the @{b}COMPOSE
MESSAGE window@{ub} by holding down the @{i}shift key@{ui} when you click on the @{b}[Call
Address Book]@{ub} gadget.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} When @{b}AEMail@{ub} is loaded it will automatically create an address book
entry for the @{i}Nickname@{ui} @{b}AEMAIL@{ub} with a @{i}UserID@{ui} for my email address:
@{b}jzachar@calweb.com@{ub}.  You can use this entry whenever you wish to
@{" report a bug " link AEM-9700} or send a message concerning @{b}AEMail@{ub} to me.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-8600 "AEMAIL WINDOWS/Message Display Window"

                          @{b}Message Display Window@{ub}

The @{b}Message Display@{ub} window will be displayed in the lower portion of the
screen whenever you double click on a message in the @{" Message List " link AEM-8200} window.
If you are already displaying a message, clicking on the @{" NEXT " link AEM-6040} or
@{" PREVIOUS " link AEM-6030} command icons will display either the next or previous
message.

If you have a non-interlaced screen (640 x 200), the display will cover
the folder strip to allow more room for the message display.  With an
interlaced screen (640 x 400) you will be able to see and use the
@{" folder strip " link AEM-5100}.

To re-display the Message List, click on the @{" folder " link AEM-6120} icon on the Command
Icon Tool Bar or one of the folders in the folder icon bar (if visable).

The message is divided into two sections: @{i}message header information@{ui},
which is always present, and a @{i}scrolling list that displays the message@{ui}.
Header information will also be displayed in the scrolling message
listview, but only those header lines that you want displayed.

The @{i}message header portion@{ui} of the screen is set up as follows:


 @{b}From: xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx Date: DOW, MMM DD YYYY HH:MM:SS
 To: xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx [ATTACHMENT]
 Subject: xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx  Active Msg@{ub}


The @{b}From:@{ub} and @{b}To:@{ub} fields will show the @{b}Real Name@{ub} (@{i}if present@{ui}) from the
appropriate header.  If the @{b}Real Name@{ub} is not present in the header, then
the @{b}UserID@{ub} will be used instead.  If a @{b}Nickname@{ub} is being used for a message
being sent, then the @{b}Nickname@{ub} will appear. (@{i}see @{" Address Book " link AEM-8500}for discussion
of @{b}Nicknames@{ub}@{ui})

The @{b}Subject:@{ub} field will have the @{b}RE:@{ub} or @{b}(FWD)@{ub} preappended to the field for
messages that are REPLIES and/or are FORWARDED.

If the message has attachments, either @{b}MIME@{ub} or @{b}UUENCODED@{ub}, the @{b}[ATTACHMENT]@{ub}
button will appear at the right of the @{b}To:@{ub} line.  If no attachments are
present this button will say @{b}[SAVE TEXT]@{ub} instead.  Clicking on the @{b}[SAVE
TEXT]@{ub} button will bring up the @{" Save Text Requester " link AEM-8620} along side the
@{b}[SAVE TEXT]@{ub} button.

For messages that are active (not deleted), @{b}Active Msg@{ub} will appear in a
text box to the right of the @{b}Subject@{ub} line.  If the message is a deleted
message @{b}Deleted Msg@{ub} will appear in red in place of @{b}Active Msg@{ub}.

The complete message will be displayed in the message listview including
any text type attachments.  If the attachments are @{b}UUENCODED@{ub} attachments
or are non-text type attachments, they will not be shown, but can be
retrieved by clicking on the @{b}[ATTACHMENT]@{ub} button.  This will bring up an
attachment requestor which is described below under
@{" Attachment Requester " link AEM-8610}.

Messages that are encoded with @{b}Quoted-Printable@{ub} notation as well as text
messages encoded with @{b}encoded binary (BASE64)@{ub} will be correctly displayed
as well.  Since these types of messages will be saved with their encoding
intact when saved using the @{" SAVE MESSAGE " link AEM-6050} icon or the @{b}Export...@{ub} item
under the @{" Messages " link AEM-7300} menu, the @{b}[SAVE TEXT]@{ub} gadget has been provided to save
message text correctly decoded for messages without attachments.  For
messages with attachments, the first entry in the Attachment list is the
body of messages itself.

The message display is a scrolling list.  There are four methods that you
can use to scroll the message:

    (1) Use the @{b}scroll bar@{ub} to the right of the message.

    (2) Use the @{b}scroll arrows@{ub} at the bottom of the scroll bar.

    (3) Use the @{b}up and down cursor keys@{ub}.  You can also move the listview
        with other keys as follows:

        @{b}Home@{ub} or @{b}ALT Cursor Up@{ub} moves the listview to the top.
        @{b}End@{ub} or @{b}ALT Cursor Down@{ub} moves the listview to the botton.
        @{b}PgUp@{ub} or @{b}Shift Cursor Up@{ub} pages the listview one @{i}page@{ui} up.  The
            top line of the previous page will be displayed as the bottom
            line of the new page.
        @{b}PgDn@{ub} or @{b}Shift Cursor Down@{ub} pages the list view one @{i}page@{ui} down.
            The bottom line of the previous page will be displayed as the
            top line of the new page.
        The cursor up/down keys on the keypad will have the same action as
            the normal cursor keys with the exception of the shift
            feature.

    (4) click the mouse on the list display and while holding down
        the left mouse button, move above or below the display.
        When you lift up on the mouse button after the list
        starts to scroll, you can continue to scroll by moving
        the mouse up or down.  Clicking into the display will
        stop the scrolling action.

While messages are loaded into the listview, you will not see them until
they are completely read.  A busy pointer will be displayed until the
listview is completely built.

You can change the font for the message display.  If you want a larger
font for displaying message text, go to the @{" Fonts Page " link AEM-4800} of the
@{" Configuration Setup " link AEM-4200} (activated by the @{" Configuration/Edit " link AEM-7101} menu item under
the @{" Project menu " link AEM-7100}) and change the font in the @{b}Message Font@{ub} section.  Any
font or font size can be used, but @{i}selecting a proportional font for some
messages may take longer for the message to load@{ui}.  If you are an
@{b}un-registered user@{ub} you will be able to change the font for the current
session of @{b}AEMail@{ub} but you will @{u}not@{uu} be able to save the font selection for
subsequent @{b}AEMail@{ub} sessions.

You can also edit and save lines from the message to the clipboard by
double clicking on any line in the message.  This will open a window at
the top of the screen for editing and saving the line to the clipboard.
See @{" Using the Clipboard with AEMail " link AEM-5500}.

If the line you double click on contains an email address (@{i}determined by
the @{b}@@{ub} between adjoining strings@{ui}) or a web address (@{i}determined by @{ub}www.@{ub}
within the string@{ui}), just the email address or the web address will be
transferred to the string.  If the web address does not have @{b}http://@{ub} at
the beginning of the string, that will be added.

If you hold down the shift key when you double click on such an address,
the entire line will be trasferred, not just the email or web address.

If you have transferred an email or web address you can also hit a
@{" function key " link AEM-4700} to execute an @{b}ARexx@{ub} script.  The email address or web address
will be transferred to a special variable and the script will be executed.
If the script contains the @{b}ARexx@{ub} command @{" GETVAR " link AEM-9530} it will receive the
variable string in the @{b}RESULT@{ub} variable and can act on it.  Several sample
@{b}ARexx@{ub} scripts have been placed in your @{b}ARexx@{ub} directory which can extract
the address from the special variable and call your web browser to go to
that web page (@{b}gotowww.aem@{ub}), send a message to the email address
(@{b}sendmsg.aem@{ub}) or place the email address in the address book either as an
individual address (@{b}placeaddr.aem@{ub}) or as a group address (@{b}placegrp.aem@{ub}).

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-8610 "AEMAIL WINDOWS/Message Display Window/ATTACHMENT REQUESTER"

                           @{b}Attachment Requester@{ub}

When you click on the @{b}[ATTACHMENTS]@{ub} button on the @{" Message Display Window " link AEM-8600},
an @{b}Attachment Requester@{ub} will be displayed.  It looks like this:


      @{b}|============================================================|
      |[o]  Attachment List                                        |
      |============================================================|
      |                MimeType/SubType          File Name         |
      | ========================================================== |
      | | 1  SHOWN     text/plain                              | | |
      | |    Description: (None)                               | | |
      | | 2  VIEWABLE  image/gif                 castle.gif    | | |
      | |    Description: Picture of a castle                  | | |
      | | 3  SAVE ONLY application/octet-stream  aemail.lha    | | |
      | |    Description: The AEMail archive                   | | |
      | ========================================================== |
      |                                                            |
      |   [    VIEW   ]       [VIEW & SAVE]        [ SAVE FILE ]   |
      |                                                            |
      |   [ SAVE CLIP ]       [ CLIP UNIT ]        [    EXIT   ]   |
      |____________________________________________________________|@{ub}


This requester is initially placed at the top center of the window
partially obscuring the command and folder icons and the top portion of
the message.  You can drag the requester around the window to expose other
items of the display.  You can also use the scroll bar on the message
display listview to show different parts of the message; however, none of
the commands on the command or folder bar or the menu bar can be activated
until after you click on the @{b}[EXIT]@{ub} button in the @{b}Attachment Requester@{ub}.

The @{b}SHOWN@{ub} designation is used for any attachment that is displayed in the
message window.  This is generally any attachment that has a @{b}MIME@{ub} type of
@{i}text@{ui} or @{i}message@{ui}.  However, standard @{b}Mailcap@{ub} entries have been included in
the @{" Mailcap file " link AEM-9101} to also display and save these attachments from the
Attachment window.

Any message with attachments will generally have one section (the initial
message) which is displayable text and will be shown as an attachment with
the @{b}SHOWN@{ub} designation.  You will also be able to @{b}VIEW@{ub} all @{b}SHOWN@{ub} parts of
the message separably.  You will always be able to save any item in the
list in it's un-encoded form.

@{b}UUENCODED@{ub} attachments will have the designation @{b}UUENCODED@{ub} displayed in the
@{b}MIME @{i}types/subtypes@{ui}@{ub} field.

Any attachments that do not have a @{b}MIME@{ub} type of @{i}text@{ui} or @{i}message@{ui} will have
either a @{b}VIEWABLE@{ub} or @{b}SAVE ONLY@{ub} designation.  The @{b}VIEWABLE@{ub} designation is
used for those @{b}MIME @{i}types/subtypes@{ui}@{ub} which have a program designated in the
@{" mailcap " link AEM-9100} file for displaying this @{b}MIME @{i}type/subtype@{ui}@{ub}.  If no program is
designated for this @{b}MIME @{i}type/subtype@{ui}@{ub} the @{b}SAVE ONLY@{ub} designator will appear
on the attachment line and the @{b}[VIEW]@{ub} and the @{b}[VIEW & SAVE]@{ub} buttons will
be disabled.

@{b}UUENCODED@{ub} attachments are always @{b}SAVE ONLY@{ub} attachments.

To select an attachment to @{i}view, view & save,@{ui} or to @{i}save only@{ui}, select the
appropriate attachment line in the list view gadget.  You can select the
main description line (with @{b}number, mime type,@{ub} and @{b}filename@{ub}) or the second
line with the @{b}Description:@{ub} heading.

After selecting the attachment, the buttons below the listview will perform
the following actions:

    @{b}[VIEW]@{ub}

        This will display the attachment with the program you
        selected in the @{" mailcap " link AEM-9100} file for this @{b}MIME @{i}type/subtype@{ui}@{ub}.
        If a program was not pre-defined for this @{b}MIME @{i}type/subtype@{ui}@{ub}
        this button will be disabled and you will not be able to
        display the attachment.  You will also see @{b}SAVE ONLY@{ub} rather
        than @{b}VIEWABLE@{ub} on the description of this attachment.

    @{b}[VIEW & SAVE]@{ub}

        A file requester will pop up which allows you to select a file
        to save your attachment to.  The default directory designated
        to receive attachments is @{b}RAM:@{ub}; however, you can change this
        with the file requester or set a different default with the
        @{" Default Path Parameters " link AEM-4500} display on the @{" Configuration Setup " link AEM-4200}
        window.

        If a file name was provided in either the @{b}Content-Type:@{ub} or
        @{b}Content-Disposition:@{ub} headers, the file name will be shown on
        the attachment description and will be pre-set as the default
        filename in the file requester.  You can, of course, change this
        name if you wish.

        After the file is saved, the attachment will be displayed
        with the program you selected in the @{" mailcap " link AEM-9100} file.

        If a program was not pre-defined for this @{b}MIME @{i}type/subtype@{ui}@{ub}
        this button will be disabled and you will not be able to
        display the attachment.  You will also see @{b}SAVE ONLY@{ub} rather
        than @{b}VIEWABLE@{ub} on the description of this attachment.


    @{b}[SAVE FILE]@{ub}

        A file requester will pop up which allows you to select 
        a file to save your attachment to.  The default directory 
        designated to receive attachments is @{b}RAM:@{ub}; however, you can 
        change this with the file requester or set a different 
        default with the @{" Default Path Parameters " link AEM-4500} page on the 
        @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

        If a file name was provided in either the @{b}Content-Type:@{ub} or
        @{b}Content-Disposition:@{ub} headers or with the @{b}UUENCODED@{ub} @{b}@{i}begin@{ui}@{ub} line,
        the file name will be shown on the attachment description and
        will be pre-set as the default filename in the file requester.
        You can, of course, change this name if you wish.

        You will always be able to save any attachment even if it
        is @{b}SHOWN@{ub} and a filename is not specified.

    @{b}[SAVE CLIP]@{ub}

        If the attachment has an encoding type of @{b}7-bit@{ub}, @{b}8-bit@{ub}, or
        @{b}quoted-printable@{ub}, you can save the attachment to the current
        clipboard unit.  If the attachment is not a text type attachment
        (@{b}encoded binary@{ub}), this button will be ghosted.

    @{b}[CLIP UNIT]@{ub}

        This will bring up the requester that allows you to change the
        current clipboard unit (see @{" Using the Clipboard with AEMail " link AEM-5500}).

    @{b}[EXIT]@{ub}

        After performing all the operations you wish for any
        particular attachment, click on this button to remove
        the Attachment Requester.  This requester also has a
        @{b}CLOSE@{ub} gadget which you can also use to exit from the
        requester.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-8620 "AEMAIL WINDOWS/Message Display Window/SAVE TEXT REQUESTER"

                           @{b}Save Text Requester@{ub}

When you click on the @{b}[SAVE TEXT]@{ub} button on the @{" Message Display Window " link AEM-8600}, a
a tiered set of five buttons will appear to the left of the @{b}[SAVE TEXT]@{ub}
gadget that look like this:

                         @{b}[    VIEW   ]
                         [ SAVE FILE ]
                         [ SAVE CLIP ][SAVE TEXT]
                         [ CLIP UNIT ]
                         [   CANCEL  ]@{ub}


Clicking on one of the buttons will perform the appropriate action as
described below.  With the exception of @{b}[CLIP UNIT]@{ub}, the buttons will
disappear at the completion of the action.

    @{b}[VIEW]@{ub}

        This will display the message text with the program you selected
        in the @{" mailcap " link AEM-9100} file for the @{b}"text" MIME@{ub} type.  If a program was
        not pre-defined for this @{b}MIME@{ub} type, this button will be disabled
        (ghosted).  This option is given so that you can select special
        message display programs to display the message and perhaps
        perform special operations of the message.  As an example, you
        could specify an editor which would allow you to make
        modifications to the message and then save portions of it to a
        file or clipboard.

    @{b}[SAVE FILE]@{ub}

        A file requester will pop up which allows you to select
        a file to save your message to.  If the message used a coding
        scheme such as @{b}quoted-printable@{ub} or @{b}encoded binary@{ub} it will be
        properly converted before it is saved.  The default directory
        designated to receive this text file is @{b}RAM:@{ub}; however, you can
        change this with the file requester or set a different
        default with the @{" Default Path Parameters " link AEM-4500} Page on the
        @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

    @{b}[SAVE CLIP]@{ub}

        If the text has an encoding type of @{b}7-bit@{ub}, @{b}8-bit@{ub}, or
        @{b}quoted-printable@{ub}, you can save it to the current clipboard unit.
        If the text is @{b}encoded binary@{ub}, this button will be ghosted.

    @{b}[CLIP UNIT]@{ub}

        This will bring up the requester that allows you to change the
        current clipboard unit (see @{" Using the Clipboard with AEMail " link AEM-5500}).

    @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub}

        This gadget is provided to exit from the request without
        performing any action.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-8700 "AEMAIL WINDOWS/Compose Message Window"

                          @{b}Compose Message Window@{ub}

The @{b}Compose Message Window@{ub} is brought up whenever you click on the
@{" COMPOSE MESSAGE " link AEM-6080} command icon or select the @{" Compose... " link AEM-7301}, @{" Reply... " link AEM-7301}, or
@{" Forward... " link AEM-7301} sub-menus under the @{" Messages menu " link AEM-7300}.  If a message is selected
when you click on the @{b}COMPOSE MESSAGE@{ub} command icon it will act as a
@{i}Reply to this message@{ui} action.

The @{b}Compose Message window@{ub} will cover the entire screen.  You must proceed
sequentional through the actions or cancel to abort the compose operation.

The @{b}Compose Message window@{ub} looks like this:


  @{b}=====================================================================
  Compose a Message (Signature: [full path of signature file active])
  =====================================================================

         To: [                              ][CLR] [Call Address Book ]

         cc: [                                                   ][CLR]

        bcc: [                                                   ][CLR]

   Reply To: [                                   ][CLR] [ Use Default ]

    Subject: [                                                   ][CLR]

             [] New Message                    [] 7-Bit
             [] Reply to Message               [] 8-bit
             [] Forward Message                [] quoted-printable
                                             [] encoded binary

   [ ] Quote Original Message Text   Quote Prefix[>                    ]

     Quote Header: [                                                   ]

   [ ] Add Signature Block   [Select Signature]        [ Edit Signature]

   [Compose/Edit Message]    [  Add Headers   ]        [Add Attachments]

   [Send Message Now] [Queue Message] [Save In Pending] [Cancel Message]

  ======================================================================@{ub}

The title bar on the @{b}Compose Message@{ub} window will contain the full path
name to the current, in use @{" signature file " link AEM-9160}.

When the @{b}Compose Message@{ub} window first appears and if the message is a
replied message, the following requester will appear if the replied
message had @{b}To:@{ub} recipients other than yourself:


       @{b}|=========================================================|
       | Multiple Recipients                                     |
       |---------------------------------------------------------|
       |             The message you are replying to             |
       |                has other To: recipients.                |
       |              Do you want to send the reply              |
       |                                                         |
       | [o] to only the sender of the original message?         |
       | [ ] to all To: recipients of the original message?      |
       | [ ] cc: to all To: recipients of the original message?  |
       | [ ] bcc: to all To: recipients of the original message? |
       |                                                         |
       |                       [ Continue ]                      |
       |                                                         |
       |=========================================================|@{ub}

With this requester you can send the message you are composing to @{i}none@{ui} of
the other recipients, @{i}directly to@{ui} all the other recipients (in the @{b}To:@{ub}
line), @{i}as a cc@{ui} to all the recipients, or @{i}as a bcc@{ui} to all the other
recipients.

If there is a single recipient to the message and that recipient is the
same as either your @{b}From:@{ub} or @{b}Reply-To:@{ub} address, you will not see the
requester.  Also, when the list of recipients is transferred to the
appropriate address line in the Compose window, any address that is the
same as your @{b}From:@{ub} or @{b}Reply-To:@{ub} address will be stripped.  If you want
to send the message also to the @{b}From:@{ub} or @{b}Reply-To:@{ub} address you will have
to add the address yourself.

When you have selected the action you want, hit @{b}[Continue]@{ub} and the list of
@{b}To:@{ub} recipients will be transferred to the appropriate string gadget in
the @{b}Compose Message@{ub} window.

@{b}@{u}SPECIAL CONSIDERATION:@{uu}@{ub}  If the message you are replying to was received by
a version of @{b}AEMail@{ub} @{i}prior to 1.42@{ui}, you will not be able to transfer
recipients that @{i}extend beyond one line@{ui}.  You can solve this problem,
however, by saving the message you want to reply to to a file (using the
@{" export " link AEM-6050} function) and then reading it back into version 1.43 of @{b}AEMail@{ub}.
To read it back in using the @{" From Local File.. " link AEM-7401} menu item under the
@{" Retrieve Msgs " link AEM-7400} menu.

@{i}One point of warning@{ui}.  If the recipient of the original message was the
name of a @{b}list@{ub} rather than the name of an @{b}individual@{ub}, you will also see
this requester.  Unfortunately, there is no way to know that the recipient
name is a list name rather than an individual name.  In this event, you
should always select @{b}"to only the sender of the original message"@{ub} since
the list name is probably not a valid recipient.

If there were @{b}cc:@{ub}'s to the original message, you may also see the
following similar requester for sending to the @{b}cc:@{ub} recipients:

       @{b}|=========================================================|
       | Multiple Recipients                                     |
       |---------------------------------------------------------|
       |             The message you are replying to             |
       |             has one or more cc: recipients.             |
       |              Do you want to send the reply              |
       |                                                         |
       | [o] to only the sender of the original message?         |
       | [ ] to all cc: recipients of the original message?      |
       | [ ] cc: to all cc: recipients of the original message?  |
       | [ ] bcc: to all cc: recipients of the original message? |
       |                                                         |
       |                       [ Continue ]                      |
       |                                                         |
       |=========================================================|@{ub}

Again, after you have selected the action you want, hit @{b}[Continue]@{ub} and the
list of @{b}cc:@{ub} recipients will be transferred to the appropriate string gadget
in the @{b}Compose Message@{ub} window.

If the message is a replied message, the @{b}To:@{ub} string gadget will also be
filled in with the @{b}Reply-To:@{ub} address from the message you are replying to
or, if that is not present, the @{b}From:@{ub} @{i}real name@{ui} and @{i}user ID@{ui} of the
message you are replying to.  This is in addition to any action caused by
the previously mentioned requesters.

You can force the @{b}From:@{ub} address to be used by holding down the shift key
when clicking on the @{" compose " link AEM-6080} icon or selecting the menu sub-item @{b}Use
From...@{ub} on the @{" Reply " link AEM-7301} menu item of the @{" Messages menu " link AEM-7300}.

Also, if the message is the result of a @{b}mailto: call@{ub}, the @{b}To:@{ub} string
gadget will be filled in with the @{i}userid@{ui} passed by the @{b}mailto: call@{ub}.

If the message is a replied or forwarded message, the @{b}Subject:@{ub} string
gadget will be automatically filled in with the subject from the replied
or forwarded message.  @{b}RE:@{ub} or @{b}(fwd)@{ub} will also automatically appear in
front of the subject.

You may enter names, either @{b}Nicknames@{ub} or @{b}Real Names@{ub} and/or @{b}UserID's@{ub}, for
any of the @{b}To:, cc:,@{ub} or @{b}bcc:@{ub} fields.  If a @{b}Real Name@{ub} and/or @{b}UserID@{ub} is
entered, it should be entered as

        @{b}Real Name<userid@domain>@{ub}              @{i}or@{ui}
        @{b}userid@domain(Real Name)@{ub}              @{i}or@{ui}
        @{b}userid@domain@{ub}


The @{b}domain@{ub} can be left off if the recipient is at the same domain as the
user.  However, it is best that the full @{b}userid@domain@{ub} be used so there is
no confusion with @{b}Nicknames@{ub}.

If a @{b}Nickname@{ub} is used it will be automatically expanded when the message
is sent.

If multiple users are placed in any of the @{b}To:, cc:,@{ub} or @{b}bcc:@{ub} fields they
must be separated by commas.

If the users you are sending the message to are in your Address Book, you
can click on the @{b}[Call Address Book]@{ub} button.  This will call up an
abreviated form of your @{" Address Book " link AEM-8500} and you can select the user you want.
Clicking on the user will transfer the @{b}Nickname@{ub} for that user to the
appropriate field indicated by the cycle gadget at the bottom of the
@{b}Address Book@{ub} window (@{b}To:, cc:@{ub}  or @{b}bcc:@{ub}).  The @{b}Nickname@{ub} for the user will
be automatically added to the appropriate field in the @{b}Compose window@{ub}.  If
you make a mistake and the wrong name is added or it is added to the wrong
field, you can use the backspace key to remove the offending @{b}Nickname@{ub} or
the @{b}[CLR]@{ub} gadget to completely clear the field.

The @{b}Address Book@{ub} window will remain displayed to allow you to select
multiple names.  Multiple names in any field will be automatically
separated by commas.

To exit from the @{b}Address Book@{ub} display, either click on the Close gadget at
the top of the Address Book window or the @{b}[CLOSE]@{ub} button at the bottom of
the window.  Alternately, you can @{i}double click@{ui} on the last name you add to
a field.

You can also use the @{b}[Call Address Book]@{ub} gadget to place the @{b}userid@{ub} from a
@{b}mailto:@{ub} call into your @{b}Address Book@{ub}.  In this case the full address book
will be shown rather than the abbreviated one.  You can also access the
full Address Book by pressing the @{i}shift key@{ui} when you click on the @{b}[Call
Address Book]@{ub} gadget.

All of the gadgets in the @{b}Compose Window@{ub} remain active when you are
displaying the @{i}abbreviated@{ui} form of the @{b}Address Book@{ub}.  They are @{b}not@{ub} active
when you display the full @{b}Address Book@{ub}.  The @{b}select@{ub} cycle gadget in the
@{b}Address Book@{ub} can be used to select the field you want the address
transferred to, or alternately, you can click into the field you want and
the cycle gadget will automatically be set to that field.  When you do
this, the @{b}Address Book@{ub} window will immediately become activated to allow
you to select the address you want or to move the @{b}Address Book@{ub} list view
with the cursor keys.

The @{b}cc:@{ub} field is used to send a "carbon copy" of the message to the
people in the list on the @{b}cc:@{ub} line.  The @{b}cc:@{ub} header will appear on the
message sent to the @{b}To:@{ub}, @{b}cc:@{ub} and @{b}bcc:@{ub} recipients.  The @{b}bcc:@{ub} field is
used the send a "blind carbon copy" to the people in that list.  The @{b}bcc:@{ub}
recipients will not be identified to any of the recipients of the message.

The @{b}Reply To:@{ub} field is used to place a @{b}Reply-To:@{ub} address header in the
message.  This field is intended for people who want replies directed to a
different email address than their @{b}From:@{ub} address.  The configuration item
@{b}Reply-To:@{ub} will automatically be loaded into this field when the compose
window is displayed.  If the @{b}Reply To:@{ub} address for this message should be
different than the configured @{b}Reply-To@{ub} address, then place it here.  If
you click on the @{b}[ Use Default ]@{ub} button, your configured @{b}Reply-To@{ub} address
will be placed in this field.  If the @{b}Reply To:@{ub} field is left blank, no
@{b}Reply-To:@{ub} header line will be added to the message.

The @{b}Subject:@{ub} field is used to create a subject header for your message.
If the message is a reply, @{b}RE:@{ub}  will be placed in front of the subject.
If the message is forwarded, @{b}(fwd)@{ub} will be placed after the subject.

The @{b}[CLR]@{ub} gadget to the right of the @{b}To:, Reply To:, Subject:, cc:,@{ub} and
@{b}bcc:@{ub} string gadgets allows you to easily clear the data in the
appropriate string gadget.

Below the @{b}Subject@{ub} field is two columns of Radio buttons for selecting the
@{b}type message@{ub} to create and to specify the @{b}encoding method@{ub} for the message
body.  The first column of radio buttons specifies the message type to
create.  These can be:

    @{b}New Message
    Reply to Message
    Forward Message
    Edit Message@{ub}

Which buttons appear depends on the way the @{b}Compose Message@{ub} window was
called.

@{b}New Message@{ub} and @{b}Edit Messages@{ub} appear if a message was selected from the
@{b}PENDING@{ub} or @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folders and the @{b}COMPOSE MESSAGE@{ub} command icon was
selected or the @{b}Edit...@{ub} menu item was selected from the @{b}Messages menu@{ub}.
The @{b}Edit Message@{ub} button is initially highlighted.

@{b}New Message@{ub}, @{b}Reply to Message@{ub}, and @{b}Forward Message@{ub} appears if a
message was selected from an input folder (such as @{b}INBOX@{ub}) and the @{b}COMPOSE
MESSAGE@{ub} command icon was selected or one of the @{b}Reply@{ub} or @{b}Forward...@{ub}
menu items were selected from the @{b}Messages menu@{ub}.  If a @{b}Reply@{ub} sub-menu
item was selected, the @{b}Reply to Message@{ub} button will be initially
highlighted.  If @{b}Forward...@{ub} is selected, the @{b}Forward Message@{ub} button
will be intially highlighted.

Only @{b}New Message@{ui} appears and is highlighted if no message was selected,
if the @{b}Compose..@{ub} menu item was selected, or if a message in the @{b}SENT@{ub}
folder was selected.

@{b}New Message@{ub} also appears if the @{b}Compose message window@{ub} was activated by
a @{" mailto: call " link AEM-5300} from a browser.  If a @{b}message=@{ub} argument was provided on
the shell call to @{b}AEMail@{ub}, both the @{b}New Message@{ub} and @{b}Edit Message@{ub} will
appear and the @{b}Edit Message@{ub} item will be highlighted..

If the @{b}Edit...@{ub}, @{b}Reply@{ub} or @{b}Forward...@{ub} menu items are selected and a
message @{i}was not selected@{ui}, an error message appears.  If the "Compose..."
sub-menu is selected, a new message will @{i}always@{ui} be created.  Likewise,
messages cannot be replied to or forwarded from the @{b}PENDING@{ub}, @{b}QUEUED@{ub} or
@{b}SENT@{ub} folders.  If the @{b}Edit...@{ub} menu item is selected, the message must
come from either the @{b}PENDING@{ub} or @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder.

You can always change the preferred type of message to one of the other
ones allowed by clicking on the appropriate message type.

The checkmarked menu items under the @{" Messages " link AEM-7300} menu (@{" Display Full Hdr " link AEM-7307},
@{" Fwd Body Txt Only " link AEM-7306}, and @{" Incl Hdr in Resp " link AEM-7308}) can effect how "Reply" and
"forward" messages are constructed.  The @{b}Incl Hdr in Resp@{ub} is the only
checkmarked item to effect "Reply" messages.  It's effect is described
below under quoting message text.

For forwarded messages, the normal minimum header information is, by
default, included (see @{b}Set Minimum Headers@{ub} under the @{" General Parameters " link AEM-4900}
page in the @{" Configuration Setup " link AEM-4200}).  If you want all the headers to be 
included in the forwarded message, checkmark the @{b}Display Full Hdr@{ub} item.
If you don't want any headers to be included checkmark the @{b}Fwd Body Txt
Only@{ub} item.  This will also prevent any attachments from the original
messages being included in the forwarded message.

@{b}Please Note:@{ub} If the fowarded message contains attachments and @{b}Fwd Body
Txt Only@{ub} is not checked, the full header will be sent in the forwarded
message regardless of the setting of the @{b}Display Full Hdr@{ub} item.

The radio button column on the right of the window is for the @{b}encoding
method@{ub} for the @{b}message body@{ub}.  Four items appear here:

    @{b}7-Bit
    8-Bit
    quoted-printable
    encoded binary@{ub}

@{b}The default is 8-bit@{ub}.  Some Internet gateways, however, can not handle
8-bit data - only 7-bit.  If this is the case with your situation, select
7-bit, or if your message contains characters above ASCII 128 (most
foriegn character sets have these types of characters), select
@{b}quoted-printable@{ub} or @{b}encoded binary@{ub}.

The @{b}quoted-printable@{ub} encoding is preferred in this instance.  You will
be able to read most of the raw message except for the extended character
set characters.  The @{b}encoded binary@{ub} encoding will encode the message in
@{b}BASE64@{ub} encoding which is totally un-readable in it's raw format.  @{b}AEMail@{ub},
however, is able to handle the translation of both @{b}quoted-printable@{ub} and
@{b}encoded binary@{ub} in the message body for both sending and receiving
messages.

If the message is a reply, the @{b}Quote Original Message Text@{ub} box will be
checked if you have selected this option in the @{" General Parameters " link AEM-4900} page of
the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.  You can un-check this box if you don't
want the original text quoted in the message (or check it, if the default 
action was not to include text).  For all other types of @{b}Compose windows@{ub}, 
this checkbox will be disabled.

The @{b}Quote Prefix:@{ub} string gadget will indicate what is to be placed in
front of each quoted line.  This, by default, is @{b}>@{ub}; however, you can add
whatever you like here (such as the person's initials followed by @{b}:@{ub} or
@{b}>@{ub}).  You can also permanently change this field with the @{" General Parameters " link AEM-4900}
page of the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

A @{b}Quote header:@{ub} will be placed on the line in front of the quoted
material.  Currently, the default header which will appear in the @{b}Quote
Header:@{ub} string gadget is:

    @{b}On &(week), &(date2), at &(time), &(name) wrote:@{ub}

The @{b}&@{ub} followed by a field name in parenthesis indicates substitution of
data from the original message headers.  The values that can be
substituted are:

    @{b}&(name)@{ub}     The @{b}Real Name@{ub} of the sender of the original
                message.  If the @{b}Real Name@{ub} is not available,
                the sender's @{b}UserID@{ub} will be used instead

    @{b}&(subject)@{ub}  The subject from the original message.  Any @{b}RE:@{ub}
                or @{b}(fwd)@{ub} will be stripped.

    @{b}&(week)@{ub}     The day of the week that the original message
                was sent.

    @{b}&(date)@{ub}     The date the original message was sent in the form
                @{i}dd mmm yyyy@{ui}, where @{i}dd@{ui} is the day of the month,
                @{i}mmm@{ui} is month in the form @{b}Jan, Feb, Mar,@{ub} etc, and
                @{i}yyyy@{ui} is the full 4 digit year.

    @{b}&(date1)@{ub}    Same as @{b}&(date)@{ub}.

    @{b}&(date2)@{ub}    The date in the form @{i}mmm dd, yyyy@{ui}.

    @{b}&(time)@{ub}     The time the original message was sent in the
                form @{i}hh:mm x@{ui}@{b}M@{ub} where @{i}hh@{ui} is the hour on a @{u}12 hour@{uu}
                clock, @{b}mm@{ub} is the minute, and @{i}x@{ui}@{b}M@{ub} is @{b}AM@{ub} or @{b}PM@{ub}.

    @{b}&(to)@{ub}       The email address the message was sent to.  For
                mailing lists this could be the name of the mailing
                list if that is what appeared in the @{b}To:@{ub} header.

The @{b}Quote Header@{ub} is designed to be modified by the user and can be
changed with the string gadget.  This change is only in effect for this
message, however.  You can permanently change the @{b}Quote Header@{ub} with the
@{" General Parameters " link AEM-4900} page of the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

Whether on not the quoted message's headers are to be included in the
quote is controlled by the @{" Incl Hdr in Resp " link AEM-7308} item under the @{" Messages main " link AEM-7300}
menu.  If this item is checked the @{b}Date@{ub}, @{b}To@{ub}, @{b}From:@{ub}, @{b}Reply To:@{ub}",
@{b}Subject:@{ub}, @{b}cc:@{ub}, and @{b}bcc:@{ub} headers will be displayed from the original
message.  If it is not checked, no header information will be included.

The amount of header information in the quoted message is also controlled
by the @{" Display Full Hdr " link AEM-7307} item in the @{b}Messages@{ub} menu.

The row of gadgets below the @{b}Quote Header:@{ub} is used to specify
characteristics of your signature file if you want one.  They work in
conjunction with the full path name of your @{b}current active signature file@{ub}
shown in the title bar of the @{b}Compose Message@{ub} window.

If a @{" signature file " link AEM-9160} is present, the @{b}Add Signature Block@{ub} box will be
checked and the path name of that signature file will appear in the title
bar.  If the @{b}signature@{ub} file is not present, this checkbox will be disabled.
The default signature file is @{b}AEMail:.signature@{ub}.  However, @{b}if you are a
@{u}registered@{uu} user@{ub}, you can change to any other signature file by clicking on
the @{b}[Select Signature]@{ub} gadget.  This will call up a file requester in
which you can select the appropriate file.  The file does not have to
exist; you can create it with the @{b}[Edit Signature]@{ub} gadget.

@{i}If you are an @{u}un-registered@{uu} user@{ui}, the @{b}[Select Signature]@{ub} button will be
ghosted and you can only use the standard @{b}AEMail:.signature@{ub} file.

If you want to create or edit the current selected signature file, you can
click on the @{b}[Edit Signature]@{ub} button.  This will call up your editor to
allow you to create or edit the selected @{b}signature@{ub} file.  After you have
edited or created your signature file in your editor, save the file and
exit from the editor.  This will return you to the @{b}COMPOSE MESSAGE window@{ub}
and the @{b}Add Signature Block@{ub} check box will now be enabled.

If you do not want the signature block placed at the end of your message,
uncheck the @{b}Add Signature Block@{ub} box.

@{b}Note:@{ub} if the message is being edited, the @{b}Add Signature Block@{ub} box @{b}WILL
NOT@{ub} be checked.  This is done to prevent two signature blocks being added
to the message.  However, rather than disable this item, it is left to
allow the user to add a signature block in the event one was not added to
the original message or you selected the @{b}new Message@{ub} radio button.

The @{b}[Add Attachments]@{ub} button brings up the @{" Add Attachments Requster " link AEM-8710}.  This
requester allows you to add one or multiple files as attachments to your
message.  You can bring up this requester at any time.  If it is brought up
a second time, the old attachment information will appear in the attachment
list.  You can add to this information or delete entries as you desire.

The @{b}[Compose/Edit Message]@{ub} gadget calls up the editor you specified in the
@{b}General Parameters@{ub} page of the @{b}Configuration Setup@{ub}.  If you are editing a
previously composed message, you will see that message in your editor
window.  You can make changes as appropriate.  Also, if you specified
@{b}Quote Original Message Text@{ub} you @{i}will@{ui} see the quoted text.  You can
delete and insert lines as appropriate.

One of the things you will @{b}NOT@{ub} see in the editor window are your message
headers or the @{b}signature block@{ub} unless it is an edited message.  The
@{b}signature block@{ub} is always added after you compose the message.  If this is
a @{b}new@{ub} message, you will see a blank editor screen when the editor is
first called.  Enter whatever text you wish to use in your editor's window
and then select @{b}Save@{ub} and @{b}Quit@{ub} from your editor's menus.  This will
return you to the @{b}Compose Message@{ub} window.

You will not be able to edit or add headers when you @{b}[Compose/Edit
Message]@{ub}.  If you need to add additional headers to a message you can use
the @{b}[Add Headers]@{ub} gadget to add the headers.  @{b}This feature is ONLY
available to registered users@{ub}.  Un-registered users will find this gadget
ghosted.

Clicking on the @{b}[Add Headers]@{ub} gadget will bring up the @{" Add Headers window " link AEM-8720}
which is very similar to the @{b}Information@{ub} window for a icon which is
called from the @{b}Workbench menus@{ub}.

At the bottom of the @{b}Compose Window@{ub} is a row of four action buttons as
follows:

 @{b}[Send Message Now] [Queue Message] [Save In Pending] [Cancel Message]@{ub}

If you decide that you do not want to compose a message after all,
click on the @{b}[Cancel Message]@{ub} button to exit the @{b}COMPOSE MESSAGE
window@{ub}.

Otherwise, if all the correct information has been added in the
@{b}COMPOSE MESSAGE window@{ub}, click on the appropriate action button
at the bottom of the window.  @{b}[Save In Pending]@{ub} will save your newly
created message in the @{b}PENDING@{ub} folder.  @{b}[Queue Message]@{ub} will place the
message in the @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder and @{b}[Send Message Now]@{ub} will send the message
provided that you are connected to you Internet Provider.  If you were
unsuccesful with sending the message, it will be stored in the @{b}QUEUED@{ub}
folder to allow you to immediately send the message when you re-connect to
your Internet Service Provider.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-8710 "AEMAIL WINDOWS/Compose Message Window/ADD ATTACHMENTS"

                        @{b}Add Attachments Requester@{ub}

When you click on the @{b}[ADD ATTACHMENTS]@{b} button on the @{" Compose Message " link AEM-8700},
Window, an @{b}Add Attachments Requester@{ub} will be displayed which looks like
this:


       @{b}=============================================================
       [o]  Add Attachments
       =============================================================

                     Filename: [                              ][REQ]
       Attachment Description: [                                   ]
         Content Type/SubType: [                                   ]
                               =====================================
                               | text/plain                      | |
                               | text/enriched                   | |
                               | text/richtext                   | |
                               =====================================
                     Encoding: |@|           Plain Text            |

        Mime Type/Sub-Type   FileName                 Encoding
       =============================================================
       |                                                         | |
       |                                                         | |
       |                                                         | |
       |                                                         | |
       =============================================================

       [  ADD ]         [DELETE]         [ APPLY ]         [CANCEL ]

       =============================================================@{ub}


The @{i}Filename@{ui} string gadget should contain the @{b}@{u}FULL@{uu} path name@{ub} and @{b}filename@{ub}
of the attachment.  Clicking on the @{b}[REQ]@{ub} gadget will bring up a file 
requester which will allow you to select the appropriate file.  The
filename portion of this string will be used as the "file=" parameter of 
the @{b}Content-Type@{ub} MIME header and as the "filename=" parameter of the 
@{b}Content-Disposition@{ub} MIME header.

The initial directory that is chosen for the file requester is the 
directory that was set up in the @{b}Add Attachment from Directory@{ub} string
gadget in @{" Configuration: Default Path Parameters " link AEM-4500}. If you are adding
multiple attachments to the message, clicking on @{b}[REQ]@{ub} will bring up
the last directory that you used.

If you enter a non-existant file, an error requester will be displayed
when you try to @{b}[ADD]@{ub} the file to the attachment list.

The @{i}Attachment Description@{ui} is an optional string gadget for entering a
description of the attachment.  If present, this string gadget will create
a @{b}Content-Description@{ub} MIME header.

@{i}Content Type/SubType@{ui} is a string gadget which contains the MIME @{b}Content
Type/Subtype@{ub} entry which will appear on the @{b}Content-Type@{ub} MIME header.
@{i}THIS IS A REQUIRED ENTRY UNLESS YOU ARE ADDING AN UUENCODED attachment.@{ui}
It is not used for UUENCODED attachments.

A scrolling list below this gadget is used to select an appropriate
@{b}type/sub-type@{ub}.  Predefined @{b}type/subtypes@{ub}, as defined in @{b}RFC 1341@{ub} and
@{b}RFC 1521@{ub}, are included in this list as follows:


        @{b}text/plain
        text/enriched
        text/richtext
        message/rfc822
        message/partial
        message/external-body
        multipart/mixed
        multipart/alternative
        multipart/digest
        multipart/parallel
        application/octet-stream
        application/postscript
        image/gif
        image/jpeg
        audio/basic
        video/mpeg@{ub}


Also added to this list will be any additional @{b}type/subtypes@{ub} added through
the @{" mailcap file " link AEM-9100} and any type/subtypes encountered when displaying 
attachments during @{b}THIS RUN OF AEMAIL@{ub}.  @{b}AEMail@{ub} has no way to remember
differing type/subtypes that it encounters unless they are included in the 
@{b}mailcap@{ub} file.

You can also add your own @{b}type/subtype@{ub} by directly entering it in the
@{i}Content Type/SubType@{ui} string gadget.  Unless the @{b}type/subtype@{ub} is well known
and published, you should pick one of the existing types (@{b}text/, message/,
application/, image/, audio/,@{ub} or @{b}video/@{ub}) and use a subtype beginning with 
"@{b}x-@{ub}".  As an example, you might want to define an IFF image (not part of
the mime published standard) as:


        @{b}image/x-iff@{ub}


It is suggested that you use a @{b}mailcap@{ub} entry for @{b}image/x-iff@{ub} to cause
it to permanently appear in the list of @{i}Content Type/Subtypes@{ui}.
Attachments must be in the format you select.  @{b}AEMail@{ub} will do no 
conversion.  As an example, if you select @{b}application/postscript@{ub}, the file
you attach should already be in postscript format.

Also, @{i}DO NOT use the follwing @{b}types/subtypes@{ub}:@{ui}


        @{b}message/partial
        message/external-body
        multipart/mixed
        multipart/alternative
        multipart/digest
        multipart/parallel@{ub}


All of the @{b}multipart@{ub} types are not supported except at the highest level
(specifying the initial attachment list), and this is done automatically
by the program.

The @{i}encoding@{ui} cycle gadget has four states as follows:


        @{b}Plain Text
        Quoted-Printable
        Encoded Binary
        UUENCODED@{ub}


Generally, @{b}Plain Text@{ub} should be used for:

        @{b}text/
        message/@{ub}

The exception to this is when the attachment contains characters outside
the range of ASCII 32 to ASCII 128 and you ISP can not handle 8-bit codes.
If the document you are attaching contains these characters (usually
present in documents using foriegn character sets), you should use
@{b}Quoted-Printable@{ub} or @{b}Encoded Binary@{ub} encoding.

Generally speaking @{b}Encoded Binary@{ub} should be used for the following
types:


        @{b}application/
        image/
        audio/
        video/@{ub}


@{b}UUENCODED@{ub} should be selected if you want the attachment to be in
UUENCODED format.  You can @{b}not@{ub} mix UUENCODED attachments with MIME
attachments!

When a @{i}type/subtype@{ui} is selected, the appropriate encoding format is
automatically selected.  Of course, you can change this with the cycle
gadget if there is a need.

Once all of the attributes for any particular attachment are selected,
click on the @{b}[ADD]@{ub} gadget to add the attachment to the attachment list.
If the @{i}Filename@{ui} field or @{i}Content Type/Subtype@{ui} field (other than for 
UUENCODED attachments) is blank an error requester will appear indicating
that you must have a valid entry in these fields.  As many attachments as
you want can be added to this list, but you can not mix MIME type
attachments with UUENCODED attachments.

If you wish to delete any particular gadget, select the attachment from
the list and click on @{b}[DELETE]@{ub}.  There is no way to modify attachment
attributes once they have been added to the list.  If you want to do this, 
first click on @{b}[DELETE]@{ub}, make the appropriate changes, and then click on
@{b}[ADD]@{ub}.

Once you are satisfied with your attachment list click on @{b}[APPLY]@{ub}. The
@{b}Add Attachments Requester@{ub} will disappear and the attachments will be
automatically added to your message after it is composed.

If you decide that you don't want to add attachments after all, click on
@{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} and the attachments will not be added when you compose your message.

Clicking on the @{b}Close Gadget@{ub} at the top of the window has the same effect
as if you clicked on @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub}.

If you are editing a message which has attachments and you select the
@{b}[ADD ATTACHMENTS]@{ub} button in the @{b}Compose Window@{ub} and then decide you do not
want to change the attachments you have previously added, you should click
on @{b}[APPLY]@{ub}.  Clicking on @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} at this point will bring up a special
warning requester which says:

             @{b}Continuing will delete all previous attachments
                   Use APPLY if you wish to keep them.

             [CONTINUE]                  [APPLY ATTACHMENTS]@{ub}

To keep the attachments you should click on @{b}[APPLY ATTACHMENTS]@{ub}.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-8720 "AEMAIL WINDOWS/Compose Message Window/ADD HEADERS"

                            @{b}Add Headers Window@{ub}

Clicking on the @{b}[Add Headers]@{ub} gadget in the @{b}Compose Message@{ub} window will
bring up the @{b}Add Headers window@{ub} which is very similar to the @{b}Information@{ub}
window for a icon which is called from the @{b}Workbench menus@{ub}.  The @{b}Add
Headers@{ub} window looks like this:

     @{b}|=============================================================|
     |[o]  Add Additional Headers                                  |
     |=============================================================|
     |                                                             |
     |         ====================================================|
     | Headers |                                                | ||
     |         |                                                | ||
     |         |                                                | ||
     |[ NEW  ] |                                                | ||
     |         ====================================================|
     |[DELETE] [                                                  ]|
     |                                                             |
     |     [ SAVE ]            [CLEAR ALL]              [CANCEL]   |
     |                                                             |
     |=============================================================|@{ub}

Your additional headers will appear in the scrolling list.  To add a
header to the list, click on @{b}[NEW]@{ub} and enter the complete header line in
the string gadget below the scrolling list.  @{i}Be sure and include the
header identifier as well as the header text.  To add this new header to
this list hit the @{b}[RETURN]@{ub} key.  To transfer a header to the string
gadget for editing or deleting it, click on the header line in the
scrolling list.  Clicking on @{b}[DELETE]@{ub} will then delete the header from the
list.  If you want to edit the header, make the changes you want and then
hit @{b}[RETURN]@{ub}.  When you are satisified with the headers you want to add,
click on @{b}[SAVE]@{ub} and the new headers will be saved and added to your
message.  @{b}[CLEAR ALL]@{ub} will clear all the headers from the list and
@{b}[CANCEL]@{ub} will cancel the operations.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-8730 "AEMAIL WINDOWS/Compose Message Window/MULTIPLE RECIPIENTS"

                        @{b}Multiple Recipient Window@{ub}

When the @{b}Compose Message@{ub} window first appears and if the message is a
replied message, the following requester will appear if the replied
message had @{b}To:@{ub} recipients other than yourself:


       @{b}|=========================================================|
       | Multiple Recipients                                     |
       |---------------------------------------------------------|
       |             The message you are replying to             |
       |                has other To: recipients.                |
       |              Do you want to send the reply              |
       |                                                         |
       | [o] to only the sender of the original message?         |
       | [ ] to all To: recipients of the original message?      |
       | [ ] cc: to all To: recipients of the original message?  |
       | [ ] bcc: to all To: recipients of the original message? |
       |                                                         |
       |                       [ Continue ]                      |
       |                                                         |
       |=========================================================|@{ub}

With this requester you can send the message you are composing to @{i}none@{ui} of
the other recipients, @{i}directly to@{ui} all the other recipients (in the @{b}To:@{ub}
line), @{i}as a cc@{ui} to all the recipients, or @{i}as a bcc@{ui} to all the other
recipients.

If there is a single recipient to the message and that recipient is the
same as either your @{b}From:@{ub} or @{b}Reply-To:@{ub} address, you will not see the
requester.  Also, when the list of recipients is transferred to the
appropriate address line in the Compose window, any address that is the
same as your @{b}From:@{ub} or @{b}Reply-To:@{ub} address will be stripped.  If you want
to send the message also to the @{b}From:@{ub} or @{b}Reply-To:@{ub} address you will have
to add the address yourself.

When you have selected the action you want, hit @{b}[Continue]@{ub} and the list of
@{b}To:@{ub} recipients will be transferred to the appropriate string gadget in
the @{b}Compose Message@{ub} window.

@{b}@{u}SPECIAL CONSIDERATION:@{uu}@{ub}  If the message you are replying to was received by
a version of @{b}AEMail@{ub} @{i}prior to 1.42@{ui}, you will not be able to transfer
recipients that @{i}extend beyond one line@{ui}.  You can solve this problem,
however, by saving the message you want to reply to to a file (using the
@{" export " link AEM-6050} function) and then reading it back into version 1.43 of @{b}AEMail@{ub}.
To read it back in using the @{" From Local File.. " link AEM-7401} menu item under the
@{" Retrieve Msgs " link AEM-7400} menu.

@{i}One point of warning@{ui}.  If the recipient of the original message was the
name of a @{b}list@{ub} rather than the name of an @{b}individual@{ub}, you will also see
this requester.  Unfortunately, there is no way to know that the recipient
name is a list name rather than an individual name.  In this event, you
should always select @{b}"to only the sender of the original message"@{ub} since
the list name is probably not a valid recipient.

If there were @{b}cc:@{ub}'s to the original message, you may also see the
following similar requester for sending to the @{b}cc:@{ub} recipients:

       @{b}|=========================================================|
       | Multiple Recipients                                     |
       |---------------------------------------------------------|
       |             The message you are replying to             |
       |             has one or more cc: recipients.             |
       |              Do you want to send the reply              |
       |                                                         |
       | [o] to only the sender of the original message?         |
       | [ ] to all cc: recipients of the original message?      |
       | [ ] cc: to all cc: recipients of the original message?  |
       | [ ] bcc: to all cc: recipients of the original message? |
       |                                                         |
       |                       [ Continue ]                      |
       |                                                         |
       |=========================================================|@{ub}

Again, after you have selected the action you want, hit @{b}[Continue]@{ub} and the
list of @{b}cc:@{ub} recipients will be transferred to the appropriate string gadget
in the @{b}Compose Message@{ub} window.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9000 "AEMAIL FILES"

                               @{b}AEMAIL Files@{ub}

The following are the various files used by @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  Normally, they all
reside in the user's mail directory with the exception of the
@{b}Configuration@{ub} file and the @{b}TCPLOG@{ub} file.  The configuration file for the
primary user of AEMail normally is called @{b}aemail.cnfg@{ub} and resides in the
@{b}S:@{ub}  directory although it can be named differently or reside anywhere.
Other user's configuration files must be called something different and
may also reside anywhere.  @{b}TCPLOG@{ub} file may reside in any directory
depending on the user's preference.

    @{" aemail.cnfg " link AEM-9110} file: @{i}Main AEMail Configuration file@{ui}
    @{" folder.config " link AEM-9130} file: @{i}configures folders@{ui}
    @{" [folder_name].config " link AEM-9140} file: @{i}configures message lists@{ui}
    @{" Message " link AEM-9170} files: @{i}each individual message@{ui}
    @{" .signature " link AEM-9160} file: @{i}your signature@{ui}
    @{" .addrbook " link AEM-9150} file: @{i}address book entries@{ui}
    @{" .headers " link AEM-9120} file: @{i}list of headers for minimum headers@{ui}
    @{" mailcap " link AEM-9100} file: @{i}used for displaying MIME attachments@{ui}
    @{" TCP Trace Log File (TCPLOG) " link AEM-9180}: @{i}transaction trace file@{ui}

The mail directory is the directory given in the @{" MAIL_DIR= " link AEM-4102} Tool Type and
you can change the name and location of the @{b}aemail.cnfg@{ub} file with the
@{" CONFIG= " link AEM-4119} Tool Type.

With the exception of the @{b}mailcap@{ub} file, you can begin @{b}AEMail@{ub} without any
of the other files being present.  They will be automatically created as
you process messages or do other @{b}AEMail@{ub} actions.

The @{b}mailcap@{ub} file, if used can be setup prior to executing @{b}AEMail@{ub} or it can
be created or modified using the Viewer Page of the Configuration Setup.
If the @{b}mailcap@{ub} file is setup outside the @{b}AEMail@{ub} environment it can be done
using any text editor.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9100 "AEMAIL FILES/mailcap"

                               @{b}mailcap file@{ub}

The @{b}mailcap@{ub} file is used to establish programs that should be executed to
display MIME attachments.  Use of this file allows @{b}AEMail@{ub} to use any
AmigaDOS operating system 2.1 or above.

The @{b}mailcap@{ub} file is a standard Internet file which is specified in RFC
(@{i}Request For Comment@{ui}) 1524.  Since it is standard, you can use a @{b}mailcap@{ub}
file that was created for another program that specified a display program
for the same media type.  If you use a @{b}mailcap@{ub} file created outside the
@{b}AEMail@{ub} environment it can be copied to the mail directory when @{b}AEMail@{ub} is
@{" installed " link AEM-3000} if you use the @{b}expert@{ub} level of the Install.

@{b}AEMail@{ub} only uses the two required fields of the RFC 1524 standard.  Other
fields are ignored at this time.

Each @{b}mailcap@{ub} file consists of entries that describe the proper handling of
one media type at the local site.  A @{b}mailcap@{ub} file consists of a sequence of
such individual entries separated by @{b}LINE FEEDS@{ub}.  Blank lines and lines
starting with '@{b}#@{ub}' are considered comments and are ignored.  Long entries
may be continued on multiple lines if the line to be continued ends with
a backslash character (@{b}'\'@{ub}).  In this event, mutiple lines are to treated
as a single @{b}mailcap@{ub} entry.  Note that for such "continued" lines, the
backslash must be the last character of the line to be continued.

Each @{b}mailcap@{ub} entry consists of a number of fields each separated by a
semicolon ('@{b};@{ub}').  The first two fields are required, and must occur in the
specified order.  The remaining fields are optional and may appear in any
order.  @{i}@{b}NOTE:@{ub} At this time @{b}AEMail@{ub} does not use these optional fields and
if they are present, ignores them.  Because of this, these optional fields
WILL NOT be discussed in this documentation.@{ui}

The general format of the @{b}mailcap@{ub} entry is:


    @{b}content type; view command [; ......] LINE FEED@{ub}


The first field is the @{i}@{u}content type@{uu}@{ui}, which indicates the type of data this
@{b}mailcap@{ub} entry describes how to handle.  It is to be matched against the
@{i}type/subtype@{ui} specification in the @{b}Content-Type@{ub} MIME header (see the
@{" Add Attachment Requester " link AEM-8710} which is part of the @{" Compose Message window " link AEM-8700}).

If the subtype is "@{b}*@{ub}", it is intended to match all subtypes of the named
content type.

Examples of the @{i}content type@{ui} field are:


    @{b}images/gif@{ub}


which is intended to match only the @{i}images/gif@{ui} @{b}type/subtype@{ub} whereas


    @{b}images/*@{ub}


matches all image types (@{i}images/gif, images/jpeg, etc@{ui}).

The second field, @{i}@{u}view command@{uu}@{ui}, is a specification of how the attachment
meeting the @{i}@{u}content type@{uu}@{ui} specification is viewed.  For any particular
operating system, this would indicate how the display program is called.
For @{b}AEMail@{ub} this would include the entire path name for calling the program
and any parameters that are needed on the command line.  A @{b}%s@{ub} is used to
indicate the substitution of the attachment name.  The entire entry should
be surrounded by quotes.  As an example:


    @{b}"sys:Utilities/multiview %s screen"@{ub}


would call MultiView, placing the displayed attachment on its own screen
(the @{i}@{b}screen@{ub}@{ui} parameter).

If you needed to have the display on the Workbench screen you can add the
keyword @{b}wb;@{ub} in front of the program path.  As an example, if you wanted
MultiView to open on a window on the Workbench screen, you could use:


    @{b}"wb;sys:Utilities/multiview %s"@{ub}


@{b}Note@{ub} the use of the quotes (@{b}"@{ub}) surrounding the parameter.  This is necessary
so that the @{b}mailcap@{ub} interpreter will be prevented from treating special
characters (such as @{b};@{ub}) as part of the @{b}mailcap@{ub} syntax.

Also note the absence of the @{i}@{b}screen@{ub}@{ui} keyword.  The above call would push
the Workbench screen to the front when MultiView was called and the Workbench
screen would be used for the MultiView window.  The only problem with this
is you would be limited to the number of colors and the resolution specified
for Workbench.  Some other programs, however, might only be able to open as
a window on the Workbench screen and would be hidden by the @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen
when those programs were called unless the @{b}wb;@{ub} parameter was specified.

An example of a complete @{b}mailcap@{ub} entry to use MultiView to display all images
would be:


    @{b}image/*; "sys:Utilities/multiview %s screen"@{ub}


Any @{b}image/@{ub} type, regardless of the subtype, would be displayed providing
there was an appropriate data type present for that image subtype.

A @{" sample mailcap file " link AEM-9101} is included with the archive which uses MultiView
for text, message, sound, image, and video files.  Since MultiView is a 3.x
program using datatypes, this @{b}mailcap@{ub} file will ONLY work with 3.x systems.
To make it work for 2.x systems, you would need to change the display programs
to your favorite programs that work with your system.  You might also have
to be specific as to the subtype for a specific display @{b}type/subtype@{ub}.  If you
@{" install " link AEM-3000} @{b}AEMail@{ub} on a 2.1 system using the provided installation script,
you will be able to create the @{b}mailcap@{ub} file provided you selected @{i}Expert@{ui}
mode for the installation "@{i}user mode@{ui}".


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9101 "AEMAIL FILES/mailcap sample file"
                          @{b}Sample @{i}mailcap@{ui} file@{ub}

@{i}This is the sample @{b}mailcap@{ub} file used for AmigaDos 3.x that uses @{b}MultiView@{ub}
as the display agent.  Please note the use of the @{u}screen@{uu} parameter which
tells @{b}MultiView@{ub} to open on it's own screen rather than the WorkBench
screen.  This allows the use of all colors in the image's palette.@{ui}


    @{b}text/*;  "sys:Utilities/multiview %s"
    message/*; "sys:Utilities/Multiview %s"
    image/*; "sys:Utilities/multiview %s screen"
    audio/*; "sys:Utilities/multiview %s screen"
    video/*; "sys:Utilities/multiview %s screen"@{ub}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9110 "AEMAIL FILES/aemail.cnfg"

                 @{b}General Configuration File (aemail.cnfg)@{ub}

The @{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub} file is the General Configuration file for your primary
user.  This file contains various configuration information including the
version and revision number of the @{b}AEMail@{ub} version that was last loaded.  A
special flag in this file indicates whether this file should take
precedence over the Tool Type entries.

You do not have to store this file in the @{b}S:@{ub} directory nor do you have to name
it @{b}"aemail.cnfg"@{ub}.  This is only the default name and location for this file.
With the use of the @{" CONFIG= " link AEM-4119} @{b}Tool Type@{ub} or the @{" config=  " link AEM-5200} parameter on the
shell call for @{b}AEMail@{ub}, you can rename the file and place it anywhere you
want.

Starting with @{b}AEMail version 1.13@{ub} you can also have multiple configuration
files.  This allows you to set up multiple configurations for different
users of @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  You can select which configuration you want through the
@{" Project/Configuration/Open " link AEM-7101} menu item or by executing an @{b}AEMail@{ub} user's
Project icon.  If you use the @{b}Project/Configuration/Open@{ub} menu to bring
in a different user's configuration file, @{i}that user must have the @{u}same@{uu}
mail directory as the previous user@{ui}.

If the configuration is never changed with the @{" Configuration Setup " link AEM-4200}, the
@{" Tool Type entries " link AEM-4100} will take precedence.  If either the @{b}[SAVE]@{ub} or @{b}[SAVE TO]@{ub}
gadgets in the @{b}Configuration Setup Window@{ub} is selected, or the
@{" Project/Configuration/Save " link AEM-7101} or @{" Project/Configuration/Save to " link AEM-7101} menu items
are selected, the @{b}General Configuration@{ub} file will always take precedence.

The @{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub} (or @{b}CONFIG=@{ub} Tool Type or @{b}config=@{ub} shell parameter) is
referred as your @{i}base configuration file@{ui}.  You can always return to the
@{i}base configuration@{ui} through the @{" Project/Configuration/Restore Default " link AEM-7101}
menu item.

If you display the @{b}AEMail General Configuration @{ub}file with a text editor,
you will find that not all portions of the file are readable as text.  The
only way you can create and update the @{b}general configuration@{ub} file is
through @{b}AEMail@{ub} itself.

As part of this file is your password stored in encrypted format.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9120 "AEMAIL FILES/.headers"

                                @{b}.headers@{ub}

The @{b}.headers@{ub} file provides a list of message headers.  Those that
you want displayed in the message as "minimum headers" are preceded
by an asterick (*); all other headers are preceded by a space.

The @{b}.headers@{ub} file may not be present.  If it is not, the following
are displayed as the "minimum headers":

    @{i}Date:
    From:
    Reply-To:
    To:
    cc:
    bcc:
    Subject:@{ui}

See the discussion on configuring minimum headers in the @{" General Parameters " link AEM-4900}
section of the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9130 "AEMAIL FILES/folder.config"

                            @{b}folder.config@{ub}

This file gives the general information about each of the folders including:

    @{b}Flags (@{i}long word, 4 bytes@{ui}):@{ub} general flags concerning this folder
    @{b}Name (@{i}9 bytes including ending NULL@{ui}):@{ub} short folder name
    @{b}Pen (@{i}1 byte@{ui}):@{ub} pen number for folder tab
    @{b}Sort Keys (@{i}8 bytes@{ui}):@{ub} the permanent sort keys for the folder
    @{b}Folder Description (@{i}string ending in LINE FEED@{ui}):@{ub} the folder
        description.  If this is a folder for one of the pre-set
        folders, this string will be empty (@{b}LINE FEED@{ub} only) unless
        the user has decided to change the folder description.
    @{b}Each Filter string@{ub} @{i}ending in a LINE FEED@{ui}.  Each string begins with 4
        bytes that provide filter parameters as follows:
            1 byte indicating the header to be searched
            2 bytes of flags
            1 byte indicating the compare criteria
    @{b}Three successive LINE FEEDS@{ub} ends each folder config entry.

For those fields that are strings:  if the field is empty there will be a
@{b}LINE FEED@{ub} with no data preceding it.  If filters have been specified, each
filter will have at least @{b}4 bytes@{ub} followed by the search arguement (if
present) and a @{b}LINE FEED@{ub}.

@{b}folder.config@{ub} files for versions prior to 1.40 can be read by @{b}AEMail@{ub}
version 1.40 or later.  However, once a filter has been added, earlier
versions can not properly read the version 1.40 or later @{b}folder.config@{ub}.
If no filters are added, earlier versions of @{b}AEMail@{ub} can still read the
@{b}folder.config@{ub} file.

@{i}It is suggested that you copy your current @{b}folder.config@{ub} file to
@{b}folder.config.old@{ub} before implementing @{b}AEMail@{ub} 1.40.@{ui}  The Install script
will do this for you with a prompt.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} if for some reason your @{b}folder.config@{ub} file becomes corrupted or is
accidently deleted, you can restore all of the folders and the messages
within them, providing a @{" [Folder_Name].config " link AEM-9140} file is present for the
folder, by doing the following:

        @{b}delete any current folder.config file (or rename it so it is
            no longer recognized).
        Run @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  Add any additional folders that you previously
            had added.  (INBOX, PENDING, QUEUED and SENT will automatically
            be created).  You must use the exact name you had previously
            used.
        The new folders will show 0 messages.
        Quit @{b}AEMail@{ub}.
        Re-Run @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  The new folders should now show the appropriate
            number of messages provided a valid @{i}Folder_Name@{ui}.config
            file was present for that folder.  The name of the new
            folder must exactly match the @{i}Folder_Name@{ui} in the
            @{i}Folder_Name@{ui}.config file.@{ub}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9140 "AEMAIL FILES/Folder_Name.config"

                       @{b}@{i}Folder_Name@{ui}.config@{ub}

For each of the folders that contain messages there will be a configuration
file which gives information on the messages in that folder.  The name of
the file will be the short folder name with "@{b}.config@{ub}" appended to it.

For this version of @{b}AEMail@{ub}, the @{b}@{i}Folder_Name@{ui}.config@{ub} file contains
the following information for each message in the folder:

    @{b}Message Flags (@{i}word, 2 bytes@{ui}):@{ub} Flags describing the message.
    @{b}File Code (@{i}long word, 4 bytes@{ui}):@{ub} this field is a binary field
        which is used to derive the file name for the @{" message file " link AEM-9170}
        itself.
    @{b}Message Size (@{i}long word, 4 bytes@{ui}):@{ub} size of message.
    @{b}Body Displacement (@{i}word, 2 bytes@{ui}):@{ub} the position where the
        body of the message starts.
    @{b}From (@{i}string ending in LINE FEED@{ui}):@{ub} the information in the
        @{b}From:@{ub} field in the message header.
    @{b}Subject (@{i}string ending in LINE FEED@{ui}):@{ub} the information in the
        @{b}Subject@{ub}: field in the message header.  The @{b}RE:@{ub} and @{b}FWD:@{ub}
        headings at the beginning of the Subject header are
        stripped, but indicated by flags in the @{i}Message Flags@{ui} field
        so that the exact subject field can be reconstructed.
    @{b}Date (@{i}string ending in LINE FEED@{ui}):@{ub} the information in the
        @{b}Date:@{ub} field in the message header.
    @{b}To (@{i}string ending in LINE FEED@{ui}):@{ub} the information in the
        @{b}To:@{ub} field in the message header.
    @{b}Reply-To (@{i}string ending in LINE FEED@{ui}):@{ub} the information in the
        @{b}Reply-To:@{ub} field in the message header.
    @{b}cc (@{i}string ending in LINE FEED@{ui}):@{ub} the information in the
        @{b}cc:@{ub} field in the message header.
    @{b}bcc (@{i}string ending in LINE FEED@{ui}):@{ub} the information in the
        bcc: field in the message header.

For those fields that are strings: if the field is empty, there will be a
@{b}LINE FEED@{ub} without any data preceding it.

@{b}@{u}NOTE:@{uu}@{ub}  For @{b}AEMail@{ub} versions @{i}prior to 1.42@{ui}, only the first header line of
any particular header type (ie, @{b}To:@{ub}, @{b}cc:@{ub}, etc.) was saved in the header
strings of the @{b}@{i}Folder_Name@{ui}.config file@{ub}.  For version 1.42 and later, the
complete header string is saved with all lines of the particular header
type.  @{i}Up to 4096 characters can be saved@{ui} (if there are that many lines
for a particular header type).

This is particularly important for messages that have multiple @{b}To:@{ub} or @{b}cc:@{ub}
recipients.  This means that the complete list of recipients can be
examined in @{" Filter " link AEM-5600} commands and also provides the capability to send
replys to @{" all the recipients " link AEM-8700} of a message.

This does create a problem, however, if the @{b}@{i}Folder_Name@{ui}.config@{ub} created
by Version 1.42 or later is read by a version of @{b}AEMail@{ub} prior to 1.42.
The Version 1.42 or later @{b}@{i}Folder_Name@{ui}.config@{ub} file that contains any
message that has long multiple recipient lists (more than one line) can
not be read correctly by versions prior to 1.42.  If you need to revert to
an earlier version of @{b}AEMail@{ub}, you can do the following:

With Version 1.42 or later, @{" export (save) " link AEM-6050} all messages with multiple
recipients that were read by 1.42 or later to a file.  You do not have to
worry about messages read by earlier versions.

@{" Delete " link AEM-6070} all of the messages you just saved.

Then, from the earlier version of @{b}AEMail@{ub}, @{" retrieve from file " link AEM-7401} the messages
you just saved.  The header lines will be truncated by the earlier
version.

The reverse is also possible.  Messages with multiple recipients read by
earlier versions will have their header data truncated.  You can @{b}export
(save)@{ub} the message to a file and then re-read it into @{b}AEMail@{ub} with all
header data intact.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9150 "AEMAIL FILES/.addrbook"

                           @{b}.addrbook@{ub}

This file provides address book information.  Each record looks like this:

    @{b}Version (@{i}word, 2 bytes@{ui}):@{ub} The address book version.  Prior to
        Version 1 of the address book, this and the following field
        did not exist.  The flag $8000 identifies this as a
        legitimate version field to distinguish the addess book
        file from version 0.  @{b}NOTE: The Address Book version is
        @{u}NOT@{uu} the same as the AEMail Version.@{ub}  The Address Book
        version only changes when the format of the Address Book
        changes.
    @{b}Flags (@{i}word, 2 bytes@{ui}):@{ub} Flags describing group actions.  In
        Version 0, the flags field was given in the high order byte
        of the count field which limited the group count to 255.
    @{b}Count (@{i}word, 2 bytes@{ui}):@{ub} If this field is zero, the entry is
        a single user entry.  If this field is greater that zero
        it represents a group entry and indicates the number of
        UserIDs in the group.
    @{b}Nickname (@{i}string ending in LINE FEED@{ui}):@{ub} the Nickname for this
        entry (both group or user).
    @{b}Real Name (@{i}string ending in LINE FEED@{ui}):@{ub} the Real Name for
        individual users or the group description for group
        entries.
    @{b}UserID (@{i}one or more strings ending in LINE FEEDS@{ui}):@{ub}  The number
        of UserID fields is determined by the count at the
        beginning of the record.  For individual users, this MUST
        be the UserID and Domain for that user.  For group users
        this can be a Nickname that points to the real user.

For a description of how entries in the address book can be created and
displayed see the @{" Address Book " link AEM-8500} window.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9160 "AEMAIL FILES/.signature"

                              @{b}.signature@{ub}

This is a flat ASCII file that contains the signature block that is to be
appended to any composed messages.  Each line of the signature block must
end in a @{b}LINE FEED@{ub}.

A facility is provided when composing messages to create and or edit this
signature block (see the @{" Compose Message " link AEM-8700} window description).

Starting with AEMail Version 1.20, multiple signature files can be used.
These signature files can be named whatever the user wishes and can be
placed wherever the user wishes (@{b}Registered Users @{u}ONLY@{uu}@{ub}).

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9170 "AEMAIL FILES/Messages"

                                 @{b}Messages@{ub}

Each message is stored as an individual file with a cryptic file name
generated from the File Code in the @{" [Folder_Name].config " link AEM-9140} file.  This name
begins with "@{b}AE@{ub}" and ends with "@{b}M@{ub}" with a number of numeric digits in
between.  The message is stored as a flat ASCII file as it is received
from the @{b}POP Server@{ub} with any @{b}CARRAGE RETURNS@{ub} in a @{b}CARRAGE RETURN/LINE FEED@{ub}
sequences stripped.  This follows the AMIGA format for ASCII files.

The complete message is stored along with any attachments as they were
orginally received.  Any particular message can be copied to a named file
anywhere in your system through the @{" SAVE MESSAGE TO FILE " link AEM-6050} command.  If
you have an off line program that can process a @{b}MIME@{ub} message or a message
with @{b}UUENCODED@{ub} attachments, you can use that program against this file to
extract the attachments or you can save that attachment directly with the
@{" Attachment Requester " link AEM-8610} in the @{" Message Display Window " link AEM-8600}.

If messages are left in the @{b}PENDING@{ub} or @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folders, two additional
files may be created when @{b}AEMail@{ub} terminates.  If attachments were added to
the message when it was created, a file with the same name as the message
file but with @{b}AT@{ub} appended to it will be created.  This file contains
information about the attachments.  A second file may be created if
additional headers were created.  This file has @{b}HD@{ub} appended to the
original message name.

Both of these files are deleted when @{b}AEMail@{ub} is loaded and the @{b}PENDING@{ub} and
@{b}QUEUED@{ub} message lists are created internally.  The files are re-created if
the messages remain in the @{b}PENDING@{ub} or @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folders when @{b}AEMail@{ub}
terminates.

@{b}PLEASE NOTE:@{ub} if the @{i}Folder_Name@{ui}.config file is deleted you will lose
all capability of retrieving your messages unless you have previously
copied them to named files.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9180 "AEMAIL FILES/TCPLOG"

                       @{b}TCP Trace Log File (TCPLOG)@{ub}

This file is present if you have specified

    @{b}TCPLOG=@{i}name-of-log-file@{ui}@{ub}

in the @{" Tool Types " link AEM-4100} parameters or named a @{b}TCP Logging File@{ub} in the
@{" Default Path Parameters " link AEM-4500} page of the @{" Configuration Setup Window " link AEM-4200}.  Since
@{i}name-of-log-file@{ui} should be the full path name of the log file, this file
may reside in any directory.  If there is no path name, the log file will
reside in you @{b}AEMail@{ub} program directory.

The @{b}TCP Trace Log File@{ub} traces every TCP transaction.  Each time @{b}AEMail@{ub} is
started the following record is written to the file:

    @{b}Logging Beginning at @{i}dd mmm yy hh:mm:ss@{ui}@{ub}

where @{i}dd@{ui} is the day of the week, @{i}mmm@{ui} is the month (Jan, Feb, Mar, etc),
@{i}yy@{ui} is the 2 digit year (97) and @{i}hh@{ui}, @{i}mm@{ui}, and @{i}ss@{ui} are the hour (24 hour
clock), minutes, and seconds.

Each logging record will consist of a 38 byte header and up to 82 bytes of
either descriptive information or actual data received or sent over the
TCP interface. The header consists of a 21 byte date/time stamp (@{i}@{b}dd mmm
yy hh:mm:ss@{ub}@{ui}) and a 16 byte routine name of the routine in @{b}AEMail@{ub} that called
the trace.

If data is displayed, instances of a @{b}CARRAGE RETURN@{ub} will be displayed as
@{b}<CR>@{ub} and of @{b}LINE FEEDS@{ub} as @{b}<LF>@{ub}.  If the data exceeds 82 bytes, @{b}<--->@{ub}
will be placed at the end of the line.

When @{b}AEMail@{ub} terminates, or the @{b}TCPLOG@{ub} file name is changed by the 
@{b}Default Path Parameters@{ub} page of the @{b}Configuration Setup@{ub}, the following
record is written to the file:


    @{b}Logging Ending at @{i}dd mmm yy hh:mm:ss@{ui}@{ub}


Each @{b}AEMail@{ub} session is stacked behind the previous one, so that any single
@{b}TCPLOG@{ub} file can become quite large.  Periodic purging of the file can occur
by deleting the @{b}TCPLOG@{ub} file in between sessions of @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  Also, a new file
is created when you change the name of the @{b}TCPLOG@{ub} file with the @{b}Configuration
Setup@{ub}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9400 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE"

                          @{b}AEMail ARexx Interface@{ub}

                               @{u}Introduction@{uu}

@{b}AEMail@{ub} has a very powerful set of @{b}ARexx@{ub} commands that can be used to
control @{b}AEMail@{ub} from external @{b}ARexx@{ub} scripts.  You can also execute @{b}ARexx@{ub}
scripts and AmigaDOS scripts from within @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

See @{" Synopsis of ARexx Commands " link AEM-9410} for a list of the @{b}AEMail ARexx@{ub} commands.

When you want to send commands from an @{b}ARexx@{ub} script to @{b}AEMail@{ub}, you must
tell @{b}ARexx@{ub} how to locate the @{b}AEMail ARexx@{ub} message port.  The @{b}AEMail ARexx@{ub}
Port Name is normally @{b}AEMAIL1@{ub}.  You can change this port name with the
use of the @{" AREXXPORT= " link AEM-4125} tool type.  The current @{b}Arexx Port Name@{ub} is shown
in the @{b}About@{ub} message obtained with the @{" About " link AEM-7104} item under the Project
Menu.

You tell @{b}ARexx@{ub} what the message port name for @{b}AEMail@{ub} is by using the @{b}ARexx@{ub}
@{b}ADDRESS@{ub} command in an @{b}ARexx@{ub} script like this:

    @{b}ADDRESS AEMAIL1@{ub}

If you call an @{b}ARexx@{ub} script from @{b}AEMail@{ub}, the @{b}ADDRESS@{ub} command is
automatically set to the @{b}AEMail ARexx@{ub} message port.

There are several ways you can execute an @{b}ARexx@{ub} script in @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  You can
use the @{" ARexx/DOS menu " link AEM-7600} items @{" Send AREXX/DOS Command... " link AEM-7106}
@{" Send Last Command " link AEM-7107} or, if a menu title has been assigned to the 
@{b}ARexx@{ub} script, by the @{" menu item " link AEM-7601} with that title.  You can also bind 
@{b}ARexx@{ub} scripts to a function key.  You can have up to 40 selections since 
the @{b}Shift, CTRL@{ub}, and @{b}ALT@{ub} keys can be used in conjunction with the function 
keys.  When you press the appropriate function key the @{b}ARexx@{ub} script bonded
to it will be executed.

@{" Two event exits " link AEM-5800} have also been provided which can have ARexx scripts
executed when you double click on a web address or an email address in a
message.

Setting the menu title, the event exits, or the function key assigned to
the command is done with the @{" ARexx Page " link AEM-4700} of the @{" Configuration Setup " link AEM-4200}

After each command directed at @{b}AEMail@{ub} from an @{b}ARexx@{ub} script is executed,
the standard @{b}ARexx@{ub} result variable, @{b}RC@{ub}, will report the success or failure
of the command.  A @{b}0@{ub} in @{b}RC@{ub} indicates that the command was understood and
executed successfully.  An @{b}RC@{ub} value other than @{b}0@{ub} indicates an error
severity indicator.  The exact error text is reported in the @{b}ARexx@{ub}
@{b}AEMAIL.LASTERROR@{ub} variable.

All of the @{b}AEMail ARexx@{ub} commands also report back information if they
were executed successfully (@{b}RC = 0@{ub}).  This information is reported in the
@{b}ARexx@{ub} variable @{b}RESULT@{ub}.  To receive this information you must supply the
following @{b}ARexx@{ub} command at the beginning of the @{b}ARexx@{ub} script:

    @{b}OPTIONS RESULTS@{ub}

You will notice that some commands have possible negative numbers for
@{b}RESULT@{ub} values.  The @{b}RESULT@{ub} variable usually returns either a numeric value
or a string.  If a numeric value is returned and if it is positive and
above zero, the expected result was achieved.  If the value was 0 or
negative, the expected result was not achieved.  Some commands that
normally return strings in the @{b}RESULT@{ub} variable may also return a NULL
string or a negative numeric value.  The negative numeric value is used to
denote various reasons the string value was not returned.  If there is
only one reason, the command will normally return a "0" or a NULL value;
but if there is more than one reason, the additional reasons will be
indicated with a negative number.  An example would be a command that is
expected to return the Subject:  from the current message.  A result of
NULL or blank indicates that there was no Subject:  header and a result of
"-1" indicates that there is no current message.  These two conditions
need to be distinguished.

A list of the currently available @{b}AEMail ARexx@{ub} commands is given under the
@{" Synopsis of ARexx Commands " link AEM-9410}.  Each command is linked to a description of
that command.  @{b}Many of the commands are available to registered users
only.@{ub}  These will be so noted in the command list.

Some of the commands are composed of multiple words.  To avoid confusion
these multiple words are sometimes separated by an underline character
(@{b}_@{ub}).  As an example @{b}ADDRESS_BOOK@{ub} separates @{b}ADDRESS@{ub} and @{b}BOOK@{ub} with the
underline.  This is to avoid confusion with @{b}ADDRESS@{ub} which is a standard
@{b}ARexx@{ub} command.  If an underline is required, it will be shown in the
command syntax.

@{b}QUOTING:@{ub}  Some command have parameters with embedded @{b}ARexx@{ub} command
characters such as @{b}+, -, |,@{ub} etc.  To avoid the possibilty of @{b}ARexx@{ub}
interpreting these as @{b}ARexx@{ub} operations, the parameter should be surrounded
by quotes (either single or double quotes).  An example of where this is
very important is the first parameter of the @{" OKAY2 " link AEM-9520} command.  Each of the
possible responses in the @{b}OKAY2@{ub} command is separated by a vertical bar
(@{b}|@{ub}) such as @{b}"OK|CANCEL"@{ub}.  The entire response parameter needs to be
surrounded in quotes as shown or otherwise the vertical bar will be
intrepreted by @{b}ARexx@{ub} as an "inclusive or" operation.

Another condition requiring quoting is passing strings with embedded
spaces.  This usually requires a bit of "creative" quoting because @{b}ARexx@{ub}
always strips at least one set of quotation marks from all strings.
Fortunately @{b}ARexx@{ub} considers both the double quote (") and the single quote
(') as quotes.  To provide for the proper treatment of strings with
embedded spaces (such as some file and path names or title strings), you
have to use a double grouping of quotes.

For example:

    @{b}GETFILENAME '"The Title String"' '"A file name path"'@{ub}

will send @{b}"The Title String"@{ub} and @{b}"A file name path"@{ub} to @{b}AEMail@{ub} which will
recognize these strings as two quoted operands.

@{b}ARexx@{ub} variables which might have embedded spaces in their contents must
also be quoted as above.  You can do this as follows:

    @{b}filename = "A file name path"
    title = "The Title String"
    GETFILENAME '"'title'"' '"'filename'"'@{ub}

This ensures that @{b}ARexx@{ub}, when it strips off a set of quotation marks and
replaces the variables with their contents, will also pass a set of
quotation marks around the resulting strings.  @{b}AEMail@{ub} will then recognize
the passed strings as two string operands rather than many unconnected
words.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9410 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command Synopsis"
                        @{b}Synopsis of ARexx Commands@{ub}

The following is a list of the currently available @{b}AEMail ARexx@{ub} commands.
This list also indicates which commands are only available to registered
users with an @{b}(R)@{ub} following the command.

A complete description of of each command and the command variations
can be obtained by clicking on the command in this list.

Shown with each command description is what you can expect to have
returned in the @{b}RESULT@{ub} variable.  Please note the use of the @{" OKAY1 " link AEM-9519} and
@{" OKAY2 " link AEM-9520} commands.  You can use these to report back information to the
@{b}AEMail@{ub} user.  These commands put up a requester with the information you
provide.

You will also notice in the command descriptions the use of the term
@{b}current message@{ub}.  This applies to @{b}ARexx@{ub} commands only and is not the
@{b}selected message@{ub} that is indicated by an asterick (@{ub}*@{b}) in the displayed
message list; although, you can make the most recent (current) @{b}selected
message@{ub} the @{b}current message@{ub} (see the @{" CURRENT IS SELECTED " link AEM-9504} command below)
and you can @{b}select" a current message (the @{" MESSAGE SELECT " link AEM-9517} command).
Initially @{b}current message@{ub} is un-defined, but once it is defined it will
remain defined through multiple calls from @{b}ARexx@{ub} scripts until @{b}AEMail@{ub}
terminates or the @{b}current message@{ub} is changed through the use of another
@{b}ARexx@{ub} command.

@{" ADDRESS_BOOK " link AEM-9500} @{b}(R)@{ub}    Manipulates the @{b}AEMail@{ub} Address Book
@{" BCC " link AEM-9501} @{b}(R)@{ub}             Returns the BCC header in a message
@{" CC " link AEM-9502} @{b}(R)@{ub}              Returns the CC header in a message
@{" COMPOSE " link AEM-9503}             Composes a message
@{" CURRENT IS SELECTED " link AEM-9504} Makes the selected message current
@{" DATE " link AEM-9505} @{b}(R)@{ub}            Returns the DATE header in a message
@{" EXTRACT " link AEM-9506} @{b}(R)@{ub}         Parses a name string to real name or email address
@{" FIRST " link AEM-9507} @{b}(R)@{ub}           Selects first message in folder or name in name string
@{" FLAGS " link AEM-9508} @{b}(R)@{ub}           Returns the flags in a message
@{" FOLDER " link AEM-9509} @{b}(R)@{ub}          Returns information on folders
@{" FROM " link AEM-9510} @{b}(R)@{ub}            Returns the FROM header in a message
@{" GETCLIP " link AEM-9511} @{b}(R)@{ub}         Get a clip from the clipboard
@{" GETFILENAME " link AEM-9512}         Brings up the @{b}AEMail@{ub} file requester
@{" GETLISTITEM " link AEM-9529}         Brings up the AEMail list view requester
@{" GETNUMBER " link AEM-9513}           Brings up the @{b}AEMail@{ub} numeric requester
@{" GETSIZE " link AEM-9514} @{b}(R)@{ub}         Returns the size of a message or message body
@{" GETSTRING " link AEM-9515}           Brings up the @{b}AEMail@{ub} string requester
@{" GETVAR " link AEM-9530}              Gets a variable from message
@{" LAST " link AEM-9516} @{b}(R)@{ub}            Selects last message in a folder
@{" MESSAGE " link AEM-9517} @{b}(R)@{ub}         Sets various flags in a message
@{" NEXT " link AEM-9518} @{b}(R)@{ub}            Selects next message in folder or name in name string
@{" OKAY1 " link AEM-9519}               Brings up @{b}AEMail@{ub} notification requester
@{" OKAY2 " link AEM-9520}               Brings up @{b}AEMail@{ub} notification requester with responses
@{" PREVIOUS " link AEM-9521} @{b}(R)@{ub}        Selects the previous message in a folder
@{" QUEUE " link AEM-9522}               Queues a passed message
@{" QUIT " link AEM-9531}                Terminates AEMail
@{" REPLYTO " link AEM-9523} @{b}(R)@{ub}         Returns the REPLY-TO header in a message
@{" SAVE " link AEM-9524} @{b}(R)@{ub}            Saves a message or message text
@{" SCREENTOBACK " link AEM-9525}        Brings a screen to the back of the display
@{" SCREENTOFRONT " link AEM-9526}       Brings a screen to the front of the display
@{" SUBJECT " link AEM-9527} @{b}(R)@{ub}         Returns the SUBJECT header in a message
@{" TO " link AEM-9528} @{b}(R)@{ub}              Returns the TO header in a message

When a command returns an @{b}RC@{ub} value other than @{b}0@{ub}, @{b}AEMAIL.LASTERROR@{ub} will
contain an @{" error message " link AEM-9600}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9500 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: ADDRESS_BOOK"

                               @{b}ADDRESS_BOOK@{ub}

This command is used to manipulate the @{b}AEMail@{ub} @{" Address Book " link AEM-8500}.  There are a
number of variations of the @{b}ADDRESS_BOOK@{ub} command.  They are listed below.
If the correct command keyword (@{b}LIST, FIND, ADD@{ub}, etc.) is not
present, an @{b}RC@{ub} code of severity level 5 will be returned and
@{b}AEMAIL.LASTERROR@{ub} will contain @{" 101:  Syntax Error " link AEM-9600}.

Note the use of the parameter called @{b}@{i}userid@{ui}@{ub}.  This can be either an
email address or a referenced nickname pointing to another individual or
group entry.  When a @{i}userid@{ui} is returned, you can test if it is a nickname
by using the @{b}ADDRESS_BOOK GET @{i}nickname@{ui} TYPE@{ub} command.

***

@{b}Syntax: ADDRESS_BOOK LIST ALL [DESCRIPTION] [@{i}pad@{ui}]
        ADDRESS_BOOK LIST GROUP [DESCRIPTION] [@{i}pad@{ui}]
        ADDRESS_BOOK LIST INDIVIDUAL [DESCRIPTION] [@{i}pad@{ui}]

This command will list the nicknames in your address book.  The operand
@{b}ALL@{ub} will list all of the nicknames, the operand @{b}GROUP@{ub} will list just
the group nicknames, and @{b}INDIVIDUAL@{ub} will list just the individual
nicknames.

The optional keyword @{b}DESCRIPTION@{ub} can be used to also return the
@{b}Description@{ub} or @{b}Real Name@{ub} field following the nickname.  In this event the
nickname will be padded out with spaces so that so that it will be a fixed
length of 11 characters (always ending with at least one space).  This
means that the description field will always start in a fixed position.

Normally each nickname is separated by a space.  However, this can be
changed by a specifying a @{i}pad@{ui} string at the end of the command.  You can
use the @{b}LF@{ub} keyword to specify a line feed or use some other character
sequence for the @{i}pad@{ui} string.  As an example:  @{b}", "@{ub} will insert a comma
followed by a space between each nickname in the list.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} The list of nicknames separated by the @{i}pad@{ui} string.

***

@{b}Syntax: ADDRESS_BOOK FIND @{i}nickname@{ui}
        ADDRESS_BOOK FIND @{i}nickname@{ui} @{i}userid@{ui}@{ub}

This command is used to find out if a particular @{i}userid@{ui} (email address or
referenced @{i}nickname@{ui}) is contained in a group entry in the Address Book.
You can explicity give the userid or the email address can be obtained
from the @{b}Current Message@{ub}.  If the @{i}userid@{ui} is not specified, both the From:
and Reply-To:  addresses from the current message will be used to check if
the email address is in the group entry specified by @{i}nickname@{ui}.  The
@{i}nickname@{ui} operand is required and must be a group nickname.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -3          No current message if userid not given
        -2          The @{i}nickname@{ui} is not for a group entry in the Address
                    Book
        -1          The @{i}nickname@{ui} given is not in the Address Book.
        0           The @{i}userid@{ui} was not found
        1           The @{i}userid@{ui} found.  If not supplied, the userid that
                    was found was an email address from the From: address
                    in the current message.
        2           The Reply-To: address in the current message was found
                    in the group.
        3           Both the Reply-To: and From: addresses were found.
                    @{b}Note:@{ub} @{i}these addresses may actually be the same.@{ui}

***

@{b}Syntax: ADDRESS_BOOK CREATE GROUP @{i}nickname@{ui} ["SEND-HEADER-ONLY"|SHO],
            FROM|REPLYTO|@{i}userid@{ui} @{i}description@{ui}@{ub}

This entry creates a new group entry in the Address Book.  When you create
a group entry you must have one @{i}userid@{ui} (email address or referenced
nickname) entry to place in the group.  You are not allowed to have a
group without any entries.

The @{i}nickname@{ui} for the new group must be supplied and it must not be greater
than 9 characters.  It can not, of course, match any existing nickname.

@{b}"SEND-HEADER-ONLY"@{ub} is an optional keyword operand which sets the "Send
Header Only" flag in the group entry and must be quoted.  You can use the
shorthand abreviation @{b}SHO@{ub} instead of the full @{b}"SEND-HEADER-ONLY"@{ub} string.

The @{i}userid@{ui} which is added can be explicity specified or it can be the
email address taken from either the From:  or Reply-To:  address in the
@{b}Current Message@{ub}.  Use the keyword operands @{b}FROM@{ub} or @{b}REPLYTO@{ub} to specify
which header field in the current message is to be used.  If you specify
@{b}REPLYTO@{ub} and that header is missing, an error condition will be returned
(@{i}see below@{ui}).

There is no validation performed on the @{i}userid@{ui}.  If it is an email
address it should be one word without any intervening spaces.  It should
be within a quoted string to avoid confusion with ARexx special symbols.
If it is a nickname with embedded spaces it must be double quoted (two
pairs of quotation marks - ie, @{b}'"........"'@{ub}.

The @{i}description@{ui} operand is placed in the @{b}Real Name@{ub} field in the Address
Book entry and must be given.  It may have embedded spaces and should be
quoted.  If you want quotes to appear in the group description you should
use the ARexx method for including embedded quotes (i.e.,
@{b}'"....string...."'@{ub} or @{b}'"'@{i}variable@{ui}'"'@{ub}.


@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -4          The @{b}REPLYTO@{ub} operand was specified and there is no
                    Reply-To: header in the current message.
        -3          No current message if @{i}userid@{ui} not given
        -1          The @{i}nickname@{ui} given is greater than 9 characters.
        0           The @{i}nickname@{ui} given was already defined in the Address
                    Book.
        1           The group entry was successfully created.

***

@{b}Syntax: ADDRESS_BOOK ADD TO GROUP @{i}nickname@{ui} FROM
        ADDRESS_BOOK ADD TO GROUP @{i}nickname@{ui} REPLYTO
        ADDRESS_BOOK ADD TO GROUP @{i}nickname userid@{ui}@{ub}

This command adds an userid (email address or referenced nickname) to an
existing group in the Address Book.  The @{i}nickname@{ui} operand specifies the
group the userid is to be added to and is a required parameter.

The userid which is added can be explicity specified or it can be the
email address taken from either the From:  or Reply-To:  address in the
@{b}Current Message@{ub}.  Use the keyword operands @{b}FROM@{ub} or @{b}REPLYTO@{ub} to specify
which header field in the current message is to be used.  If you specify
@{b}REPLYTO@{ub} and that header is missing, an error condition will be returned
(@{i}see below@{ui}).

There is no validation performed on the @{i}userid@{ui}.  If it is an email
address it should be one word without any intervening spaces.  It should
be within a quoted string to avoid confusion with @{b}ARexx@{ub} special symbols.
If it is a nickname with embedded spaces it must be double quoted (two
pairs of quote marks - ie, @{b}'"........"'@{ub}.


@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -4          The @{b}REPLYTO@{ub} operand was specified and there is no
                    Reply-To: header in the current message.
        -3          No current message if @{i}userid@{ui} not specified.
        -2          The @{i}nickname@{ui} is not for a group entry in the Address
                    Book
        -1          The @{i}nickname@{ui} given was not found.
        0           The @{i}userid@{ui} given was already defined in the group.
        1           The @{i}userid@{ui} was successfully added to the group.


***

@{b}Syntax: ADDRESS_BOOK ADD INDIVIDUAL @{i}nickname@{ui} FROM [@{i}real-name@{ui}]
        ADDRESS_BOOK ADD INDIVIDUAL @{i}nickname@{ui} REPLYTO [@{i}real-name@{ui}]
        ADDRESS_BOOK ADD INDIVIDUAL @{i}nickname userid@{ui} [@{i}real-name@{ui}]@{ub}

This command adds a new individual nickname to the Address Book.  The
@{i}nickname@{ui} for the new group must be supplied and it must not be greater
than 9 characters.  It can not, of course, match any existing nickname.

The userid which is assign to the new nickname is required and can be
explicity specified or it can be the email address taken from either the
From:  or Reply-To:  header in the @{b}Current Message@{ub}.  Use the keyword
operands @{b}FROM@{ub} or @{b}REPLYTO@{ub} to specify which header field in the @{b}Current
Message@{ub} is to be used.  If you specify @{b}REPLYTO@{ub} and that header is
missing, an error condition will be returned (@{i}see below@{ui}).

There is no validation performed on the user_id.  If it is an email
address it should be one word without any intervening spaces.  It should
be within a quoted string to avoid confusion with ARexx special symbols.
If it is a nickname with embedded spaces it must be double quoted (two
pairs of quote marks - ie, @{b}'"........"'@{ub}.

The @{i}real-name@{ui} operand is placed in the "Real Name" field in the Address
Book entry.  It is an optional entry.  It may have intervening spaces.  It
should be quoted.  If you want quotes to appear in the group description
you should use the ARexx method for including embedded quotes (i.e.,
@{b}'"....@{i}string@{ui}...."'@{ub} or @{b}'"'@{ub}@{i}variable@{ui}@{b}'"'@{ub}.

If a current message is used to obtain the userid (either the @{b}FROM@{ub} or
@{b}REPLYTO@{ub} keyword operands) any real name supplied with the header will
take precedence over the real-name operand if it is present.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -4          The @{b}REPLYTO@{ub} operand was specified and there is no
                    Reply-To: header in the current message.
        -3          No current message if @{i}userid@{ui} not specified.
        -1          The @{i}nickname@{ui} given is greater than 9 characters.
        0           The @{i}nickname@{ui} given was already defined.
        1           The @{i}nickname@{ui} and @{i}userid@{ui} was successfully added to the
                    Address Book.

***

@{b}Syntax: ADDRESS_BOOK DELETE FROM GROUP @{i}nickname@{ui} FROM
        ADDRESS_BOOK DELETE FROM GROUP @{i}nickname@{ui} REPLYTO
        ADDRESS_BOOK DELETE FROM GROUP @{i}nickname userid@{ui}@{ub}

This command deletes a userid from the group indicated by @{i}nickname@{ui}.

The @{i}userid@{ui} which is to be deleted is required and can be explicity
specified or it can be the email address taken from either the From:  or
Reply-To:  address in the @{b}Current Message@{ub}.  Use the keyword operands
@{b}FROM@{ub} or @{b}REPLYTO@{ub} to specify which header field in the @{b}Current Message@{ub}
is to be used.  If you specify @{b}REPLYTO@{ub} and that header is missing, an
error condition will be returned (@{i}see below@{ui}).

There is no validation performed on the user_id.  If it is an email
address it should be one word without any intervening spaces.  It should
be within a quoted string to avoid confusion with ARexx special symbols.
If it is a nickname with embedded spaces it must be double quoted (two
pairs of quote marks - ie, @{b}'"........"'@{ub}.

If the userid is the only userid in the group, it will not be deleted.
No group can exist without at lease one userid.  In this special case a
RESULT code of -5 will be returned.  To delete the one remaining userid
you must delete the entire group (see "ADDRESS-BOOK DELETE GROUP" below.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -5          The userid specified was the only userid in the
                    group and WAS NOT DELETED.  Use the @{b}ADDRESS_BOOK
                    DELETE GROUP@{ub} command to delete entire group.
        -4          The @{b}REPLYTO@{ub} operand was specified and there is no
                    Reply-To: header in the current message.
        -3          No current message if @{i}userid@{ui} not specified.
        -2          The @{i}nickname@{ui} is not for a group entry in the Address
                    Book
        -1          The @{i}nickname@{ui} given was not found.
        0           The userid was not present in the group.
        1           The userid was deleted from the group.

***

@{b}Syntax: ADDRESS_BOOK DELETE GROUP @{i}nickname@{ui}@{ub}

This command deletes the entire group specified by @{i}nickname@{ui} and all of
it's associated userids.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -2          The @{i}nickname@{ui} given is not for a group entry in the
                    Address Book
        -1          The @{i}nickname@{ui} given was not found.

        1           The group was successfully deleted.

***

@{b}Syntax: ADDRESS_BOOK DELETE INDIVIDUAL @{i}nickname@{ui}@{ub}

This command deletes the @{i}nickname@{ui} provided.  It must be the nickname for
an individual.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -2          The @{i}nickname@{ui} given is for a group entry in the
                    Address Book.  No deletion was performed.
        0           The individual's @{i}nickname@{ui} was not present.
        1           The individual's @{i}nickname@{ui} was successfully deleted.

***

@{b}Syntax: ADDRESS_BOOK GET @{i}nickname@{ui} TYPE@{ub}

This command obtains the type (group or individual) for the Address Book
entry specified by @{i}nickname@{ui}.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1          The @{i}nickname@{ui} given does not exist.
         0          The @{i}nickname@{ui} was for an individual entry.
         1          The @{i}nickname@{ui} was for a group entry.

***

@{b}Syntax: ADDRESS_BOOK GET @{i}nickname@{ui} REALNAME@{ub}

This command obtains the "Real Name" or Group Description for the Address
Book entry specified by @{i}nickname@{ui}.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1              The @{i}nickname@{ui} given does not exist.
         NULL or blank  No real name was present.
         "Real Name" or group description string

***

@{b}Syntax: ADDRESS_BOOK GET @{i}nickname@{ui} USERID@{ub}

This command obtains the userid for the Address Book entry specified by
@{i}nickname@{ui}.  This command can only be used with Individual nicknames.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -2          The nickname given is not for an individual entry.
        -1          The nickname given does not exist.
         @{i}userid@{ui}    This may be either an email address or a referenced
                    nickname.  Use the ADDRESS_BOOK GET nickname TYPE
                    command to determine if it is a nickname rather than
                    an email address.

***

@{b}Syntax: ADDRESS_BOOK GET @{i}nickname@{ui} FIRST USERID@{ub}

This command obtains the first userid for the Address Book group entry
specified by @{i}nickname@{ui}.  This command can only be used with Group
nicknames.

This command must be issued before the @{b}GET NEXT USERID@{ub} command described
below is issued.  When this command is issued it resets the group for
which you are attempting to obtain userids.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -2          The nickname given is not for a group entry.
        -1          The nickname given does not exist.
         @{i}userid@{ui}     This may be either an email address or a referenced
                    nickname.  Use the ADDRESS_BOOK GET nickname TYPE
                    command to determine if it is a nickname rather than
                    an email address.

***

@{b}Syntax: ADDRESS_BOOK GET @{i}nickname@{ui} NEXT USERID@{ub}

This command obtains the next userid for the Address Book group entry
specified by @{i}nickname@{ui}.  This command can only be used with Group
nicknames.

A @{b}GET @{i}nickname@{ui} FIRST USERID@{ub} command must be issued for the same nickname
before the a @{b}GET @{i}nickname@{ui} NEXT USERID@{ub} command is issued.  This command
will continue to get userids for the @{i}nickname@{ui} until a @{b}NULL@{ub} is received
which signifies the end of list of userids for the group.  If you continue
to try to issue @{b}NEXT USERID@{ub} commands after the last userid is obtained you
will get an error result as shown below.

RESULT: -3          A prior FIRST USERID command was not issued for this
                    group nickname.
        -2          The nickname given is not for a group entry.
        -1          The nickname given does not exist OR you have issued
                    the NEXT USERID command after the last one was
                    obtained.
         @{i}userid@{ui}     This may be either an email address or a referenced
                    nickname.  Use the ADDRESS_BOOK GET nickname TYPE
                    command to determine if it is a nickname rather than
                    an email address.
         NULL       There are no more userids in the group.

***

@{b}Syntax: ADDRESS_BOOK GET @{i}nickname@{ui} "SEND-HEADER-ONLY-FLAG"|"SHO-FLAG"@{ub}

This command obtains the state of the "Send Header Only" flag for the
group entry specified by @{i}nickname@{ui}.  The operand can be specified as
either @{b}"SEND-HEADER-ONLY-FLAG"@{ub} or @{b}"SHO-FLAG"@{ub} and must be quoted.  This
command can only be used with Group nicknames.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -2          The @{i}nickname@{ui} given was not for a group entry.
        -1          The @{i}nickname@{ui} given does not exist.
         0          The "Send Header Only" Flag was @{b}OFF@{ub}.
         1          The "Send Header Only" Flag was @{b}ON@{ub}.

***

@{b}Syntax: ADDRESS_BOOK GET @{i}nickname@{ui} COUNT@{ub}

This command obtains the count of userid entries in the group entry
specified by @{i}nickname@{ui}.  This command is can only be used with Group
nicknames.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -2          The @{i}nickname@{ui} given was not for a group entry.
        -1          The @{i}nickname@{ui} given does not exist.

         @{i}n@{ui}          The count of userids in the group entry.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9501 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: BCC"

                                   @{b}BCC@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: BCC@{ub}

This command returns the bcc:  header of the @{b}Current Message@{ub} without the
bcc:.  It has no operands.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1              No current message
        NULL or blanks  No bcc: header
        bcc: header



@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9502 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: CC"

                                    @{b}CC@{ub}


@{b}Syntax: CC@{ub}

This command returns the cc:  header of the @{b}Current Message@{ub} without the
cc:.  It has no operands.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1              No current message
        NULL or blanks  No cc: header
        cc: header


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9503 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: COMPOSE"

                                 @{b}COMPOSE@{ub}

All of the variations of the @{b}COMPOSE@{ub} command bring up the @{b}AEMail@{ub} @{" compose " link AEM-8700}
window for further action.  If for any reason the Compose window returns
any error such as the failure to open the Compose window or an out of
memory condition, the error will be returned in @{b}AEMAIL.LASTERROR@{ub} with the
RC set to a severity level of 20.  This error will not have an error
number associated with it.

The syntax of the various variations of the @{b}COMPOSE@{ub} command are as
follows:

***

@{b}Syntax: COMPOSE@{ub}

The @{b}COMPOSE@{ub} command without any operands brings up the Compose window to
compose a new message.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} 0:          User canceled message compose.  No message composed.
        1:          Message composed and placed in @{b}PENDING@{ub} folder.
        2:          Message composed and placed in @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder.
        3:          Message composed and sent.

***

@{b}Syntax: COMPOSE NEW MESSAGE@{ub}

The Compose window will be brought up to compose a new message.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} 0:          User canceled message compose.  No message composed.
        1:          Message composed and placed in @{b}PENDING@{ub} folder.
        2:          Message composed and placed in @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder.
        3:          Message composed and sent.

***

@{b}Syntax: COMPOSE REPLY@{ub}

The Compose window will be brought up to compose a reply to the @{b}Current
Message@{ub} using the Reply-To: address as the recipient.  If the Reply-To:
address is not available, the From:  address will be used.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1:         There is no current message defined.
         0:         The user cancelled the operation.  No message was
                    composed.
         1:         Message composed and placed in @{b}PENDING@{ub} folder.
         2:         Message composed and placed in @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder.
         3:         Message composed and sent.
***

@{b}Syntax: COMPOSE REPLY FROM@{ub}

The Compose window will be brought up to compose a reply to the @{b}Current
Message@{ub} using the From: address as the recipient.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1:         There is no current message defined.
         0:         The user cancelled the operation.  No message was
                    composed.
         1:         Message composed and placed in @{b}PENDING@{ub} folder.
         2:         Message composed and placed in @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder.
         3:         Message composed and sent.

***

@{b}Syntax: COMPOSE FORWARD
        COMPOSE FORWARD @{i}userid@{ui}@{ub}

The Compose window will be brought up to forward the @{b}Current Message@{ub}.  If
the userid (email address or referenced Address Book nickname) is
provided, this will be used as the recipient (To:  address) of the
forwarded message; otherwise, the To:  address will be blank and user will
have to provide it.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1:         There is no current message defined.
         0:         The user cancelled the operation.  No message was
                    composed.
         1:         Message composed and placed in @{b}PENDING@{ub} folder.
         2:         Message composed and placed in @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder.
         3:         Message composed and sent.
***

@{b}Syntax: COMPOSE MAILTO @{i}userid@{ui}@{ub}

The Compose window will be brought up to compose a new message to be
mailed to the recipient indicated by the @{i}userid@{ui}.  The @{i}userid@{ui} can be either
an @{" Address Book " link AEM-8500} nickname or a full email-address and must be given.

No validation is made on the @{i}userid@{ui}.  If it is invalid, either the user
will receive an error when the message is sent or a message will be
received indicating "Returned mail:  User unknown".

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} 0:          The user cancelled the operation.  No message was
                    composed.
        1:          Message composed and placed in the @{b}PENDING@{ub} folder.
        2:          Message composed and placed in the @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder.
        3:          Message composed and sent.

***

@{b}Syntax: COMPOSE "@{i}message-file-name@{ui}"@{ub}

The Compose window will be brought up and the message file indicated by
"@{i}message-file-name@{ui}" will be read into the system and used as the message
to edit.  This message must have correctly formatted headers.  Only the
To:, From:, Reply-To:, Subject:, cc:, and bcc: headers will be recognized.
A blank line must separate the headers from the body of the message.

The @{b}"@{i}message-file-name@{ui}"@{ub} should be the full path name of the message file
and it should be quoted since the path will contain characters that @{b}ARexx@{ub}
will attempt to interpret as operators or possibly embedded spaces.

Any address provided with the To: header can be either an Address Book
nickname or a full email address.  Multiple To: addresses can be provided
as well as multiple cc: or bcc: addresses.

No headers have to be provided with the message.  The headers can be
provided on the Compose window.  However, if this is done, a blank line
MUST precede the message body in the message file.

Additional @{b}RC@{ub} type errors can be received by this command if the
message-file-name is invalid or an error occurred reading in the message
file.  Each of these errors have a severity level of 5 with one of the
following messages placed in the @{b}AEMAIL.LASTERROR@{ub} variable:

    @{b}105: Error Opening Passed Message
    106: Error retrieving passed message@{ub}

If you would like to use the File Requester to obtain the file name before
passing it to this command, you can use the @{" GETFILENAME " link AEM-9512} command to obtain
the full path name of the message.

No validation is made on the To:  address in the message.  If it is
invalid, either the user will receive an error when the message is sent or
a message will be received indicating "Returned mail:  User unknown".

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} 0:          The user cancelled the operation.  No message was
                    composed.
        1:          Message composed and placed in @{b}PENDING@{ub} folder.
        2:          Message composed and placed in @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder.
        3:          Message composed and sent.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9504 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: CURRENT IS SELECTED"

                           @{b}CURRENT IS SELECTED@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: CURRENT IS SELECTED@{ub}

This command makes the currently selected message the @{b}Current Message@{ub}.
The currently selected message is the message that is @{i}highlighted@{ui} in the
message list or the message that is currently being displayed.  The
message may or may not have a selection asterick.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} 0           There was no selected message.
        1           Current message is now the selected message.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9505 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: DATE"


                                   @{b}DATE@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: DATE
        DATE MDY
        DATE DMY
        DATE YMD@{ub}

This command returns the Date:  header of the @{b}Current Message@{ub} header
without the "Date:".

Without an operand, this command returns the date as it was received in
the Date:  header of the message.  With the operand @{b}MDY@{ub} it returns the
date as mm/dd/yy.  The operand @{b}DMY@{ub} returns the date as dd/mm/yy and
@{b}YMD@{ub} returns yy/mm/dd.  All of the fields are two digits which means that
yy will be the last 2 digits of the year.

The alternate formats are provided so that the date field can be stored in
a data base such as one created with @{b}"Final Data"@{ub}.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1              No current message
        NULL or blanks  No Date: header
        Date: field

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9506 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: EXTRACT"

                                 @{b}EXTRACT@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: EXTRACT REALNAME @{i}name-string@{ui}
        EXTRACT USERID @{i}name-string@{ui}@{ub}

This command extracts either the @{b}REALNAME@{ub} or the @{b}USERID@{ub} (email address
or address book nickname) from a name string that is usually the result of
the @{" FIRST TONAME, FIRST CCNAME, FIRST BCCNAME " link AEM-9507} or @{" NEXT NAME " link AEM-9518} commands
(see below).  Because of the various formats of a name string; ie,

        @{b}email-address (Full Name)
        Full Name <email-address>
        email-address
        addressbook-nickname@{ub}

it is easier to use this command rather then to use standard @{b}ARexx@{ub}
commands to parse the name string.

If you use the @{" ADDRESS_BOOK " link AEM-9500} @{b}GET @{i}nickname@{ui} TYPE@{ub} command you can determine if
a userid that is returned is a nickname or email address.

The @{i}name-string@{ui} variable should be quoted since it will contain blanks and
other characters @{b}ARexx@{ub} may not like including double quote marks.  As an
example:

    @{b}OPTION RESULTS
    FIRST TONAME
    name=RESULT
    if name = "" THEN EXIT
    EXTRACT USERID '"'name'"'
    emailaddr=RESULT
    ADDRESS_BOOK GET '"'emailaddr'"' TYPE
    if RESULT = 0 THEN OKAY1 emailaddr" is an individual nickname."
    ELSE if RESULT = 1 THEN OKAY1 emailaddr" is a group nickname."@{ub}

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} NULL or blank   No real name if REAL-NAME operand used.
        Either the real name or userid string.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9507 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: FIRST"

                                  @{b}FIRST@{ub}

This command is used to select the first message in the current folder or
to select the first name string from the list of To:  or cc:  recipients.

***

@{b}Syntax: FIRST
        FIRST NEW
        FIRST SELECTED
        FIRST DELETED@{ub}

Without an Operand this command selects the first message in the current
selected folder as the current message.

With the @{b}NEW@{ub} operand, this command selects the first un-read (new) message
in the current selected folder as the current message.

If a message is unread but deleted, it will NOT be considered an un-read
message.

With the @{b}SELECTED@{ub} operand, this command selects the first selected
(message marked with an asterick) message in the current selected folder
as the current message.

With the @{b}DELETED@{ub} operand, this command selects the first message marked as
deleted in the current selected folder as the current message.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} The order of the messages in the folder is the un-sorted order.
This generally means that the first message is the oldest message in the
folder.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} 0       No messages of the particular type in the folder
        1       First message is now the current message.

***

@{b}Syntax: FIRST TONAME
        FIRST CCNAME
        FIRST BCCNAME@{ub}

This command returns the first name from the appropriate header field
(To:, cc:, or bcc:) in the current message.  The name can be in one of the
following formats:

        @{b}email-address (Full Name)
        Full Name <email-address>
        email-address
        addressbook-nickname@{ub}

Names in the header recipient lists are separated by commas; however, a
comma may be embedded within a real name if the real name is surrounded by
quotes.

If you wish to extract either the Full Name, email-address, or the
addressbook-nickname from the @{b}RESULT@{ub} you can set the @{b}RESULT@{ub} to a variable
and then use the @{" EXTRACT " link AEM-9506} command with that variable as the argument.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1              There is no current message
         NULL or blank  There are no names in this field.
         The first name in the appropriate header.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9508 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: FLAGS"

                                  @{b}FLAGS@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: FLAGS@{ub}

This command returns the flags for the @{b}Current Message@{ub}.  The flags are
returned in the @{b}RESULT@{ub} field as indicated below.  A message can have
multiple flags which means that a value will be returned with the two or
more values for the flags added together.  As an example, a message that
is unread and new with attachments will return a value of 11.  You will
need to use the ARexx operator for logical AND to isolate the flag you
want.

Here is a piece of ARexx code to isolate a message that is unread:

    @{b}OPTION RESULTS

    FLAGS

    IF RESULT = -1 THEN OKAY1 "There is no current message"
    ELSE DO

        IF RESULT & 2 THEN OKAY1 "This message is unread"
        ELSE OKAY1 "This message has been read"

        END@{ub}

Note the distinction between flag values 1 (for New) and 2 (for Unread).
Generally, when a message is first read into the system both flags are
set.  If the message is read, both flags are turned off.  However, if the
message should be deleted without being read, the Unread flag will be
turned off but the New flag will remain on.  If that message then becomes
un-deleted and the New flag is still on, the Unread flag will be turned
back on.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1          No current message
        0           There is a current message but no flags are set
        1           Message is New and unread (can be deleted)
        2           Message is unread but not deleted
        4           Message is a reply
        8           Message has attachments
        16          Message has been forwarded
        32          Message is deleted
        64          Message is selected

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9509 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: FOLDER"

                                  @{b}FOLDER@{ub}

There are a number of variations of the @{b}FOLDER@{ub} command.  They are listed
below:

***

@{b}Syntax: FOLDER@{ub}

The @{b}FOLDER@{ub} command with no operands is used to return the current selected
folder name.

RESULT: 0           No folder currently selected
        The folder Name (i.e., "INBOX", "QUEUED", etc.)

***

@{b}Syntax: FOLDER LIST_FOLDERS [@{i}pad@{ui}]@{ub}

This command will list all of the folders in your system.  Normally each
folder is separated by a space.  However, this can be changed by
specifying a @{i}pad@{ui} string at the end of the command.  You can use the @{b}LF@{ub}
keyword to specify a line feed or use some other character sequence for
the pad string.  As an example:  @{b}", "@{ub} will insert a comma followed by a
space between each folder name in the list.

Notice that the keyword here is @{b}LIST_FOLDERS@{ub} with an underline between
@{b}LIST@{ub} and @{b}FOLDERS@{ub}.  If the keyword was simply @{b}LIST@{ub} it might be
mis-interpreted as a folder named LIST.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} The list of folders separated by the @{i}pad@{ui} string.

***

@{b}Syntax: FOLDER @{i}folder-name@{ui}@{ub}

This command selects the the folder indicated by @{i}folder-name@{ui}.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1: folder-name is invalid.  Could be the result of a misspelling
            of one of the operands used with the FOLDER commands so that
            the operand is mis-interpreted as a folder-name.
         0: The folder folder-name could not be selected.
         1: The folder folder-name was selected.

***

@{b}Syntax: FOLDER DESCRIPTION
        FOLDER @{i}folder-name@{ui} DESCRIPTION
        FOLDER @{i}folder-name@{ui} SELECT DESCRIPTION@{ub}

This command returns the description of either the selected folder or, if
present, the folder indicated by folder name.  If the folder name is
present, it will not become the new selected unless the @{b}SELECT@{ub} keyword
immediately follows it.  This allows you to obtain the description of a
folder without selecting it.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub}  If the folder-name is left off the command and any of the
parameters is misspelled, it could result in the misspelled parameter
being mis-interpreted as a folder-name.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1: folder-name is invalid.  Could be the result of a misspelling
            of one of the operands used with the following FOLDER commands
            so that the operand is mis-interpreted as a folder-name.

         The description of either the folder specified with folder-name
            or the selected folder.

***

@{b}Syntax: FOLDER NUMBER_MESSAGES
        FOLDER @{i}folder-name@{ui} NUMBER_MESSAGES
        FOLDER @{i}folder-name@{ui} SELECT NUMBER_MESSAGES@{ub}

This command returns the number of messages contained in either the
selected folder or, if present, the folder indicated by folder name.  If
the folder name is present, it will not become the new selected folder
unless the @{b}SELECT@{ub} keyword immediately follows it.  This allows you to
obtain the number of messages from a folder without selecting it.

Please note the spelling of the operand @{b}NUMBER_MESSAGES@{ub} with the underline
between @{b}NUMBER@{ub} and @{b}MESSAGES@{ub}.  This makes the operand string longer than a
folder-name so that it does not interfer with any existing folder-name.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub}  If the folder-name is left off the command and any of the
parameters is misspelled, it could result in the misspelled parameter
being mis-interpreted as a folder-name.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1: folder-name is invalid.  Could be the result of a misspelling
            of one of the operands used with the following FOLDER commands
            so that the operand is mis-interpreted as a folder-name.

         @{i}n@{ui}: The total number of messages in the folder including ones that
            are unread or deleted.

***

@{b}Syntax: FOLDER NEW_MESSAGES
        FOLDER @{i}folder-name@{ui} NEW_MESSAGES
        FOLDER @{i}folder-name@{ui} SELECT NEW_MESSAGES@{ub}

This command returns the number of new (@{i}unread@{ui}) messages contained in
either the selected folder or, if present, the folder indicated by folder
name.  If the folder name is present, it will not become the new selected
folder unless the @{b}SELECT@{ub} keyword immediately follows it.  This allows you
to obtain the number of new messages from a folder without selecting it.

If a message is unread but deleted, it will not be included in the count
of new messages.

Please note the spelling of the operand @{b}NEW_MESSAGES@{ub} with the underline
between @{b}NEW@{ub} and @{b}MESSAGES@{ub}.  This makes the operand string longer than a
folder-name so that it does not interfer with any existing folder-name.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub}  If the folder-name is left off the command and any of the
parameters is misspelled, it could result in the misspelled parameter
being mis-interpreted as a folder-name.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1: folder-name is invalid.  Could be the result of a misspelling
            of one of the operands used with the following FOLDER commands
            so that the operand is mis-interpreted as a folder-name.

         @{i}n@{ui}: The number of new or unread messages in the folder.

***

@{b}Syntax: FOLDER DELETED_MESSAGES
        FOLDER @{i}folder-name@{ui} DELETED_MESSAGES
        FOLDER @{i}folder-name@{ui} SELECT DELETED_MESSAGES@{ub}

This command returns the number of deleted messages contained in either
the selected folder or, if present, the folder indicated by folder name.
If the folder name is present, it will not become the new selected folder
unless the @{b}SELECT@{ub} keyword immediately follows it.  This allows you to
obtain the number of deleted messages from a folder without selecting it.

Please note the spelling of the operand @{b}DELETED_MESSAGES@{ub} with the
underline between @{b}DELETED@{ub} and @{b}MESSAGES@{ub}.  This makes the operand string
longer than a folder-name so that it does not interfer with any existing
folder-name.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub}  If the folder-name is left off the command and any of the
parameters is misspelled, it could result in the misspelled parameter
being mis-interpreted as a folder-name.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1: folder-name is invalid.  Could be the result of a misspelling
            of one of the operands used with the following FOLDER commands
            so that the operand is mis-interpreted as a folder-name.

         @{i}n@{ui}: The number of deleted messages in the folder.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9510 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: FROM"

                                   @{b}FROM@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: FROM@{ub}

This command returns the From:  header of the @{b}Current Message@{ub} without the
"From:  ".  It has no operands.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1              No current message
        NULL or blanks  No From: header
        From: header

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9511 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: GETCLIP"

                                 @{b}GETCLIP@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: GETCLIP
        GETCLIP @{i}n@{ui}
        GETCLIP UNIT @{i}n@{ui}@{ub}

This command will return the current contents of the clipboard in the
result variable.  If @{b}UNIT @{i}n@{ui}@{ub} or @{i}n@{ui} is not specified, it will be from the
current active clipboard.  If @{b}UNIT @{i}n@{ui}@{ub} or @{i}n@{ui} (without @{b}UNIT@{ub}) is specified
it will be from the clipboard unit specified by @{i}n@{ui}.

If the clipboard unit is specified, the current active clipboard will be
changed to that unit UNLESS the clipboard unit was non-existant.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} NULL or blank   This clipboard unit is empty or non-existant.
        Data from the clipboard unit.

***

@{b}Syntax: GETCLIP UNIT@{ub}

This command will return the current active clipboard unit number.  Notice
that is similar to the previous command @{u}WITHOUT@{uu} the clipboard unit number
(@{i}n@{ui}).

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} @{i}n@{ui}       This current active clipboard unit number.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9512 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: GETFILENAME"

                               @{b}GETFILENAME@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: GETFILENAME
        GETFILENAME @{i}title@{ui}
        GETFILENAME @{i}title defaultpath@{ui}@{ub}

This command brings up the @{b}AEMail@{ub} file requester so you can solicit file
names that can be used with commands that require file names.

If no operands are provided with this command, the file requester will
have @{b}ARexx File Request@{ub} as the default title in the requester and a
default path of @{b}PROGDIR:@{ub} (the directory from which @{b}AEMail@{ub} was called).

The second form of this command allows you to provide your own title in
the file requester which may be more descriptive of what kind of file you
want.

The third form gives the user the ability to provide both a title and a
default file path and (if wanted) filename.  This is particularly useful
if you want to reference a different directory than your program
directory.  A default filename can be part of this path.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} If you supply a default path without a filename (directory only) you
must end the string with @{b}:@{ub} or @{b}/@{ub} to indicate that it is a directory and
not a filename path.

Be very careful in using this command since this is one that will require
"creative" quoting to insure that you have no more than two operand
strings.  As an example you should use something like this:

    @{b}GETFILENAME '"The Title String"' '"A file name path"'@{ub}

This will send @{b}"The Title String"@{ub} and @{b}"A file name path"@{ub} to @{b}AEMail@{ub} which
will recognize these strings as two quoted operands.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub}  NULL or blank if the no filename was entered or the requester was
            cancelled.
         The full path and filename of the file that was selected.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9529 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: GETLISTITEM"

                               @{b}GETLISTITEM@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: GETLISTITEM @{i}list@{ui}
        GETLISTITEM @{i}list title@{ui}@{ub}

This command brings up the @{b}AEMail@{ub} list view requester so the user can
solicit a member of the list.  The operand list is a list of items, each
member of the list being separated by a line feed.  Many of the AEMail
commands can supply such a list.  As an example, @{b}ADDRESS_BOOK LIST GROUP
DESCRIPTION LF@{ub} will supply a list of group Address Book entries and their
descriptions separated by line feeds.  Another example is @{b}LIST_FOLDERS LF@{ub}
which will provide a list of all the folders in the system.

The list should be a quoted variable such as:

    @{b}ADDRESS_BOOK LIST GROUP DESCRIPTION LF
    grplist = RESULT
    GETLISTITEM "'"grplist"'"@{ub}

This will insure that the entire list is treated as a single variable.

The second operand is the title that you want for the list view.  If this
operand is not provided, the list view requester will have @{b}ARexx Select
List Item@{ub} as the default title.  The title should also be quoted.

When the list view is displayed and an item selected from the list it will
appear in a string gadget below the listview.  You can modify the
information in this string gadget if you wish.  An @{b}[OK]@{ub} and @{b}[CANCEL]@{ub}
gadget will also be displayed.  If you click on @{b}[OK]@{ub} or press @{b}RETURN@{ub}, the
information in the string gadget will be returned in the @{b}RESULT@{ub} variable.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub}  NULL or blank if the string gadget is blank or the requester was
            cancelled.
         The string that was entered in the string gadget at the bottom of
            the list view.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9513 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: GETNUMBER"

                                @{b}GETNUMBER@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: GETNUMBER
        GETNUMBER @{i}title@{ui}
        GETNUMBER @{i}title default@{ui}
        GETNUMBER @{i}title default min@{ui}
        GETNUMBER @{i}title default min max@{ui}@{ub}

This command brings up the @{b}AEMail@{ub} numeric requester so you can solicit a
numeric value.

If no operands are provided with this command, the numeric requester will
have @{b}ARexx Enter Number@{ub} as the default title in the requester and a
default value of @{b}0@{ub}.

The second form of this command allows you to provide your own title in
the numeric requester which may be more descriptive of what purpose you
want the number for.

The third form gives the user the ability to provide both a title and a
default numeric value.

The fourth form gives you the ability to provide a minimum value that can
be entered, and the fifth for allows both a minimum or maximum value.   f
a value outside this range is entered, the screen will flash.  Also, the
minimum and maximum limits are given in a text string below the numeric
entry gadget.

Be very careful in using this command since this is one that will require
"creative" quoting for the title to insure that strings between embedded
spaces are not interpreted as part of the numeric values.  As an example
you should use something like this:

    @{b}GETNUMBER '"Enter a number between 3 & 7"' 5 3 7@{ub}

This will place @{b}Enter a number between 3 & 7@{ub} in the title bar of the
requester, use 5 as the default value in the numeric entry gadget, and set
the minimum and maximum possibilities to 3 and 7 respectively.  This will
also recognize the full title string as a proper quoted operand.

The numeric entry gadget is followed by a @{b}[+]@{ub} (@{i}increment@{ui}) and a @{b}[-]@{ub}
(@{i}decrement@{ui}) gadget.  Clicking on one or the other of these gadgets will
increment or decrement the value in the numeric entry gadget.  This value
can not decrement below the minimum value or 0 (if no minimum is given) or
increment above the maximum value.

The numeric entry gadget is in @{b}replace@{ub} mode so that entering a number
will replace what was previously there.  Hitting @{b}[OK]@{ub} or pressing the
@{b}RETURN@{ub} key will terminate the requester with the numeric value entered
returned in the @{b}RESULT@{ub} variable.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub}  NULL or blank if the the requester was cancelled.
          @{i}n@{ui}     The numeric value entered in the requester.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9514 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: GETSIZE"

                                 @{b}GETSIZE@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: GETSIZE MESSAGE
        GETSIZE TEXT@{ub}

This command will get the size of the @{b}Current Message@{ub}  .  If the operand
@{b}MESSAGE@{ub} is given, it will be the size of the complete message.  If the
operand @{b}TEXT@{ub} is given, it will be only the size of the text portion of
the message (Message size less the header size and any attachment size).

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} 0       No Current Message
        The size of the Current Message or just the text size.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9515 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: GETSTRING"

                                @{b}GETSTRING@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: GETSTRING
        GETSTRING @{i}title@{ui}
        GETSTRING @{i}title defaultstring@{ui}@{ub}

This command brings up the @{b}AEMail@{ub} string requester so you can solicit a
string from the user.

If no operands are provided with this command, the string requester will
have @{b}ARexx Enter String@{ub} as the default title in the requester with no
default string.

The second form of this command allows you to provide your own title in
the string requester which may be more descriptive of what purpose you
want the string for.

The third form gives the user the ability to provide both a title and a
default string that will appear in the requester when it is first brought
up.

Be very careful in using this command since this is one that will require
"creative" quoting to insure that you have no more than two operand
strings.  As an example you should use something like this:

    @{b}GETSTRING '"Enter a Folder Name"' '"INBOX"'@{ub}

This will send @{b}"Enter a Folder Name"@{ub} and @{b}"INBOX"@{ub} to @{b}AEMail@{ub} which will
recognize these strings as two separate quoted operands.  Since @{b}INBOX@{ub} is
one word, it does not have to have the special quoting on it but can be
simply @{b}'INBOX'@{ub}.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub}   NULL or blank if the no string was entered or the requester was
            cancelled.
          The string that was entered in the requester.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9530 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: GETVAR"

                                  @{b}GETVAR@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: GETVAR@{ub}

When you are displaying a message and you double click on a message line,
the @{" Clipboard Window " link AEM-5500} appears.  If you hit one of the @{" function keys " link AEM-4700} to call
an ARexx script, the line currently being displayed in the clipboard
string will be transferred to a special variable.

In your @{b}ARexx@{ub} script you can use @{b}GETVAR@{ub} to extract that string.  If the
string was an email or web address, your script can use the variable thus
obtained to send a message to the email address or to call your web
browser to go to the web address.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} The string that was in the clipboard line.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9516 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: LAST"

                                   @{b}LAST@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: LAST
        LAST NEW
        LAST SELECTED
        LAST DELETED@{ub}

Without an Operand this command selects the last message in the current
selected folder as the current message.

With the @{b}NEW@{ub} operand, this command selects the last un-read (new) message
in the current selected folder as the current message.

If a message is unread but deleted, it will NOT be considered an un-read
message.

With the @{b}SELECTED@{ub} operand, this command selects the last selected
(message marked with an asterick) message in the current selected folder
as the current message.

With the @{b}DELETED@{ub} operand, this command selects the last message marked as
deleted in the current selected folder as the current message.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} The order of the messages in the folder is the un-sorted order.
This generally means that the last message is the newest message in the
folder.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} 0       No messages of the particular type in the folder
        1       Last message is now the current message.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9517 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: MESSAGE"

                                 @{b}MESSAGE@{ub}

This command is used to set various flags on the @{b}Current Message@{ub}.  After
the execution of this command, the message list, if it is currently being
displayed, will be re-displayed with the changed status.  The forms of
this command are as follows:

@{b}Syntax: MESSAGE SELECT@{ub}

This command marks the @{b}Current Message@{ub} as selected.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1  There is no Current Message.
         0  The Current Message is already marked as selected.
         1  The Current Message is now marked as selected.

***

@{b}Syntax: MESSAGE UNSELECT@{ub}

This command marks the @{b}Current Message@{ub} as un-selected.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1  There is no Current Message.
         0  The Current Message is not marked as selected.
         1  The Current Message is now marked as un-selected.

***

@{b}Syntax: MESSAGE DELETE@{ub}

This command marks the @{b}Current Message@{ub} as deleted.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1  There is no Current Message.
         0  The Current Message is already marked as deleted.
         1  The Current Message is now marked as deleted.

***

@{b}Syntax: MESSAGE UNDELETE@{ub}

This command marks the @{b}Current Message@{ub} as not deleted.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1  There is no Current Message.
         0  The Current Message is not currently marked as deleted.
         1  The Current Message is now no longer marked as deleted.

***

@{b}Syntax: MESSAGE READ@{ub}

This command marks the @{b}Current Message@{ub} as being read.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1  There is no Current Message.
         0  The Current Message is already marked as being read.
         1  The Current Message is now marked as being read.

***

@{b}Syntax: MESSAGE MAKE NEW@{ub}

This command marks the @{b}Current Message@{ub} as unread or new.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} If the message was marked as deleted, only the "new" flag is set;
otherwise, both the "new" and "unread" flags are set.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1  There is no Current Message.
         0  The Current Message is already marked as unread (new).
         1  The Current Message is now marked as unread.

***

@{b}Syntax: MESSAGE SELECT ALL@{ub}

All messages in the current selected folder are marked as selected.  This
command does not change the @{b}Current Message@{ub} status.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub}  0  There are no messages in the selected folder.
         1  All of the messages in the selected folder are marked as
            selected.

***

@{b}Syntax: MESSAGE SELECT NONE
        MESSAGE UNSELECT ALL@{ub}

This command can be expressed in either form above.

All messages in the current selected folder are marked as un-selected.
This command does not change the Current Message status.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub}  0  There are no messages in the selected folder.
         1  All of the messages in the selected folder are now marked as
            un-selected.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9518 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: NEXT"

                                   @{b}NEXT@{ub}

This command is used to select the next message in the current folder or
to select the next name string from the list of To:  or cc:  recipients.

***

@{b}Syntax: NEXT
        NEXT NEW
        NEXT SELECTED
        NEXT DELETED@{ub}

Without an operand this command selects the next message, regardless of
it's status, in the current selected folder as the current message.

With the @{b}NEW@{ub} operand, this command selects the next un-read (new) message
in the current selected folder as the current message.

If a message is unread but deleted, it will NOT be considered an un-read
message.

With the @{b}SELECTED@{ub} operand, this command selects the next selected (message
marked with an asterick) message in the current selected folder as the
current message.

With the @{b}DELETED@{ub} operand, this command selects the next message marked as
deleted in the current selected folder as the current message.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub}  The order of the messages in the folder is the un-sorted order.
This generally means that the order of the messages in the folder is that
older messages are before newer messages.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} 0       No more messages of the particular type are in the folder.
                At the end of the message list.
        1       The next message is now the current message.

***

@{b}Syntax: NEXT NAME@{ub}

This command returns the next name from the header field that was
referenced by the last @{" FIRST " link AEM-9507} command.  A @{b}FIRST TONAME@{ub}, @{b}FIRST CCNAME@{ub}, or
@{b}FIRST BCCNAME@{ub} command must have been issued prior to issuing the first
@{b}NEXT NAME@{ub} command.  Each @{b}NEXT NAME@{ub} command that is issued retrieves the
next name in that header field.  Once the end of the name list is reached,
another @{b}FIRST@{ub} command must be issued before another @{b}NEXT NAME@{ub} command is
issued.  The name can be in one of the following formats:

        @{b}email-address (Full Name)
        Full Name <email-address>
        email-address
        addressbook-nickname@{ub}

Names in the header recipient lists are separated by commas; however, a
comma may be embedded within a real name if the real name is surrounded by
quotes.

If you wish to extract either the Full Name, email-address, or the
addressbook-nickname from the @{b}RESULT@{ub} you can set the @{b}RESULT@{ub} to a variable
and then use the @{" EXTRACT " link AEM-9506} command with that variable as the arguement.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -2              The name string has not been started with the
                        FIRST command.
         NULL or blank  You are at the end of the list.  There are no
                        more names in the current header field.
         The next name in the appropriate header.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9519 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: OKAY1"

                                  @{b}OKAY1@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: OKAY1 @{i}text@{ui}@{ub}

This commands presents the @{b}AEMail@{ub} notification requester containing the
supplied text.  If there are any @{b}ARexx@{ub} specific command operators within
the text stream, the stream should be surrounded in quotes.

The notification requester has one button marked @{b}Continue@{ub}.  Clicking on
this button will terminate the requester and the @{b}OKAY1@{ub} command.

@{b}Warning:@{ub} Be careful of the size of the text string that you pass to this
command.  If the string is too long without intervening line feeds, the
@{b}Continue@{ub} button could be positioned off the screen and you will have no
way to terminate the requester.  This can be particularly true of returned
strings that are being displayed.  It is best to use the @{b}ARexx LEFT()@{ub}
function to insure you have a short enough string.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} 1           Always returned

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9520 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: OKAY2"

                                  @{b}OKAY2@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: OKAY1 @{i}responses text@{ui}@{ub}

This commands presents the @{b}AEMail@{ub} notification requester containing the
supplied text.  If there are any @{b}ARexx@{ub} specific command operators within
the text stream, the stream should be surrounded in quotes.

@{i}responses@{ui} provides a list of possible responses to the requester.  Any
number of responses can be provided.  Each response must be separated by
the vertical bar (@{b}|@{ub}).  The entire response string must be surrounded by
quote marks.

The notification requester has as many buttons as they are responses.  The
wording in these buttons is controlled by the response string.  Clicking
on any of these buttons will terminate the requester and the @{b}OKAY2@{ub}
command.

@{b}RESULT@{ub}: 0           The last response in the response string was selected.
        1           The first response was selected.
        @{i}n@{ui}           The second through @{i}nth@{ui} (@{b}last - 1@{b}) response was selected.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9521 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: PREVIOUS"

                                 @{b}PREVIOUS@{ub}
@{b}Syntax: PREVIOUS
        PREVIOUS NEW
        PREVIOUS SELECTED
        PREVIOUS DELETED@{ub}

Without an operand this command selects the previous message, regardless
of it's status, in the current selected folder as the current message.

With the @{b}NEW@{ub} operand, this command selects the previous un-read (new)
message in the current selected folder as the current message.

If a message is unread but deleted, it will NOT be considered an un-read
message.

With the @{b}SELECTED@{ub} operand, this command selects the previous selected
(message marked with an asterick) message in the current selected folder
as the current message.

With the @{b}DELETED@{ub} operand, this command selects the previous message marked
as deleted in the current selected folder as the current message.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub}  The order of the messages in the folder is the un-sorted order.
This generally means that the order of the messages in the folder is that
older messages are before newer messages.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} 0       No more messages of the particular type are in the folder.
                At the beginning of the message list.
        1       The next previous is now the current message.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9522 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: QUEUE"

                                  @{b}QUEUE@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: QUEUE "@{i}message-file-name@{ui}"
        QUEUE "@{i}message-file-name@{ui}" MAILTO @{i}userid@{ui}@{ub}

The message file indicated by @{b}"@{i}message-file-name"@{ui}@{ub} will be read into the
system and will be placed in the @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder.  This message must have
correctly formatted headers.  A blank line must separate the headers from
the body of the message.

The @{b}"@{i}message-file-name@{ui}"@{ub} should be the full path name of the message file
and it should be quoted since the path will contain characters that @{b}ARexx@{ub}
will attempt to interpret as operators.  It may also contain embedded
spaces.  If it does contain embedded spaces, double quote pairs must be
used, ie. @{b}'"@{i}filename string@{ui}"'@{ub} or @{b}'"'@{ub}@{i}variable@{ui}@{b}'"'@{ub}.

Any address provided with the To: header can be either an Address Book
nickname or a full email address.  Multiple To: addresses can be provided
as well as multiple cc: or bcc: addresses.

Instead of a To: address provided in the message the optional @{b}MAILTO@{ub}
keyword can be used to provide a userid which can be an Address Book
nickname or an email address.  The @{b}MAILTO@{ub} address will be added to any
addresses provide with a To: header.

If the From: or Reply-To: addresses are not given, these addresses will be
taken from the default From: and Reply-To addresses.

Any Date: header is ignored since the Date: header will be constructed
when the message is sent.

Any other non-standard headers can be supplied in the message file and
they will be included with the message.

Only the To:  header has to be provided unless the MAILTO parameter is
given.  If the MAILTO parameter is used, no headers have to be provided
with the message.  However, if this is done, a blank line MUST be the
first line in the message file.

Additional RC type errors can be received by this command if the
message-file-name is invalid or an error occurred reading in the message
file.  Each of these errors have a severity level of 5 with one of the
following messages placed in the @{b}AEMAIL.LASTERROR@{ub} variable:

    @{b}105: Error Opening Passed Message
    106: Error retrieving passed message@{ub}

No validation is made on the To:  address in the message.  If it is
invalid, either the user will receive an error when the message is sent or
a message will be received indicating "Returned mail:  User unknown".

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} 1:          Message was placed in the @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9531 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: QUIT"

                                   @{b}QUIT@{ub}
@{b}Syntax: QUIT@{ub}

This command will terminate @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  It operates silently so no messages
will appear.

After issuing this command, you can @{u}not@{uu} issue any more commands to @{b}AEMail@{ub}
since @{b}AEMail@{ub} and the @{b}AEMail ARexx Port@{ub} will no longer be there to receive
amy commands.

@{b}RESULT: None@{ub}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9523 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: REPLYTO"

                                 @{b}REPLYTO@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: REPLYTO@{ub}

This command returns the Reply-To:  header of the @{b}Current Message@{ub} without
the "Reply-To:  ".  It has no operands.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1              No current message
        NULL or blanks  No Reply-To: header
        Reply-To: header

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9524 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: SAVE"

                                   @{b}SAVE@{ub}

This command can save the @{b}Current Message@{ub} or selected messages or the text
portion of a message to a file.  The @{b}Current Message@{ub} or @{b}Current Message@{ub}
text can also be directly returned in the @{b}RESULT@{ub} variable.  The @{b}Current
Message@{ub} text can also be saved to the clipboard.

The various forms of this command are given below:

@{b}Syntax: SAVE MESSAGE@{ub}

This command will return the @{b}Current Message@{ub} in the @{b}RESULT@{ub} variable. This
will be the complete message including all headers, message body, and all
attachments.

@{b}WARNING:@{ub} This will return only the first @{b}4092@{ub} characters of the current
message.  Line Feed characters will be included at the end of each line in
the message.

You can use the @{" GETSIZE MESSAGE " link AEM-9514} command to obtain the size of the message
to see if it will fit.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} NULL or blank       There is no Current Message
        The message (up to 4092 characters)

***

Syntax: SAVE MESSAGE [TO] filename

This command will save the @{b}Current Message@{ub} to the file whose complete path
and file name is filename.  This should be a quoted variable.  You can
solicit a filename by using the @{" GETFILENAME " link AEM-9512} command before issuing this
command.

The keyword @{b}TO@{ub} is optional.

The message saved is the complete message including all headers, message
body, and all attachments.  Except for available disk space, there is no
limit on the size of the message.  Line Feed characters will be included
at the end of each line in the message.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub}  0      There is no current message
         1      The current message has been saved.

***

@{b}Syntax: SAVE SELECTED MESSAGES [TO] filename@{ub}

This command will save all of the selected messages in the current
selected folder to the file whose complete path and file name is filename.
This should be a quoted variable.  You can solicit a filename by using the
@{" GETFILENAME " link AEM-9512} command before issuing this command.

All of the messages will be saved in the single file specified as a @{" block " link AEM-6050}
of messages.

The keyword @{b}TO@{ub} is optional.

The messages saved include the complete message including all headers,
message body, and all attachments.  Except for available disk space, there
is no limit on the size of the message.  Line Feed characters will be
included at the end of each line in the message.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub}  0      There is no messages selected
         1      The current message has been saved.

***

@{b}Syntax: SAVE TEXT
        SAVE TEXT NOLF@{ub}

This command will return the text body of the @{b}Current Message@{ub} in the
@{b}RESULT@{ub} variable.  This will be only the body text without headers or
attachments.

Normally the text is returned with a line feed separating each line.  If
you use the @{b}NOLF@{ub} operand, this line feed will be left off.  This means
that the body lines will be one continuous string of data.  This can be
very helpful if you have a short message generated by a forms command sent
by email in a web page.

@{b}WARNING:@{ub}  This will return only the first @{b}4092@{ub} characters of the current
message body text.  Line Feed characters will be included at the end of
each line in the message unless @{b}NOLF@{ub} is specified.

You can use the @{" GETSIZE TEXT " link AEM-9514} command to obtain the size of the message
body to see if it will fit.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} NULL or blank       There is no Current Message
        The message text (up to 4092 characters)

***

@{b}Syntax: SAVE TEXT [TO] @{i}filename@{ui}@{ub}

This command will save the text body of the @{b}Current Message@{ub} to the file
whose complete path and file name is filename.  This should be a quoted
variable.  You can solicit a filename by using the @{" GETFILENAME " link AEM-9512} command
before issuing this command.

The keyword @{b}TO@{ub} is optional.

The text saved is only the body text without headers or attachments.
Except for available disk space, there is no limit on the size of the
message text.  Line Feed characters will be included at the end of each
line in the message.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub}  0      There is no current message
         1      The current message text has been saved.

***

@{b}Syntax: SAVE TEXT [TO] CLIPBOARD
        SAVE TEXT [TO] CLIPBOARD @{i}n@{ui}@{ub}

The first form of this command will save the text body of the Current
Message to the clipboard unit that is currently active.  The second form
will allow you to save the text to the clipboard unit specified by n.

You can determine which clipboard is currently active by using the @{" GETCLIP " link AEM-9511}
@{b}UNIT@{ub} command.

If you use the @{b}@{i}n@{ui}@{ub} parameter, the currently active clipboard unit will be
changed to n after the command is successfully executed (@{b}RESULT@{ub} of 1).

The keyword @{b}TO@{ub} is optional.

The text saved is only the body text without headers or attachments.
Except for available RAM space, there is no limit on the size of the
message text.  Line Feed characters will be included at the end of each
line in the message.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub}  0      There is no current message
         1      The current message text has been saved to the clipboard.

***

@{b}Syntax: SAVE "@{i}string of text@{ui}" [TO] CLIPBOARD
        SAVE "@{i}string of text@{ui}" [TO] CLIPBOARD @{i}n@{ui}@{ub}

The first form of this command will save the string of text passed as a
quoted string to the clipboard unit that is currently active.  The second
form will allow you to save the string to the clipboard unit specified by
@{i}n@{ui}.

You can determine which clipboard is currently active by using the @{" GETCLIP " link AEM-9511}
@{b}UNIT@{ub} command.

If you use the @{b}@{i}n@{ui}@{ub} parameter, the currently active clipboard unit will be
changed to n after the command is successfully executed (@{b}RESULT@{ub} of 1).

The keyword @{b}TO@{ub} is optional.

The string saved must be quoted to allow for embedded spaces and special
characters.  As an example:

    @{b}SAVE '"This is a string of characters"' TO CLIPBOARD 3@{ub}

will save the string @{b}This is a string of characters@{ub} to clipboard number
3.

The string is limited to 119 characters. If a larger string is given it
will be truncated at 119 characters.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub}  1      The string has been saved to the clipboard.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9525 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: SCREENTOBACK"

                               @{b}SCREENTOBACK@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: SCREENTOBACK AEMAIL
        SCREENTOBACK WORKBENCH
        SCREENTOBACK @{i}public-screen-name@{ui}@{ub}

This command brings either the @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen, the Workbench screen or
the named @{i}public-screen-name@{ui} to the back of the display.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} 0   The @{i}public-screen-name@{ui} is invalid or no longer open
        1   The specified screen has been moved to the back.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9526 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: SCREENTOFRONT"

                              @{b}SCREENTOFRONT@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: SCREENTOFRONT AEMAIL
        SCREENTOFRONT WORKBENCH
        SCREENTOFRONT @{i}public-screen-name@{ui}@{ub}

This command brings either the @{b}AEMail@{ub} screen, the Workbench screen or
the named @{i}public-screen-name@{ui} to the front of the display.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} 0   The public-screen-name is invalid or no longer open
        1   The specified screen is now the front most screen.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9527 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: SUBJECT"

                                 @{b}SUBJECT@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: SUBJECT@{ub}

This command returns the Subject:  header of the @{b}Current Message@{ub} without
"Subject: ".  It has no operands.

Also, the @{b}RE:@{ub} and @{b}(fwd)@{ub}, if present, are stripped from the header string.
You can use the @{" FLAGS " link AEM-9508} command to determine if the current message is a
reply or forwarded message.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1              No current message
        NULL or blanks  No Subject: header
        Subject: header

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9528 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/ARexx Command: TO"

                                    @{b}TO@{ub}

@{b}Syntax: TO@{ub}

This command returns the To:  header of the @{b}Current Message@{ub} without the
"To: ".  It has no operands.

@{b}RESULT:@{ub} -1              No current message
        NULL or blanks  No To: header
        To: header

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9600 "AEMAIL AREXX INTERFACE/AEMail ARexx Error Messages"

                       @{b}AEMail ARexx Error Messages@{ub}

When a command returns an @{b}RC@{ub} value other than 0 the @{b}RC@{ub} code represents a
severity code.  Severity codes are usually 5 or 20.  A string error
message will also appear in the @{b}AEMAIL.LASTERROR@{ub} variable.  These errors
can be interrogated and displayed.

The errors that you can expect from @{b}AEMail@{ub} are as follows:

        @{b}"100: Unknown command"
        "101: Syntax Error"
        "102: No Operand Required"
        "103: Missing Operand"
        "104: Too Many Operands"
        "105: Error Opening Passed Message"
        "106: Error retrieving passed message"
        "110: Out of Memory"@{ub}

Additional errors which will not have a error message number associated
with them are:

        @{b}"Unable to open input mail file"
        "Error reading input mail file"
        "Unable to open output file"
        "Error writing to output file"@{ub}

@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9700 "BUG REPORTS & SUGGESTIONS"

                          @{b}Bug Reports and Suggestions@{ub}

Bugs should be reported to:

    @{b}jzachar@calweb.com@{ub}

by email.  You can also use the nickname @{b}AEMAIL@{ub} which has been automatically
stored in your @{" address book " link AEM-8500}.

In reporting bugs, be as complete as possible in describing the circumstances
leading up to the bug.  It would be helpful if you indicate all actions
(mouse clicks, etc) that you took before the problem occurred.  If you are
having problems connecting to your Internet provider, or sending or receiving
mail, you should activate the @{" TCP Log file " link AEM-9180} and send a copy of the log as an
attachment to your message.  You might want to block out any password that
is contained in the file before you send it to me, however.  You can do that
with any text editor.

I would also appreciate any suggestions that you have for improving @{b}AEMail@{ub}.
I will not guarantee that I will accept all suggestions or that I will
necessarily implement them in the next release; however, I do take each
suggestion seriously.  In the past I have implemented a number of suggestions
made by my testers.  I will attempt to respond to each suggestion that is
made.

In making suggestions keep in mind some of the restraints that I have
placed on @{b}AEMail@{ub}:

    (1) The program should be able to be run on any version of
        AmigaDos 2.1 or greater, and

    (2) with the exception of @{b}TCP/IP stack@{ub} software (@{i}the standard Amiga
        does not come with such software which is required for Internet
        access@{ui}) or @{b}ClassAct@{ub}, @{b}AEMail@{ub} should not require any extension to
        your system that does not come with a standard AmigaDOS release.
        This effectively rules out @{b}MUI@{ub} although @{b}ClassAct@{ub} is an alternative
        to @{b}MUI@{ub}.

        @{b}ClassAct@{ub} utilizes @{b}Boopsi Classes@{ub} which have been an integral part
        of the Amiga OS since version 2.  @{b}ClassAct@{ub} also allows
        capabilities in AmigaDos 2.1 that the standard gadtools interface
        does not.  The @{b}ClassAct@{ub} classes @{b}AEMail@{ub} requires are provided as a
        part of the @{b}AEMail@{ub} release which means that the user does not have
        to provide anything additional.

        Using an editor of your choice also meets this criteria since you
        can use the standard AmigaDOS editors, @{b}ED@{ub} or @{b}MEMACS@{ub}, which come
        with the standard Amiga systems.

When reporting bugs or making suggestions, please be as complete as possible
in describing the circumstances that brought about the problem or how the
suggestion could be implemented.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9800 "REVISION HISTORY"
                             @{b}REVISION HISTORY@{ub}

@{b}Version 2.30@{ub}    @{i}Released March 31, 2000@{ui} at the @{b}A2K@{ub} computer show in
                St.Louis.  Enhancements and corrections in this release
                are:

                Final release of @{" help " link AEM-5900} system in AEMail.

                The @{" message list window " link AEM-8200} is modified to display a four digit
                year rather than a 2 digit year and the subject field is
                expanded to 50 characters to allow for users with larger
                width displays.

                Two @{" event exits " link AEM-4700} have been provided which will directly call
                @{b}ARexx@{ub} scripts to handle web and email addresses embedded in
                a message.  If these exits are activated the appropriate
                @{b}ARexx@{ub} script will be executed immediately when you double
                click on either a @{" web or email address " link AEM-5800} embedded in a
                message.

                Exiting from AEMail has been improved so that the
                @{b}folder.config@{ub} is not rewritten.  This reduces the instances
                when a corrupted folder list may be written.

                @{" Menu items " link AEM-7204} have been provided which allow you to backup and
                restore your folder list.  You can restore a folder list
                different from your current folder list, but you must exit
                and reload @{b}AEMail@{ub} for this different folder list to take
                effect.

                A @{" Menu item " link AEM-7300} has been added which allows you to lock and
                unlock messages in the @{b}PENDIN@{ub} and @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folders.  Locked
                messages will not be sent until they are unlocked.

                A problem with the @{" sort " link AEM-8400} on the @{b}Subject@{ub} field has been
                corrected.  If @{b}Subject@{ub} was included as part of the sort,
                but not as the last field of the sort criteria, the sort
                would be terminated without going to the rest of the
                criteria.

                An additional script has been added to the @{b}ARexx@{ub}
                directory.  This script is the @{b}deladrgrp.aem@{ub} script
                which allows you to delete an email address from a group
                in the @{" Address Book " link AEM-8500}.

                The installation script has been reworked.  Among the
                changes is the ability to delete users.  See the
                @{" Installation " link AEM-3000} section for a further description of the
                changes.

                @{b}AEMail@{ub} is now available on @{b}CD-ROM@{ub} as well as a two disk
                diskette version and the archived Internet version.

@{b}Version 2.22@{ub}    @{i}Released January 10, 2000.@{ui}  This is a very limited release
                which implements the @{b}Help@{ub} key.  It is still in evaluation
                and there may be further enhancements to the help system.

                To accomodate the help screens, the Configuration Setup
                Window has been moved from the Workbench screen to the
                AEMail screen.

                A new menu item, called @{" Getting Help " link AEM-7104}, has been added to
                the @{" Project " link AEM-7100} menu.

                A new @{b}Tool Type@{ub} called @{" HELP= " link AEM-4126} has been added.  This @{b}Tool
                Type@{ub} allows an alternate location for the help file
                (@{b}AEMail.guide@{ub}).

@{b}Version 2.21@{ub}    @{i}Released December 19, 1999.@{ui}  This version corrected one
                major bug that occurred in @{b}Version 2.20@{ub}.  Mail with
                attachments generated with some email programs would not
                properly show the mail or the attachments.

@{b}Version 2.20@{ub}    @{i}Released December 15, 1999.@{ui}  Major enhancements and 
                corrections in this release are:

                Removed @{b}Send ARexx/DOS Command...@{ub} and @{b}Send Last
                Command@{ub} from the @{" Project Menu " link AEM-7000} and added them to a new
                @{" ARexx/DOS " link AEM-7600} menu.

                Changed name of @{b}Configuration Screen@{ub} to @{b}Configuration
                Setup@{ub} Window.

                In the @{" ARexx " link AEM-4700} page of the @{b}Configuration Setup@{ub} added a
                @{b}Title@{ub} column to the List View and added the @{b}Menu Title@{ub}
                string gadget.  This menu title is added to the
                @{" ARexx/DOS " link AEM-7601} menu to call the particular @{b}ARexx@{ub} or @{b}DOS@{ub}
                command.  @{i}If a menu title is not given, that command @{b}WILL
                NOT@{ub} be added to the menu.@{ui}

                In the @{b}Edit and save message line to clipboard; set ARexx
                variable@{ub} requester added one menu column:  @{b}Rexx/DOS@{ub}
                which is the same as the main menu. (see 
                @{" USING WEB AND EMAIL ADDRESSES EMBEDDED IN MESSAGES " link AEM-5800}

                Added @{" Move... " link AEM-7201} to the @{" folder menu " link AEM-7200} to re-arrange folders
                in the folder list and on the folder bar.

                Added @{b}Clone Workbench Screen Mode@{ub} checkmark gadget to the
                @{" General " link AEM-4900} page of the @{" Configuration Setup " link AEM-4200}.  When this is
                checked, the @{b}Set Screen Mode@{ub} gadget is disabled and
                whichever Screen mode is selected for the Workbench (by the
                Preferences/Screen Mode program) will be used for the
                @{b}AEMail@{ub} Screen Mode.

                Fixed a major problem when using a @{b}graphics@{ub} card and
                @{b}CyberGraphX@{ub} software.  If a large number of folders were
                added to the folder strip so that they extended beyond the
                visable window, those folders would be garbled when they
                were moved into the visable portion of the window.

                Since the icon information is not available when @{b}AEMail@{ub} is
                called from the @{" shell " link AEM-5200}, the configuration file will be read
                from @{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub} and the @{b}AEMail mail directory@{ub} stored
                in this configuration file as the mail directory.  Even if
                you have created a configuration file called something
                else or in a different directory, you should save the
                configuration file you want to use with shell commands in
                @{b}s:aemail.cnfg@{ub}.

                When creating new folders certain names are illegal.  This
                includes the name @{b}folder@{ub} (@{i}case insensitive@{ui}) and any name
                containing the characters @{b}:@{ub}, @{b}/@{ub}, or @{b}\@{ub}.  Edits have been
                placed in the @{" Folder Configuration Window " link AEM-8300} to prevent
                creating folder names that are illegal.

                @{" Install script " link AEM-3000} corrected to prevent calling the
                configuration file @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  If the configuration file is
                called @{b}AEMail@{ub} it would wipe out the @{b}AEMail@{ub} program.

                @{" Install script " link AEM-3000} changed to save temporary files in @{b}T:@{ub} rather
                than @{b}RAM:@{ub}  In most cases @{b}T:@{ub} is normally assigned to @{b}RAM:@{ub}

                @{" Install script " link AEM-3000} modified to allow bypassing configuring
                users if Version 2.00 or higher was previously installed.

                Corrected a problem when replying to a message directed to
                multiple addresses when one of the addresses far down the
                list had a real name associated with it and earlier ones
                did not.  If that happened, the system would either freeze
                or crash when the messages in the folder list were
                displayed.

                Mime attachments that use the @{b}multipart/alternative@{ub} mime
                @{b}type/subtype@{ub} are now correctly handled to show all 
                attachments.  This mime type/subtype is widely used in the
                Macintosh and PC world.

                Fixed a problem when @{" retrieving messages from a file " link AEM-6111} which
                were exported as a group from a different @{b}UserID@{ub} than the
                one for which the group file was being retrieved.  The
                group was being retrieved as a single message without being
                broken up into individual messages.

                Fixed a problem that brought up a console window on the
                Workbench when you call a DOS program asynchronously.  The
                console window is no longer brought up.

                @{b}AEMail@{ub} now display headers with Quoted-Printable
                information in them correctly.  A quoted-printable header
                is identified by:

                    @{b}=?(font)?Q?...(header)....?=@{ub}

                The header only is now displayed with translation to the
                foriegn character set which is contained in the header.

                @{b}PLEASE NOTE:@{ub}  There are other header formats that sometimes
                occur with a character sequence other then @{b}"?Q?"@{ub}. These 
                formats are @{b}not@{ub} currently handled correctly, but instead
                are left in their original format.

                One additional script has been added to the @{b}ARexx@{ub}
                directory.  This script is the @{b}html2.aem@{ub} script which
                allows you to select between several browsers when
                displaying @{b}html@{ub} attachments or calling an @{b}html@{ub} document
                from an embedded @{b}web@{ub} address in a message.

@{b}Version 2.01@{ub}    @{i}Released March 24, 1999.@{ui}  This is a minor release
                correcting bugs discovered after the release of 2.00,
                Corrections in this release are:

                The @{" folder font " link AEM-4800} name was not properly saved when it was
                changed.  It always reverted back to the @{b}Topaz@{ub} font.  This
                has been corrected.

                The @{b}folder font size@{ub} was not correctly calculated when
                return was made from the @{b}configuration@{ub} page.  This has been
                corrected.

                Added @{b}Right Amiga p@{ub} to the string editing keys for the
                @{b}POP3 UserId@{ub} string gadget on the Configuration @{" Identity " link AEM-4300}
                page to bring up the @{b}"Set Password"@{ub} requester.

                The ARexx flag was not correctly remembered on the @{b}Start Net@{ub}
                and @{b}Stop Net@{ub} scripts on the @{" TCP/IP " link AEM-4400} configuration page.
                This has been corrected.

                The @{b}mail directory@{ub} could not be properly changed with the
                installation script.  It would always revert back to the
                old mail directory.  This has been corrected.

                When creating a group entry in the @{" Address Book " link AEM-8500}, the @{b}Send
                Header Only@{ub} flag remained disabled.  When you click on
                Group, the @{b}Send Header Only@{ub} now becomes enabled.

                Additional scripts have been added to the @{b}ARexx@{ub} directory.
                See the @{b}ARexx.readme@{ub} in the @{b}ARexx@{ub} directory for an
                explaination of these scripts.

@{b}Version 2.00@{ub}    @{i}Released March 13, 1999@{ui} at the @{b}Amiga '99 computer show@{ub} in
                St.Louis.  Enhancements and corrections in this release
                are:

                A complete rewrite of the @{" configuration " link AEM-4200} section of @{b}AEMail@{ub}
                using @{b}ClassAct@{ub}.  Among the major changes to the
                configuration are:

                    (1) Addition of a @{" Viewer " link AEM-4600} page.

                    (2) Addition of an @{" ARexx " link AEM-4700} page.

                    (3) Addition of a @{" Fonts " link AEM-4800} page.  This will allow the
                        user to assign different fonts to different
                        sections of @{b}AEMail@{ub} with certain restrictions.
                        These sections are:

                            @{b}Configuration Page font.

                            AEMail Screen Font.

                            AEMail General Font.

                            Folder Font.

                            Message Font.@{ub}

                    (4) Smarter defaults in the @{" Identity " link AEM-4300} page providing the
                        TCP/IP stack has been loaded before the
                        configuration screen is called.

                    (5) Added @{b}Right Amiga d@{ub} to the @{" string editing " link AEM-5400}
                        functions to bring in the default value for strings
                        that have defaults.  (applies only to @{" Configuration " link AEM-4200}
                        Screen) 

                    (6) Added @{b}Right Amiga f@{ub} to the @{" string editing " link AEM-5400}
                        functions to bring up the file requester for those
                        strings that have a file requester associated with
                        them.  (applies only to @{" Configuration " link AEM-4200} Screen)

                    (7) Elimination of the mailcap directory in the @{" Paths " link AEM-4500}
                        page since the @{" mailcap " link AEM-9100} now must be in your mail
                        directory.

                    (8) Other minor changes to the Configuration pages.

                When AEMail is first loaded, a window will appear on the
                Workbench indicating the progress of loading the
                configuration data.

                When AEMail quits, the "Updating All AEMail Files" message
                will show the progress of the update (what files are being
                updated).

                Corrected a bug where the updating occurred with files that
                didn't need updating.

                When @{b}AEMail@{ub} first loads after a new version is installed, a
                special @{" Notification Message " link AEM-2500} requester will appear asking
                if a message should be sent to the author requesting
                update notification.

                A menu item has been added to the @{" Project " link AEM-7100} menu to bring up
                the "Notification Message" if the user wants to inform the
                author of changes in his email address or system
                configuration.

                AEMail no longer automatically sends the special
                "Notification" message when you send your first message.

                The @{" hot keys " link AEM-5700} for moving to the next and previous messages
                have been changed to the right and left cursor keys.  The
                old hot keys ("." and ",") are still also in effect.

                The @{" hot keys " link AEM-5700} for moving to the next and previous folders
                have been changed to the shifted right and left cursor
                keys.  The old hot keys (">" and "<") are still also in
                effect.

                The @{" ALT Cursor Up " link AEM-5700} will move lists or the message display to
                the top of the list rather than cursor left.

                The @{" ALT Cursor Down " link AEM-5700} will move lists or the message display
                to the bottom of the list rather than cursor left.

                When a line in a message that has a email address or web
                address is double clicked, just the email or web address is
                displayed on the @{" clipboard window " link AEM-5500}.  If you have an
                appropriate ARexx script assigned to a function key,
                pressing the function key will perform such functions as
                calling your web browser to display the web address,
                placing the email address in your address book, or
                composing a message to the email addressee.

                A bug was corrected that when printing a message from a
                displayed message, the message was deselected which
                preventing other operations to be performed on that message
                (such as deleting, exporting etc.).  The message now
                remains selected.

                If the user's address was the last address in the To: or
                cc:  line when replying to a message with multiple
                recipients and the user chose to send the reply to all the
                recipients, the system went into a loop.  This bug has been
                corrected.

                When exporting a large number of messages as a group, if
                you cancelled the file requester, the system went into a
                loop bringing up the file requester.  This bug has been
                corrected.

                When sending a message to a recipient with a long email
                address the message:

                    Error: Recipient name too long to fit on line!

                could occur.  This has been corrected.

                When using multiple "body" or "other header" filters on
                more than one folder, you could freeze the system.  This
                has been corrected.

                When composing a message and adding attachments, if you
                tried to delete an attachment beyond the second attachment,
                you could freeze the system.  This has been corrected.

                Addition of the @{" QUIT " link AEM-9531} and @{" GETVAR " link AEM-9530} Arexx commands.
                Additional sample ARexx scripts have also been added to
                the ARexx directory.

                The @{" Installation script " link AEM-3000} for Version 2.00 has been
                completely re-written to install multiple users and the
                ClassAct classes.

@{b}Version 1.52@{ub}    @{i}Released October 3, 1998@{ui} (dated October 1, 1998) at the
                @{b}Midwestern Amiga Exposition (AMICON)@{ub} in Columbus, Ohio.
                Enhancements and corrections in this release are:

                @{" Keyboard hotkeys " link AEM-5700} have been added for each of the commands
                on the @{" command icon bar " link AEM-6000}.  You no longer have to click on
                the icon to activate the command.  You can enter a key on
                the keyboard to accomplish this.  You can also advance to
                the next level (such as the list of messages or the
                display of a message) by pressing the @{b}RETURN@{ub} key rather
                than double clicking.

                The @{" message display " link AEM-8600} has been modified to show whether a
                message is @{b}active@{ub} or @{b}deleted@{ub}.

                If a line in the body of a any message exceeded 256
                characters and you were using body text @{" filtering " link AEM-5600}, the
                system blew when such a message was received.  This has
                been corrected.

                @{" Fowarded " link AEM-8700} messages did not include headers unless @{b}Display
                Full Hdr@{ub} was checked.  Now, if @{" Display Full Hdr " link AEM-7307} is not
                checked a minimum set of headers will be sent.

                A new checkmark item,@{" Fwd Body Txt Only " link AEM-7306} has been added
                to the @{" Messages menu " link AEM-7300} so that you can forward messages with
                headers.

                A copies requester has been added to the @{" print " link AEM-6060} command so
                that multiple copies of a message, message list, or
                address book can be printed.

                Several new @{b}ARexx@{ub} commands have been added.  They include:

                    @{" GETLISTITEM " link AEM-9529}
                    @{" ADDRESS_BOOK GET nickname FIRST USERID " link AEM-9500}
                    @{" ADDRESS_BOOK GET nickname NEXT USERID " link AEM-9500}

                The optional keyword @{b}DESCRIPTION@{ub} has been added to the
                @{b}ARexx@{ub} @{" ADDRESS_BOOK LIST " link AEM-9500} command and the @{b}ARexx@{ub} @{" GETNUMBER " link AEM-9513}
                display has been modified to contain @{b}[+]@{ub} and @{b}[-]@{ub}
                increment/decrement gadgets.

                The @{b}ARexx@{ub} script @{b}Addtogrp.aem@{ub} has been modified to
                utilize the new @{b}GETLISTITEM@{ub} command.

                Several new @{b}ARexx@{ub} scripts have been added to the @{b}ARexx@{ub}
                directory.  They include:

                    @{b}compose.aem@{ub}     Send or Queue a message from a text
                                    file.
                    @{b}DB2ABK.aem@{ub}      Copy email address from data base to
                                    Address Book.
                    @{b}Modgrpnknm@{ub}      Modify group nickname in Address Book.

                See the @{b}readme@{ub} files for each of these scripts to see how
                they can be utilized.  The @{b}readme@{ub} files are contained in
                the @{b}ARexx@{ub} directory along with the scripts themselves.


@{b}Version 1.51@{ub}    @{i}Released March 21, 1998.@{ui}  This is a minor update version
                which corrects these bugs:  (@{i}No enhancements have been
                added@{ui})

                If you are not connected to the Internet when you attempt
                to send a message not previously saved in the @{b}PENDING@{ub} or
                @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folders, the message will now be saved in the @{b}QUEUED@{ub}
                folder.  @{b}AEMail@{ub} was always intended to work this way, but a
                bug that crept in in Version 1.43 saved the message in the
                @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder and then promptly removed it.  This has been
                corrected.

                The @{b}AEMail ARexx@{ub} command @{" ADDRESS_BOOK CREATE GROUP ... " link AEM-9500}
                created the group with it's first user-id truncated to 19
                characters.  This has been corrected.

                The @{b}ARexx@{ub} script @{b}Addtogrp.aem@{ub} has been added to the @{b}ARexx@{ub}
                directory.  This script is used to add To:  and cc:  names
                from a received message to a group entry in the @{b}Address
                Book@{ub}.


@{b}Version 1.50@{ub}    @{i}Released March 14, 1998 at the @{b}Gateway Amiga'98@{ub} show.@{ui}
                Major enhancements and corrections in this release are:

                Added @{" ARexx " link AEM-9400} support.  @{b}AEMail@{ub} now has a very powerful set
                of @{b}ARexx@{ub} commands that can be used to control @{b}AEMail@{ub} from
                external @{b}ARexx@{ub} scripts.  You can also execute @{b}ARexx@{ub}
                scripts and AmigaDOS scripts from within @{b}AEMail@{ub}.
                Additional @{b}ARexx@{ub} commands are planned with the next
                release of @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  Eventually all @{b}AEMail@{ub} menus and
                commands will have @{b}ARexx@{ub} equivalents.

                The Install Script will create a new directory in your
                @{b}AEMail@{ub} program drawer called @{b}ARexx@{ub}.  It will contain the
                @{b}ARexx@{ub} portion of the @{b}.doc@{ub} file called @{b}AEMail-ARexx.doc@{ub}
                which can be printed out and referred to.  The @{b}ARexx@{ub}
                drawer will also contain some sample @{b}ARexx@{ub} scripts with
                associated @{b}.readme@{ub} files.

                A special @{" mailcap " link AEM-9101} file and a script called @{b}html.aem@{ub} is
                also in the @{b}ARexx@{ub} drawer which can display @{b}HTML@{ub}
                attachments using your browser.  Be sure and read the
                @{b}html.readme@{ub} file which is also in the @{b}ARexx@{ub} drawer.

                Added two menu items under the @{" Project " link AEM-7100} Menu called
                @{" Send AREXX/DOS command " link AEM-7106} and @{" Send Last Command " link AEM-7107}.
                Currently using these menu items is the only way to send
                ARexx or DOS commands.  A future version will allow you to
                assign commands to function keys.

                Added the @{" AREXXPORT= " link AEM-4125} Tool Type.  Special note: by default
                the ARexx Message Port name is @{b}AEMAIL1@{ub}.  This Tool Type
                is not needed if you use the default port name.

                Added the ARexx port name to the @{" About " link AEM-7104} menu item.

                Corrected a bug that appeared in Version 1.43 in which
                messages with a bcc: header were not being sent to the
                bcc: recipients.

                When editing messages with to:, cc:, or bcc: header
                strings that exceeded 256 bytes, a system crash could have
                occurred.  This bug has been corrected.

                Changed the placement of the @{b}[Send Message Now]@{ub} and the
                @{b}[Save in Pending]@{ub} gadgets on the @{" Compose Message " link AEM-8700} window.
                @{b}[Send Message Now]@{ub} now appears as the left most gadget
                since this will probably be the most likely gadget to hit.

@{b}Version 1.43@{ub}    @{i}Released January 15, 1998@{ui}.  This release is essentially
                identical to Version 1.42 with the addition of the
                documentation files and the installation script.  Some
                bugs that appeared after 1.42 was released are also
                corrected.

                @{i}Bug fixes and new features in version 1.42 (version 1.43)
                are as follows:@{ui}

                Corrected a bug with the @{" Address Book Window " link AEM-8500} where
                selecting a group nickname would sometimes wipe out the
                address left in the address field.  It now works correctly
                in all situations.  The address is left in the address
                field to faciliate adding addresses to group entries.

                Corrected a bug in the @{" sort order " link AEM-8400} when selecting messages
                in the order received if the folder contained in excess of
                999 messages.  The order is now correct to 9,999 messages.
                @{b}Note:@{ub} because some messages do not have the correct date in
                them (their computers did not have a correct date set), you
                will see messages that appear out of order by date if you
                set the @{b}order received@{ub} criteria.  This is not a bug since
                even though the date was incorrect, the order is maintained
                as to when the message was received.

                If you gave a description to a folder that was too large to
                fit on the @{" Message List Window " link AEM-8200} list view heading line, the
                system crashed.  The description is now truncated if it
                will not fit in the list view heading.

                Corrected a bug in which a @{" minimum header " link AEM-4900} specification
                would not display a header that did not have the same case
                as the specification (i.e., @{b}CC:@{ub}, @{b}Cc:@{ub}  headers would not
                display for a @{b}cc:@{ub} minimum header specication).  The check
                is now case insensitive.

                Added the @{" Last Selected " link AEM-7302} menu item under @{" Messages " link AEM-7300}.  If
                you did a multiple selection on a group of messages and
                then performed an operation on the group of messages (such
                as deleting, copying, saving the group to a file, etc.),
                the messages will be de-selected as the operation is
                performed on each message.  The @{b}Last Selected@{ub} menu item
                will allow you to re-select the same previously selected
                messages so that you can perform another operation on the
                same group of messages.

                Added @{b}[Last Saved]@{ub} and @{b}[Last Used]@{ub} buttons to the
                @{" Sort Window " link AEM-8400}.  This allows the user to restore the sort
                criteria that was last saved or last used.

                @{" Filtering " link AEM-8330} of messages is now no longer restricted to the
                first line of a particular header.  This is particularly
                true of messages that have been sent to or cc'd to multiple
                recipients.  Now the entire @{b}To:@{ub} or @{b}cc:@{ub} header is checked
                if specified as the filtering criteria.

                To accomodate the ability to filter on the complete list
                of recipients and to provide the capability to send
                replies to all @{b}To:@{ub} and @{b}cc:@{ub} recipients (@{i}see below@{ui}), the
                @{" Folder-Name.config " link AEM-9140} file format has been changed.

                The @{" filtering " link AEM-8330} criteria specification for headers which
                contain substrings is changed from "Equals" to "Contains"
                and from "Not Equal" to "Does Not Contain".  This provides
                no difference in operation and is only a syntatical change.

                For @{b}registerd users@{ub} only, two new field types have been
                added for filtering:  @{b}Other Message Hdrs@{ub} and @{b}Message
                Body@{ub}.  Filtering for @{b}Other Message Hdrs@{ub} will check any
                other header that might be in the message and @{b}Message
                Body@{ub} will check data that is contained within the message.

                Increased the size of the string gadgets in the
                @{" COMPOSE MESSAGE window " link AEM-8700} for @{b}To:@{ub}, @{b}cc:@{ub}, and @{b}bcc:@{ub}  to allow
                long multiple address strings.  Up to 4096 bytes are now
                allowed for these strings.  Individual addresses (name and
                email address) are still restricted to what can fit on one
                message line (maximum of about 70 characters).

                Allowed the ability to add multiple recipients of messages
                that are responded to to either the @{b}To:@{ub}, @{b}cc:@{ub}, or @{b}bcc:@{ub}
                fields.  If there are multiple recipients or one or more
                @{b}cc:@{ub} addresses in a message that is being replyed to, a
                special requester will appear on the @{" COMPOSE MESSAGE " link AEM-8700}
                window to allow the addition of these addresses.

                Corrected a bug that sometimes caused headers in messages
                being composed to be garbled. This was a rare occurance.

                When sending messages using the @{" Send Message Immediately " link AEM-6090}
                command from the @{" Command Icon Tool Bar " link AEM-6000} the default folder
                used to send the message is now the @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder and not
                the @{b}PENDING@{ub} folder.  You will have to select the @{b}PENDING@{ub}
                folder if you want to send the messages from there.

                When @{" sending messages " link AEM-6090} to more than one recipient, the
                progress window will now report @{b}Sending to @{i}n@{ui} of @{i}n@{ui}
                recipients of message @{i}n@{ui} of @{i}n@{ui}@{ub}.  You can also abort the send
                as each recipient is contacted.

                When you call the @{" Address Book " link AEM-8500} from the @{" Compose window " link AEM-8700},
                you can click into the @{b}To:@{ub}, @{b}cc:@{ub}, or @{b}bcc:@{ub} field to select 
                which field you want the address from the @{b}Address Book@{ub}
                to be added to.  You will notice that the select cycle gadget
                will automatically reflect the field you are adding the
                address to. This works with both the special @{b}Address Book@{ub}
                and the full @{b}Address Book@{ub} if it is called from the compose
                window.

                If you call the @{" Address Book " link AEM-8500} directly, the select cycle
                gadget is ghosted since it has no effect.  If you call the
                compose window FROM the @{b}Address Book@{ub} the selected address
                will appear in the @{b}To:@{ub} field only (@{i}this is the way it
                always has worked even if you were to have selected a
                different field in the cycle gadget@{ui}).

                Additional icons are active when the @{" Address Book " link AEM-8500} is
                called directly.  These are the current folder message
                list icon and the previous and next folder message list
                icons.

@{b}Version 1.42@{ub}    @{i}Limited release on January 1, 1998@{ui}.  This release
                contained the changes and bug fixes listed above under
                Version 1.43 without the documentation files or
                installation script.

@{b}Version 1.41@{ub}    @{i}Limited release on November 1, 1997.@{ui}  Released on diskette
                as a registered version at the MAE show.  Several minor
                bugs were corrected with this release as follows:

                Corrected a bug that occurred when you double-clicked on a
                name in the Address Book when @{" composing a message " link AEM-8700}.  The
                @{b}[Call Address Book]@{ub} gadget remained ghosted (disabled)
                after the Address Book was closed.  It is now enabled.

                When reading @{" attachments " link AEM-8610}, if the @{b}[Save Clip]@{ub} button is
                ghosted (disabled), the @{b}[Clip Unit]@{ub} button will also be
                disabled.

                If there are multiple attachments to a message, when you
                @{" save an attachment " link AEM-8610} @{b}AEMail@{ub} will now remember the drawer you
                saved it to.  However, if you read another message with
                attachments, the directory will return to the default save
                directory.

                If you are unable to send a message when you click on
                @{b}[Send Message Now]@{ub} in the @{" compose window " link AEM-8700} the message will
                be stored in the @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder rather than the @{b}PENDING@{ub}
                folder.  This will allow you to immediately send the
                message when you re-connect to your Internet Service
                Provider.


@{b}Version 1.40@{ub}    @{i}Released October 10, 1997@{ui}.  Major enhancements and
                corrections in this release are:

                Added the ability to filter incoming messages to specified
                folders.  (@{i}see@{ui} @{" Filter Selection Window " link AEM-8330}) This ability acts
                on information in the header of the message to determine
                where to direct a message.  Wild card capability, ignoring
                case capability, and simple AND or OR relationships can be
                specified in the filtering criteria.  You can also exclude
                messages from being stored in any folder including the
                INBOX.

                Corrected a bug which caused the system to freeze if you
                double clicked on the @{b}[Add Address Book]@{ub} gadget in the
                @{" Compose Message window " link AEM-8700} (or clicked on the gadget after the
                @{" Address Book " link AEM-8500} was displayed).  When you click on the
                @{b}[Add Address Book]@{ub} gadget in the @{b}Compose Message window@{ub} it
                will now become disabled until you close the @{b}Address Book@{ub}
                window.

                Corrected a problem that sometimes occurred if you received
                an error from your service provider when you were sending a
                message.  You would get constant error messages saying that
                the system could not open the output mail.  The error
                message from the service provider was also shifted to the
                right and off the screen.  It is now correctly displayed.

                Corrected a problem that could cause a GURU when sending a
                message if the combined length of the Real Name (from the
                @{" Address Book " link AEM-8500}) and the @{b}UserID@{ub} from the @{b}Address Book@{ub} was
                greater than 71 characters.  Now, if this occurs, only the
                @{b}UserID@{ub} is placed in the @{b}To:@{ub} field of the message.  Also,
                when placing the @{b}UserID@{ub} in the @{b}Address Book@{ub} you are
                limited to 70 characters.

                The @{b}Novice@{ub} user level has been removed from the
                @{" AEMail_Installation " link AEM-3000} script.  @{b}Intermediate@{ub} is now the
                minimum user level that you can install @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  The
                Installation script also provides for backing up your
                @{b}folder.config@{ub} file.


@{b}Version 1.31@{ub}    @{i}Limited release on September 24, 1997@{ui}.

                Increased the size of the @{b}UserID@{ub} that could be entered.
                All configuration items in the @{" Identity " link AEM-4300} configuration page
                have a maximum entry size of 99 characters with the exception
                of the @{b}Password@{ub} which is limited to 30 characters.

@{b}Version 1.30@{ub}    @{i}Released September 1, 1997@{ui}.   Major enhancements and
                corrections in this release are:

                @{" Clipboard " link AEM-5500} support has been added to @{b}AEMail@{ub} in the following
                manner:

                    (1) All @{" string entry gadgets " link AEM-5400} allow copying to and
                        pasting from the clipboard.

                    (2) @{b}Multiple clipboard units@{ub} can be specified (up to
                        256)

                    (3) The message body can be copied in it's entirety to
                        the clipboard.

                    (4) Any line in a message can be edited and copied to
                        the clipboard.  While it is being edited you can
                        paste data from another clipboard unit into the
                        line being edited.

                    (5) A unique feature has been added where you can
                        display the contents of all clipboard units
                        currently active.  You can select a item from this
                        list to paste into a string entry gadget.

                The @{" [Save Text] " link AEM-8620} button used when displaying text will now
                call up a special requester which will allow you to select
                from a number of options including a @{b}VIEW@{ub} option which will
                allow you to use your @{b}mailcap@{ub} viewing program to display
                and manipulate the message.

                The @{" [Attachment] " link AEM-8610} requester has been modified to include
                options for saving to the clipboard.

                Messages marked for deletion were not being deleted if no
                other activity had been performed on the folder that
                contained the messages.  This has been corrected.

                Occasional problems were occuring when double clicking on a
                message caused a "Error: Select Folder Logic Error!!!"
                message to appear and @{b}AEMail@{ub} exited.  This has been
                corrected.

                A period instead of a comma was being incorrectly placed
                after the day of the week in the Date: header.  This has
                been corrected.

                If you attempted to send a message to a group with the
                @{b}Expand@{ub} not checked in the main Address Book display
                (@{i}registered users only@{ui}), the message was not being sent to
                any of the group addresses and you would get an error
                message saying that the message could not be sent.  This
                has been corrected.

                The @{b}Quote Original Message@{ub} box remained checked if you
                changed from a reply to either a forwarded or new message.
                This has been corrected so that @{b}Quote Original Message@{ub}
                will be un-checked if you change from a reply to either a
                forwarded or new message.

                The @{b}Add Signature Block@{ub} box remained unchecked if you
                changed from editing a message to creating a new message.
                This has been corrected so that @{b}Add Signature Block@{ub} will
                become checked when you switch to creating a new message.

                (@{i}some of the above bug corrections were in the 1.22
                release@{ui})

@{b}Version 1.22@{ub}    @{i}Limited release on July 21, 1996@{ui}.

                A problem occurred with one particlular ISP
                (@{b}bcsupernet.com@{ub}) in which small, partial buffers were being
                sent from the ISP.  @{b}AEMail@{ub} could not recognize the reponse
                because it was not complete in the buffer that @{b}AEMail@{ub}
                received.  @{b}AEMail@{ub} was corrected so that, if it received an
                incomplete buffer, it continued to ask for data until it
                received the ending line feed.

@{b}Version 1.21@{ub}    @{i}Released July 6, 1997@{ui}.  Major corrections to this release
                are:

                A major bug has been corrected in which lines greater than
                78 characters could cause @{b}AEMail@{ub} to hang or guru when
                exiting from the @{" Compose " link AEM-8700} window.

                Depending on your screen dimensions, some of the gadgets on
                the Compose window could have overlayed others, especially
                at the bottom of the screen.  This was partially caused by
                the use of large Screen fonts in the screen and window
                titles (set by the Fonts Preferences).  @{b}AEMail@{ub} now more
                intelligently calculates the placement of gadgets on the
                Compose screen.  It also @{i}forces@{ui} the use of the @{b}Topaz 8@{ub} font
                for screen and window titles.

                The word wrap feature in the @{" message display " link AEM-8600} window was
                not taking full advantage of the width of the listview.

                The @{b}EXPAND@{ub} checkmark gadget in the @{" address book " link AEM-8500} displays
                did not work properly with certain screen widths.

                If you were display a message when you decided to Compose a
                reply, the message did not remain selected so that you
                could delete or transfer it without re-selecting it.  The
                message now remains selected until you exit from the
                message display.

                New cursor commands have been added to the control of the
                listviews.  They include:

                    @{b}Home@{ub} or @{b}Cursor Left@{ub} moves the listview to the top.
                    @{b}End@{b} or @{b}Cursor Right@{ub} moves the listview to the
                        botton.
                    @{b}PgUp@{ub} or @{b}Shift Cursor Up@{ub} pages the listview one
                        @{i}page@{ui} up.  The top line of the previous page will
                        be displayed as the bottom line of the new page.
                    @{b}PgDn@{ub} or @{b}Shift Cursor Down@{ub} pages the list view one
                        @{i}page@{ui} down.  The bottom line of the previous page
                        will be displayed as the top line of the new page.
                    The cursor up/down keys on the keypad will have the
                        same action as the normal cursor keys with the
                        exception of the shift feature.

                The slider bar on the message listview did not move the
                message as you moved the slider, but only when you release
                the left button.  The listview now moves as you move the
                slider.

                Some of the command tool bars have been modified -
                primarily as to color.

                Two new @{" command tool bar  " link AEM-6000} icons have been added
                corresponding to the menu items Copy Messages and Transfer
                Messages.  These are placed after the delete icon and
                before the startnet icon.  The copy icon looks like two
                sheets of paper and the transfer icon looks like a sheet of
                paper with arrows going out horizontally.

                Mode requester in the @{" General Parameters Configuration " link AEM-4900}
                page now displays the current screen mode in the requester.

                The problem with hacks or commodities that moved a window
                to the front when you clicked into it such as the
                @{b}Click-To-Front@{ub} commodity (@{i}the folder window disappeared@{ui})
                has been corrected.  Any other hack or commodity that
                automatically brings the current window to front either
                when you click on it or when you pass the cursor over it,
                should work now.  Please let me know if you are still
                having problems.

@{b}Version 1.20@{ub}    @{i}Released July 1, 1997@{ui}.  Major enhancements and corrections
                in this release are:

                For registered users you can use @{" password protection " link AEM-5000} to
                access @{b}AEMail@{ub}.  This is particularly useful for multiple
                user configurations.

                The @{" command tool bar " link AEM-6000} as been re-designed and re-arranged.
                The icons are now in color and several new ones have been
                added including:

                    @{" Display Previous Folder's Message List " link AEM-6120}
                    @{" Display Current Folder's Message List " link AEM-6120}
                    @{" Display Next Folder's Message List " link AEM-6120}
                    @{" Start TCP/IP Network Connection " link AEM-6130}
                    @{" Terminate TCP/IP Network Connection " link AEM-6130}

                The @{" folder icon bar " link AEM-5100} has been re-designed and made smaller.
                Since the vertical and horizontal size of each folder icon
                depends on the font used, the @{b}font and size@{ub} for the folder
                bar can be @{b}user defined@{ub}.

                The @{" Compose Message window " link AEM-8700} has been completely revised.
                It now allows message text to be encoded with
                @{b}printed-quotable@{ub} and @{b}BASE64@{ub} encoding.  Also, when calling
                your editor, the @{b}compose window is re-activated@{ub} when you
                save and quit from the editor.  Only the body of the
                message appears in the editor window.  @{i}This change makes
                the use of any editor that relenquishes control (such as
                CygnusEd (CED)) usable without any special considerations@{ui}.

                You can save messages from the @{b}Compose Message@{ub} window in
                either the @{b}PENDING@{ub} or @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folders or you can
                @{i}immediately send them@{ui}.

                The @{" Address Book " link AEM-8500} when called from the @{b}Compose Message@{ub}
                window will normally have only the Group header without
                the members of the group shown.  @{b}For registered users, you
                will be able to expand the group names@{ub}, however.  Also,
                the @{b}Address Book@{ub}, when called from the @{b}Compose window@{ub},
                will not have the data entry fields for adding addresses
                to the @{b}Address Book@{ub} (although there is an option to call
                the complete @{b}Address Book@{ub}).

                @{b}For registered users@{ub}, when you directly call the @{b}Address
                Book@{ub}, you will be able to "shrink" the Groups to show only
                the Group header.

                @{b}For registered users@{ub}, different signature files are
                possible.

                @{b}For registered users@{ub}, additional user headers can be
                defined.

                @{b}Attachments@{ub} can use @{b}quoted-printable@{ub} encoding.

                When composing messages that are stored in the @{b}PENDING@{ub} or
                @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folders the system will @{i}remember@{ui} previous
                attachments and additional headers that were added.

                When editing messages, the message that is edited will be
                @{i}completely removed@{ui} from the @{b}PENDING@{ub} or @{b}QUEUED@{ub} folder
                rather than marked deleted.

                For all major list views, you can use the @{b}cursor keys@{ub} to
                move the lists up or down.

                For users of AmigaDOS 3.0 or above, @{b}drag select@{ub} has been
                implemented for the Message list.  You can @{i}select@{ui}
                multiple messages by holding the left mouse button down
                and dragging it over several messages.

                The messages counts that are shown in the folder icons
                will have deleted messages subtracted out.

                Several new menu items have been added including the
                ability to "hide" deleted messages and to show only unread
                messages.  You can also force a reply to a message to the
                "From:" address even if there is a "Reply-To:" address.

                If you print a message, it will be marked as "un-read" the
                same as if you displayed it.

                If you are reading a message when you receive additional
                messages, delete a message, or print a message, the
                display will remain on the message and not switch to the
                message list.

                A &(to) parameter has been added to the @{" Quote Header " link AEM-4900} for
                quoted replies.

                Corrected a problem where (fwd) was not recognized at the
                end of the subject line.  AEMail will now recognize the
                (fwd) at either the beginning or end of the line.  Compose
                now also places the (fwd) correctly at the end of the
                subject line.

                Other minor corrections have been made.


@{b}Version 1.15@{ub}    @{i}Released April 5, 1997.@{ui}  Major corrections to this
                release are:

                The @{" message display " link AEM-8600} routines have been speeded up
                considerably.  @{i}As a result of this, the restriction
                which prevented text attachments from being "shown"
                in the message window if they exceeded 5000 characters
                has been lifted.@{ui}  Further increases in message display
                speed will be implemented in future releases.

                Foreign character sets requiring 8-bit display are now
                correctly shown and sent @{i}provided your provider can
                handle 8-bit encoding@{ui}.  Other encoding methods, such
                as "quoted-printable" on output, are not handled as
                yet. They will be handled in a future version.

                When messages are marked for deletion, the on-disk
                configuration file is NOT updated.  This greatly speeds
                up the deletion marking process.  The downside of this
                is that, if the system crashes or your system is turned
                off before AEMail terminates, these messages will not
                be deleted or remain marked for deletion when AEMail
                is re-loaded.

                Daylight Saving Time was only being calculated correctly
                for the United States.  The United Kngdom and Europe
                use "Summer Time" which starts one week before DST in
                the United States (last Sunday in March rather than
                the first Sunday in April).  This has been corrected.

                By using a special @{b}AEMail @{i}tz@{ui}@{ub} @{" environmental variable " link AEM-3100}
                you can now specify time zone increments in half
                hours and with names longer than 3 characters (up to
                9 characters for both Standard Time and Daylight
                Savings/Summer Time).

                In versions prior to 1.15, whenever you sent your first
                email (and, as a result, sent the registration message),
                the @{" ABOUT " link AEM-7104} window would indicate you were "** REGISTERED **.
                This is no longer true.  The "** REGISTERED **" designation
                will only occur when your shareware fee is acknowledged.

                The @{" Installation " link AEM-3000} script has been modified so that it
                no longer copies the sys:rexxc directory to C:.  Instead,
                an assign statement has been added which adds the
                assignment of SYS:REXXC to C:.


@{b}Version 1.14@{ub}    @{i}Released March 20, 1997.@{ui}  Minor correction release.

                Fixed Installation script (Install_AEMail).  It would
                not properly install AEMail if AEMail had not been
                installed previously.

                Insured that the Mail directory and the Mailcap
                directories ended with either ':' or '/'.  If the
                definitions did not, an '/' was appended to the
                path definitions.

                Corrected a problem where the Mailcap directory was
                being used instead of the Mail directory hor the
                .header file (this was not apparent in the Mail
                directory and the Mailcap directory were the same).

                Corrected a problem where the .header file was being
                read before the configuration file.  This again
                probably would not have been an apparent problem.

                Corrected a problem with the "Remove DELETED Msgs"
                menu item in which selecting [CANCEL] would go
                ahead and delete the messages anyway.  [CANCEL] will
                now exit without deleting any messages.

                Corrected a problem when AEMail was called from the
                shell. The "config=" parameter was not working
                properly.  It now works correctly.

@{b}Version 1.13@{ub}    @{i}Released March 10, 1997.@{ui}  Bugs that were corrected are:

                If a message file is missing, AEMail no longer terminates
                if you try to access that file.

                A busy pointer has been added to a number of processes.

                When AEMail terminates and you don't want to check for mail,
                AEMail no longer attempts to access your POP server.  This
                can result in a requester, however, that states you are online,
                even when you are not.

                Duplicate hot key menu calls have been eliminated.

                Other minor corrections have been made.

                For @{b}enhancements@{ub} see @{" Version 1.12 and 1.13 Enhancements " link AEM-9802}.


@{b}Version 1.12@{ub}    @{i}Released February 15, 1997.@{ui}  This version was a special version
                without updated documentation or install script.  It was not
                uploaded to AmiNet.  @{i}It featured the following corrections:@{ui}

                There was a limitation (or bug) in the address book routine
                which limited the number of addresses you could store in a
                group to 255.  This limitation has been lifted.  You can now
                store up to 32,000 addresses in a group.

                The buttons to call up file requesters have been changed
                from @{b}[DIR]@{ub} to @{b}[REQ]@{ub}.

                Other minor corrections have been made including the
                recognition of additional UUencoding formats.

                For @{b}enhancements@{ub} see @{" Version 1.12 and 1.13 Enhancements " link AEM-9802}.

@{b}Version 1.11@{ub}    @{i}Released October 14, 1996.@{ui}  This version corrects some minor
                bugs as follows:

                Corrected the installation script which incorrectly identified
                the "Amitcp:bin" directory.

                Corrected bug that did not allow files in the file requester
                for the "stopnet" script in the Configuration screen.

                Implemented the 9 character NickName for the address book that
                was suppose to be implemented in Version 1.10.

                Made minor revisions in the printout formats for message lists
                and the address book.

                Corrected the display of dates in the mm/dd/yy format when the
                year was beyond 2000.


@{b}Version 1.10@{ub}    @{i}Released September 29, 1996@{ui}.  The following bugs have been
                corrected (@{i}includes bugs corrected with Versions 1.04 a, b,
                and c.@{ui}):

                Corrected bug caused by multiple line SMTP responses.  This
                would result in a "hang" when trying to send messages.

                Prevents a GURU (8000005 - Divide-By-Zero error) from
                occuring when AEMail was unable to determine the size of
                a message that was being retrieved from the POP Server.

                Corrected a bug in which not enough memory was being
                allocated for error message requester displays.  This
                caused a GURU after the error message was displayed.

                When a group address book entry had an actual UserID
                rather than a Nickname for one of it's addresses, the
                entire group was not sent.

                A guru or freeze occurred when reading certain messages.
                These messages had an incomplete Content-Type: header.

                Some requester windows had overlapping fields when a
                large Screen Text font was used.

                If you tried to change your .signature file after you
                composed a message, you could not save your .signature
                file (the .signature file was left open).

                If you composed a message without an ending Carriage
                Return and you added attachments, the attachments were
                not correctly recognized.  AEMail now forces a Carriage
                Return before attachments are added to the file.

                Headers were not being printed when you printed a message.

                Did not properly decode quoted-printable Content-Transfer-
                Encoding.

                Times from 12 noon to 1 PM and from 12 midnight to 1 AM
                were incorrectly displayed.  Changed from 0:xx PM to
                12:xx PM and from 0:xx AM to 12:xx AM.

                Changed install script so that it does not require AmiTCP:
                assign or TermiteTCP environmental variable at the Novice
                level.  If the AmiTCP: assign is not present, AEMail will
                be installed in a AEMAIL directory on your largest disk
                partition.  Also corrected some problems with install
                script.

                Did not save default @{i}Save Attachment Path@{ui} in @{b}AEMail.cnfg@{ub}
                file.

                For @{b}enhancements@{ub} see @{" Version 1.10 Enhancements " link AEM-9801}.

@{b}Version 1.04c@{ub}   @{i}Limited release on September 11, 1996@{ui}.

                Corrected bug caused by multiple line SMTP responses.

@{b}Version 1.04b@{ub}   @{i}Limited release on September 4, 1996@{ui}.

                Corrected divide-by-zero error with progress indicator.

@{b}Version 1.04a@{ub}   @{i}Limited release on September 2, 1996@{ui}.

                Added the time zone capability and corrected a number
                of bugs.

@{b}Version 1.03@{ub}    @{i}Released August 28, 1996@{ui}

                Corrects bug in which clicking on a folder after the
                folder strip was slid to the side selected the wrong
                folder.  This occurred when more folders were present
                than could fit on the display.  @{i}The correction of this
                bug was considered important enough to immediately
                release this version.@{ui}

                Corrected a bug when messages that were not read were
                transferred to another folder.  The number of unread
                messages on the foldr strip was incorrect.  Also, if you
                delete a message that was unread, it will reduce the
                unread count for that folder (the total message count
                still includes messages marked for deletion).  If you
                undelete a message that was never read, the unread count
                will increase.

@{b}Version 1.02@{ub}    @{i}Released August 25, 1996@{ui}

                @{b}Major bug found and corrected!@{ub}  When sending email there
                was a problem with parsing the email addresses of the
                recipients of the message which could cause the system
                to freeze or guru.

                Made minor changes to accomodate TCP/IP stacks other than
                @{" AmiTCP " link AEM-9910}, but which are compatable with @{b}AmiTCP@{ub}.  Tested with
                @{" TermiteTCP " link AEM-9910} and @{" Miami " link AEM-9910}.

                Added arguments when invoking @{b}AEMail@{ub} from the shell.  This
                was to allow @{b}AEMail@{ub} to be used as a @{b}mailto@{ub} agent with
                several Amiga web browsers.  Tested with @{" Voyager " link AEM-9910} and @{" AWeb " link AEM-9910}.
                Consult @{" USING AEMail AS A MailTo AGENT " link AEM-5300} for how to
                implement this feature.

                Set default editor to C:ed.

                Made changes to install script to create an easier
                installation.

                Corrected bug when Text Attachments had lines longer than 100
                characters.

                Changed Start Net and Stop Net menu items to provide for
                starting and stopping the network connection when your
                TCP/IP does not provide an automatic way to start or stop
                the Internet connection (signing onto your provider).  See
                the @{" TCP/IP Parameters " link AEM-4400} Section of the @{" Configuration screen " link AEM-4200}
                on how this function works.

                (some of the above changes were in the 1.01 release)


@{b}Version 1.01@{ub}    @{i}Released August 5, 1996@{ui}

                Limited release incorporating some changes for @{b}TermiteTCP@{ub}.


@{b}Version 1.0@{ub}     @{i}Released July 24, 1996.  @{b}First BETA release.@{ub}@{ui}

                This is the first public version of @{b}AEMail@{ub} released at the
                Sacramento Amiga Computer Club meeting.  The release includes
                the complete @{b}AEMail@{ub} package including an installation script
                and documentation in AmigaGuide (MultiView) format.


@{b}Version 0.06@{ub}    @{i}Released July 8, 1996@{ui}

                Implemented expanded configuration windows.

                Added feature in which @{b}AEMail@{ub} periodically checks for
                mail on your POP Server.

                Added the "Iconify AEMAIL" feature and the menu item that
                supports it.


@{b}Version 0.05@{ub}    @{i}Released June 18, 1996@{ui}

                Added UUENCODED attachment support.

                Added "Change Password" capability to main "Configure" window.

                Added requirement that minimum configuration data be entered
                prior to starting @{b}AEMail@{ub}.

                Added QUEUED message check at program startup and when
                StartNet script is executed.

                Added POP message and QUEUED message check at program
                termination.


@{b}Version 0.04@{ub}    @{i}Released June 2, 1996@{ui}

                Added the "About" menu item.

                Added the delete folder menu item.

                Implemented the printing of messages with your preferences
                printer.

                Added "Progress" Windows to both the Send Message and
                Receive message processes.

                @{b}AEMail@{ub} now automatically recognizes whether it is connected to
                your Internet provider on program startup.

                A Tool Type was added (@{b}AUTOCONNECT=YES@{ub}) which automatically
                executes the StartNet script at program startup.

                Added check to automatically to see if any messages are
                currently available on your POP server at program startup
                or when the StartNet script is executed.


@{b}Version 0.03@{ub}    @{i}Released on May 21, 1996@{ui}

                Added the "Startnet" and "Stopnet" menu items under a new
                "AmiTCP" menu and added the Tool Types to specify the calls
                for the STARTNET and STOPNET scripts.

                Added the Configuration screen activated by the "Configuration"
                menu item under the PROJECT menu.


@{b}Version 0.02@{ub}    @{i}Released on April 20, 1996.@{ui}

                Added MIME support for attachments.


@{b}Version 0.01@{ub}    @{i}Released on March 20, 1996.  @{b}First ALPHA version.@{ub}@{ui}

                This initial version could handle sending and retrieving text
                messages only; no attachment capability was present.  Certain
                features were not yet available and configuration was by
                Tool Types only.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9801 "VERSION 1.10 ENHANCEMENTS"

                            @{b}Version 1.10 Enhancements@{ub}

Version 1.10 of @{b}AEMail@{ub} incorporates a number of enhancements and revisions
suggested by users.  These include:

    o   Added time zone support.  This was both a "bug", in the sense
        that it was overlooked in the earlier version of @{b}AEMail@{ub}, and an
        enhancement.  Consult @{" Setting the Time Zone " link AEM-3100} for how to setup your
        local time zone.

    o   A window is now displayed when @{" exiting AEMail " link AEM-7105} which informs you
        that AEMail is updating it's configuration files.  If you had
        turned your computer off before this update was complete, you
        would have corrupted configuration files.

    o   Eliminated the @{" Delete/Undelete " link AEM-6070} Verification Requester.  This
        requester seemed unneccesary since you could always "undelete"
        a message you deleted by mistake.

    o   The @{" Copy " link AEM-7304} and @{" Transfer " link AEM-7305} operations no longer require you to click
        on "Continue" to complete the operation.  Instead, an informational
        window will be displayed with a "Cancel" button.  Closing the
        window is automatic when you click on a folder.  Clicking on
        "Cancel" will abort the operation.

    o   After a @{b}Copy@{ub} or @{b}Transfer@{ub} operation, the folder message list
        @{b}FROM@{ub} which the messages were copied or transferred will be
        displayed.

    o   @{" Printing " link AEM-6060} has been enhanced to allow the user to print a list
        of messages in a folder and to print the contents of the @{b}Address Book@{ub}.

    o   The @{" Address Book window " link AEM-8500} has been modified to include a number
        of new features including:

            The @{b}Nickname@{ub} has been increased in size to @{b}9 characters@{ub}.

            The @{b}Previous@{ub} and @{b}Next@{ub} command icons are activated to exit
            from the @{b}Address Book@{ub} and display either the previous or
            next message in a message list.  This facilitates adding
            addresses to the @{b}Address Book@{ub}.

            Double clicking on an address in the list view when the
            @{b}Address Book@{ub} is called from the @{b}Compose window@{ub} will
            immediately return to the @{b}Compose window@{ub} transferring
            the @{b}Nickname@{ub} of the appropriate Compose string gadget.

            In @{b}the Address Book@{ub}, when you click on a group's
            @{b}DISTRIBUTION LIST@{ub} line, any existing address in the
            @{b}Address:@{ub} string will not be destroyed.  This facilitates
            adding addresses to the group.

    o   Allowed messages in @{" QUEUED folder to be edited " link AEM-6080}.

    o   Remembers the last directory used when @{" adding multiple attachments " link AEM-8710}.
        Also allows you to establish a @{" default path " link AEM-4500} for adding
        attachments.

    o   Sets an environmental variable called @{b}AEMail_dir@{ub} during the
        @{" install process " link AEM-3000} which contains the directory @{b}AEMail@{ub} was installed
        in to facilitate future @{b}AEMail@{ub} updates.

For more information on these revisions and/or enhancements click on the
appropriate links above.


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9802 "VERSION 1.12 ENHANCEMENTS"

                          @{b}Version 1.12 and 1.13 Enhancements@{ub}

Versions 1.12 and 1.13 of @{b}AEMail@{ub} incorporate a number of enhancements and
revisions.  These are listed below (The version number that applies is shown
in parenthesis after the revision description).


    o   Several @{" menu " link AEM-7300} items have been changed or added:

            AEMail now allows for @{" multiple configuration files " link AEM-4000}.  The
            @{" Project/Configuration " link AEM-7101} menu item now has five sub-items:
            @{b}Open@{ub}, @{b}Edit@{ub}, @{b}Save@{ub}, @{b}Save As@{ub} and @{b}Restore Default@{ub}
            The old @{b}Save Settings@{ub} and @{b}Restore Settings@{ub} menu items
            have been removed from the @{" Project menu " link AEM-7100}. (1.13)

            Under the @{" Folders menu " link AEM-7200}, an item called @{" Remove DELETED Msgs " link AEM-7203}
            has been added.  This will IMMEDIATELY delete @{b}ALL@{ub} messages 
            @{i}marked for deletion@{ui} in the current active folder. @{b}(1.12)@{ub}

            A new menu item has been added under the @{" Messages menu " link AEM-7300} group
            called @{" Edit... " link AEM-7301}. @{b}(1.12)@{ub}

            The TCP Logging File process has been changed to provide
            additional menu control over the logging file.  A new menu
            sub-group called @{" TCP Logging File " link AEM-7503} has been added under the 
            @{" TCP/IP menu " link AEM-7500} group.  This sub-group has three menu sub-items
            called @{b}Active@{ub}, @{b}Purge@{ub}, and @{b}Display/Edit...@{ub}. @{b}(1.12)@{ub}

    o   The @{" configuration " link AEM-4200} screens have been totally revamped. Some new 
        items have been added and others re-named or moved to other
        configuration 'pages'.  The heading for the @{b}Required@{ub} screen
        has been changed to @{b}Identity@{ub} to more clearly indicate its
        purpose and the buttons to call the various configuration
        'pages' have been moved to the top of the screen.  When you
        select a configuration page, the button for that page will
        "light" up and stay "lit" while you are on that page. (@{b}1.12@{ub})

        Other changes involving the configuration (including Tool Types)
        include:

            A @{b}Save As@{ub} button has been added to the Configuration
            screen. @{b}(1.13)@{ub}

            @{b}From (email) Address:@{@{ub} (@{i}your email address@{ui}), @{b}Reply To:@{ub}
            and Organization items have been added to the @{" Identity " link AEM-4300} page.
            New @{" Tool Types " link AEM-4100} have also been added to correspond to these
            items. @{b}(1.12)@{ub}

            The @{b}Edit Call:@{ub} has been moved to the @{" GENERAL " link AEM-4900} parameter 
            page. @{b}(1.12)@{ub}

            A new checkmarked item is added under the @{b}TCP Logging File:@{ub}
            item in the @{" PATHS " link AEM-4500} page of the configuration screen called
            @{b}TCP Logging active on AEMail startup@{ub} @{b}(1.12)@{ub}.

            To accomodate multiple configurations, the @{b}Mail Directory@{ub}
            has been removed from the Configuration screen. It is still
            available as a @{" Tool Type " link AEM-4102}, however. @{b}(1.13)@{ub}

            A @{" CONFIG= " link AEM-4119} @{b}Tool Type@{ub} has been added to allow @{b}AEMail@{ub} to start
            up with a specified configuration file. @{b}(1.13)@{ub}

            The @{" Install script " link AEM-3000} has been modified to provide for the added
            configuration items. @{b}(1.13)@{ub}

    o   When you reply to a message, the @{" compose message " link AEM-8700} routine will
        first try to send the reply to any @{b}Reply-To:@{ub} address that
        was in the message you are replying to.  If the @{b}Reply-To@{ub}
        header was not present, it will then send the reply to the
        @{b}From:@{ub} header address. @{b}(1.12)@{ub}

    o   The same applies to transferring addresses to the address book.
        If you want to transfer the address from a message you are
        reading (by clicking on the @{" address book " link AEM-6020} icon), it will first
        try to transfer the address in the @{b}Reply-To:@{ub} header.  If that
        is not present, it will use the @{b}From:@{ub} header address.  YOU
        CAN FORCE it to use the @{b}From:@{ub} header address by pressing
        the SHIFT key when you click on the Address Book. @{b}(1.12)@{ub}

    o   The @{" address book window " link AEM-8500} has been modified to include a check
        mark item for group addresses to send only the group header in
        any message sent to a group rather than the email addresses of
        each member of the group. @{b}(1.12)@{ub}

    o   When sending a message to a group, the messages will be sent 
        in groups of 50.  This is to allow for limitations in some
        SMTP servers that will not allow a message to be sent to more
        then a difinitive number of recipients.  Most SMTP servers 
        should be able to handle 50 recipients at a time. @{b}(1.12)@{ub}

    o   A @{" busy pointer " link AEM-8600} is now being displayed while a message is being
        read into the viewer.  You can not scroll the message display
        while this busy indicator is being displayed. @{b}(1.12)@{ub}

    o   Attachments that are text attachments are generally shown in the
        message window itself with @{b}SHOWN@{ub} indicated for the attachment
        in the Attachment requester.  The behaviour of AEMail has been 
        changed for messages with @{" attachments " link AEM-8610} exceeding 5000 bytes.
        Now, with such messages, the text attachment will not be shown
        in the main message window, but you would be able to save or
        view it with the attachment requester. @{b}(1.12/1.13)@{ub}

    o   @{b}text/*@{ub} and @{b}message/*@{ub} have been added to the @{" mailcap file " link AEM-9101} using 
        MultiView (3.x users only).  This allows you to view long text
        attachments that are not @{b}SHOWN@{ub} (see above). @{b}(1.13)@{ub}

    o   Miami @{" Start Net " link AEM-4116} and @{" Stop Net " link AEM-4117} scripts have been provided. @{b}(1.13)@{ub}

    o   A special @{" CygnusEd script " link AEM-4110} has been provided to properly use
        CygnusEd (CED) as your editor. @{b}(1.13)@{ub}


@ENDNODE

@NODE AEM-9900 "IN CONCLUSION"

                              @{b}IN CONCLUSION@{ub}

As payment for receiving and using the unregestered version of @{b}AEMAIL@{ub}, I
would like any bugs, comments, or suggestions reported to me.  You can
send me email at

    @{b}jzachar@calweb.com@{ub}

or use the @{b}AEMAIL@{ub} Nickname created in your @{" Address Book. " link AEM-8500}

You can also register AEMail for a shareware fee of $30.  (See the discussion
on @{" REGISTRATION " link AEM-2500}.

See the @{" Bug Reports and Suggestions " link AEM-9700} section for the reporting procedure.

If you give an unregistered version of this program to anyone else to use
and evaluate, please include the complete archive as distributed.  This
includes the @{b}AEMail@{ub} program, the installation script, and all
documentation and readme files.  @{b}DO NOT GIVE A REGISTERED VERSION OF
AEMAIL TO ANYONE!@{ub}

The @{b}complete, unregistered@{ub} archive may be posted to any BBS.  If it is
posted to any particular BBS, I would appreciate it if the person posting
it to the BBS would send me an email message indicating the BBS it was
posted to.

I have a web site at:

    @{b}http://www.calweb.com/~jzachar@{ub}

The latest version of @{b}AEMail@{ub} will be posted to this web site.  Major
releases will also be posted on @{b}AmiNet@{ub}.

Whenever a new version of @{b}AEMail@{ub} is available, I will email all users of
@{b}AEMail version 2.00@{ub} and above for which I have received notification
messages (see @{" Notification Requester " link AEM-2510}) with a notice of the new version.
Users of @{b}AEMail@{ub} prior to Version 2.00 who are @{i}not@{ui} registered users and who
have not upgraded will no longer receive this notice.  To receive these
notices it is important that you send the notification message when you
upgrade.

Thanks,

John Zacharias

@{b}jzachar@calweb.com

www: http://www.calweb.com/~jzachar@{ub}

@ENDNODE

